    'body' => 'On Nobles, Power, and the Imperium

>P.S. And about those 10,000 families who own 50% of Imperial wealth... 
>     
>With THAT kind of wealth, it\'s likely that they form the backbone of 
>Imperial society, and have final say on what - or what doesn\'t - happen 
>in it.

Consider that one of the reasons that an Imperial Family member has been
willing to place the Interdict on a world, has been in order to make
certain worlds owned by certain powerful noble families entirely private.
Lewis/Aramis is an example of this.  Minor Tukera family interests hold
a fief there (the Barony of Inselberg?) and once owned the rest of the
planet outright; they still own most of it.  For various reasons, the 
Tukeras wanted to shut off all interstellar traffic to the world but 
their own, and through the sponsorship of the Marquis Leonard 
Bolden-Tukera of Aramis, and also "various interests at Court" (do you 
see a pattern here?) arranged to have the Interdict placed on the entire 
world of Lewis.  Tukera ships can come and go at will, under a special 
access dispensation.  Everyone else is prohibited from the world.  

The Tukera family owned something like 30% of the Tukera Lines megacorp
outright.  Tukera had a virtual monopoly on long-distance interstellar
travel in some core subsectors.  By the figures I came up with this fall,
the assets they controlled just in bulk shipping could have been worth
several quadrillion credits.  The family helped Cleon found the Third
Imperium itself.  Do they have a say at Court?  Sure looks like it.

The fact that there are Imperial citizens on Lewis who are now totally
cut off from interstellar contact unless they are willing to leave and
never return, well, that seems to be "an internal matter of the world
government of Lewis", which is the Tukera family.  

The Tukeras aren\'t the only large family that has this kind of power 
and influence.  The Hortalez family, for instance, is even wealthier
than the Tukeras.  A Shiishuginsa daughter married an Alkhalikoi
emperor.  The Imperium is big enough to give rare individuals and
groups of individuals incomprehensible amounts of personal power.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
