    'body' => '
First, Michael Llaneza in Digest 133 said that "The interesting thing 
about fashions in the Imperium, as well as music and other cultural 
traits is the time lag in communications."  Not only this, but the high 
population density of certain systems, but each system seperated by a 
week at least.

In effect, you have about 900 \'cities\' with, say, 90 \'mega-cities\' at Pop 
A.  Each city is largely alone in time: communication in the (Tl A+) city is 
instantaneous between each member of that society, but to communiate 
off-world massive gaps of at least a week appear.

The difference between \'in-system\' and \'out-system\' becomes quite large, 
with \'in-system\' pratically meaning face-to-face, and \'out-system\' 
meaning way-out-there-somewhere.  Such a strong dichonomy would be very 
interesting to explore.

Llaneza\'s \'context and mutation\' points are also quite good.  And what 
woould be the consequences of the loss of sociological casuality; could 
you explore this concept a bit more for me?  Thanks for your post!

(And don\'t forget the \'base cultures\' of the Vilani, Solomani, and plain 
vanilla Imperial, too!)

----

Back to my first love, interstellar strategy.

First, a brief review.  Im my original post, I postuated a war in ten 
years between \'Gov1\' and \'Gov2\'.  I said (editing somewhat) -

Gov1 has about 150% of the pop of Gov2 
Gov1 is about a sector in size, Gov2 is about a sector and a half
Gov1 is evenly spread out compared to Gov2, which has two \'high-pop\' 
     areas, with the rest of the area near-empty.
Gov1 is primarily TL C, with high-pop systems ranging from TL A to F.  
     Gov2 is primarily TL E, with high-pop systems ranging fromn TL D to F. 
There is a large buffer state between them, about 2 subsectors in size, 
     at TL D-F.  An ally of Gov1, but more like U.S./Japan rather than 
     U.S./Britain.  It has no love for Gov2, but does not wish to commit 
     it\'s limited forces unles certain of victory.  Moreover, it does not 
     fully trust Gov1.

* * * * *

OK.  Now Steven H. recommends that Gov1 surrender gracefully, as it can\'t 
seriously fight against Gov2.  I\'ll assume that that\'s true (sorry: no 
experience at playing TCS!).  *But* he also says that "a single hogh-pop 
TL 15 world pretty much makes that polity a TL 15 polity, NOT a TL14 (or 
TL 12) polity."

I\'m assuming that the implication is that military of that polity would just 
funnel all military expendeture through that TL F high-pop world. Humm.  
Excluding the \'space patrol\', \'colonial squadrons\' and suchlike, he 
would be correct - for Gov1, which is a unitary state.   Gov2 has a host 
of different navies, as well as a "Grand Fleet" which is farly largish, 
but kept too small to dominate Gov2 [in effect, a crack naval task 
force].      

You know, I think that the ground just shifted under my feet.

Well, let\'s follow thru on this.  Assume that Gov1 (the big \'TL C\' govt) 
has only recently begun to funnel military funds into the TL F systems.  
Let\'s also postuate that Gov2, resting on their laurals (remember, they 
have been \'winners\' for the last 400 years) is more tied up into \'inner 
politics\' rather than the \'primitive foreginers\'.  They are comparatively 
uninterested in the faint rumblings coming from Gov1.

Now *this* is interesting!

Going on with Steve H.\'s comment\'s

"There is no numerical superiority." (Regarding Gov1\'s navy vis-a-vis 
Gov2\'s navy.  Gov1 has 150% of Gov2\'s population)

Why not? <quizzical look>

"Yes." ...on does anyone here read Dragon.

Well then. 
I asked the question (semi-jokingly) because Dragon would seem to be the 
total antithesis of Traveller\'s attitude towards technology and reality. 
I sometimes look through it, but usually nothing strikes me as interesting.
Still, I wanted to see if nyone here is quote "Broadminded" unquote to 
read something totally at odds with the Traveller universe.
So there.

Last word from Steve H. "NOTE: I am ignoring the possibility of genocidal 
war..."

Yea, so am I.
Actually, im my private universe the attitudes between the citizens of 
Gov1 and Gov2 were initally genocidal: sterilization capagins using Big 
Rocks and genetic warfare were common in the earlier centuries.

Later, tact agreements to let the loser\'s leave the system in return for 
an end to the fighting arose.  These have been formalized rituals by the 
time this war starts.

What I\'m hoping to do is to let Gov1 capture a major portion of Gov2\'s 
population (the smaller High-Pop cluster), but be forced to keep the 
population in place rather than move or kill them.  The question I want 
to explore with this senario [after a glorious round of wargaming ;] is 
"What happens when two ancient foes, with a long history of hatred and 
henious acts against each other, are rammed in the same room and forced 
to live with rach other?"

I know, I know; this question has been dealt with to death in literature, 
history and situation comedies.  The new factors I\'m bringing up are  A) 
_actual_ physical differences, rather than simple racism (ie. the 
consequenses of widespread genetic engineering), B) the actual 
sociological effects of a long, long race war -- between technological near-
equals -- the ideologies that power it, and the forces needed to end it, 
without a decisive defeat of one or the other.

As a side bar: The buffer state was originally a part of Gov1.  However, 
because of it\'s close proximity to Gov2 - and the constant incursions - 
it quickly developed into a high-tech region of Gov1, and eventually 
became independent ablut 300 years ago. (Imagine if the Northern States 
choose to seceede from the Union in 1861, and you have an idea of what I 
want.)  I do plan to have Gov1 conquer them, and see what happens when 
they are reunited with their unloved brethern.  Will they find a way to 
re-seceede?  How would Gov1 appease their pride, tempt them to identify 
with Gov1, and put down any political unrest without alienating the 
general population?  

And Seven H. also noted that you can\'t tell Pyrrhic Wars until after 
their end.  Well, I agree that fighting, ONCE STARTED, tends to go on and 
on beyond all reason.  But a careful and pessimistic look at the facts 
can often prevent a war before it starts. 

 * * * * * * *

Now, on to J Roberson\'s "The Warring States":

"Train hard".  OK, Gov1 does so.

[Thanks to Steve H.\'s comment\'s Gov1 will now be a largely TL F navy.  
However, out of curiousity, how much can good, tough training make up for 
a deficency of technology?  I know that the excellent Zulu warrious still 
ws simply slaughtered by the British Maxims: I also know that the Mongol 
Hordes brought down empires far more advanced then they were (partially 
by using the tech of conquered nations, partially by specializing in a 
form of technology (horseback warfare) that the Chinese, say, did poorly in.

The equivelant would be, perhaps, Gov1 specializing in throwing rocks 
(ie. massive, low-tech mass drivers; asteroids leaving jump 100 km above 
the target world) while Gov2 retaliates with biowar.  This can stand more 
thought.]

"How many of Gov2\'s low/no-popworlds are still uses? [umm, \'usable\']  
Thai is, do any of them have vital resources?"  Well, not in the 
dollars-and-cents way you mean.  After TL B+, say, a typical system 
doesn\'t _need_ anything outsystem that it can\'t make on it\'s own. 
(Excluding radioactives: but their importance is drastically diminished 
when fusion power plants arise).

No: most of those worlds act as a psychological \'comfort/growth zone\'.  
Only a few worlds are key transportation bottlenecks (the kind of worlds 
you want).  All those worlds work more like Russia\'s massive area, to 
disperse and slow the enemy\'s advance, and for pride - and internal 
politics.

I said "There is a large buffer state between them, about 2 subsectors in 
size..."
Roberson says "Annex them."

I like his style!

To leverage my numerical superiority, he says "Blitz.  Pick some 
poor-defended but important world and throw everything you can at it.  
Repeat as often as needed."  Yumm!  It\'s too bad that I can\'t email my 
maps to you, so we can get down to the nit-and-gritty of it.  Careful 
planning would be needed.

----

Finally: 

I bought a book at university years ago, Fred Charles Ikle\'s _Every War 
Must End_.  An excellent book, emphasising the planning of a war and the 
necessity of drawing out _all_ the implications of a war, right to it\'s 
end. (You\'d be surprised how many leaders only planned the attack, but 
did not consider the results of their actions, or the likely denouncement 
of the war.  Gov1, take note!)  

The highlight, in a nutshell...

A) Far too much energy is spent planning the tools, compared to linking 
tools to their results.  I.e. Pearl Harbour was a nearly-perfectly 
excecuted, well-though-out plan for a single battle, but noone took even 
a look at the likely consequences of this action.  No one planned out the 
most likely results of this action, or took them to their likely conclusion.

And other things to remember...
   As fighting continues it\'s purposes change.
   ie. trying to position itself for the _next_ war, reconciliation may 
become a wiser choice than outright victory (see the Franco-Prussian 
War), today\'s enemy becomes tomorrow\'s friend

   Means becomes ends.
   ie. the military strives to conquer territory because it benefits from 
conquering.  Whether this benefits the nation is something else again.
Also, personal considerations and clique goals affect wars, although the 
national interest is usually considered, sort-of.  

   What resources would be used?  Is this a war with bounds?
   I bet that Strephon didn\'t think that Black War tactics would be used 
against him!

   What outside help?  How much?
   Will the cost coerce the enemy?
   The problem of the Final War - why it was so destructive - is that for 
Lucan and Dulinor, there was no such thing as "too high a price" (As 
Steven H. pointed out)  This also comes to play in religious/racial/
ideological wars. [Can you imagine that at one time the entire Earth 
could have been gutted because of a set of bloody economic theories?  
Ridiculous!]

   What is the enemy up to?  What is he thinking?
   Which estimates to believe?
