    'body' => 'Just a few questions - and comments - along this thread. Quite interesting,
actually (the thread; I\'m not trying to be self-effacing here ;)

>OK.  Now Steven H. recommends that Gov1 surrender gracefully, as it can\'t
>seriously fight against Gov2.  I\'ll assume that that\'s true (sorry: no

>I\'m assuming that the implication is that military of that polity would just
>funnel all military expendeture through that TL F high-pop world. Humm.

Not to second-guess Steve\'s own words, here, but initially I agreed with
him - A sector with a high-tech capital is effectively a high-tech sector -
the technology is a little more diffused. It\'s like how Starbucks Coffee
took over Seattle years ago and has only recently (this is an unconfirmed
rumor) made it to Tulsa, OK. I hope that the specifics don\'t confuse the
point - yes the tech is there, but without a decent proportion of high-tech
worlds to populated space, the technology gets diffused and even though the
polity *can* build a B2 bomber, they\'lll probably rely on cheaper bombers
that can be manufactured easily on more worlds.

Besides which, as was pointed out by the original poster, the high-tech
sector is a more diverse coalition, rather than a singular unifed state. To
me it is akin to NATO vs the Soviet Union - Yes NATO had superior tech, but
each army was its own force and limited to its own natonal resources (for
the most part). I do not think that graceful capitulation is even close to
an agreeable option, especially given the avowed nature of the lower-tech
state.

>>"There is no numerical superiority." (Regarding Gov1\'s navy vis-a-vis
>>Gov2\'s navy.  Gov1 has 150% of Gov2\'s population)
>Why not? <quizzical look>

I think he meant that the technological advantage would far outweigh the
numerical superiority, and that the higher-tech society would make better
use of their resources - it would take less to beuild a match for the
enemy. That strategy only works to a given point.

>Later, tact agreements to let the loser\'s leave the system in return for
>an end to the fighting arose.  These have been formalized rituals by the
>time this war starts.

How quaint ;) I have always been of the opinion - and I am no hawk,
precisely because I feel this way - that anything worth fighting for is
worth by any means. If war is to be the last means of resolution, then
putting little rules on it that lessen its effects will only make it more
attractive. THis is precisely what happened in Europe time and again.
People were upset about German U-Boats because (among other things) they
fired from below the surface of the ocean. Can you imagine that?! <:0=

If I estimate the aggressor state correctly, they will not let any
"articles of war" prevent them from gaining an advantage. They won\'t break
the rules too often, lest the opposition follow suit - but they will break
the rules when the prize outweighs the risk.

>What I\'m hoping to do is to let Gov1 capture a major portion of Gov2\'s
>population (the smaller High-Pop cluster), but be forced to keep the
>population in place rather than move or kill them.

I like the role-playing questions you intend a a result of this enforced
closeness. There are many reasons not to move or kill the population.

THe systematic and efficient elimination of a people can be accomplished -
witness the Holocaust - but it isn\'t always easy. In fact, at that tech
level it may be more efficeient to use high techology to brainwash key
people and pacify the population that way, freeing up your resources for
the war effort. Moving them poses just as much of a problem. It can be
difficult to balance a war budget using slave labor - the Germans did it
for a while - It\'s easier to take key points of power and turn high-ranking
people to your cause than to systematically kill them all, especially with
a war on.

>I know, I know; this question has been dealt with to death in literature,

Don\'t sweat it. Nobody\'s been original since the end of the Ancietn Age. ;)

>[Thanks to Steve H.\'s comment\'s Gov1 will now be a largely TL F navy.
>However, out of curiousity, how much can good, tough training make up for
>a deficency of technology?  I know that the excellent Zulu warrious still

Quite a bit, IMHO.Unfortunately, I have no figures off hand to back this
up. . . *shrug* but I\'m good trainging is always an advantage. If you are
really curious, look into figures comparing the Stormtroopers against
frontline French, Belgian, and English troops. A great deal of the German
Army\'s success in WW2 was shock tactics - tactics that only worked because
the soldiers had trained hard. In short, practice makes perfect.

>"How many of Gov2\'s low/no-popworlds are still uses? [umm, \'usable\']
>Thai is, do any of them have vital resources?"  Well, not in the
>dollars-and-cents way you mean.  After TL B+, say, a typical system
>doesn\'t _need_ anything outsystem that it can\'t make on it\'s own.

Need, no. Want, yes. And while they can suffice, they may effectively drop
a TL or two. Look at War Bonds and recycling in WW2. People stopped driving
cars, wearing pantyhose, and planted their own gardens to help the war
effort. Some have postulated that if money had been spent on NASA instead
of Vietnam, we\'d have an orbital station or even a moon base by now. A
planet under siege will still be the provider of resources - including
governmental authority - that other planets will need.

This last bit is one reason why capitals are so important. You;d think that
capturing the capital would be no big deal - the government will just meet
someplace else,right? But where? And how many will make it to this new
place? How can you govern effectively when city small has just been reduced
to so many anti-particles? Capturing low-pop worlds demoralizes the rest of
the nation. Capturing hihg-pop worlds merely exacerbates this effect.

>(Excluding radioactives: but their importance is drastically diminished
>when fusion power plants arise).

Not when your friends are there, your relatives are there, and your
business interests are there. Even boring worlds can become rally points.
Witness the Alamo.

>>Roberson says "Annex them."
>
>I like his style!

Thank you. Believe me, I\'m not like this in real life. ;)

