    'body' => '
J Roberson has a thing about my \'formalized rituals\'.  Well, let me say 
why I instituted them in the first place, then go on from there.

These rituals - call them "highly complex methods of communication", if 
you like - I created for the same reason why certain animals \'fight\', 
but rarely or never to the death.  These rituals exist more to limit 
the damage and extent that the (early) genocidal wars would cause: it has 
very little to do with \'fairness\' or \'understanding\', and a lot more to 
do with survival.

One of the most basic reasons I put them in is that I can\'t imagine truly 
unlimited warfare - between relative equals - that wouldn\'t soon (ie. 
within 150 years) either kill off both combatants or result in a *very* 
decisive victory for one side.  It certainly wouldn\'t have resulted in a 
900-year stalemate, which is what I want.

Thus, I decided that both Gov1 and Gov2 saw (after a serious amount of 
deaths and devestation, and several wars) that the profound hatred that 
they feel toward each other was threatening their own survival, and 
backed off, using these diplomatic rituals (and the use of expulsion 
rather than extermination) to cool down the situation and limit the lust 
for vengeance (well, compared to what it was previously).

Moreover, these rituals create a \'buffer\' of (strictly psychological!) 
safety, permitting both to turn inwards for a few centuries.  Moreover, 
Gov2 (you know, the TL D-F federation) obtained a decisive technological 
lead over Gov1, enough to be able to \'afford\' internal dissension. 

---- Long Aside ----

[Question: Why didn\'t Gov2 use this lead to finish Gov1?
 Answer: A) The Tech lead, although large enough to insure safety, was 
            not so large as to *guarantee* victory in an offensive war.
         B) The *threat* of war is often much more effective than the actual
            implimentation of that threat.  Prime example: The Third 
            Reich has a large technological lead over Russia, better  
            training, better leadership.  Hitler\'s correct choice should 
            have been to continue to intimidate the Soviet Union, but NOT to 
            actually go ahead with an attack.  He decided - to head off a 
            possible two-front war, which he feared -  to attack Russia 
            while she was weak.  Oops.
         C) Gov2 doesn\'t have total, accurate information on Gov1\'s total 
            tech situation, and suspected that they couldn\'t conquer 
            enough of Gov1 before Gov1 starts catching up - quickly - in 
            TL\'s.  Moreover, both societies are \'closed\' to each other, 
            leaving too many \'blank spaces\' in the information picture.  
            Better to remain as they were, with their superior strategic 
            situation.                                                  ]

---- End Aside ----

Now we can deal with the heard to J Roberson\'s argument: any war that is 
to be fought is to be fought with all the resources at hand.

Well, this is nice to say, but quite a lot of the time the internal 
political situation won\'t permit this (ie. all those body bags and ugly 
pictures).  The external political situation may not permit this (what if 
the U.S. (or China, later) nuked Vietnam?).  And exhellation (you know 
the word I\'m trying to spell) may be counter-productive (what if Iraq 
used poison gas?).

On the other hand, war isn\'t a parlour game.

Moreover, oftentimes the use of ritual in war requires a shared 
religion/ideology between combatents (ie. no warfare on Sundays in 
Christian medieaval Europe, the creation of the Art of War in  
China to encourage careful planning, espionage, and misinformation rather
than
open and unconsidered conflict.)  

It\'s quite true that Gov1 will attempt to \'flex\' the rules as far as 
it thinks it can get away with.  Still, since the consequences for being 
caught is so severe, and because it\'s rather difficult to hide the use of 
biowar agents, massive rock showers, and genocidal (non-military) nuclear 
strikes, it\'s unlikely that cheating will occur much.  Moreover, it\'s the 
losing side that\'s tempted to cheat the most: and Gov2 would be in a poor 
position to bring the war to the enemy, a nessessary precondition to 
dropping rocks on cities.  (NOT so neccessary when it comes to biowar: 
but both governments have long experienxe in dealing with _THAT_ kind of 
conflict.  Moreover, it\'s breaking the ritual... something that will be 
certainly be avoided, since much (or all!) of the war wiuld be fought in 
*their* systems.) 

To summarise: In this situation, diplomatic/military ritual is, I feel, 
defendable as a important factor in the relationship of Gov1/Gov2.  


 -- Long aside --

[The _Art of War_ assumes that all combatents are rational and share the 
same basic ideology.  Ie. no racial/religious/ideological battles are 
assummed.  True in China during the Warring States period, but 
possibily worthless in other situations.

Of course, since A) most wars *are* political B) the _Art of War_ is tied 
to rationalism, rather than a obviously religious framework, C) it does 
not assume the existance of a powerful, united Church, it\'s lessons are 
far more generally applicable to our society than teh thought of 
Medieaval Europe]

-- End Aside -- 


----
Alvin Plummer
