    'id' => '<Pine.SOL.3.91.950106001023.16700A-100000@mercury>',
    'index' => 'aa610',
    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 142',
    'body' => '	I\'ve had a few thoughts about attacking a populated, high-tech
planet. I\'ll assume a Hi Pop, Hi Stellar world for the sake of discussion.
And Black War and genocide will be ruled out; the objective will be to
gain control of the target planet.

	First of all, the attacker must keep and maintain control of
local space. The volume around the target planet must be under firm
control for an extended period of time.
	Space superiority is the province of the Navy, and is very
straightforward and consists of preventing the defender from operating
any spacecraft within the 100 diameter limit.

	Secondly, orbit must be cleared of defenses. Anything capable of
relaying targetting data to meson guns must be eliminated. The defender
must be deprived of the ability to detect ships in orbit. Weapons of
course must also go. The defender will be stocked with small, remote
weapons stations designed to hide in orbit, deloy passive sensors and
launch weapons. Something as small as a missile would work. Thousnads
would be needed since many will be found and destroyed. The attacker will
be forced to maintain constant minesweeping operations to minimize losses
from that source.


	Thirdly, ground based sensors must be eliminated. Fixed sensor
arrays, active and passive, are large enough to be visible to optical and
IR sensors. They will be camoflauged, so the attacker must rely on image
analysis and operator skill to locate hidden sensors. A higher tech level
will help, so will peacetime spying; always do your homework. Lack of fire
control will effectively silence the planetary defense guns. The defender
may counter the loss of fixed sensors by using synthetic array sensors
with the individual elements mounted on grav vehicles. These will have to
be eliminated.

	Fourth, ground-based defenses capable of hiting a ship in orbit
must be analyzed to determine their extent, capabilities, and location.
This is accomplished during the campaign to clear orbit and the sensor
arrays. This is done as much to allow them to be avoided as to
immediately destroy them.

	Of course, high value targets in all categories must be destroyed
as soon as they are detected.

	The final stage is blockade. The orbital blockade against
defending warships will double as an economic blocade. More importantly,
ships in orbit must interdict ground-based transport, particularly food
transport to cities. I very seriosly doubt that every person on a Hi Pop
planet can be fed with food produced within easy reach. There are
situations where food will have to be produced in the cities, self
contained cities in on inhospitable planets for one. In these cases food
production facilities will have to be destroyed, captured, or sabotaged.

	The population of the planet will have to be starved into
submission. Nothing ele will work. Terror bombing has never decided a
campaign, and industry will keep producing even under heavy bombardment.
Besides, the economy is what you want. It may prove possible or
desireable to land troops to capture cities or factories. In any event,
anything that moves on the planet surface must be destroyed. No vehicles
may move, mass transportation lines have to be cut.

	When paralysis sets in, nothing moves, and the food doesn\'t get
to the cities, the citizens are trapped in their homes. Fear sets in and
surrender becomes possible. I suggest that one city be captured to prove
to the population that it can be. It also gives psychological and
symbolic benefits.  After that, wait for people to get hungry.

	Final note, never commit atrocities in territory you want to
keep. Retribution killings for guerilla attacks are worthless. Don\'t get
the population mad at you, any more than you have to anyway. The
objective is to control planet, not a graveyard.

	Any comments people?  Working out the details is going to be a
lot of work, but building a wargame scenario for BR and Striker out of
this would be worthwhile, and worth publishing.

	Alvin, I want to see your scenario. UWP\'s to the mailing list
perhaps? Can you share notes yet?



Michael Carter Llaneza
Conceptual Design Services             The Worse it gets,
Pi Kappa Phi                           The more I get used to it.
"I am the NRA"			       Duty Now For The Future

