    'topic' => 'RE: XBOAT digest 142',
    'body' => 'Tech Level Superiority:
>yet, I note that TL13-14 ships cost an average of only 75% (or less, for
>a well designed ship) of the cost of a similar ship built at TL12-.  A
>TL15 ship will cost less than 60% of the cost of a TL12- ship.

While I do believe that good training can overcome a technological
disadvantage (Peter the Great turned the easily defeated Russian army
into the not-so-easily defeated Russian army) I must concede that a TL12
force defeating a TL15 force is highly unlikely.

The trick about technology is that while the top-of-the-line ships
are more expensive, it costs less to do the same. Look at the cost and
power of your personal computer compared to ENIAC (Pentiums excepted ;)
Even with a smaller budget, the more advanced force could have superior
firepower.

Holocaust:
>    It is NEVER easy.  Note that the Germans (a remarkably efficient
>people) did NOT succeed in exterminating the targetted peoples (Jews,

Clarification
My reference wasn\'t to systematic destruction. German economists
calculated the value of human beings, weighing the maintenace cost (what
was considered food and shelter for the camps) vs. how productive each
prisoner could be. They even calculated the value of the corpse (they
made by-products of skin & hair)

Capital Battles:
>    I disagree that capturing the capital is a trivial exercise.  It
>certainly hasn\'t been trivial in any TCS game *I* have ever played.

I\'m sorry, I don\'t recall saying it was trivial. I certainly don\'t
believe capitals are easy to capture.

>    I also disagree with the notion that capturing low-pop worlds is
>demoralizing.  90%+ of the population is on the high-pop worlds.  So

I think it would depend on the values of the civilization. If all life
is valued, then even the smallest world being taken will affect the
populace. If the society is used to war it may take the capture in
stride. It\'s like with people: Punch someone who has never fought in
their life; they\'ll take it a lot harder than a similar punch to
an experienced barroom brawler.

>if any effect on popular morale.  Loss of a significant fraction of
>the Army or Navy (whichever is the dominant arm) will severely
>demoralize most civilians, however.

I think that the cultural forces are different. Assuming we are using
Continental Europe as our main historical source, I\'d like to point
out that the states were almost always in a state of war with somebody.
People were used to war. Furthermore, people tended to settle in the same
area - your relatives usually didn\'t live on the other side of the country.
People simply didn\'t get about as much as they do now.

Contrast this with the modern U.S. We have not been invaded for a long
time (that strip of rocks the Japanese took from Alaska doesn\'t count!;)
and a lot people - at least people I know - have friends and relatives all
across the country. If one part gets invaded (say, Maine or Hawaii) a
good portion of the general population will have friends, relatives, or
even just business interests there. If the same is tru of GOV2, then
there will be hue and outcry about a small world being taken.

Shipbuilding:
>    It\'s about to shift again.  A TL15 warship costs MUCH less than a
>TL12 warship.  It is virtually certain that the lads in the TL12-14
>worlds will buy TL15 warships instead of building their own, UNLESS
>the ENTIRE capacity of the TL15 yards are used to support the

This gets back to Steve\'s question of TL. If the average TL of the
sector is only about 12, then those TL15 shipyards can charge an
arm and a leg for their advanced services. Compare the costs of typing
your resume on a typewriter vs getting it professionally set by
a resume service. It depends on how coherent Gov1 is as a polity.


> "There is no numerical superiority." (Regarding Gov1\'s navy vis-a-vis
> Gov2\'s navy.  Gov1 has 150% of Gov2\'s population)

The only flaw here is that no matter how good the ships are, Gov2 will
have fewer people to pull for crewing them. Of course, those high-tech
ships will need fewer people, but still. . .Gov1 has a higher potential
body count.

>    This should be interesting.  IMHO, after conquest of the buffer
>state, Gov1 will be incapable for many years of taking on Gov2.  First

That depends largely on how they do it. If Gov1 is smart, they\'ll sow
dissent so that when they invade, they are "liberating" the buffer state.
Much like Hitler "invaded" an all-too friendly Austria.

>    And the Army has to be increased in size (to provide massive numbers
>of Occupation Troops for the buffer state, plus more to attack worlds

Unless the population is behind you. Ten years? Plenty of time.

>    They don\'t do this, though.  Taking a low-pop world is meaningless
>to the polity as a whole (no benefit for you, no loss to him).  Bypassing

Unless you want to cover your rear, hoping that the enemy won\'t use it
as a landing point, much the way the American territory in China is in the
Axis & Allies game.

>it is quite easy.  So a competent admiral will ignore the little worlds
>and gun for the high-pop worlds that are worth grabbing...

A Great Admiral will secure those worlds with minimal force.

>    Sure would.  Try it against _me_, and I\'ll ruin you while you
>concentrate on "Stalingrad"...:-)

Damn Russians. There\'s too many of you ;)



Sorry to cut this short - I have to leave now.



J Roberson
