    'body' => 'Alvin Plummer:

> J Roberson has a thing about my \'formalized rituals\'.  Well, let me
> say why I instituted them in the first place, then go on from there.

> One of the most basic reasons I put them in is that I can\'t imagine
> truly unlimited warfare - between relative equals - that wouldn\'t
> soon (ie. within 150 years) either kill off both combatants or result
> in a *very* decisive victory for one side.  It certainly wouldn\'t have
> resulted in a 900-year stalemate, which is what I want.

    This sounds like a Star Trek episode.  It is a frankly stupid idea
to ritualize war to the point where it becomes a permanent fixture.
Admittedly, people do really stupid things now and then :-), but the
likelihood of a really stupid idea surviving for 900 years is pretty
small...


> [Question: Why didn\'t Gov2 use this lead to finish Gov1?
>  Answer: A) The Tech lead, although large enough to insure safety, was
>            not so large as to *guarantee* victory in an offensive war.

    Well, no.  Actually, the TL lead you described is MORE than enough
to win the war.


>         B) The *threat* of war is often much more effective than the
>            actual implimentation of that threat.  Prime example: The
>            Third Reich has a large technological lead over Russia,
>            better training, better leadership.  Hitler\'s correct
>            choice should have been to continue to intimidate the
>            Soviet Union, but NOT to actually go ahead with an attack.
>            He decided - to head off a possible two-front war, which
>            he feared -  to attack Russia while she was weak.  Oops.

    Well, no.  Technologically, the Russians were pretty much the equal
of the Germans.  They were doctrinally behind the Germans in their
military (no correspondent to the Panzer Division), but technically
ahead in many ways (their AFVs were generally superior to the German
designs, the Russian service rifle was better, etc.).  Their only real
technical weakness was their poor electronics (their radios were TERRIBLE),
and a poor supply infrastructure which mandatred short, bloody offensives
followed by rebuilding of the force and starting the offensive over -
a wonderful way to ensure that you have to make the "break-out" over
and over and over again, thus increasing casualties to a high degree...
    Hitler was NOT "intimidating" Russia before the attack.  All he was
accomplishing was to give Russia time to modernize their doctrine to
deal with the Blitzkrieg.  Note that Hitler MIGHT have been able to beat
the Russians IFF he had launched Barbarossa on the original schedule,
as opposed to bailing the Italians out in Greece and Yugoslavia first.
    Probably not, but that was his big window of opportunity.

    As to the "threat of war".  Consider the effectiveness of threats
against the Bosnian Serbs.  As opposed to the effectiveness of actual
war against, say, Imperial Japan...



>         C) Gov2 doesn\'t have total, accurate information on Gov1\'s total
>            tech situation, and suspected that they couldn\'t conquer
>            enough of Gov1 before Gov1 starts catching up - quickly - in
>            TL\'s.  Moreover, both societies are \'closed\' to each other,
>            leaving too many \'blank spaces\' in the information picture.
>            Better to remain as they were, with their superior strategic
>            situation.                                                  ]

    Well, no. Unless Gov1 is a dictatorship like unto the Soviet Union or
Nazi Germany, it is extremely unlikely that they could have kept their
technological capabilities secret (any more than we can today).  In any
case, living with huge blank spots in their information picture makes a
war MORE likely, not less.  When was the last time that a military
assumed that they were incapable of defeating an unknown enemy.  Especially
one they have defeated regularly for centuries?



> Now we can deal with the heard to J Roberson\'s argument: any war that is
> to be fought is to be fought with all the resources at hand.

    OK.


> Well, this is nice to say, but quite a lot of the time the internal
> political situation won\'t permit this (ie. all those body bags and ugly
> pictures).

    This won\'t be a problem if all the body bags are full of guys on the
other side.  After all, you assume that these people HATE each other.
    And a genocidal war will result in massive casualties on the side
being hit, with minimal casualties on the other side.  Unless BOTH sides
get genocidal, in which case PEACE will break out REAL FAST!  Then the
next war will no longer be inevitable...


> The external political situation may not permit this (what if
> the U.S. (or China, later) nuked Vietnam?).

    Bad example.  Vietnam had the Soviets to protect them from American
or Chinese nukes.  Gov2 has no protector to threaten certain destruction
of Gov1 if Gov1 begins a genocidal war on Gov2.


> And exhellation (you know the word I\'m trying to spell) may be
> counter-productive (what if Iraq used poison gas?).

    Again, bad example.  Iraq could have used poison gas, which would
have annoyed the US no end.  And resulted in Iraq getting hit even
harder.  This consideration may not have applied if the war were
between equals.  Note that Soviet war plans assumed the use of gas in
any attack on Nato.  THEY weren\'t really afraid of any meaningful
change in the course of the war as a result of the use of chemical
agents (since they assumed the war would go to the finish no matter
what weapons were used...)


> On the other hand, war isn\'t a parlour game.

    Damn straight.  And if you play it that way, sooner or later,
someone will hand you your head while you are crying "but they
broke the Rules! <sniffle>"


> Moreover, oftentimes the use of ritual in war requires a shared
> religion/ideology between combatents (ie. no warfare on Sundays in
> Christian medieaval Europe, the creation of the Art of War in
> China to encourage careful planning, espionage, and misinformation
> rather than open and unconsidered conflict.)

    Wars were, in fact, fought on Sundays in medieval Europe.  The Pope
tried several times to convince people not to fight under certain
conditions (Sundays, Lent, one whole year one time).  It never worked
out, though...
    And the Chinese so-called "Art of War" was developed to make wars
MORE effective, not LESS.  The elements of the "Art of War" were just
guidelines for commanders to use to do the job well - just like in
Europe, where the "Art of War" was used to describe EFFECTIVE
principles of war-making...


> It\'s quite true that Gov1 will attempt to \'flex\' the rules as far as
