    'body' => '
I have some general points I would like to make here, based mostly on 
my formal education in history/philosophy, I know I am making a few 
sweeping generalisations so if anyone can refute what I\'m saying here 
I would be most interested.

Rituals in Warfare:

Ritualised warfare seems to develop between states which are roughly 
equal (equal at least in the sense that no one state has a clear 
ascendancy over the others).  An example of this would be the Spring & 
Autumn period (about 800-400 BC from memory) in Chinese history.  
China. At that stage China had over 300 sovereign polities, by about 
250 BC only a dozen were left.

The "rituals" develop as a "safety measure" which acts to minimise 
your potential loss from any one conflict.  Warfare tends to be 
limited rather than "total", eg rules for prisoner exchanges at the 
conclusion of hostilities.  This is something that I think will hold 
true in the future.

While rituals such as formal mechanisms for declarations of war and 
peace negotiations may be ineffective in brute force equations, in a 
multi-state system the other states not involved in a conflict will 
collectively act to punish the state breaking the rules (eg mass 
slaughter of the rulers of a state tends to upset other aristocrats 
deeply).

Break down of rituals happens when a clear hegemon appears.  Being 
powerful enough to ignore other states "moral-political" force they can 
write their own rules in any given conflict.  This happened with the 
Ch\'in state towards the end of the Warring States period (400-221 BC).
The development of the Legalist school of Philosophy at the time 
encouraged very harsh penalties on those defeated in war.  Both the 
Ch\'in and the Legalists were wiped out by a popular rebellion in the 
reign of the Second Ch\'in Emperor.

Anyway, I think that limited war between Gov1 and Gov2 would be much 
more likely if there were other Gov#s out there.  "Look Gov1 used 
Dino-Killers on Gov2s capital, get him before he gets us!".  If Gov1 
and Gov2 are the main powers then total war is more likely.


Ethics of Warfare:

Modern western war ethics seems to be based on the backlash from the 
extremes of the 30 Years War in Europe (which was an extremely 
unpleasant religious conflict).  The idea of not targeting civilians 
in wars worked for as long as the range of battlefield weapon systems 
was restricted largely to line of sight.  It was not unreasonable for 
civilians to take a picnic lunch to a battle.

Once you get longer range weapons you can no longer determine if their 
are civilians in your target zones.  So you get "collateral damage" no 
matter how hard you try and do it.  Currently this causes a big media 
story and public revulsion.  I would not like to bet a Cr on how views 
on civilian deaths will be like in the future but it seems unlikely 
that mega-deaths will ever be considered acceptable except in rare 
cases (such as ideologically motiviated wars).


Terror Bombing:

I see Terror Bombing of civilians as a weak form of strategic bombing 
(ie when you want to blow up industry but lack the strength, skill or 
technology to do so eg Zeppelin Raids in England in The Great War).

There is a definite moral effect from terror bombing (eg workers 
hiding in subway stations rather than doing a night shift).  Its not a 
decisive weapon by any means but it does affect home front moral and 
production.  

It also causes Governments to do two things.  They will invest a lot 
of resources into protecting the home front (which is the main reason 
why the Germans continued with the Zeppelin raids long after they 
realised Zepps were going out on suicide missions) and they will also 
pour resources into retaliation against the enemy (civilians are more 
likely to stand up to terror bombing if they know that they enemy is 
also suffering).

This is all part of the "jigsaw" by which you can try and overstretch 
your opponents resources.  Strategic bombing didn\'t destroy Germany in 
WWII but it helped (80,000 88mm flak guns defending Cities rather than 
front line Divisions).

So, when you are beseiging a world it is worthwhile to carry out some 
form of bombardment on civilian populations.  If the defender does not 
commit resources to civilian defense then there should be political 
consequences (something which is difficult to implement in an abstract 
game)

I think you can draw a distinction between "terror weapons" and 
"ahniliation weapons".  I have played in a TCS campaign which ended 
with very few survivors because the GM allowed players to deploy bio- 
weapons and dino-killers.  In hindsight some kind of political effect 
in the players state might have reduced the speed with which we 
resorted to rocks and plagues.

Regards
Dillon
