In message
<Pine.OSF.3.91.950106124317.9637E-100000@hubble.sheridanc.on.ca>,
Alvin Plummer writes:

>Hi!
>
>Could anyone tell me the powers that a typical high-tech (TL B+) police 
>officer had in the Imperium?  I\'m thinking not so much about police 
>powers (which of course varies) but about the tools available to him: ie. 
>what new tools does new technology give the police officer?  

Well, let me think of a few things.  The first assumption I will make
is that the attitude of the society towards law enforcement is
something like that of the modern US.  Obviously a police state can
have additional measures in place that are not available to the police
in a society that wouldn\'t approve of, say, small robots that patroll
inside peoples homes listening in on conversations and taking
photographs.

First off, the TL B+ police officer is going to be able to detect much
smaller amounts of foreign substances easily.  For example by TL 15
kilers may be convicted based on the evidence of a single strand of
their DNA found in the (washed) fingernail of their victim.

Collection of physical evidence would be easier.  One advance I\'d
expect to see is a robot that makes extremely high resolution
holograms of the crime scene.  Something with enough resolution to
pick up a human hair and even have some data about it, (i.e. color,
length, basic cross-sectional shape).  This device could probably also
pick up fingerprints.  Obviously this wouldn\'t be
simple, but would be no more difficult than the efforts of todays FBI
crime lab.  This could be done on a lesser scale for less important
cases.  Some imagination would be required to guess at how difficult
this would be at a given TL and what resources the police are willing
to put into it.  Very rarely is a full FBI crime lab style
investigation carried out for a simple purse-snatching.

Data processing should be sufficiently advanced that a computer could
take this hologram and perform the more mechanical aspects of
searching for clues, i.e. matching fingerprints, hairs, etc to each
other and to known databases.  

Probably "chemical" techniques could pick up the residues left in the
air, or that settled on surfaces around the crime scene (dead skin
cells, body oils, etc).  Perhaps by remote spectroscopic techniques.
The hologram robot might be able to do this too.

>And how 
>would PC\'s -- which are currently suffering a \'small legal 
>misunderstanding\' in the local system -- find a way to foil this?  Can 
>they? (I have heard of a TL F robot that can *perfectly* tell if a lie is 
>being used)

Vacc suits when committing a crime?  A good cover story as to why (as
the physical evidence so clearly shows) they had contact with the
victim/crime scene?  A good lawer to get them off on legal tricks?
Forged evidence, "But the court will see that defense exhibit #3 shows
that clearly the defendant was on Aramis when the crime occured."
Obviously a sucessful crime will require even more forethought and
planning.  

>A micro-review of police duties: finding and apprehending criminals
>                                 a reliance of non-lethal use of
>                                       force
>                                 crowd control
>                                 detective equipment
>                                 patrolling the streets/cyberspace/near
space
>                                      /ocean/roads/air-raft lanes
>                                 aid and assisstance

I\'m sure there will be hundreds of developments along these lines.  

eg, from the news of the wierd mailing list:
* At a June open house, officials at the Sandia National
Laboratories demonstrated its latest law enforcement technology,
including strobe lights that make criminals disoriented and
nauseous (but Sandia has not yet perfected eye shields to immunize
police officers from the light), a receiver inside an officer\'s
gun so he can disable it if a criminal steals it, and a gun that
shoots out a goo so sticky (actually developed by a guy named Tom
Goolsby) that it completely immobilizes the target. [Albuquerque
Journal, 6-3-94]

Sadly I can\'t seem to do better than the real world...

>
>Also: which worlds (and governments) would be most likely to equip their 
>   police forces with starships?  

Asteroid worlds, vaccum worlds, worlds with signifigant populations on
other bodies besides the main planet.

>   How would police from Imperial worlds behave
>   outside of their juristicion?  What about extradition treaties?

Depends on the nature of the police, and the planets they are
operating from/on.  The imperium is likely to consider the debate
between two planets over whether planet A "arrested" or "kidnapped" the
citizen of planet B.  

I would imagine extradition treaties were pretty common.

>How would the less ethical police forces operate?  

Truth drugs of unbelievable usefulness.  Use of high technology to
produce falsified evidence.

>The best police?  

I view the qualifier "best" in police work to mean honest, hard
working, dedicated.  These qualities will be largely independant of
TL, but obviously the higher TL police will, all other things equal,
catch more criminals.

>   Religious police?  TL 2 police?  And how would they all interact?
>   What about if a TL 6 bobby meets a TL C space pirate, but doesn\'t 
>   feel the need to die right now - what could he do?  

Set a trap for the pirate (Harry Turtledove did a nice story about
some roman vigiles catching some time travelling bad guys).  Or, just
fill out the paperwork to have him extradited from the TL 15 planet
next door next time he stops in to refuel :-)

> How does officers on vacuum worlds differ from officers on
> waterworlds?

Well, obvioulsy their patrols are gonna be somewhat different as are
the problems they encounter.  But most of the crimes they encounter
will occur in the places where people live, which are likely to be
pretty similar.

> What are the differences between a cop on a pop6, TL A world w/
> tainted atmosphere and a cop who has spent her entire time pursuing TL
> G credit fraud?

About the same as those between a mexico city patrollman, and a IRS
auditor.  Their jobs will have very little in common, aside from the
occasional trip to court.

>Could a low-tech cop even hope to deal with high-tech fraud?  

Certainly, if the people committing the fraud screw up.  i.e. forget
to alter the tax returns, or one of their accomplices fesses up to his
role in the scam.

