    'topic' => ' DOE control of nukes in USA',
    'body' => '>No.
>They don\'t.
>The DOE may control the BUILDING of nukes, but they have NO
>control over the USE of nukes.

        In principle, the DOE has control over production and storage of
all nuclear materials, including weapons. They are sort of like an official
watch-dog group. This was set up under Truman (with a Republican Congress
;-), partly in reaction to Gen. MacAurthurs\' deplorable behavior. In
practice, power is spread throughout the Department of State, DOE, and DOD,
with the DOE more-or-less ont eh short end. I should have been more clear
on this. There was a fair bit of debate on this topic in Washington
recently, and the transfer of weapon control to the DOD from DOE was one
possibility to reduce executive costs (if they had trasferred control, it
was probable that the DOE would have been eliminated entirely).

> The President is the only civilian who controls the USE of nukes.

        Absolutely not true, at least in peace time, anyway. The president
may authorize the use of (strategic) nuclear weapons in an emergency only,
otherwise the consent of Congress is needed. Also note that the presidents
cabinet could - in principle - belay the order, declare the president unfit
for ofiice, and have the VP (now P) cancel the order.

        Also, if, say during the Gulf conflict, Congress got a bug up it\'s
ass and decided to nuke Iraq, and passsed legislating dictating the use of
such force. Assume enough votes were present to override a veto, the pres
would be forced to use the weaons. Congress is a civilian power, last I
checked.

        To be fair, the chances of another MacAurthur - or a president -
using such weapons without congressional approval (and getting away with
it) are much higher than a congressional - or cabinet - override.

>NOTE:  I served in the Navy on two nuclear-capable platforms.  Both carried
>nukes at one time or another.   Neither had DOE
>personnel onboard to control access to the nuclear weapons.
>BOTH had provisions whereby the officers of the ship could use
>the nuclear weapons at their own discretion in certain extraordinary
>circumstances (like the destruction of higher command/control)

        You\'d be surprised how military looking some civies get for some
occupations. Ofcourse exceptions were made for the use of nuclear weapons-
absolute adherence to what I detailed above would have crippled two legs
(subs and land launched ICBM\'s) of the nuclear triad, and hampered the
third, making the "Mutualy Assured Destruction" strategy the "Possibly
Mutualy Assured Destruction" strategy.

>Admittedly, word from Russia is that the KGB DID control the
>release codes for the Soviet nuclear arsenal.  Unfortunately, or
>fortunately, depending on your POV, the USA has no constitutional
>provision for control to be divided that way (the President is
>Commander-in-Chief, and that\'s that.)

        Thank God they did! One only needs to look at Chechen and how the
military is ignoring Yeltson to see the wisdom of that system.

        The prez may be the CiC, but Congress had curtailed such power
considerably (eg, the War Powers Act).

        Michael








