    'body' => 'Michael:

>        In principle, the DOE has control over production and storage of
> all nuclear materials, including weapons.

       Storage and production I can believe.  Not use.  Note that the DOE has
no REAL control of deployment of weapons on the SSBNs...


>> The President is the only civilian who controls the USE of nukes.

>        Absolutely not true, at least in peace time, anyway. The president
>may authorize the use of (strategic) nuclear weapons in an emergency only,
>otherwise the consent of Congress is needed.

     Incorrect.  Congress has only two powers as regards use of the military
:
       1)  they control the budget.  Without congressional approval, it don\'t get
bought or paid for.
        2)  they may declare war.  Note that declare war is NOT synonymous with
"fight war".  Witness Vietnam, Korea, the Gulf War...

     The President is the ONLY civilian in the Chain of Command of the military,
and therefore the ONLY civilian who may give orders to the military.  The President
MAY, at HIS descretion, delegate some of his authority to others.  The "Two Man Rule"
is a good example.  Nukes will not be launched in ordinary circumstances without 
confirmation of a Presidential order by another government official (who may be
a member of Congress, but need not be.  As far as I know, the only requirement  is
that the guy be subject to Senate Confirmation for his post - there may be
others.)
    Note that in an emergency (the USA is under nuclear attack is the only valid one 
O know of), the President may order the use of nukes on his own authority without
confirmation of the order.


> Also note that the presidents
>cabinet could - in principle - belay the order, declare the president unfit
>for ofiice, and have the VP (now P) cancel the order.

      Check your Constitution.  The Cabinet may only declare the President unfit if
the Vice-President agrees.  The Congress may do so also (it\'s called "Impeachment").
Note also that Cabinet approval (or even knowledge) of the order (to use nukes) is 
NOT required.
     Note that if the President is declared incompetent by the VP and Cabinet, then
he may declare himself competent (thus throwing the issue to the Congress).  His
declaration of competence theoretically means that he resumes the powers of
the Presidency immediately, though there are ambiguities in the 25th (?)
Amendment that MAY require that the issue be settled by the Supreme Court
should the Amendment ever be invoked.
     Note also that when the VP becomes the P, he may then give the order in his
own right, again, without the approval of either the Cabinet or the Congress.
     Note also that once a VP has taken over in that fashion, he may only be 
removed by either Act of Congress, or restoration of the President.  He may 
NOT be removed by the Cabinet, since they no longer have a VP to front for
them (and the VP is required for declaration of incompetence).

>        Also, if, say during the Gulf conflict, Congress got a bug up it\'s
>ass and decided to nuke Iraq, and passsed legislating dictating the use of
>such force. Assume enough votes were present to override a veto, the pres
>would be forced to use the weaons. Congress is a civilian power, last I
>checked.

     Congress has no legal authority to specify the force used by our military in
any conflict.  They may exert control only through their power to limit the military
budget (which does not apply in use of existing weapons - only in building new
ones).  Again, read your Constitution...

>        To be fair, the chances of another MacAurthur - or a president -
>using such weapons without congressional approval (and getting away with
>it) are much higher than a congressional - or cabinet - override.

     Actually, the internal military safeguards against misuse of nukes is such
as to prevent "another MacArthur" from doing so.  At least, not without the 
cooperation of several dozen to several hundred other officers NOT under
his direct command.  As to Presidential misuse, the ONLY real safeguard 
currently in place is the "Two Man Rule", and the remote possibility of a 
