    Right!  But *I* actually don\'t believe that most interstellar 
wars are genocidal, even slightly.  I believe in the notion that
"war is an extension of politics by other means".  Which means we
need to decide what the strategic objective of the war is as the
first step.
    Once we know the strategic objective, we can decide whether
war is a useful method to achieve this goal.  It probably isn\'t in
space war.  If it is, then specific methods can then be worked out
to achieve the goal...
    These methods may or may not require genocidal techniques.  I
tend to think not, myself.

    The problem you are seeing is the difficulty of DECISIVE WAR
occurring without genocidal conflict.  I agree that the probability
of a decisive war (like the one we fought in 1941 thru 1945) is
pretty slim given the capabilities in Trav.  However, note that
we were unable to execute any decisive wars during the entire life-
time of the "Evil Empire".  The Gulf War (as decisive as any I\'ve 
read of) only happened because the collapse of the Soviet Union had
passed the point of no return by that time.
    For that matter, note that no wars in history which WERE decisive
were NOT genocidal.  To one degree or another.  There have been few
wars in history that left both sides substantially intact (with only
changes in allegiance affecting the civilian populace) that were also
decisive...
    Note also that wars between equals are seldom decisive.



