> size and tech face each other, or if a large low-tech state attacks
> a small high-tech state.  A question: how much can tech compensate
> for size?  Any ratio\'s, anyone?

    Depends on specific technologies, actually.  Meson weapons, for
instance, upset the balance badly.  If a TL13 civilization developed
meson weapons, and fought a TL15 civilization without meson weapons,
the TL13 civilization will probably win.  In High Guard rules.  In MT
rules, the TL15 civilization will win in spite of the meson weapons.
I don\'t know about TNE.
    But, for generic high tech civilizations, using HG rules, I think
the following equations are pretty good:


    TL      15  14  13  12  11  10   9

        15   1
        14   2   1
        13  10   2   1
        12  1C  50   5   1
        11  1K  5C  20   3   1
        10   *  1K  5C  25   2   1
         9   *   *   *  5C  10   2   1

where (*) = don\'t bother, the lower TL people lose.  Every time.

    A lot depends on the exact ship mix involved.  A well-designed
fighter of a given TL can fight anything short of a battleship two
TLs lower to a draw, AT LEAST!  But those numbers do NOT assume 
fighters...because:

    This does try to take into account jump-capability, which has
nothing to do with combat ability per se.  But Jump affects strategic
mobility in big ways, and is a big force multiplier when looking at
large-scale actions spread across many solar systems...


