Gov2 (tech F, right?) takes Gov1. In a few months (years) what to stop the
Gov1LO from randomly nuking Gov2 cities (i.e terrorism). Hell, a tech7
world could do this. Nothing like a spoilsport :-)

        I think it\'d be better for Gov2 to dominate Gov1 politically, this
means diplomacy, commerce, and, occationaly, a little war or two. For
conflicts I\'m thinking of something like the Franco-Prussian war, or,
perhaps, how The Great Frog handled the Hapsburg Monarchy before FUBARed
his Russian canpaign.

>New Assumption: The navy of Gov1 is about the same size and "weight" as
>the navy of Gov2.  The larger amount of people that Gov1 has is offset by
>their lower tech level (and thus, the smaller per capita amount of TL F
>Dollars sent to the navy).
>
>Since you don\'t have the UWP codes, I only want to know if the above
>assumption *can* be a valid, reasonable one.

        Yes (more or less).

>Question: what are the benefits and problems of a TL F navy in a TL C-F
>civilization?  One thing that immediately comes to mind is those low-tech
>ports: the Gov1 navy will be quite dependent on their naval basis,
>compaired to Gov2.

        Assuming Gov1\'s "low-tech" populations are productive (i.e. not
like the Soviet Union or China), then it may well have an advantage.
Remember, tomorrows wars are fought with the weapons of yesterdays. Gov1
will have a core of top-of-the-line vessels, with plenty of lower tech
vessels providing "bulk" could hold on for quite some time, possibly enough
to take Gov2, or at the very least force a stalemate. I just hope you don\'t
have only one or two Agricultural worlds feeding your high-population
industrial worlds. That could get ugly (for Gov1).

>Associated question: It seems absolutely necessary for Gov1 to siege the
>buffer state first for the sake of all those yummy, high-tech ports.
>What I want to know is how long it would take to annex the buffer state
>assuming warfare, and how long to repair the annexed civilization to it\'s
>previous state: a guesstimate will do, since you all still lack the UWP
>codes.  Assume genocidal warfare is possible, but the idea is conquest,
>not extermination.

        Gunboat diplomacy may be your best solution here- or even better,
make the buffer state a belligerent neutral, in Gov1\'s favor. If there is a
war, now Gov2 needs to take the buffer state to get to you- and you get an
ally, to boot.

>By the way...
>
>If I had kept Gov1\'s navy at TL C, how long would it take for them to
>conquer the TL F buffer state?  Or would the state win (which would occur
>if they destroyed 1/4 of Gov1\'s navy, at a cost of 1/8 or less of the
>buffer state\'s navy.)

        I don\'t know, but even if Gov1 did win, they\'d probably be weakened
enough that they\'d but an easy target for Gov2.

>It seems that all major interstellar wars are at least partially
>genocidal, not necessarily because of the hatred involved, but simply
>because of the kind of defenses and weaponry involved.  Well, as Steve H.
>would say, this isn\'t a parlour game.

        Pretty much the same risk we are now entering- any potential
conflict could result in several of our cities destroyed. If you are saying
the (mythical) gentleman\'s conflict is gone, you\'re right.

>This would make an interstellar war a very high-risk venture, with
>uncertain rewards - up to a point.  Warfare between large and small
>states of equal tech would be rare: the small state will quickly look
>for decent surrender conditions.  Warfare between states of large tech level
>differences (ie TL C, TL E) would also be rare: the lower-tech state is
>well advised to get along with it\'s high-tech neighbour, or face a
>disasterous war.

        The first possibily is a game of Russian Roulette- except the state
with more vessles has more bullets chambered (but again, don\'t forget
spoilsports). The second example was covered above.

>The "uncertain rewards" actually comes in only when states of equal size
>and tech face each other, or if a large low-tech state attacks a small
>high-tech state.  A question: how much can tech compensate for size?  Any
>ratio\'s, anyone?

        The former scenario would likely result in a stalemate, since their
economies would collapse. The latter scenario could vary widely, depending
on the tech discrepency- but when the possibility of one of the states
falling becomes real, it becomes a game of brinksmanship, now and forever.


