Regards this throwing-rock-stuff...

in xboat digest 148, erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca wrote about accelerating 
rocks to high velocities....

Sending it through jump is all very well but accelerating it up to high 
speeds before entry into jump is a bit pointless - the problem is that 
when you exit from jump you will more than likely miss the planet - you 
will be going in excess of the escape velocity of the planet, especially 
if Earth is larger than average (2d6-2, roll of a ten resulting in 8000 
mi diameter).  Most worlds will have a lower escape velocity than Earth.

Result - one new large meteor in an elliptic orbit, and one close call.

The only way around this is to EXTENSIVELY survey the target system prior 
to attack, which an associate of mine did back a few years in a very 
large and somewhat unbalanced campaign set in the Old Expanses sector 
(well thought of Aaron).  Only then can the rock be brought out of jump 
space at the correct place, after some hideous computer calculations and 
last second updates.

