>The only way around this is to EXTENSIVELY survey the target system prior
>to attack...

I beg to differ - to HIT the target planet won\'t be that difficult. The 
information needed is available in any astrogation data program. The 
planets in the target system won\'t shift, so any reasonably accurate data 
set (like those that merchants use for general astrogation) will do just 
fine.

If you are concerned, a small computer, a large radar set (low power) and 
a set of nukes placed about the back surface of the rock will do:

1. Rock comes through, turns of radar.

2. Rock determines location and direction of planet, compares to rocks 
   current vector.

3. If not on target (should be awful close), fire nukes required for 
   appropriate thrust.


BTW, those deep meson sites need to power up, not to mention that a 
series of humans need to (in order):
1. recognize a threat
2. verify that it is a threat.
3. Pass info up command chain
4. Find people of appropriate authority
5. make decision
6. Pass decision down through chain of command
7. load targeting data and fire.

So, a few minutes may be all that is needed - the rock will impact while 
folks are still looking for the planetary defense commander (who may have 
just stepped down the hall for a pseudocoffee as the last act of his/her 
professional career).

				Ted7
