    'index' => 'aa660',
    'body' => 'I\'ve been following the discussions on thrown rocks, tech level 
differences, so here\'s my two-peneth.

Tech Level differences:
Tech level differences of a few points won\'t make that much difference.  
What has far more effect is the quality, motivation, and iginuity of the 
troops.

In Vietnam the US far outclassed the Vietcong technologically, but were 
effectively beeten in the field.  The Vietcong were very motivated, and 
very, very ingenious booby trap makers.  They even came up with a homemade
anti-helicopter mine!

There\'s an old quote (I think from an American general), that goes...
	"If the British were as well equipped as the US, their troops 
	 wouldn\'t be anything like as good as they are now"
The British military doesn\'t have as much access to high tech kit in any 
quantity.  So the emphsis has to be on the skills of the troops.  If the 
US Marines were to take on the Royal Marines, I know where I\'d put my 
money.

In any event taking hostile teritory, is very difficult (if you want 
anything left at the end).  Look at the Russian forces in Chetchenyar, 
though it looks as though they may take the city, it will be rubble, and 
then they have years of fighting guerilla forces in the surrounding 
countryside.

I Played a Striker campagn some years ago.
My opponent had a large Millitia, mainly mechanised infantry, and 
supporting units.

My force was Elite, a tenth of the size.  Mainly on foot or horse (at 
tech-8 !).

Although outnumbered and outgunned, I took the field.

Incidently the horse borne troops were very useful.  They could go 
anywhere that a man on foot can, ie. where vehicles cannot go, at a 
faster speed.  So using hit-and-run tactics, I was able to make several 
attacks, and then evade the opposing troops, who had to go on foot, and 
make a second attack behind the infantry before they could return

Rocks:
I agree that the astrogation data needed to hit a planet is trivial, but 
performing the navigation accuratly enougth is a bit harder, though not 
imposible, military ships will routinely navigate to the standards 
required.

Why do rocks need to go that fast, even at moderate speeds (someone 
quoted 9min warning), by the time the threat has been confirmed, 
permission to fire given, and the firing solution locked, the rock will 
be so close that you wouldn\'t be able to do much.

Nuclear explosions, and meason weapons won\'t shift a rock sideways that 
much.  A warhead detonating on the surface will have most of its force 
expended outward in a hemisphere, the actual component perpendicular to 
the line of flight will be small.  Ditto meason weapons.

The best use of meson weapons is to fragment the rock, then use nuclear 
warheads to vapourise what you can.  The task being to break the rock up 
into small enougth portions to burn up on re-entry, and/or cause minimal 
damage.

Using mesons to cause _interior_ explosions could provide enougth of a 
sideways component to cause fragments to pass _either_side_ of your 
planet.  Very steady nerves needed.

> but anyone know what it\'d take to shatter a small planet?
Probably quite large.
One of Jupiters moons (I forget the name) shows a 
huge fracture, it was split at one point be held together under its own 
gravity.

Why bother spitting a planet anyway?  A good rock will cause large scale 
damage at the impact point.  May introduce enough siesmic energy to 
unlock major faults (san-andreas like ones).  And the lensing effect of 
the planets core, may refocus the siesmic waves from the impact, to a 
point antipodal to it, causing a Major explosion, earthquake etc at this 
point as well.

If you badly hurt a planet, but leave a good portion alive.  Think of all 
the rersources, ships, manpower, supplies,  that have to be diverted to 
it for relief operations.

----
Apologies for the long post, I\'ll try to keep future ones shorter.
