I think it was more a matter of the U.S. fighting a contemporary offensive
war in terrain which heavily favored defensive guerilla tactics.  The U.S.
goal was to defeat the VC.  The VC goal was to hang on until the U.S. got
tired and left.

The British ran into the same problem during the U.S. Revolutionary war.
Marching on roads in perfect formation isn\'t very conductive to survival
when your enemy shoots at you from inside forests.

Note that in terrain which favors contemporary offensive war-making (or
disfavors guerilla tactics depending on how you think of it), i.e. the
Gulf war, the U.S. did spectacularly.

> Nuclear explosions, and meason weapons won\'t shift a rock sideways that
> much.  A warhead detonating on the surface will have most of its force
> expended outward in a hemisphere, the actual component perpendicular to
> the line of flight will be small.  Ditto meason weapons.

The energy transferred by a hemispherical explosion is a bear to calculate,
but the answer and concept turns out to be pretty simple.  Just project the
hemisphere onto a plane (i.e. a circle) and use that as the surface area
the energy flux goes through (all of it perpendicular).  So for a
hemispherical explosion the ratio of useful energy transferred to total
energy generated is the ratio between area of a circle to the area of a
hemisphere is the ratio between pi*r^2 to 2pi*r^2 or 50%.  Obviously you
want this offset 90 degrees from the rock\'s velocity vector to have the
largest perpendicular component.

> The best use of meason weapons is to fragment the rock, then use nuclear
> warheads to vapourise what you can.  The task being to break the rock up
> into small enougth portions to burn up on re-entry, and/or cause minimal
> damage.

Has anyone bothered to calculate how much energy is needed to change a
rock\'s direction?  Find the angle you need to displace the velocity for a
miss, find how much energy you need to cause that change.  In fact...

My back of the envelope calculation says the energy E you\'ll need to divert
by angle theta a mass M moving at you at velocity V is:

  E = 1/2 * M * ( V * tan(theta) )^2

This ignores the gravity of your planet, but should be good enough for an
order of magnitude calculation.  I didn\'t save any of the previous messages
on this topic.  What were some of the masses and velocities being *ahem*
thrown around? :-)  And while we\'re at it, what was the conversion between
Joules and Megatons of TNT?

> > but anyone know what it\'d take to shatter a small planet?
> Probably quite large.
> One of Jupiters moons (I forget the name) shows a huge fracture, it was
> split at one point be held together under its own gravity.

I think it was Minerva around Saturn.  It\'s got a huge impact crater that
makes it look like a large round spaceship.
