    'date' => 'Sun, 15 Jan 1995 18:54:39 +0000 (GMT)',
    'body' => 'In Digest 150, merrick @ rt66.com says something along the line of  
\'...this sort of planetary (velocity/location) data is available in 
standard astrogation packages....\'

well Im just remembering the quote from CT and I think MT that reads 
loosly \'...ships usually jump at low relative velocities...as when they 
exit from jump they cannot determine what their _vector_ will be with 
respect to the target planet...\'

however if you want to get too picky just realise that every star system 
is moving relative to every other and you find that exiting from jump 
into a (for example) transient system (one moving through the galaxy at 
high speed) would result in a high velocity with respect to the target 
system.  So...may solve problem of rock velocity!!

Also - using mid flight guidance of the rock is dubious if going at 
\'high\' velocities...somthing to do with E(k)=1/2*m*v^2.  I know nukes 
have a high energy output, but v^2 is a large number when talking in 
km/sec.  Tak the quoted (elsewhere) number of 1500km/sec...1500,000^2 is 
2.25 * 10^6, multiplied by the mass in kilos.  If your rock is going in the 
wrong direction then you need quite a few megatons worth of \'thrust\', 
most of which are wasted blowing large holes in the rock.  Another 
drawback...if you need multiple corrections, then you may destroy your 
second or further charges with the first if it is in the order of 5 
megatons, and if you need a hybrid direction change that requires 
charges to go off in different locations then unless your rock has been 
prestressed; the collection of charges will shatter it.

Also....if you are sending it through jump, remember the fuel 
requirement!!  You may not find a suitably sized rock that can withstand 
multiple 10-megaton charges going off on it within 1 jump of the 
target...

Several jumps later, fuel shuttles to ferry fuel to either the 
rock or it\'s tug, the time involved for the operation, and the 
magnitude of the operation.  All the enemy needs is a few stealth ships with 
gravity/densitometer sensors patrolling all nearby systems for enemy 
activity.  They can\'t help but notice the one LARGE, previously uncharted, 
\'high\' gravity object moving around a gas giant or in system.  

Hey presto a single (very) large object..no sizeable escorts..enemy sends in 
strike force (albeit suicide or so they think - a \'ship\' of that size 
must be well armed...).  When they find an unarmed rock with a tug 
dedicated to jump, powerplant and manoevre engines they proceed to 
destroy all sensors and signs of electronics on rock and tug.  (Also no 
shipyard activity to represent a ship of that magnitude being built by 
enemy...)

If you put a battle escort with it then you might as well write \'HERE WE 
ARE\' all over your naval communiques...because the first thing I would do 
is riddle my (potentially) hostile neighbours spy service and navy with 
agents - read what The Marches did to \'the enemy\' in the closing stages 
of a very entertaining campaign run by <azazel@dudael.equinox.gen.nz>.


