    'from' => 'Ralph Ferneyhough ralph@psygnosis.co.uk',
    'body' => '
Surely this whole problem boils down to the fact that the DM should employ
his/her powers to ensure that the universe remains consistent. S/he should
come
up with a reason why everyone doesn\'t do this all the time.

This is a similar problem to one from my early days of DM-ing traveller. The
players devised a tactic to jump into a system to a known point at exactly
the
right velocity that they would slow down just in time for planetfall. This
was
to save in travel time to planet from jump point. Also useful for the fastest
speed strike attacks. Soooo.....

In with two solutions:

1) The \'Elite\' solution. Each jump will not put you in the same place. It is
impossible to place yourself in a specific position in space at the
destination. I decided that a good explanation of this would be that jump
space
is a link between points of equal gravitational potential. Thus, if a ship
jumps at the normal 100 diameters out from the planet, it will arrive 100
diameters out from the destination BUT not at a specific point on the sphere
that that point would describe. This then makes jumping dangerous at very
high
speeds because you may end up heading towards the planet unable to stop. I
would allow players to roll to get roughly the right orientation to the
planet
on arrival, given that the jump route is likely to be a straight line in
normal
space, and the ship will fall out of jump space at the first intersection
with
the 100 diameter sphere it is aiming for. Just disallow the accuracy needed
to
drop high speed rocks on a collision course.

This also has the interesting side effect that jumps cannot be made into
empty
sectors with no gravitational potential (thus explaining why there are no
artificial refuelling points in place across the rift).

2) The uncertainty principle error. Simply rule that the faster a ship is
travelling as it enters warp, the more inaccurate will be its exit at the
other
end. (perhaps an extension of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle - it is
impossible to define both velocity and position accurately at the same time).
Thus, if a ship enters jump at 0 velocity relative to the gravitational
source,
it can accurately place itself where it likes at the destination at 0
relative
velicity. However a fast moving ship has a large positional error. Given that
entering warp takes some time (I tend to use about one minute), a good rule
of
thumb would be the positional error could be the amount of distance it could
move in that time. e.g. a ship at 1/10th speed of light (3000 km s-1) could
be
out by 60*3000= 180,000 km. Easily enough to miss a planet....

Adjust this formula to enable your planet to have a chance. I would rule that
it would be impossible to use a planetoid as a weapon without at least a
couple
of hours sensor warning.

Ralph.

