Yes!  I was always told it was bad form for a ref to drop
a gigantic invisible rock on the players, but as long as 
there\'s a plausible excuse.... :) :)

>triggered my query was a dim memory of an adventure in JTAS
>which had the players ferrying nukes onto a plunging
>asteroid via a scout/courier.

An Amber Zone I remember well was _A Dagger at Efate_.  Somebody
(ok, probably the Zhodani) sends an empty Broadsword merc cruiser
on a collision course with Efate, and the primary Imperial troop
concentration there, during the Siege of Efate in the 5FW.  The
players have to stop the Imperial Vice-Marshal\'s troops from 
getting their supply depot smushed by a multi-megaton impact.

(Blowing it out of the sky wasn\'t an early option for the space
defenses; they were a bit tied up, and it wasn\'t clear that the
ship wasn\'t still an Imperial paramilitary vessel coming in on
a normal approach with its\' com system fried.)

The players got eight hours to stop it, which for Efate\'s 3.2
light-second 100 diameter limit meant the _Dagger_ had a vector
of 2; that\'s 120,000 km/h!

One problem with the high-speed rock idea depends on how accurate
in time jump exit is.  The less accuracy you have, the harder it
is to hit a target directly.  Something moving slower can home in
on the target and jink around while using less fuel.

