    'body' => '
George Herbert <gherbert@crl.com> wrote:

>Hans correctly points out that there\'s a (up to days) variance in arrival
>time with a Jump.  This is true, but it\'s also an inconsistency in the
>game rules.  Space combat operations are described as having simultaneous
>arrival of attacking forces.  The planets movements over several days will
>change time of travel to surface when arriving by a whole lot... like
>days, also.

This was noticed in MT.  DGP claimed that ships could spend longer 
periods of time prior to jump computing their jump co-ordinates, and
synchronize their data in order to make a more accurate jump.  
So then fleets would spend a fair amount of time right before jump
synchronizing their jump exit co-ordinates, but single ships jumping
with less accuracy could jump faster.

This would be a great place for some use of Navigation skill.  A
good navigator might be able to get you a better solution faster,
say with a vector pointed at the world or a shorter period of
time in jumpspace.  Great for drama, too: the crack navigators
of the Imperial fleet compute a near-perfect jump exit; tens of
ships step out of jump over a period of fifteen minutes, catching
the beseiging Zhodani fleet off their guard.  :)

Mitchell Schwartz <Ted7@world.std.com> wrote:

>count sez:
>>well Im just remembering the quote from CT and I think MT that reads
>>loosly \'...ships usually jump at low relative velocities...as when they
>>exit from jump they cannot determine what their _vector_ will be with
>>respect to the target planet...\'

Not true in MT also, I believe.  However, it took a good navigator to
properly compute a jump breakout that would have the vector pointing
in a useful direction.  I suppose the Ref\'s supplement (with all
the TL charts) would be the place to look for those rules.

>need a decent safety factor to ensure you are outside the 100 diameter 
>limit for anywhere during those three days!  Otherwise, you may re-enter
>normal space deep within the gravity well - or not re-enter at all. 

I don\'t know where or if it explicitly says this in the rules, but
I think Marc Miller said in his jumpspace JTAS article that ships
are automatically forced out of jumpspace at the 100 diameter limit
if they attempt to jump into a gravity well.  (Jump exit might be a
bit rough, however, so you still might want a safety factor.)

In fact, now that I think about it, I vaguely recall something about
a 30000 km positional uncertainty in jump exit from Marc Miller\'s
article.  That may be enough to discourage the fast-big-rock type
of attack but not the slow-maneuverable-rock-or-ship attack, and
wouldn\'t affect space combat much, at least for MegaTraveller and
Battle Rider (which is a good fleet combat system, and might even
be useable with High Guard ships with some slight modifications.)

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
'
