    'body' => 'I don\'t know why anyone would think it\'s hard to target a world with a
high speed rock dropped when you emerge from jump.  Normal navigation
requires you to know where the planet is and where it\'s going so you can
rendezvous and land.  Rock-bombing is at worst equally difficult, you just
have to arrive at 100 diam with a vector pointed through the world.

>>>>>	I\'ve remained silent through all of this, but this brings me to life.

	The 100 diameter limit is from *all* massive bodies in the system.  
	The 100 diameters from the star may be farther out than 100 times the 
	planets diameter.  Check the position of nearby gas-giants.  Also
	remember that this is the *minimum* distance.  A ship exiting jump is
	going to be further out depending on how well they did their 
	navigation.  Orentation of the emerging weapon will be more or less
	random, so an low Vo would be optimal for the attacker.  Even at
	six g, the defenders will have several hours to respond.

	Any system defence is going to be in depth, so detection and 
	classification with immediate action won\'t be a problem.  If 
	neighboring hostiles are fielding KE weapons, then immediate action
	plans can be assumed.

	SDBs with atomic and possibly anti-matter weapons would be at the
	outer reaches of the system.  Spinal mounts burried on major worlds
	could be brought to bare immediatly.

	Add to that the possibility of capital ships being in system, and
	defending chunks of rock that could be used to collide with the 
	inbound ship give the system an almost certain chance of foiling
	such attacks.

	You don\'t need to completely blow away the inbound chunk of rock.
	Damage the propulsion and guidance system and it will miss.  A good
	hard EMP, a few sensor damaging nukes, and a couple of engineering
	hits and it\'s all over.
