    'body' => 'I said (as part of a much bigger conversation):
>>It gets even worse at TL F+, when the "Rock" activates a 
>>Black Globe as soon as it emerges from Jumpspace and 
>>becomes *invisible* until it\'s way too close to do anything 
>>about it.

MSAMUELS @ VAXC.STEVENS-TECH.EDU who did not give his name replied:
>I doubt a society with an irreplacible artifact would waste
>it on a one shot weapon that could still miss.  Better to put
>that on your vulnerable carriers and save thousnads of lives
>a countless BCr.

1)  Yes they would.  This whole thread is based upon the interpretation
that aiming the things is possible.  One can interpret the jump and
navigation rules that way.  You choose not to.  That\'s your 
prerogative, but it invalidates NOT ONE WORD of what the rest of us
have been talking about.  Choosing the interpretation that you choose
simply makes it impossible and then there\'s no point in your joining
in this conversation.

2)  Read!  TL F+ can BUILD black globe generators.  They
are NOT irreplaceable artifacts.  Expensive?  Sure, but so
what.  Presumably the existence of the enemy on the target
planet is MORE EXPENSIVE or one wouldn\'t be bothering.

3)  Knocking out the Sensors etc. on a relativistic object?

We don\'t think so.  You\'d be lucky if your shots got within
100 asteroid diameters of the thing.  Relativistic speeds FUCK
fire control solutions.  Besides, by the time you got to that
point, it probably wouldn\'t need those sensors anymore anyway.

4)  Making course corrections?

We don\'t think so.  You do it once.  And only once.  You already
know not only exactly where the planet is, but EXACTLY where it\'s
going to be when you get there.  All that is PUBLIC INFORMATION.
Orbital data DOES get recorded, you know.  By the time they see
it coming, and get into firing range, it needs no course corrections.
Unless the defenders get *lucky*, or have their whole fleet protecting
one planet.

So, you have to physically deflect or destroy it.  What would you
do that with?

Big Meson Guns?  Steve is right.  Given a decent sized asteroid, it
simply CANNOT be done with spinal mounts.  When you start talking about
TERAWATTS of discharge energy for a spinal mount you\'re talking about:
 1) something nobody can afford to build and POWER.
 2) something nobody can afford to build a ship around.
 3) something so big that as a deep site, aiming it would be a
 major project.  Torque and flexure, you know...

So what else could you use?

Throw your SDBs at it if you want to.  Scoff, scoff...  I have yet
to see a flea deflect an elephant.  Even an armed flea.

Nukes?  Well, if you think you can hit a moving target travelling 
at relativistic speeds, which target happens to be *invisible*,
you can feel free to try.  But even if the thing doesn\'t have
a black globe, if you can hit it with nukes, then the automated
anti missile defenses on the incoming asteroid can shoot down your
nukes.  This isn\'t Mickey Mouse.  The attacker has made a huge
investment in this attack, for a reason that seems uniquely important
to it.  This thing is going to have defenses of it\'s own.

Now, let\'s say you do deflect it.  What have you done?  Saved the
population physically, but not emotionally.  They have just had the
living s**t scared out of them.  Some portion will be galvanized,
the rest will get scared and depressed.

Then another asteroid emerges the following week.

If I play this right, I could eliminate your government\'s stomach for
war by cleverly allowing you to deflect my asteroids...

