> reason Jump changed vectors.)

Off the top of my head, the peculiar motion of the sun is something like 16.5
km/s relative to the local standard of rest.  This value would obviously change
from star to star, but is somewhat typical.  It is also only about 1 BL hex per
turn.

If you wanted to add relative motion (just for kicks) in a simple way, just
make one up, or roll 1d6 for direction of motion (fixed to some imperial
standard) on the subsector map, then 1d6-2 for its magnitude in BL hexes/turn.
Write the value in the hex on the subsector map (ie: V32  would be direction 3
mag. 2, then add them together for a given jump (it\'ll at least tell you how
much delta v you need to zero your relative velocity (we\'ll disregard the
motion of nearby (jump range) stars around the galactic center since this value
would be similar for any near stars (around 250km/s if I remember right).

BTW, a rogue star that is moving at right angles to the plane, or is
travelling through the galaxy faster than its neighbors might explain otherwise interesting
systems that don\'t have xboat routes, or whatever (velocity matching the poopoo
system isn\'t worth the trouble for that crappy wine the produce as their only
valuable product:)

