    'topic' => 'Jumpspace ( Falling Rocks)',
    'body' => 'Even more on stopping falling rocks:

I looked at the old JTAS #24 "Jumpspace" article by Marc Miller 
last night, and this is what I got out of it:

 * Spatial jump exit is accurate to about one in ten billion; 
   but the accuracy can fall by a factor of ten if the drive is
   badly tuned or the computer solution is inaccurate.  (Don\'t
   use a parallelized Pentium Model/1 bis!)  This means that for 
   a one parsec  jump, the jump exit should occur within a 
   sphere with a 3000 km radius,  30000 km if the drive\'s a bit
   off.  Longer jumps have less accurate exits.

 * Ships retain the relative vector they possessed before jump.
   Commercial ships usually jump at zero vector to try to reduce
   to risk of high speed collision with something on jump exit.
   Military ships and couriers tend to jump at high vector, and
   decelerate all the way to the destination planet.

 * If a ship attempts to jump into a gravity field, it will fall
   out of jump at the "edge of the gravity field"; he probably
   means the point at which the field starts to seriously cause
   problems with the jump solution, since there isn\'t an "edge"
   to the gravity field.

 * Ships take 168 +/- 16.8 hours to complete a jump.  (This, we
   knew.)  The time is not readily controllable by the navigator.
   Exit time is usually predictable by the computer.  (This is
   modified/clarified slightly by the later decision that the 
   jump exit can be synchronized to make fleet movement 
   possible.) 
   
 * The 100 diameter limit is a rule of thumb; it includes a
   safety limit; the real safe jump point is based on the grav
   field of nearby objects. 

We also know that co-ordinates can be pre-recorded, based on some
comments in CT and the K\'kree module about self-erasing one use
jump navigation tapes for lunatic, cheap ships with no navigator.
Would you trust one? 

The 100 diameter line for a size one world is just over half a
light-second; for a size ten world it is almost five and a half
light-seconds.

Now, about stopping a rock.  Are you using CT or MT rules?  CT
combat ranges tend to be shorter than MT (or TNE).  CT merchants
can detect only to half a light-second, and CT warships can
detect to about two light-seconds.  In the CT Amber Zone 
_A Dagger at Efate_, the ground station somehow can see to the
3.2 light-second jump exit point, but this could have been made
possible by a "constellation" of detector satellites orbiting
Efate, or good ground-based detectors.

If you\'re using MT combat rules, you can probably see the ship
or rock coming, but if it\'s at nine-tenths of a light-second or
further out from you, it\'s at Extreme range for defensive fire.  


  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
   
