Hmmm.  Tricky.  Probably by putting active sensors on it, for it\'s
own defensive systems, and using them.  That\'s reasonable enough.
Sure, the ROCK is big enough to hit easily, but a 1m^2 AEMS sensor
antenna is NOT.  So this rock has several of them, to direct it\'s
antimissile defenses (lasers and nuclear dampers).

Once this are lit, the ROCK is obvious.

Then I make sure that something just happens to get through.  Since
this is a reasonably BIG ROCK, the target world is probably using
BFN\'s (Big Fucking Nukes), like 500 Megatons, say, concealed in clouds
of detonation laser missiles (hoping to take out the AEMS sensors,
but mostly to act as decoys so the big mothers can score direct hits.)
Maybe, with the LAST ROCK, I have to let couple 500 MT nukes get 
through just a little too late.  You know, so some big chunks actually
fall on the planet.  Not enough to trash the world, but maybe a city 
or two.  Then morale is shot, but the BULK of everything valuable on
the world is relatively intact.

Now, I believe that you can put up an adequate defense against these
things - in some places.  But I can bring my rocks to some other
place.  It\'s like a shell game.  I try to find the places where the
defenses are [barely] inadequate, you try to find the places where
I\'m building my planetbusters, while attempting to defeat my fleets
at the same time.  At the places where the defences are more than
adequate, I throw rocks two (or more) at a time, from different
directions.  Your public recalls your fleet.  ("Get back here and
protect the civilians!").  Etc, etc.

BTW, this is also a decent way to deal with pesky SDB\'s hiding in
the atmosphere of a Gas Giant.  

Just drop some big rocks into it, fast.  The resulting storms ought
to do the trick.  Of course, with THOSE rocks, I don\'t light up the
active sensors.  I WANT these things to come raining down 
unannounced.  Of course, *I* won\'t be able to refuel my own ships
there for awhile, but hey, you can\'t have everything.


>..and some of our rock throwers ("Plummera Rocks?"  Hey, the entire
>net is rocking now!) have brought up a very interesting question:
>exactly *WHY* isn\'t rock throwing standard military procedure in 
>wars outside of the famous \'Imperial Laws of War\' (ie the Fifth 
>Frontier War, the Rim War)? Especially in systems with asteroid 
>belts?

Good question.  Probably because they *want* what\'s on the world
reasonably intact.  It generally doesn\'t work to destroy what you\'re
looking to capture.  Look at Gorozny.  When/If the Russians finally
capture it, what good will it be to them?  It won\'t even provide
shelter for their own troops against the Winter weather.

Actually trashing an entire world with thrown rocks would probably
be limited to cases of necessity, genocidal hatred, desperation,
or my plan of letting the enemy seem to be just lucky enough
(this time) to avert disaster (but who knows about next time).

1)  There\'s no value to that world.  Nobody lives there, it has
S**t for soil and Piss for oceans, you can\'t breathe the air.  But
there\'s a BFMB (Big F**king Military Base (tm)) there, for whatever
reason.  <Necessity>

Drop a rock on it.

2)  You are good.  They are evil.  They mean to destroy you utterly,
you must do it to them first.  <Genocidal Hatred>

Drop rocks on them.

3)  They are winning.  They have captured some of our most important
(most resource rich, high pop, high tech) worlds.  We\'ve got to
bring this war to an immediate halt *and* get our worlds given back
to us.  <Desperation>

Drop rocks on them.

4)  My own case, as described above.  I won\'t retype it here.

Drop rocks ALMOST on them.

Now, why isn\'t case 4 being done all the time.  Well, it may actually
be too difficult or too expensive.  Building BIG throwaway jump, and
thrust engines, not to mention powerplants and disposable defensive
systems...  Big Buckaroos.  And it would take *TIME*.  Maybe too much
time.  So, maybe it would be something, as Alvin suggests, that 
really is *Alien*.  I dunno.


Enough for now, my claws are tired.

----
Derek Smith - Lotus Development Corporation - Release Engineering

