    'topic' => 'Rocks and Jumps',
    'body' => '(1) ROCK THROWING
(2) 100 DIAMETER JUMPS

(1)
Alvin asks:
>exactly *WHY* isn\'t rock throwing standard military procedure in wars
outside of the famous \'Imperial Laws of War\' (ie the Fifth Frontier War, the
Rim War)? Especially in systems with asteroid belts?

And Derek points out:
>Well, it may actually be too difficult or too expensive.  Building BIG
throwaway jump, and thrust engines, not to mention powerplants and
disposable defensive systems...  Big Buckaroos.  And it would take *TIME*.

My own quick thoughts:
BIG ROCKS
One-off splat-them philosophy is required here with, as Derek says, no
desire to have anything worthwhile left on the world afterward. Such rocks
are hugley expensive and take a long time to \'construct\' and can only be
used for their one purpose, i.e. planet destruction.
SMALL ROCKS
Unless you\'re talking about a few tons in mass drivers, small rocks (with
drives, defences, scanners and/or black globes) just don\'t make sense
because they\'re using up huge amounts of budget for a \'wipe em out\'
philosophy which few planets have. It is far more useful to use the money on
a standard space navy which gives you the ability to handle any space
incident anywhere (anti-piracy, siege, counter-insurgency, covert
operations, starship battles, etc.) while providing lots of shiny ships for
fly-bys, etc. and for IMPRESSING the enemy. This last point is very
important - if the opponent sees you have a big shiny navy, he\'ll be less
likely to hassle you (i.e gunboat diplomacy). If you\'ve got a small navy but
you\'re working on a top secret huge rock somewhere, the enemy will probably
think you\'re weak and attack you before you launch the rock anyway. Rocks of
ANY size just can\'t do what a Navy does, so they will only be used in
one-off ventures between planets that really really REALLY hate each other\'s
guts AND that have a mad government (it doesn\'t matter how much the populace
hate each other due to real events or govt. propaganda, it\'s the govts. in
the end which have to decide they\'re going to obliterate the enemy\'s planet,
while being aware that the enemy might have a similar rock just waiting to
be auto-launched if their planet is attacked... back to Mutually Assured
Destruction again...).

Later, Derek asks:
Hostes alienigeni me abduxerunt.  Qui annus est?

To which I reply:
Don\'t worry, you have merely experienced a mild dream trauma causing
paranoia and the sensation of being abducted by strange creatures. In a few
minutes your brain will reboot and come back on line (after memory parity
check) and you will realise that you are in the year 5538AD. Some of your
peripherals may need resetting.

(2)
Just to repeat things I\'ve said before, I allow players in my game to jump
anywhere they like. Jumping in to within 100 diameters (of any high gravity
body - sun, gas giant or planet) in my game is likely to PREVENT exit from
jump - the ship effectively get\'s bounced because it can\'t form a full jump
field to break through into normal space. This is what causes misjumps - the
ship \'bounces\' off on a random vector for a random time. Now that\'s far more
scary than knowing that if you jump too close to the gravity well you\'ll
always appear at 100 diameters! When jumping out, again the players can
activate the jump drive on the planet surface if they so wish. However, the
jump field will be so distorted that it may take bits of planet with it (and
leave bits of ship behind), and the launch into jump space will be so
violent that the ship is very unlikely to assume the desired vector but more
likely to head off in a random direction.
Using this system, players can always resort to desperate measures, but
knowing that there\'s a REAL risk!

Cmdr Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
PITS Team motto: "We are never out-yomped."
* Nothing I say or do in any way reflects the views of my very kind
  and generous employers who have no interest in intermittent periods
  of jogging and walking with a heavy military backpack on. *

