    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 156',
    'body' => '>From: MSAMUELS@VAXC.STEVENS-TECH.EDU
>	Choosing the interpretation that you choose
>	simply makes it impossible and then there\'s
>	no point in your joining
>	in this conversation.

Now, now children, play nicely :-)
Seriously though, can we not get into rules interpretation/lawering.
I only have CT rules, all these references to MT and TNE, are (to me 
anyway) completely irrelavent.

----
> Howdy,
> 	I just dusted off my old FFW and we decided we\'d start a game up to
> be played over the next few weeks.  I was reading the rules again, when I
> remembered that all the BatRons for the Imperium (Zhos, too) were unstream-
> lined.  But the old CT fighting ships shows all the BBs as having fuel 
> scoops, so what\'s the deal?
>
> Has there ever been a net.fix of FFW to make it consistant with the rest 
> of CT?
Use the High Guard idea of Partial streamlining.  Enougth streamlining to 
be able to use fuel scoops in Gas Giants, but not enougth for 
atmosphereic work proper.
----
Jumping, Vectors, and Mass limits.
The way I work things, is that your KE vector is preserved through jumps, 
(relative to whatever referance frame you like).  To obtain a useful 
vector at your destination, manoeuvre in the starting system so that 
your vector relative to your jump exit point is correct, then jump.  If 
all goes well you arrive rougthly where you want to be, when you want to 
be, with the in-system vector you want.
(see the JoTAS #24 notes on jump errors).

As for 
>>>Unless you want to create a set of rules varying the 
>>>ability to get into jump space based on (what? size, weight? speed? 
total 
>>>energy?) 

Since My jumpdrives are rated for the _volume_ of material they project 
over the jump distance, theres no scope there.  (but as we probably all 
have a slightly different interpretation of how jump works).

But the 10-diameter/100-diameter limits, are levels of gravitational 
potential energy, or curvature of space time if you like.  Can you say 
that an object with a high kienetic energy similarly curves space time, 
(based on ideas of high-energy density producing curvature).

Mark Miller is the JoTAS article suggests that _Energy_ is the variable 
is making jumps (time is constant).  So energy density effects could be 
invoked.

But, this is _science_fiction_ after all.  Pick a behaviour, and as long 
as you are consistant, and not unbalencing the game to far, why worry too 
much about the details of the physics.  
After all, if I did know how jump space worked, I\'d be building the damm 
drives!!!
----

One Idea I\'m thinking of trying,
Mix methods of FTL travel in the Traveller universe.  Is jump the only 
way to go from star-to-star.
How about Warp drive.  Wormholes etc...

Would different activities find different drives more advantagous?

Would Scouts use Warp, because you can still see the real-space,
	spoting any interesting uncharted phenomina.

Navy use jump, you can\'t track a starship through jump.

etc...

Alun

