    'body' => 'MSAMUELS@VAXC.STEVENS-TECH.EDU:

>	The 100 diameter limit is from *all* massive bodies in the system.  
>	The 100 diameters from the star may be farther out than 100 times the 
>	planets diameter.  Check the position of nearby gas-giants.  Also
>	remember that this is the *minimum* distance.  A ship exiting jump is
>	going to be further out depending on how well they did their 
>	navigation.  Orentation of the emerging weapon will be more or less
>	random, so an low Vo would be optimal for the attacker.  Even at
>	six g, the defenders will have several hours to respond.

    Well, no.  The target planet MAY be within 100 diameters of the sun.
Not terribly likely if the planet is habitable, but possible.  Note that
our sun\'s 100 diameter limit is only 139,200,000 Km from the center of
the system - which places us about 10,000,000 Km outside the limit.
    As to gas giants - if the gas giant is REALLY huge (twice Jupiter\'s
diameter), and is in orbit 0 or 1, then a planet in orbit 1 or 0 MIGHT
be within the 100 diamter limit of the GG.  Or the planet could orbit
a gas giant (as Amondiage did in my last TCS game), which would protect
the planet somewhat.  At least, it would stretch transit time from the
100 diameter limit by a factor of ten or thereabouts...

    As to the sensibility of emerging at low velocity:

    Well, no.  If you can\'t calculate well enough to make sure you are
pointing at the target (unlikely IMHO, but you can interpret the rules
that way if you like), then send more than one rock...;-)

    But, the real reason I dropped back into this discussion was your next
comment:

>	Any system defence is going to be in depth, so detection and 
>	classification with immediate action won\'t be a problem.  If 
>	neighboring hostiles are fielding KE weapons, then immediate action
>	plans can be assumed.

    Well, no.  This is an idiotic idea given Trav technology.  In FF&S
you can get sensors that can detect things at 8 light seconds.  In the
earlier forms of the game, you will be lucky to detect things at 2
light seconds.  Note that 100 diameters from Terra is about 4 light
seconds.
    This limit in detection capability is crucial to the nature of
"system defenses".  That is, a ship in orbit around Jupiter would not
be capable of detecting the emergence of a ship near Mars.  It wouldn\'t
even be able to detect the emergence of a ship at Jupiter\'s 100 diameter
limit, frankly.
    A ship in orbit around Jupiter would take about 60 hours to reach
Terra at 6-Gs.
    These, coupled with the ability of a ship to jump in at the 100
diameter limit of any body in the system (plus or minus a few thousand 
(NOT million) Km) that is not itself within the 100 diameter limit of
another body, imply strongly that "defense in depth" is a ludicrous
concept in Trav.
    Any ship stationed at a gas giant is going to be irrelevant to a 
battle occurring at or near the main world for several days.  Ditto any
ship stationed at a rock that might be used as a weapon.  Gas giant
refueling is a stupid idea fostered by GDW many years ago - it made
little sense then, less now.  A Fleet intent on attacking your main
world will appear, not at a gas giant, but at the 100 diameter limit
of the main world.  And all the GG squadrons you have scattered around
the system will have front row seats to watch your main world be
smashed (if that is the attacker\'s intent), since they certainly won\'t
be in position to interfere.
    As to "immediate action" against KE weapons:
    What might those be?  If the rock is heading straight toward your
planet, it\'ll be in range of planetary defenses only the last 300,000
Km (for older versions of Trav, about 2,400,000 Km for TNE).  If the 
rock is moving in at 1500 Km/s (slow for older versions, fast for TNE),
then you only get three minutes to respond.  Since it is heading for
your planet, nothing less than destruction or redirection will 
suffice.
    And destruction is only going to be possible with LARGE nukes.
REALLY LARGE NUKES.  Which you may well have.  But you won\'t be
launching them till you detect the target, which won\'t be till about
five minutes before impact.  At 12G\'s, assuming ZERO reaction time
for local defense forces (not too likely), you get your first chance
to hit the rock at about 5000Km above atmosphere.  If the first misses,
you have no second shot.  If it hits, then, in addition to any pieces
of the rock still coming down, your entire civilization gets a lesson
in EMP generated by a large nuke popped off near the planet.

    And, of course, all my comments only apply to slow moving rocks.
Push the rock to 0.9c (any good battleship can do it in older versions
of Trav), and all bets are off.  You get first detection 0.2 seconds
before impact.  Which was about the amount of time required for you
to read the phrase "before impact" back there.  Bye, bye...


>	SDBs with atomic and possibly anti-matter weapons would be at the
>	outer reaches of the system.  Spinal mounts burried on major worlds
>	could be brought to bare immediatly.

    WHy would they be there?  *I* certainly won\'t be there attacking 
them.  I\'ll attack your main world where they are helpless to 
intervene (being days away at max accel).  And your spinal mounts
on major worlds are NOT mutually supporting, and CANNOT be brought
to bear (not "bare") immediately.  Consider the speed of traverse
of the main turrets of the New Jersey if you doubt me.  Sure, we\'ll
be able to do better in the future.  But guns big enough to matter
will be vastly larger than the New Jersey\'s piddly little guns...


