There were a few problems with the travel tables for those old
infinite delta-vee maneuver drives.  They forgot relativity.  For
example, the distance to the Oort Cloud was 50000 AU, which is the
same as 288.5 light-days.  However, according to the travel tables,
a 6G ship could get there in 258.8 days -- outpacing light itself.
Fast ships. :)  A MegaT SDB couldn\'t get there without jump shuttles
anyway, since I doubt they had more than a month or so of power.

To give folks a comparison between CT and TNE, in CT a 6G SDB could
cover the 900 million km from Earth to Saturn in 2.8 days.  A TNE
112 G-turn SDB, if it planned to stop at Saturn, could manage about
a quarter of that speed.  It would then need to refuel on arrival.
A ship micro-jumping from Earth to Saturn could beat the TNE SDB
there.

I think the CT ship hits a few percent of light-speed at the turnover
point.  So the CT quick-figure equations probably start to break down
due to relativistic effects beyond a billion kilometers of travel or
so.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
 
