 Over on the Cherryhlist we were discussing what sort of weapons her ships 
would use. They often cruise around the place at sort of relativistic 
velocities. Anyway an interesting thought that came up was along these
lines...
 The main advantage of something traveling at relativistic velocities is the 
relative speed with respect to its target. However this is also the biggest 
weakness. You just have to get something in the way. It needent be moving
very 
vast, the incoming bogey has enough speed.
 So, first you have your lag-time between when you detect the bogey and how 
much it has traveled since the wavefront you are receiving. This is extended
by 
the time to intercept of your munitions. The bogey\'s maneuverability
determines 
the maximum tangental change to its course it can make over that course of 
time. This produces a circle (or sphere if you assume it can 
accelerate/decelerate) of all the possible locations the bogey can be at time

of intercept.
 Given this information you direct your missile spread to evenly cover this 
area. (A shotgun sort of effect.) The amound of matter density you can put in

that area directly determines the amount of damage inflicted. It *must* go 
through that region. Human or tactical logic can narrow the constraints of 
maneuverability (e.g. an asteroid probably won\'t maneuver much and if a
planet 
is the likely target then that limits it further) and reduce the size of the 
sphere.
 Taking this to the logical extreme one person suggested that you could use 
*water* isntead of pellets. Thus achieving a perfectly even spread. It is
also 
more "merchant-friendly" as once past the designated target it becomes thin 
enough to be of no further damage.
 I must admit I never sat down and did the maths on this one. I don\'t know
what 
rate of fire you would have to achieve to get a meaningfull amount of mass
into 
the area. Perhaps you might think of doing it for this particular situation, 
i.e. knocking out the sensors on an inbound relativistic object.

Someone else:
