    'body' => 'MSAMUELS@VAXC.STEVENS-TECH.EDU:


> >>>>>	I realy don\'t fully understand the use of fighters and carriers
>	in MT combat.  Wouldn\'t fighters exposed to the withering fire
>	of capital ships be quickly dispatched?  Even if their weaponry
>	is comperable wouldn\'t the casualty rate of flight officers be
>	prohibitive.  It seems like a terrible waste of very expensive 
>	and highly trained personell who would be much better employed
>	in larger ships rather than squandered in small unsurvivable ships.

    The first thing that must be understood about fighters in CT/MT
combat is that what is labelled "fighter" has nothing in common with
what is labelled "fighter" in 20th century usage.  The "fighter" of
CT/MT has more in common with the PT boat than with a modern
"fighter".
    At relatively low TLs (say, 9-12), the Trav "fighter" corresponds
quite well with a modern PHM.  It has weaponry which is quite lethal
(nuclear missiles), and is (expendably) cheap.  It is also virtually
immune to fire from similar vessels (other "fighters").  Coupled with
the relative inability of large ships to harm these "fighters" (at
TL12, where the factor-9 missile bay appears, said bay weapon hits a
well-designed TL-12 fighter on 10+.  MT produces similar results),
it is easily seen that a large number of "fighters" (but a similar
VALUE of fighters) can overwhelm any large warship.
    To wit:
        500,000T warship, costing around MCr400,000 vs. 4000 fighters,
costing around MCr400,000.
    Warship has 500 missile-9 bays.  Spinal mount is ignored, since
only one can be fitted.  Hit number for the warship is 10+ (2D6).
    One hit by the warship will destroy one fighter.  Actually, given
the CT/MT rules as written, one hit will disable a fighter MOST of the
time.  But, for our purposes, we assume that a hit kills a fighter.
    "Fighters" are armed with missile-2 batteries.  Hit number for
the "fighters" is also 10+.
    One hit by a fighter will destroy one weapon, or 1% of the warship\'s
fuel supply.  
    The warship\'s armour stops about 1/12th the fighters\' hits.

    Round 1:  Warship gets 83 hits, destroys 83 fighters.
              Fighters get 611 hits, knocking out all fuel tanks on
              warship, and disabling all weapons.
    Round 2:  Warship surrenders.  Fighter pilots go home to get drunk.
              Warship crew goes to p.o.w. camp for the duration.

    Admittedly, this ignores the question of the carriers\' cost.  But
the fighters may be (should be) operating as system defense forces,
which need no carrier.  If carriers are included, the number of fighters
in the above example goes down to about 2000.  The fight then lasts two
rounds (or even three!), and costs a few more casualties...

     At higher TLs, the "fighter" corresponds better to a WW2 PT boat -
it can\'t really fight a first line warship ALONE (or even in herds), but
can assist in the destruction of warships previously damaged by your
major warships.
    In addition, "fighters" are quite capable of dealing out enormous
damage to battle-tenders and support ships (the ones without
agility-6) at ANY TL.

    As to expensive personnel - this is not usually a problem.  Any
Empire of decent size has an essentially unlimited supply of qualified
people.  Training costs money, but so does replacing 500,000T
battleships and THEIR personnel....

                                        ----Steve

