    'topic' => 'The few and the proud.',
    'body' => '
In a current _Time_ article, (or was it Newsweek?), it was argued that 
the era of mass warfare (from the French revolutionary war to Korea) was 
fading away, increasing the power of "Warrior societies" like the current 
fighters in Chesnya (sp!), where 2 million Chasnyans can hope to defend 
their land from 200 million Russian\'s.

Assuming this hold\'s true to the 57th century (a large assumption, but 
possible, given Traveller technology), what would be the place of warrior 
societies be in the Third Imperium?  I *know* that they exist, for in 
Challange 55 we have a good description of a TL F Imperial Warrior 
caste, the Answerin. (who, incidentally, have been Imperial Soldiers 
since the time of the First Imperium!)  Can anyone out there 
generate/recall other Imperial warrior castes?  

And if the Imperial Marines have warrior castes, the Imperial Navy should 
be stuffed with societies which exist only for the sake of the navy! 
(...and may well be the ruling caste: how many Noble lines have links to the 
Navy?)  

---- Aside ----

Incidentally, the Third Imperium seem\'s to treat their warriors much 
better than we do: in both Canada and the U.S., the military is looked 
down upon, and is dominated by folks of working/lower-middle class orgins.
In the Answerin article, the Answerin live on a pretty good world with 
high technology (Vland: 0431 B584A85-F).  

Another aside: the Answerin tend not to favour nobility: relatively few 
characters of B+ social standing are nobles.  

---- Back to the subject ----

What *is* the purpose of mass warfare in Imperial policy: that is, 
outside of inter-Imperial wars between member states/worlds/systems?
And does mass warfare in serious wars ever actually mean "every an a 
soldier?"  I doubt it: a serious, 57th century war seems to demand the 
funneling of massive resources into the military, but only a limited 
increase of the actual number of battlefield soldiers: the existance of 
"citizen-soldiers" would be a petty nuciance on the battlefield, esp. if 
they arn\'t very motivated boys who have no passion for the fighting, 
fear getting killed (I mean, less tolerant of the lethal risks 
usually needed to get anything done on the battlefield), and haven\'t been 
raised as warriors since birth. (and, incidentally, lack a massive tech 
edge over their opponents.)



----
Alvin Plummer
"Preserve what we created, Norris, and remember what we stood for."
                               - Strephon, 179-1126


Reply to: alvin.plummer@SHERIDANC.ON.CA

----

