    'from' => 'Brian Hoover hoover@cougar.multiline.com',
    'topic' => 'Socialogical effects of ET contact.',
    'body' => 'Hi. I was reading a novel by Dean Koontz called \'Strangers\' where
(without giving too much away, hopefully) the characters find that
their memories of extraterrestrial contact have been repressed. In the
following excerpt one character discusses why:

\'Yes\', Stefan said, \'but there\'s a difference how they react to
fictional contact and how they might react to the reality. At least
that\'s the opinion o mnay scientists, especially the soft
sciences like sociology and psychology. And anthropologists 
tell us that when an advanced culture interacts with one less 
advanced, the less advanced culture suffers a loss of confidence
in -- and often a complete colapse of -- its traditions, institutions.
The primitive culture loses respect for its religeons and systems
of government. Its sexual practices, social values, and family
structures deteriorate. Look at what happened to the Eskimos
following their encounter with Western civilization: soaring
alchoholism, family-destroying generational conflict, a high
rate of suicide... It\'s not that Western civilization is dangerous
or evil. It isn\'t. But out culture was far more sophisticated and
richly textured than the Eskimo culture, and contact led to a
serious loss of self esteem among the Eskimos that they\'ve 
never regainwed and never will.\'

             [Dean Koontz, \'Strangers\', Headling 1986]

I must say that I agree with this. I can\'t vouch for Western civilizations
influence on Eskimo culture, but it has effected Australian Aboriginal
culture this way: alchoholism, suicide, loss of esteem, the whole bit.

Has any of this been discussed in the Traveller context? Imperial contact
through surveys, wars and other such things would surely have a profound
and long lasting, if not permanent, effect on intergalactic culture, be
they humaniti (how did the Zhodani and Vilani affect the Solomani?)
or alien (Hiver, Kkree, Aslan). 

Brian (longtime TML/xboat lurker)
-- 
----
Brian Hoover, Perth Australia. hoover@cougar.multiline.com.au Multiline BBS
