    'body' => '
While thinking about the nobility, I remembered that they have their own 
court system and code of law.  I immediately wondered exactly how would 
Imperial intellectual\'s justify a two-tier code of justice to the masses.

One of the things that come to mind is the fact that every noble - up to 
a point - represent\'s the Emperor himself.  Since the laws exist at the 
pleasure of the Emperor + nobility, it cannot be expected that the 
Nobility can be judged in the same courts as the masses.

A different approach is the assumption that local law bound\'s locals, not 
Nobility, who represent an interstellar community.  The laws that do 
bound the nobles tend to be much fewer and less culturaly influenced (ie. 
local social + religious mores) than the law for the masses, but (I 
expect) would have much more strigent penalities if broken.

Yet another approach is to assume that Noble law is indeed a law 
influenced by social + religious mores, but these mores are specific to 
Noble society.  In effect, the nobles have their own local law, but this 
law is tied up to people, not systems. 

To the extent that noble law is praticed, it seems that nobles are ruled 
by a mix of Noble law, Imperial law ("the law of space"), and local 
conditions on the local Noblity.  For example, Archduke Dulinor wore 
black as Dlan\'s religion insisted that he should as a unbeliever.  A 
marque somewhere (I lack the reference, but it does exist) must be 
blinded when he assends the throne.  Without a doubt, there are other 
situations where the noble must be of Solomani decent (true for the 
Irridium Throne itself for over 600 years), do a yearly religious ritual, 
mate for life, or somesuch.

However, some laws seem to apply to all nobles: ie. the restriction on 
anagathics (a law or a custom?), a preference for natural-born families 
(Norris refered to his female clone with a euphimism, implying that he 
was breaking the norm), a specific style of succession ("Noble-style 
succession"), etc.

Finally, while some nobles may rule with brutality on their own fiefs, 
they seem to avoid this outside of their territory, implying that 
Imperial law -- a no-frills legal code, similar to the Ten Commandments 
(with piracy thrown in!) -- applies to the nobility also.  This also 
included Cleon\'s order that no living sentient may be murdered, by 
nobility or by anyone else.

---- Aside ----

I wouldn\'t be surprised if a massive section of the Noble Code revolves 
around protocol, diplomatic + trade powers, etc.  I tend to envision the 
nobility as "the great interface layer" between the Imperial government + 
megacorps and the local subjects. 

Does anyone here care to guess of the Noble Code is different for High, 
Honour and Administrative nobles?  I tend to doubt it: even barons are 
permitted into the Imperial Moot, after all.

---- And on a related subject ----

Exactly what kind of judging powers does a noble have?  Certainly, they 
are the judicary regarding interstellar matters, or any matters outside 
of a formally recognized member-world (ie uninhabited worlds).
 

----
Alvin Plummer
