    'from' => 'Mark Clark markc@brahms.udel.edu',
    'topic' => 'Sociological effects of ET contact.',
    'body' => 'Along these lines, I have seen it argued that what is happening to
isloated cultures like the Eskimos or Australian Aboriginals is a form of
both biological and cultural Darwinism.  That is to say, individuals in
our society have adapted to the technology around us over time.  Gin, for
example, was very destructive when it first became widely available in the
18th century.  Humans were used to mild intoxicating beverages like beer
and wine, and those individuals who could not handle it were bred out of
the society or were subject to social controls.  The introduction of gin
and other hard liquor caused massive social problems, as folks drank
themselves to death and such.  The result - temperance movements and
social controls on drinking to limit the damage caused by this new threat
to the society.  In the same way, we are currently trying to learn to deal
with crack and other drugs. 

The point is, we have had a long time to adapt to these changes.  
Isolated cultures coming into contact with mainstream civilization go 
through these problems all at once, not a little at a time.  As a result, 
society is under great preasure, and often collapses.  This situation is 
agravated by disease exposure, as we discussed earlier in this group.

What does this mean for Traveller?  Well, I would expect that over the 
few thousand years of Imperial civilization, humans will have invented 
vices and social problems we can\'t even imagine - addictive telesex, 
biomoney, virtual religion, you name it.  This might explain some of the 
Red and Amber zones, and might also explain why the Solomani defeated the 
First Imperium - the Vilani were all so busy posting to the Internet they 
forgot to defend their empire. :-)
