    'index' => 'aa748',
    'topic' => 'Imperial Culture',
    'body' => 'MILITARY SOCIETIES
>Incidentally, the Third Imperium seems to treat their warriors much
>better than we do: in both Canada and the U.S., the military is looked
>down upon, and is dominated by folks of working/lower-middle class orgins.
>In the Answerin article, the Answerin live on a pretty good world with
>high technology (Vland: 0431 B584A85-F).

I think there are a number of responses that can be made to such an
assertion. First of all, I do not believe the military of today is looked
upon with as much disdain today as it was twenty years ago. A good deal of
the difference is that there is greater selectivity and quality in
personnel today. While there are a few factions in society who scorn the
military, I have not observed anything close to universal disdain or
contmpt for the military. As for the many personnel having lower/working
class origins. . .the militry has traditionally been a place where men (and
now women) can further themselves in society. The military provides a good
amount of training, basic needs (food, clothing, shelter) and discipline
that can help someone who is properly motivated to rise above their
station.

This ignores, of course, the implicit assumption that an organization made
up of the lower class is inherently disdained. . . :)

>Another aside: the Answerin tend not to favour nobility: relatively few
>characters of B+ social standing are nobles.

There\'s little need for it. While not familiar with the warrior caste you
speak of, I would offer that in a military culture such as theirs, noble
rank would be superfluous. Military rank handles any need for hierarchical
social divisions.

WAR IN THE EMPIRE
>What *is* the purpose of mass warfare in Imperial policy: that is,
>outside of inter-Imperial wars between member states/worlds/systems?

Umm, do you mean "intra-Imperial wars between member states"? Your original
statement refers to wars between the member states of different Empires,
but I take it you mean to serious warfare between member states within the
Imperium.

In the latter case, I rather imagine that "serious warfare" occurs when
there is a significant contest that the Imperium is unwilling to resolve -
which would be rare. While the Imperium seems to allow combat, I doubt it
would allow major conflicts to last too long, lest they interfere with the
functioning of the Imperium itself. See Dune for an example - two Houses
duke it out over personal matters, but when interstellar trade is
threatened, the Empire comes in (and gets its ass kicked anyway :)

>"citizen-soldiers" would be a petty nuciance on the battlefield, esp. if
>they arn\'t very motivated boys who have no passion for the fighting,

Yeah, but in "serious warfare" as I read it, those citizens *would* be very
motivated - as motivated as the French were in WW2, or possibly the
Israelis in the various wars they\'ve fought in the past half-century.

CULTURAL INFLUENCES
>I must say that I agree with this. I can\'t vouch for Western civilizations
>influence on Eskimo culture, but it has effected Australian Aboriginal
>culture this way: alchoholism, suicide, loss of esteem, the whole bit.

Ahem.

I also cannot relate much about the Eskimo encounters with western
civilation. Before going further, I will say that I have never found
aboriginal cultures to have any moral superiority over the Great White
Invaders, as some would call the Euopean explorers. However, I think that
the above asserion cannot go unchallenged, given my experience with Native
Americans. It is very difficult to maintain your self-esteem when your
people are forcefully moved across a time zone or two, told that they must
stay in one place rather than roam freely (as they have done before) and
have your children taken into schools of the foreigner and disciplined for
daring to speak their native tongue. When you grow up on a reservation and
see nothing but drunken indians living in tin shacks in the middle of the
desert, suicide becomes quite an attractive option. The reasons they have
poor self-esteem are the same as poor people all through time.

If you ask me, many of the ills that plague such societies come from
restrictions placed upon them by the more advanced culture, not
overwhelming awe at their power. A more responsible approach is to teach
the less developed culture and work with them; historically this has rarely
been done.

THE NOBILITY
>While thinking about the nobility, I remembered that they have their own
>court system and code of law.  I immediately wondered exactly how would
>Imperial intellectual\'s justify a two-tier code of justice to the masses.

I would begin by looking at historical examples. Of course, in Europe a
great deal of the support came from the Church, and there doesn\'t seem to
be a vast Imperial Church. . .though there could be. At any rate, the
general thought was that there was a divene pyramid, starting with God and
going down throught the layers of liege lords all the way down to the
peasants.

>pleasure of the Emperor + nobility, it cannot be expected that the
>Nobility can be judged in the same courts as the masses.

Ah. . .sort of like Congress :)

>A different approach is the assumption that local law bound\'s locals, not
>Nobility, who represent an interstellar community.  The laws that do

Ah. . .I would like to assume that some nobles are culturally tied to the
worlds they rule. In fact, I would argue that the ruler\'s beliefs will
influence the culture\'s.

>Yet another approach is to assume that Noble law is indeed a law
>influenced by social + religious mores, but these mores are specific to
>Noble society.  In effect, the nobles have their own local law, but this
>law is tied up to people, not systems.

Here you get into grey territory. While there may not be an Imperial
Church, there must be some Imperium-wide social system for ruling these
matters.

>To the extent that noble law is praticed, it seems that nobles are ruled
>by a mix of Noble law, Imperial law ("the law of space"), and local

"Noble Law"? I\'m not that familiar with Traveller; is there such a thing?
Of course they are rules by Imperial law. As for local law. . .don\'t they
make the local laws?

>conditions on the local Noblity.  For example, Archduke Dulinor wore
>black as Dlan\'s religion insisted that he should as a unbeliever.  A

That is absolutely silly. Someone who doesn\'t believe in the faith
following one of the faith\'s rules? That\'s like a pagan feeling bad for
being excommunicated. The only reason for it would be if Dlan was a
powerful or troublesome state that Dulinor needed to pacify - and even then
he\'d probably throw on the tie-dye when the trouble was over.

>However, some laws seem to apply to all nobles: ie. the restriction on
>anagathics (a law or a custom?), a preference for natural-born families

Again, what you need is a system that enforces the same traditions across
all space. Historically this was the Church. In the Imperium, it\'s
something else, something not defined.Laws won\'t do it. It has to be
