    'body' => 'Alvin Plummera was writing about... 
>In a current _Time_ article, (or was it Newsweek?), it was argued that 
>the era of mass warfare (from the French revolutionary war to Korea) was 
>fading away...

Would anyone class the Iran/Iraq war, the Gulf war, etc. as not \'mass
warfare\'?
Okay, so we didn\'t get as far as conscription, but had (for example) the
Gulf war dragged on a while, it might have happened.

>...what would be the place of warrior societies be in the Third Imperium?

I don\'t know about whole societies but my games certainly involve a goodly
number of mercenary groups. I feel GDW must have felt this way too - you
only have to look at the amount of Mercenary-orientated data presented in
the original CT books and supplements.

>And does mass warfare in serious wars ever actually mean "every [m]an a 
>soldier?"  I doubt it... [explains why raw recruits are a pain on a high
tech
>battlefield

I don\'t think raw recruits would ever reach a high tech battlefield - as
pointed out, they just wouldn\'t have the experience to handle the
battledress and fusion guns! However, a large number could be conscripted
into the other (50%+) of the army, i.e. support services, medical
facilities, drivers, military police, etc. and those that did get into
uniform and were given guns would be posted to garrisons (to free the
trained troops needed at the front line), etc. So there is a place for the
conscript which doesn\'t involve the words "cannon fodder".
:-)

Brian Hoover then mentions the sychological/social effects of a low tech
society meeting a higher tech one.

Hmmm... can\'t see that being an easy one to make into a game. Could be a
very important factor for TNE though, given all the re-discovery of planets
going on with the RCES [apologies for mentioning TNE on this list!] :-)

Alvin Plummer then went on to discuss:

>While thinking about the nobility, I remembered that they have their own 
>court system and code of law.  I immediately wondered exactly how would 
>Imperial intellectual\'s justify a two-tier code of justice to the masses.

Imperial intellectuals don\'t have to justify a danged thing. Just as the UK
judicial system doesn\'t have to justify the fact that innocent passersby can
be (effectively) tortured into giving confessions and be locked away for
life for alleged terrorist activities whereas the excessively rich can
double deal and swindle, be caught, be locked away for a few hours, plead
the beginnings of Alzheimer\'s, be let out, go back to court and be awarded
huge damages because someone on the prosecution didn\'t dot an i somewhere.
The system already exists - if you\'ve got money or power, you get one
justice system, if you haven\'t, you\'re stuffed (sounds remarkably like our
\'National\' [ha ha ha] Health Service as well)... argh! gulp gulp (sound of
two pink pills being swallowed) "Calm down now Mr. Lilly, you know the
doctor said not to start talking about politics..."

AND FINALLY, to Keith Thoms...
Congratulations on putting some adventure into the Rocks discussion. 

Given the restricted nature of these rock throwing thingies as discussed in
many previous mailings...

