    Well, no.  Jump is accurate to within a few thousand Km, according 
to articles on the subject published by GDW.  I have never seen any 
reason for ships to be within that range of each other anyway, so the
minor error so introduced can be ignored.
    Why wouldn\'t fleets want to emerge with a low velocity?  As I 
pointed out above, it will only take an hour and a half to reach
bombardment range of your planet starting from zero velocity...
    Also, you missed my point somewhat.  Given that I choose to
emerge from jump-space somewhere within 1000 (not 100) diameters of
yuour planet, then it is likely (unless I am stupid, which I am not)
that I will avoid popping out near your GG\'s.  In which case, I will
be far enough away that the squadrons there will never get involved 
in the battle.
    Consider.  If I *REALLY* want your gas giant (for whatever insane
reason), I jump in with a fleet to attack your homeworld.  Starting 
from 1000 diameters out ot give you a good detection chance, my decoys
(destroyers without EMM, and suchlike) race toward your homeworld.
Your gas giant squadron gives chase.  About two hours before our
forces meet, my fleet jumps away.  Your gas giant squadron is no
longer protecting your gas giant, so my second fleet assumes control
by default.
    If your GG squadron was NOT lured away, then the decoys proceed 
to bombard your homeworld (even a scout can carry a lot of nuclear
weapons, and these things would be DESIGNED to carry a lot of
weapons.
    Either way, your gas giant squadron has done nothing useful.
    Consider also that even in the conventional Trav picture, your
GG squadron has to be comparable to the attacking force to do any-
thing worthwhile.  This solar system has four gas giants to defend.
If you leave one open, then I use that one.  If you don\'t, then you
have to spread your fleet into at least five unsupporting elements
to defend them all (plus your world).  Getting five:one odds is
pretty easy if your fleet is broken up into five pieces, and mine
isn\'t...;-)



