    'year' => 1995,
    'index' => 'aa760',
    'body' => 'Just read an interesting article in Soldier of Fortune about a 
sound-based system for locating snipers.  The system uses four sound 
sensors in a array linked to a computer.  The sensors detect the sound of 
a shot, transmit the info to the computer, which uses the differential in 
times to generate a vector to the target.  One version of the system also 
links a camera on a fast response pointer to the computer, so a picture 
of the sniper can be automatically taken.  Plans are to eventually link a 
weapons system to the sensor for anti-sniper use.  These sytems are being 
field tested by both the American and British armies.  At present, the 
system is limited to locating supersonic projectiles (used by most sniper 
rifles) - work is continueing to adapt the system to trnassonic and 
subsonic rounds.

The application of this technology and the reason for military interest 
is obvious - with the rise in the use of military units as peacekeepers, 
the need to deal with lone gunmen increases.

Anyway, this sounds like just the sort of system troops would like to 
have - sort of like counter-battery radar on a small scale.  I think it 
would be standard equipment for tech 9+ units, especially those involved 
in dirty little wars.

The other thing that struck me about this is how it generates a role for 
laser rifles (which have no sound signature) - interesting how they 
appear at tech level 8 and 9.


