    'body' => '
Alvin Plummer <uunet!SHERIDANC.ON.CA!plummera> writes:

> In a current _Time_ article, (or was it Newsweek?), it was argued that 
> the era of mass warfare (from the French revolutionary war to Korea) was 
> fading away, increasing the power of "Warrior societies" like the current 
> fighters in Chesnya (sp!), where 2 million Chasnyans can hope to defend 
> their land from 200 million Russian\'s.

Read it, as well as a rebuttal (which I don\'t think was in the same forum)
that called it so much bunkum, for several reasons:
     a) selective use of terminology. One could argue that modern military
         organizations -- which rely on high levels of individual training, 
         initiative, and specialized equipement -- represent a
         "warrior society/caste" far more so than do forces composed
         largely of civilian militias, such as in Chechinya, or Chiapas, or
         (raising flame-sheilds) the Viet Cong.

     b) such sweeping generalizations have a history of being self-
         congratulatory and premature.  Witness Francis Futuyama\'s
         "end of history." This self-servingness brings up:

     c) it sounds suspiciously like a trial-balloon rationale for raising
         and not cutting the military budget.  How do we counter these
          countless small warrior societies? By throwing more money at the 
          Pentagon and defense contractors!  

> Assuming this hold\'s true to the 57th century (a large assumption, but 
> possible, given Traveller technology), what would be the place of warrior 
> societies be in the Third Imperium?  I *know* that they exist, for in 
> Challange 55 we have a good description of a TL F Imperial Warrior 
> caste, the Answerin. (who, incidentally, have been Imperial Soldiers 
> since the time of the First Imperium!)  Can anyone out there 
> generate/recall other Imperial warrior castes?  

How \'bout the whole mercenary subculture.  Traveller mercs are
respected professional fighters, not a scum-of-the-earth collection
that was either drummed out of or couldn\'t hack it in real
respectable militaries.

Or are you talking about a "from birth" Spartan-type military
culture, which act as a prime recruiting ground for the Imperial
military?  That, I can\'t recall any specific examples.

> And if the Imperial Marines have warrior castes, the Imperial Navy should 
> be stuffed wit societies which exist only for the sake of the navy! 
> (...and may well be the ruling caste: how many Noble lines have links to
the 
> Navy?)  

I can envision a tapped-out belt which had a lot of belters and their
families who had to go into new lines of work.  Being top-notch 
fighting crews might be one of them.

> better than we do: in both Canada and the U.S., the military is looked 
> down upon, and is dominated by folks of working/lower-middle class orgins.

This is a can-o-worms statement, and I can even think of some things
to support it (and not the usual ones either), but by and large I think
this is off-base, at least in most of the US.

> What *is* the purpose of mass warfare in Imperial policy: that is, 
> outside of inter-Imperial wars between member states/worlds/systems?

I take it this referrs to the Rebellion?  Otherwise, there is no
intra-Imperial
warfare between member systems/quasi-states -- that\'s the whole point
of the Imperium and Imperial forces will quash this pronto.

> And does mass warfare in serious wars ever actually mean "every man a 
> soldier?"  I doubt it: a serious, 57th century war seems to demand the 
> funneling of massive resources into the military, but only a limited 
> increase of the actual number of battlefield soldiers: the existance of 
> "citizen-soldiers" would be a petty nuciance on the battlefield, esp. if 
> they arn\'t very motivated boys who have no passion for the fighting, 
> fear getting killed (I mean, less tolerant of the lethal risks 
> usually needed to get anything done on the battlefield), and haven\'t been 
> raised as warriors since birth. (and, incidentally, lack a massive tech 
> edge over their opponents.)

Depends on the situation. They don\'t neccessarily have to join a stand-up
fight with the top-notch troops.  There\'s always garrison duty, mopping up,
assorted grunge jobs to do to free the elite troopers for where they are 
needed most.

Locals can also resist occupation by acting as snipers, saboteurs, intel 
sources, thinking bad thoughts to give the Zho mindrippers headaches,
etc.


John Bogan
