happen to have ships.  Sort of like the dark ages, when the
ratio of space to force was so low that armies could only fight
each other by chance or mutual agreement.

	2)  Early warning is more or less irrelevant, depending on
geometry and TL.

		a)  The best scout ship that can be built has a Jump
capability defined by TL.
		b)  The warships I build are likewise jump-limited
by TL.
		c)  time spent in jump is more or less constant, 
irrelevant of technology.

	If you are the same TL I am, then my "fastest" warships are
every bit as fast as your "fastest" scouts.  This means that if I
send my Fleet out, your scouts will not arrive at your home
ahead of my fleets.
	BUT, if you are using J-6 scouts, and I am using J-4
warships, then your scouts will arrive first IF AND ONLY IF the
distance from my start to my target is NOT seven or eight
parsecs.  If it IS seven or eight parsecs, then my J-4 ships
will take two weeks to arrive, as will your J-6 couriers.
	Other numbers apply depending on the exact jump capabilities
of my fleet and yours, of course.
	Consider the implications of this.  It\'s important.

	3)  A fleet cannot defend any world of a system it is not in.

		a)  First warning of an attack on a system other than the
one your fleet is in will come no less than one week AFTER an
attack begins.
		b)  Minimum response time for fleet movements is one
week.

	Therefore, there is a minimum two week time period between
an attack and the arrival of reinforcements from another star
system.
	Given that attack is the stronger form of battle (as per
old Soviet Doctrine) because I can concentrate any force I
deem necessary at the point of attack, and you must defend
ALL points (since you won\'t know I am even moving until too
late (see #2 above), much less where I am moving to), I can
overwhelm any system that is not also a major fleet base (with
fleet present).  The presence of your fleet only one parsec away
is as irrelevant as if it were five parsecs away.  Or
non-existant.


	4)  Scouting will only serve to tell you where an enemy is, 
or where he is not, at any given moment.  It will not allow
you to tell where he is going when you see him.  Unlike the
modern world, where a sighting of an enemy force frequently
includes his direction of motion, direction is indeterminate
in a Jump-dominated movement system.  The only restrictions
on where I will jump are determined by the presence of
deep gravity wells near me (for instance, jumping from Earth\'s
100 diameter limit places almost half the sky off-limits due
to the Sun\'s 100 diameter limit (I\'d like to run a TCS game
including this, if I could figure out how to do it without
bogging things down too much).  But all the rest of the sky
is available to me.
	In fact, given my (personal) predilection toward deep-
space points, even that limit is pretty meaningless, unless
I am in a hurry to get somewhere and so am not willing to
take the extra week to decieve you...


	These (and other) considerations shape the very nature of 
combat in Trav.  In much the same way, radar\'s ability to "see"
things below the visual horizon shapes modern naval warfare.

	BTW, noticing as I did your Harpoon analogies, may I 
suggest something that might give you a vague feel for Trav
space combat (using Harpoon, with modifications)?
	Try this sometime:

		1)  Allow ALL units (ships, planes, missiles) to move as
if they were F-15s.  This simulates the big difference between
space ships and surface ships/planes/etc - that size is largely
irrelevant to maneuverability - a 6G Tigress is as fast as a 
6G fighter...
		2)  Allow the aggressor to place his units on the board
at any point he chooses, as long as the distance from your 
nearest unit is no less than 1 nm.
		Allow him to place any or all of his units on the map
in any turn(s) of his choice.
		3)  In the turn of placement, allow the aggressor first
shot with any guns (not missiles).
	
	This is not exactly Trav, but will give you a fair feel for
the DIFFERENCES between Trav and "modern" warfare....

                                         ----Steve

PS.  DO you have a name, and is it secret? ;-)

