In xboat 164, Steve, replying to MSAMUELS@VAXC.STEVENS-TECH.EDU about ROCKS,
made a few points to which I\'d like to add my 2 penni\'th (ancient coinage
used by Solomani): (NB: I won\'t even approach comments from xboat 165 since
people seem to be getting quite unnecessarily hot under the collar - reminds
me of a certain "technocracy" debate not that long back).

>Which means that at 1.029x10^8 light seconds, you have to roll
>3+ on 2D6 - 1,234,800,000.  Good luck...
Hmmm... not even my weighted dice could do this one. Sounds like the rules
need fixing rather than regarding them as \'law\'.

>    Travel time from Jupiter at 6Gs (average distance): 63.34 hours.
>    This is how long your GG squadron will be out of the battle.
etc.

Most analyses of the SDB/GG situation seem to assume a GG at Jupiter and the
defended planet at Earth. Personally, having used both Scouts (CT Book 6)
and the World Builder\'s Handbook, a substantial number of my mainworlds
orbit GG, rather than being millions of miles from each other. In such
cases, SDBs in the GG make perfect sense... not that this precludes my
worlds from having substantial fleets elsewhere in the system, particularly
at orbital naval bases, etc. Although CT, etc. only mark Imperial Naval
bases (in the world UWP), most high tech worlds will have their own
facilities - possibly on a nearby moon, etc.
Such proximity (GG to planet) makes GG refuelling far more common as well -
I know my players physically recoil from the idea of *paying* for their
fuel! Given that on-world refuelling is severely limited due to Imperial
ecological considerations (in my game, at least, they don\'t want hundreds of
ships fusion-driving (or whatever) their way down to any old planetary sea
or lake just to pick up some cheap fuel, meanwhile burning up a few
near-extinct life-forms, etc.)

>You _are_ aware that planetoids move, right?  It\'sa usually called
>"orbit".  So they won\'t stay in the positions you put them in.
etc.

Well, there are certain points (can\'t recall, is it Trojan?) at which things
won\'t move much relative to your planet. Alternatively, if you\'ve put the
planetoid in space with a manouevre drive (as required to move it into the
way of the incoming projectile) then surely it can use said drive to
maintain position relative to the planet. Given a sufficient size spherical
distribution of these planetoids (either immobile or rotating like, say GPS
satellites), then you could take the warning time and the distance between
planetoids, calculate the maximum spacing for which a planetoid can be
propelled into the projectile\'s path, and hence how many planetoids you need
up there. They\'d be obvious to everyone because you\'d have to have them
beaconed etc to warn off commercial traffic, but such a protective sphere
*might* solve the problem (assuming the sphere starts far enough out from
the planet that impacting the projectile would cause both it and the
planetoid to bounce away from the planet (pool-ball-physics).

>    There is perhaps such an argument.  Not likely, or it would have
>been mentioned SOMEWHERE in SOME iteration of the rules.  I personally
>believe that GDW never considered that possibility, mostly because
>they never actually calculated how long these trips actually take...

Let\'s face it, no rules system is ever perfect (except perhaps fantasy rules
where the gamesmaster can say "Because I say so, and because the Gods here
want it to work that way."

>Either way, your gas giant squadron has done nothing useful.

I guess it depends what you put in your GG squadron? CT seemed to be
exclusively few-hundred ton ships (hence SDBs were a formidable craft) until
Tril Cred Squad, et al. and MT\'s Fighting Ships. Perhaps it would be more
reasonable to picture a dreadnought using the GG as cover? Perhaps (as in my
worlds) the majority of ship battles are piracy, etc. involving smaller
commercial ships where a SDB (perhaps upgraded or upsized) can still act as
a good threat. My players are never going to own dreadnoughts so I don\'t
worry too greatly about such factors.

>You\'re still insisting that the rock can\'t hit the planet without
>extensive corrections, but that your rocks can hit my rock without
>extensive corrections.

That might be true if the projectile is at a fraction of c and coming in
from jump at several mill\' km out, whereas the spherical defence system I
mentioned earlier just has to .
Anyway, why worry about jumping and then readjusting? Why not stutterwarp
the projectile rock then you *can* make adjustments as you near the target
system, without dropping out of jump?

>WHich leaves them only 12,000,000,000 Km from my entry point
>180 degrees away from pluto in it\'s orbit.  Or 8,500,000,000 Km
etc.

Sensors would need to be closer than Pluto, etc. but if sensibly placed,
might have a goodly chance of detecting a huge body (such as the rock)
coming out of jump (assuming that exit from jump causes quite an energy
burst) - even if the rock has EMM, etc. to keep it \'invisible\' until it\'s
close to its target?

>As to your moon, doesn\'t matter, really.  I\'ll come in on the far
>side at 0.95c.  I\'ll be in weapons range of the moon for less than
>etc.

Just a personal preference but nothing in my games will ever get up to high
fractions of c (unless it\'s desperately needed by one of my game plots)
simply because of the problems of relativity. I don\'t want to have my
players start asking me about time dilation, etc.! If you want high c vels,
might I suggest stutterwarp again?

>    Okay, I\'ll bite.  How do you locate the weapon?  *MINE* is in deep
> space about two light years from any star.  Good luck...you\'ll need it.
etc.

Well, personally I\'d go for the \'crack the security\' approach, i.e. inside
man in intelligence or tracking supply ships out to whoever\'s servicing the
damned thing, etc. An asteroid among millions might be hard to find but you
might be able to detect jump exit points nearby, send in recon teams and
refine the position of the asteroid? Better still, infiltrate an engineer
into the team working on the rock\'s navigation computer - after all, it is
quite fine tuning needed to hit the target, so you make sure you include a
Pentium floating point processor unit in there somewhere [subtle \'softie\'
joke].

>Sounds like you trust your computers a lot.  I program them for
>a living, and would not be willing to allow them that much control 
>of ANY weapon.

I have to agree (see Pentium joke above).

TO CONCLUDE
Some people want to have rocks.
Others think they\'re too dangerous.
Given my previous post on the relative monetary waste of a rock compared to
buying multi-purpose warships, etc. I would say if you want to use a rock,
so be it, but in my universe the Imperium (having not yet been through the
Rebellion) will stomp pretty heavily on anyone zapping an entire planet
(with a rock, nukes or a conventional invasion)... unless of course it was
an Imperial plan in the first place. :-) That doesn\'t mean that it *can\'t*
be done, just that if it *can* be then certain worlds will die within hours.
Advert: "Come to the tourist world of Baxili VII"
Onlooker: "Not bloody likely. I\'ve only just rolled up this character and
I\'m not going to loose him in five seconds flat just because the Fungerians
hate the Baxili and have got a rock ready out there somewhere."

Anyway, rocks are small fry in comparison to some of the Ancients weapons
I\'ve experienced! Anyone fancy a small section of the local sun being
\'jumped\' out INSTANTANEOUSLY (i.e. no week in hyperspace) and arriving in
the middle of your battle fleet?

Hope these ideas were thought provoking. If not, send a complaints postcard
to John-boy, c/o 10 Downing Street, England. :-)

Cmdr Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
