    'from' => 'Mark Clark markc@brahms.udel.edu',
    'year' => 1995,
    'index' => 'aa772',
    'body' => 'I\'m a bit tired of reading about big rocks, so I thought I\'d start a new 
thread about favorite memories of playing Traveller (if that includes 
hitting a planet with a big rock, well, so be it).

My own favorite memories have to do with the very first campaign of 
Traveller I played in, back in 1979.  I was a freshman in college, and 
I\'d been wargaming for about six or seven years.  I\'d done some 
roleplaying in high school with other wargamers (a rather common way to 
get into the hobby back then), but it was all D&D.  There were other 
rather primitive RPGs out there, but I didn\'t know about them until much 
later.  Anyway, my idea of what roleplaying was all about was shaped by 
D&D - distinct character classes (much more rigid than what AD&D has evolved
into today), rigid alignments (Good/Evil, Lawful/Chaotic), and characters 
who got harder to kill the more experienced they got.

That first Traveller campaign was based on Adventure 1: The Kinunir, and 
had a GM and two players (I was one of the players.  While it may not have 
been very roleplaying oriented by todays standards (all three of us were 
wargamers), I remember just how _different_ Traveller was.  While there 
were careers, just because you were in, say, the Scouts, didn\'t mean you 
had the same skills as another Scout, due to the random generation.  This 
was completely unlike D&D, where one fighter was pretty much like any 
other fighter.  We had great fun just sitting around rolling up 
characters.  It was almost a mini-game in itself, especially since you 
could _die_ during character generation (is that wacky or what?).  

Anyway, after spending an hour or two rolling up a character 
(unfortunatly, I can\'t for the life of me remember the character\'s name 
or career, though he was probably an Other - my favorite character class, 
the Traveller thief class), we went out looking for a job.  We were on 
Regina, so we got offered tthe two jobs in the book: check out the fuel 
tanks of Kinunir ships, which we turned down, and a hunting expedition to 
Kinorb to hunt Tree Krakens, which we accepted.  The book refers to the 
noble who set up the expedition as a fop, so he never got a name - he was 
just "the Fop," our very first patron.  We went to the planet, and since 
it turned out we were hunting illegally, Imperial Marines in Battle Dress 
arrested us.  Never saw the Fop again, but we never forgot him.  We got 
put in prison (an orbital Kinunir class stripped hull), and after a few 
weeks decided to break out.

That when we learned our second lesson about Traveller - combat was
_deadly_.  The original rules pretty much meant that if you fired first
and hit, the battle was over.  My buddy and I stabbed some guards with 
plastic knives, got their guns, and went on a rampage, killing until we 
got to a ship\'s boat and escaped to the planet.

There we learned the third great thing about Traveller - Situational Ethics!
Uninhibited by the alignment structure of D&D, we killed Farmer Brown, 
raped his wife, and stole his "ground car" (thats how we knew it was 
science fiction - he owned a ground car, not an automobile).  I remember 
that we did it not out of some evil motive, but just because we could.  
Freedom from Alignment felt so good!

Anyway, the campaign went on for some time.  We went back to the prison 
to measure the fuel tanks and rescue to the Noble Senator, we eventually 
found the Kinunir in the Shionthy asteroid belt, and then went on to play 
many of the early Adventures.  Still, it is those first few aventures I 
remeber with great fondness, for opening my eyes up to a whole new kind 
of roleplaying.  I\'ve played a lot of systems since then, but a still 
have a real affection for both D&D and Traveller, because of that early 
sense of wonder and possibility.

Anyway, hope some other folks have stories they\'d like to tell.  If there\'s 
enough interest, I\'ll tell you about my favorite adventure I ran as a 
Traveller tournament session.  All I\'ll say is that it invloved some 
short, furry creatures from a well-known science fiction movie, sandwich 
spread, and scotch tape.
