    'index' => 'aa773',
    'body' => 'J Roberson:

> Steve, I have one question about the attack you mentioned a
> couple of days ago - the one where you jump in to a point 5
> light-hours away, fire, and leave before detection.

> You are at a point 5 light-hours away from the enemy. You
> detect there positions of where they were five hours ago.
> Any shots fired will hit five hours later. In that 10-hour
> difference, how can you expect to hit anything unless those
> ships stay in the same position? Even if you spend a couple
> of hours plotting movement, you can never know ehere they\'ll
> be five hours later when your shots hit.

> Just asking. . .it\'s been bugging me for a bit.

    Quite so.  You can\'t predict the positions of ships that 
are trying to avoid being targetted that far ahead.  You can
only hit the ones that are hiding in static positions (trying
to use an asteroid as cover, for instance), or the ones who
are in (reasonably) predictable paths.
    What you CAN do is hit the orbital naval bases, including
ships docked/orbitting there.  Plus satellites, merchant
traffic, aircraft, surface ships, cities, etc.  Depends on the
weapons and the desires of the attacker and defender.
    Please note that that attack is impossible in "standard"
Trav - weapons and sensors will not reach that far.  It is
only possible if one changes rules to allow sensors/weapons
to reach out and touch someone far, far away...
    I was trying to point out that changing the rules to fix
one problem will probably introduce other problems, quite
possibly much worse ones.

    Several people have pointed out that you can\'t possibly
predict every implication of a game technology.  They\'re
right - you can\'t.  But if you don\'t give it a shot, then
sooner or later your players will present you with something
that you weren\'t prepared to deal with (like a rock).  Then
you can either roll with it (wrecking your carefully laid
adventure/campaign), or declare it impossible (which puts
you into that Fantasy game someone mentioned).
    Knowing at least some of the implications of a
"technology" will go a long way toward helping to predict
your players\' options.  Ignoring the question just means
surprise after surprise (or a Fantasy game - which is 
your privilege, if that\'s what you want to play...)



    And someone pointed out that this debate was of no
interest to him, and should therefore be stopped 
because it took away from issues of interest to him.

        I should like to point out that anything I say
on this list has NO BEARING whatsoever on what you
say.  You want to discuss merchant traffic patterns
while we discuss this?  Go ahead!  Noone will stop
you.  This discussion does not in any way limit
your ability to bring up another subject.  The TML
isn\'t going to discard your messages because too
much bandwidth is being used to talk about rocks.
So if you have something you want to talk about, 
then START TALKING!  Maybe it\'ll be interesting
enough for all of us to drop the rocks (no pun
intended) and digress away from your topic
awhile.

