    'from' => 'Andy Lilly',
    'body' => 'COMPRESSED ROCKS
In X167, Archie mentions a compressed asteroid in a diamond which could form
the basis for an anti-planet \'bullet\'. What happens if this huge compressed
mass (e.g. 400 million tons) gets accelerated to 0.9c (or somesuch) - does
relativity give it extra mass? Sufficient to make a miniature black hole or
anything? Just brainstorming...

FAVOURITE MEMORIES
Mark Clark started us with his Kinunir adventure...

Yep, Kinunir was one of the first I played but the very first ones were with
the kids from the next year up back at secondary (US: high?) school. I was
about 11 and as naive as you can get. We played a group of mostly aliens and
discovered that there was this nasty group of people called RABID or
somesuch who followed a basic "Terrans are Best, Kill the Aliens" (this is
now resurrected as the "Terran League" in my games).
First fatal mistake I make is to have insufficient money left to buy a
watch. Two seconds after approaching a man offering to sell me a watch, I\'m
staring down the wrong end of a blaster (ala White Dwarf version). Now I
know these babies do 5d6 damage and I\'ve got nothing but air molecules
between its muzzle and my face, so I lose everything I started with... just
the first example of what a b*****d my first gamesmaster was - Nick Dahn, if
you\'re out there, I\'ve never forgiven you. We found an underground base next
- with robots in it. Robots with battledress armour and laser rifles. Back
then, that was an awesome combination, given that most of us had cloth and
few had afforded reflec (I didn\'t even know what it was!). Thank goodness we
had instant stim\' shots and med drugs, cos otherwise the casualties would
have been horrendous. So, we\'re in the main control room of this place now
and someone notices a label on a panel - words to the effect of "Property of
RABID". Funnily enough, despite having fought our way past 2-3 of these
killer robots, reading that sign sparked off more fear and panic in the
party (who were, admittedly, mostly aliens), than at any point in the
earlier game. We managed to swim out through some torpedo/submarine tubes
prior to the main RABID force catching up with us.

I\'ve been hooked ever since (although I\'m much, much nicer to my players...)

IN REPLY TO STEVE
Yep, yep, yep, etc. down to:

>    If I put in a large space station in orbit around a gas giant,
>and establish it as a duty-free port or some such, the merchants
>can all bring their goods to my base, for transhipment down to
>the main world or whatever.  They can then get free fuel, and I
>can make a tidy commission transhipping your goods to wherever,
>with much less risk than by buying my own ships...

Yes, this occurs on quite a number of my worlds where for safety or
ecological reasons, the planet does not allow anything other than the
smallest shuttles or ships to land. If an orbital port is set up above the
planet and fuel from the GG (assuming the planet orbits one) is transported
to the port, it\'ll still cost the user. Alternatively, as you mentioned, a
port is set up closer to the GG and fuel is cheaper or ships can scoop it
for free (although even then there may be fees). The positioning of the
orbital port can have a lot to do with how xenophobic, etc. the locals are -
if they don\'t like/trust foreign contact then having the port as far away as
possible (e.g. close in to the GG) is a good possibility.

>    Amazingly useful to my Dirty-tricks Dept, that.  That way,
>if the M-drive is sabotaged (perhaps by setting off a small nuke
>inside the M-drive?), then the rock begins a long fall down to
>your planet.  Embarrassing. Especially since it distracts you
>from other attacks that can conveniently be scheduled for that
>same time...

Probably more useful as a character-level (as opposed to intergovernmental
strife level) plot than the original rock-throwing idea?

Steve continues, down to:
>But this ignores the question of why they are at the gas giant.
>Sure, build your SDBs so they are the tonnage of the Tigress.  Make
>them 1,000,000 times that big.  It won\'t matter how big and tough
>they are if the battle is taking place 63 hours at max G away.
>Because they won\'t be there till the battle is over.

I would never bother to deploy SDBs (or their equivalents) in any GG other
than the one used by major traffic attending the main system world. Other GG
don\'t need SDB to stop the enemy refuelling - simply put mines or homing
killer nuke missiles in there - they hide until war is declared (so
commercial ships can still refuel there if they so wish), then a remote
command activates the devices and they disperse into the upper atmosphere
(of the GG). Small mines could be very difficult to detect for a scooping
ship, while being sucked into the ship (even if it\'s only the outskirts)
means they can do a lot of damage. As Steve points out, there\'s no point in
wasting actual fighting ships at such GG. One SDB performing covert
surveillance (again more likely against pirates, etc.) is all I might have
out there.

>    Wonderful example of a "fantasy" game - you can\'t go that fast
>because the GM is too lazy to figure out the implications, and so
>he declares it impossible.  What if your players decide to go that
>fast?  Do you tell them that their ship can\'t do that?  Or just
>avoid the issue by using TNE?

"Lazy" is an assumption on your part. The truth is that I know I am not an
expert in such matters. If the situation arose, I have a number of text
books to which I can refer. However, such problems rarely occur in my games
because I have experienced (as a player) too many games where the referee
has come up with a \'clever\' plot device (e.g. high-vel rock-throwing) but
after a while other players start shooting down his ideas, at which point
the referee has to apply the same fudge factors and "because I say so" rules
that I so desperately try to avoid in my games. The same is true of the AD&D
games I run each week - I have to work damned hard with a mere 13 Gods in my
pantheon, just to make sure everything to do with religion, etc. is
consistent for the players!

Steve then comments about covert operations against his rock:
>    Which does what for you?  You can attack the rock, if you want
>(starting a war).  Or you can ignore it.  If you ignore it, and
>it jumps, what then?
Given what you commented previously about diverting defensive rocks into the
home planet, obviously I\'d plug my Pentium into your rock and tell it to aim
for the homeworld of whoever built the rock. I can\'t think of a more
appropriate/ironic solution.

>> TO CONCLUDE
etc.
>> That doesn\'t mean that it *can\'t* be done, just that if it *can* be
>> then certain worlds will die within hours.
>
