    'body' => 'In message Tue, 31 Jan 1995 15:03:12 -0500,
  Derek Smith <Derek_Smith.LOTUS@crd.lotus.com>  writes:

> A.S.Lilly @ bnr.co.uk (Andy Lilly) wrote:
>>COMPRESSED ROCKS

>>  In X167, Archie mentions a compressed asteroid in a diamond which
>>  could form the basis for an anti-planet \'bullet\'. What happens if
>>  this huge compressed mass (e.g. 400 million tons) gets accelerated
>>  to 0.9c (or somesuch) - does relativity give it extra mass? Sufficient
>>  to make a miniature black hole or anything? Just brainstorming...
>
> No.  No black hole.  The diamond/rock at 0.9c relative to the
> planet has NO VELOCITY RELATIVE TO ITSELF.  Therefore, from it\'s own
> point of reference, it has no additional mass.  It just strikes the
> target planet AS IF IT DID, because it DOES from the point of
> reference of the PLANET.

If you\'re curious why this difference comes up, here\'s why:  Start with a
rock and planet with zero velocity relative to each other.  Start to
accelerate the rock by feeding it energy (rocket, reactionless thruster,
impulse drive, whatever).  Using Newtonian physics, you\'ll eventually pump
enough energy into it to exceed the speed of light ( KE=1/2*mv^2 ).
Relativity says exceeding the speed of light is not possible, but the rock
still has to store all that extra energy - from its point of view it could
have just started moving.  So from the reference point of the planet, the
rock gains mass.  That lets the rock stay below the speed of light (from
the planet\'s point of view), while absorbing enough energy to exceed it.

Relativity really warps your view of the universe.  Who\'d\'ve thought mass,
length, and time aren\'t constant.  :-)
