First of all, Derek didn\'t write that, I did.  Be careful with your
attributions.

Second, I used that formula to show why it *doesn\'t* work at relativistic
velocities (because it says you can reach the speed of light).  I didn\'t go
into the gory details of Lorentz transforms because that\'s irrelevent
within the scope of this dicussion.

> (Even though 0.99999... C is pretty close.) Nothing can ever be
> accelerated to the speed of light, that is impossible according to
> the physicists today.

Light goes at the speed of light.  No mass, but has energy.  No mass so
adding the tinest bit of energy to it accelerates it to the speed of light.
Weird stuff.

Oh, some of you may be interested to know that this is where tachyons
(no, Star Trek didn\'t make them up) come from.  While the formulae for
relativity prohibits a mass from equaling the speed of light (divide by
zero error), it doesn\'t prohibit things from going *faster* than the speed
of light.  So theoretical particles that go faster than light are called
tachyons.  Whether they exist or not is unknown, since going from STL
(slower than light) to FTL involves reaching the speed of light.
