    'year' => 1995,
    'index' => 'aa798',
    'body' => 'Mark Clark:

> This thread has been going on long enough to make me realize that
> the real question is: Why doesn\'t this happen all the time in
> Traveller Land?  Could we get your thoughts on that, please?

    Sure.  It doesn\'t happen in Trav Land much for the same reasons
that nukes aren\'t used much in wars today - it\'s much too unstable
a situation to allow use of weapons that make things still more
unstable.
    Presumably, it has happened in the past, but a few examples
were enough to convince most everyone that it was a bad idea.

    The problem arises when you consider situations like the 
Zhos vs the Impies - neither side wants to destroy the other
("we\'re not _monsters_!"), but neither side wants to be conquered
("because they _are_ monsters!"), so if one of these wars gets
out of hand, expect it to be stopped by a rain of rocks...

    Cynthia and I nattered about this last night, and came to a
couple of surprising conclusions (one of which was that the 
Rebellion/Hard Times actually made far more sense than we first
thought).  It seemed to us that the Zhos must work real hard at
NOT winning the Frontier Wars too handily.  In order to keep the
Impies from using "extreme measures", they must plan their wars
to include at least one disastrously stupid idea to use if they
start winning big.  That way, they come out a little ahead (or
at least not behind) with minimal risk of losing half their
population to Impy retaliation.  If you have a multi-thousand
year strategy (which is not unreasonable, considering the age of
the Consulate), then you can plan on nickle-and-diming the Impies
to death over the next three thousand years.  Or maybe you can
just keep the Impies at bay until they implode...

                                        ----Steve
