    'topic' => 'Nobles and the Law',
    'body' => 'Alvin Plummer asked some interesting questions about the nobility and the
law.  I haven\'t looked up any answers in the canon, but here\'s what I\'ve
done.

When I was in law school, I tried to chart the total Imperial legal system,
including local courts, manorial courts, administrative bodies, legislative
bodies, Imperial courts, admiralty courts, etc.  The etc., I saw, was really
an ad infinitum, or even and ad nauseum.  I decided that I would deal with
the exact effects of the legal system on an ad hoc basis whenever they arose
in my games.  Even players who are rules lawyers have never, in my
experience, wanted to play lawyers (but I do have some NPC lawyers who can
greatly help or horribly bedevil the players) (sometimes the same one does
both).

In broad outline, I saw the overall judicial system being divided more or
less as follows:
"Local courts" These courts hear all actions subject to the laws of the
system in which they\'re located.  There is enormous variation in what these
courts are called and how they function, just as government type and style
vary widely throughout our cosmopolitan Imperium.

"Manorial courts"  These courts hear all actions on land directly under the
control of a noble -- for example, on a fief.  They are generally an adjunct
to the noble\'s household court (where court is used in its more than solely
judicial sense).

"Imperial courts"  These courts hear all actions arising under Imperial, as
opposed to local or feudal, law.  An action for failure to assist the holder
of an Imperial warrant, e.g., would be brought here.  These courts probably
also hear appeals from decisions of Imperial administrative bodies acting in
quasi-judicial capacities.  The judges are generally appointed by the
Emperor with the advise and consent of the local Imperial ability -- in
fact, it is unlikely that the Emperor does more than rubber-stamp the sector
duke\'s recommendations, because he has too many other things to occupy his
mind.  There are not many Imperial courts in my universe--one to sixteen
trial courts per sector, and one appellate court per sector (perhaps divided
into two divisions in more populous sectors).  Much Imperial law is handled
at the administrative level (starport safety, commercial matters,
health/quarantine regulation, etc.).  Imperial judges are rank nobles.

The nobility is subject to all law that attaches to any Imperial citizen,
according to the dictates of that law.  Thus, local law may specify that it
(ignore the "it") nobles are not subject to it.  This need not be expressed
in a statute, but can be a matter of custom.  Imperial law doesn\'t exempt
anybody, except of course for the Emperor and anyone he exempts (for
example, by Imperial warrant).  Manorial law governs everyone in the fief.

Jurisdictional questions I leave for another day (I have pages of charts
that I drew then, much of which I\'ll probably reject today).

So Imperial intelligentsia in my universe don\'t generally have to justify a
two-tiered legal system.  The legal system is only two-tiered to the extent
that (1) local law exempts nobles and (2) nobles can hire more and better
lawyers and/or pay more and better bribes.

--Glenn
