    'index' => 'aa802',
    'body' => 'The first Traveller campaign that I ever ran was set in a subsector that I
rolled up myself.  The first adventure involved a psionic talisman, but, in
order to maintain suspense and not let the game devolve into technicalities,
it was always "the artifact."  The players -- a large and unruly group of
young men and women (ranging in age from about 17 to 21; I was 22 I think)
fascinated by this concept of "no alignment!" -- ran a bunch of middle-aged
ex-soldiers, scouts, merchants, and naval officers.  They were attending a
magic show at which real magic appeared to be occurring.  The magician
invited all ten of them backstage, and asked them to deliver a box to an
associate of his on a planet on the other side of the subsector.  

I had prepared a box, about 4cm on a side.  I had wrapped the box in brown
paper, which I had covered in small script that resembled Sanskrit, and tied
the box up in a waxy twine.  It was a big hit with the players, who got into
all sorts of altercations about which character should carry the box, ahow
it should be hidden, whether it contained anything illegal or dangerous,
etc.

The players wanted to buy stuff, but all that was available was a TL7
sporting goods store.  They bought everything -- faster than I could think
up prices:  camouflage hunting clothes.  Hunting rifles.  Pellet rifles.
Shotguns.  Knives.  Ammunition.  Backpacks.  Butterfly nets.  It was as if
they really were at Herman\'s or Copeland\'s with someone else\'s credit card.
Anyway, the store owner closed shop early and went to bed happy -- there was
no Terminator scene there.

At the Travellers\' Aid Society hostel, the true owner of the artifact tried
to take it back.  The owner was a pathetic, if extremely skilled and deadly,
reptile from the world to which they were to deliver it.  It slipped in
through the ventilation system at about the same time as two of the PCs were
trying to kill a third who had not told them where she was going and to whom
she was going to be speaking.  It moved about twice as fast as a human, and
was armed with very small shuriken edged with a soporific.  Someone fired a
laser at it and set a futon on fire, and it panicked and jumped through the
15th story window.  Everyone looked out to see what had happened to it, but
they didn\'t see any flat lizard on the ground because it had grabbed the
14th floor windowsill on the way down and vaulted into that room (it had
taken the precaution of renting the room below for just this contingency).
This scenario was inspired by the fight scene in the skyscraper between the
protagonist and his evil cousin in Lustbader\'s novel The Ninja.

What happened next?  Some of the players blamed others for letting them be
followed, and I think there was a firefight right in the big hostel room.
The police were afraid to break it up, and called in the local military.  It
got ugly, but it was fun.

There was definately a sense among the players and me that this system
allowed anything that we could imagine.  Our wills conflicted about what we
were imagining, but that was ok.  I would\'ve preferred that the players
pretend to be a team and not kill each other off, but then they preferred
not to go to jail or be attacked by paratroops armed with better weapons
than hunting rifles and shotguns (the laser was a mustering-out item, which
I took to mean that the character was stick-fingered in the military).

--Glenn
