    'body' => 'This is further to my rambling about the place of nobles in the Imperial 
legal system.

Nobles are subject, in addition to Imperial law and such local and 
manorial laws as may apply, to a code of honor.  This is not strictly a 
code, as it is not written down.  More important, however, one cannot 
comport oneself as a noble merely by following some minimum standards of 
ethical conduct.  Nobles are obliged to act nobly.  

The code of honor is enforced probably in two ways.  Nobles who consider 
another noble to be without honor will stop treating that noble as such.  
For example, they may refuse to provide assistance to a peer or vassal, 
or they may refuse to abide by such protocols as would apply to relations 
between them.  For example, snubbing a ring that should normally be 
kissed sends a strong signal that the snubber considers the snubbee 
honorless.

The other enforcement is legal.  A noble may be formally stripped of his 
patents, privileges, and fiefs by an appropriate court, presided over by 
a higher ranking noble.  This would happen after conviction of certain 
serious felonies, of course (like treason, or even lese majeste), but it 
could also happen to a noble who had stopped acting noble, then stopped 
being treated like a noble, and who then demanded formal recognition of 
his nobility.  It\'s sort of like a declaratory judgment action:  
Plaintiff asks the court to decide his or her rights as against the rest 
of the nobility.  The court here wouldn\'t necessarily be a regular law 
court, but would probably be the household court of the noble\'s liege 
lord, or perhaps the next level up.  If the noble couldn\'t get a fair 
hearing there, however, he might be able to take his case to the regular 
Imperial courts.

The code of honor -- my comments to the contrary nothwithstanding -- 
probably can be summarized.  I see the following areas where nobles have 
obligations beyong those imposed by law:

Integrity:  E.g., a noble keeps his or her word, even to an enemy.
Compassion:  E.g., a noble takes care of his subjects and vassals.  
Another example would be that a noble treats prisoners properly.
Loyalty:  E.g., a noble comes to the aid of his or her liege lord when 
needed or summoned.  As a practical matter, this is governed by contract 
-- the oaths of fealty taken when the noble is created.  Loyalty to the 
Emperor supercedes all other allegiance.

No doubt this can be filled out further.

--Glenn
.

