    'from' => 'Leonard Erickson',
    'body' => 'I was way behind in reading my mail or I\'d have said something sooner.

First of all, breaking an incoming rock into *smaller* pieces is the
*last* thing you want to do.

First of all, when I say "big rock" I\'m talking about the sort of
dinosuar-killer to planet-wrecker that has been discussed. And "big" is
in terms of impact energy, *not* size alone. So a big rock can be an
asteroid a few miles across at "normal" system speeds (10 or so km/sec)
or it can be a basball at a large fraction of c.

When a big rock hits, it blasts out a big crater, probably clear down to
the magama. And it throws stuff all over, creating some secondary
impacts, and throwing some stuff clear of the planet. There\'ll also be
quite a bit of quake activity, and an airborne shockwave.  And a firebal
bigger than the depth of most atmospheres, so it\'ll just sit there,
radiating all over the place (it can\'t rise!) "Thermal" radiation will go
clear into the *gamma* range.

The above holds true no matter where the rock hits on the planet. If it
hits on land, the fireball dissipates, the magma starts filling the
crater, and the scar radiates 90% of the enery back into space.

If it hits in an ocean, you get a huge tidal wave (it\'ll probably still
be of significant size even after going clear around an earth-like
world!).  Worse, when the water tries to return to the spot it was
*blasted* out of, it will hit the hot rock and turn into superheated
steam which will carry particulate matter (stirred up sediment, rock
flour from the crater bottom, sea salt) clear up into the stratosphere
and beyond. It\'ll take some time, but the ocean *will* recliam the
crater, unless it\'s all boiled away first.

So an ocean strke conveys just about 100% of the strike energy into the
ocean and atmosphere. This is going to do things to the weather that are
best not described. And all that dust in the upper atmosphere will do fun
things too. Like make it harder for the planet to radiate away the excess
energy.

BTW, this gives a way to have the "near miss" scenario one poster
mentioned. Aim the rock to look like it was intended to be an ocean
strike, but hit land instead. :-)

Now, let\'s look at the rock that got blasted to bits. All these pieces
are still aimed at the planet. The faster it is going the less chance
there is that they\'ll spread enough to miss the planet. Though low speed
cases can turn into an extended bombardment as the pieces that pass close
get their paths bent by the planet\'s gravity.

All these pieces have the same *total* impact energy as the original
rock. But in the "ideal" case where they are all small enough to burn up
before reaching the ground, you\'ve just transferred all that energy
*directly* to the atmosphere. The water vapor will show up quickly
enough as the increased temperatures increase the evaporation from the
oceans. And you get the mass of all that rock distibuted as fine dust in
the atmosphere. So the results will be almost as bad as a sea strike.

Oh yeah, with the near c rocks, unless they hit something massing a
sizable fraction of their own mass, the fact that they have vaporized
merely means that you\'ve changed the situation from getting hit by a
rock, to being exposed to the grand-daddy of all particle beams (all that
plasma will *still* be moving in much the same direction (subject to
corrections for the mass and velocity of whatever they hit). So the
plamsa cloud is going to *act* like a poorly focused particle beam! If it
hits the planet, the best  situation is a low velocity hit, which will
act much like the worst solar flare you can imagine. Average will be
almost as bad as the Maghizz(sp). Worst will be a cosmic ray shower that
will sterilize the planet.

So, breaking it up is not a viable solution. You have to nudge it into a
new orbit. *Without* breaking it up. I can just about guarantee that
even for a lowspeed rock there won\'t be time unless it is coming from
*way* out there. In which case the simplest fix is to attach your own
jump tug to it and jump it to a safe location.

This is probably cheaper too. I\'d not be surprised to find that  shortly
after jump drive was invented, someone realized that the easiest way to
deal with asteroids that were wandering too close was to have a robot
ship dock with them and then jump them elsewhere. The daring sorts might
just use a smaller drive and "misjump" the rock. (which gives us a
possible defense against an incoming rock if you can dock fast enough!)

Any spacefaring planet will have a "watch" for natural bodies that might
come too close, along for plans for dealing with the ones at "reasonable"
sizes and velocities. Luckily, telescopes *can* pick up natural bodies
*way* out in the system. So can active EM sensors (picture the Arecibo
dish being used as one of the *smaller* radar sites).  This won\'t help
much against deliberate missiles, as they can be stealthed.

It is possible to use passive sensors at interstellar ranges. But the
*time* required makes this useless for military purposes. But a scout can
merely take a few weeks to perform a star survey  from several *widely*
seperated points in a system (say by jumping to 4 or more equally spaced
points  5-10 light hours out). You sit there long enough to establish
your position to the desired degree of accuracy, then jump to the next
observation point. After you get the second set of plates, you can spend
the time during jump comparing plates to determine the parallax of the
nearer stars. You\'ll also find most of the bodies down to a mile or so
across *in* the system. (I ought to write this up in more detail as an
article on how Interstellar Surveying is done).

BTW, a ship coming out of jump is almost certainly detectable with
*current* technology. Depending on the size and range, it\'ll trip every
gravity wave detector on the planet! I\'m going to try seeing if someone
can give some reasonable estimates of how detectable at what range.

Someone was worried about trying to answer player questions about
relativistic velocities. First of all, there\'s a *simple* calculator
shortcut for calculating the tau factor.

If v is given in terms of c, (ie half the speed of light is .5) then:

    tau=arcsin(cos(v))

Or, on my TI calculator:
    type in V
    press 2nd
    press sin
    press cos
    read answer

Now, you are probably wondering what the tau factor *is*. It\'s the number
you need for figuring time dilation etc.

At a constant velocity, the timerate aboard ship is tau. That is, while
one week passed on the ground, tau weeks pass onboard the ship.

The *apparent* length of the ship in the direction of travel will be tau
times the actual length. The *apparent* mass of the ship will be the
actual mass *divided by tau.

I say "apparent" because these are what an outside observer will see,
while onboard the ship, they will see no change. And sorry, but the
apparent mass increase does *not* affect gravity according to the physics
types I\'ve talked to.

There are formulas for calculating elapsed time while at a constant
acceleration, but that book is in storage. :-(

For those planning to hide out in the Oort cloud/cometary halo and shoot
at folks, I\'d like to point out a few things. First of all, unless they
can accelerate all the way in, projectile weapons will take a *long* time
to make it to target. This could be embarassing if your bombardment
arrives after the cease-fire or the surrender!

Near c projectiles are workable, if a bit on the overkill side.

Oh yeah, there are *lots* of rocks, iceballs, even the occasional
*planet* floating around in interstellar space. Sure, the average density
is low. But the amount of space involved is *huge*.
