fire? 
> When the blast of mesons tear through the planetary crust do they send off
a 
> wave a neutrios or something? If they did you could have a wide array of 
> passive receivers (WIDE, since they travel at light speed) to time the
burst, 
> triangulate and return fire (with Mesons, of course).
>  Any other ideas?

As I understand the concept.

Measons are generated by matter/anti-matter anihalation.  The meason gun 
generates two particle beams (say electrons and positrons), collides them 
in such a way as to generate a meason beam with the correct relativistic 
velocity so as to delay meason decay, until the measons are inside the 
target.

That being the case there are two ways (that I can think of) you could 
detect a meason weapon
	1. As well as measons there would be a burst of gamma-rays and other 
	radiation/particles in addition to the measons.  These would be 
	easier to detect than the meason beam.

	2. In generating/accellerating the electron/positron streams, you 
	would generate a magnetic spike (cf. mass drivers).  This would also 
	be detectable.

	In fact, with good sensors, and data processing, it could be 
	possible to detect and identify the weapon in operation _before_ it 
	fires.  (After all meason spinal mounts are huge energy sinks.)

		"Captain, sensors indicate a massive energy surge to their 
		forward weapons array!"

		"Shields up!!"

