    'topic' => 'Rocky Reality Checks',
    'body' => 'A few comments on damage done to planets by rockfall:

>From: Leonard.Erickson@f51.n105.z1.fidonet.org (Leonard Erickson)

>So an ocean strke conveys just about 100% of the strike energy into the
>ocean and atmosphere. This is going to do things to the weather that are
>best not described. And all that dust in the upper atmosphere will do fun
>things too. Like make it harder for the planet to radiate away the excess
>energy.

To alter a planet\'s atmospheric temperature by 1 degree from a rock
strike, I figure, would take 10^22 joules of energy (assuming 4*10^20
moles of diatomic atmosphere). Accelerating a rock to this energy would
take a one-million ton, TL15 power plant (250,000,000 megawatts) about
one year. So it should be doable with a little fore-thought.

Or you could find a rock that is moving with this energy already. At
typical interstellar velocities (30 km/s), a billion-ton rock would be
needed to reach this energy range. That would require a rather expensive
jump-drive to move.

The smaller, relativistic rock seems more probable.

And further down:
>Someone was worried about trying to answer player questions about
>relativistic velocities. First of all, there\'s a *simple* calculator
>shortcut for calculating the tau factor.
>If v is given in terms of c, (ie half the speed of light is .5) then:
>    tau=arcsin(cos(v))
>Now, you are probably wondering what the tau factor *is*. It\'s the number
>you need for figuring time dilation etc.
>At a constant velocity, the timerate aboard ship is tau. That is, while
>one week passed on the ground, tau weeks pass onboard the ship.

I don\'t think this is right. The GAMMA factor is gamma^2 = 1 / (1-v^2) .
At a constant velocity, the time dialation is gamma. That is, while one
week passed on the ship, gamma weeks pass on the ground.

And from Merrick:
>  BTW, there is an article in JTAS#22 regarding nukes in striker, and
>it talks about antimatter bombs at TL15 (you get uncontrolled use a few TL 
>before powerplants, I guess (makes sense)).  It is non-canon window-dressing, I
>think, but it talks about a Mark x Contraterrene Bomb being able to turn a 
>size x world to asteroids (so they have Marks 1-whatever).  It also talks
about
>the Impys blowing up GGs if they have to to slow an enemy advance... if this

The gravitational binding energy of the Earth is over 10^32 J. It would
take the power plant I mentioned above about the age of the universe to
generate enough anti-matter to blow the Earth into asteroids. (That\'s
over a trillion tons of anti-matter, incidently.) Blowing up a gas giant
would be about a thousand times harder. 

> Impys blowing up GGs if they have to to slow an enemy advance... if this was
>canon (is it?) then "fixing" the orck problem doesn\'t matter since the solution

Seems unlikely (at least at TL15).

			-Rob Flammang
