> 	1. As well as measons there would be a burst of gamma-rays and other 
> 	radiation/particles in addition to the measons.  These would be 
> 	easier to detect than the meason beam.

True.  Also, since the mesons won\'t *all* decay in the target (even assuming
that it hits) there will be gammas radiating from the path of the mesons in
all directions (preferencially in the direction of the beam).

Ships might also have sensor drones that simply have a meson communicator on
board...  it would prematurely decay mesons that went through it.  For dealing
with planetary defense MGs, you\'d spread these drones between the planet and
the obvious targets (the capital ships).  Assuming the detector could get an
energy spectrum on the pions, you\'d also get the depth of the site, assuming
you know what the target was (draw a line between drone and limb of world to
get a cone of space the target is in, then see what target is really there, 
then work backwards)

