    'from' => 'sudet@well.sf.ca.us',
    'topic' => 'Schloobies',
    'body' => 'Traveller News Service
Regina/Regina/Spinward Marches
005-1100
Tukera Lines\' common stock fell 20 points (-16%) upon confirmation that its
newest luxury liners were to employ schloobies in all sectors.  The
schloobie, a 2-kg genetically engineered living dustmop designed
specifically to clean human waste materials from starship interiors, has
been standard equipment on Imperial Interstellar Scout Service vessels since
its invention in 1065.  It has never caught on in the private sector,
however, nor in the Navy, because most humans react to them with disgust.
As frequent traveller Enli Iddukagan noted in a recent column in this
periodical, "I don\'t know why, but they make me think of inside-out rats."

Admiral Frederick Santanocheev, interviewed for this article, harrumphed,
"We don\'t use shoobies or shlobbies or whatever the hell they are because we
have something much better -- deck swabs!  Young men and women who are
filled up with pride and patriotism and enlist in the Navy to serve the
Emperor and defend the realm, but who need some discipline!  So we teach
them to be able to do anything, anywhere, any time!  Then if it comes to a
fight, they\'re ready.  And you know what?  Our adversaries out here in the
Marches, the Zhodani, they don\'t use shoobboos either!  And that makes me
respect them, even though they disgust me!"

Tukera Lines spokesperson Daiqing Cziller defended her company\'s actions,
however, noting that significant savings would be realized "in the near
term.  After all, the semi-autonomous hair-mobile onboard biocleanser, or
shob, for short, is pre-trained, and replaces not only assistant Stewards
but many trainers.  We believe that the market will come to accept the Shob
within a short time, and that this action will prove beneficial to
stockholders and passengers alike."

Bookings on Tukera Lines and its subsidiaries from Credo Down Starport were
off 37% as of this date.

