    'body' => 'Subject: Re: Jump drive variant

Alun Moon <A.J.Moon@newcastle.ac.uk> wrote:
>>         So G at 100 diameters is 2.94185e-5 gees.  Remember  from  your
>>         high school physics that 1 gee is 9.80665 m/s/s and you get G =
>>         2.99985e-6 m/s/s.
>
>Err....
>	I tried this last night and got g=2.8e-4 m/s/s?
>	(I used g=GM/r^2, G=6.67e-11, Me=6e24, and M=Me*Mrel, Mrel=1.566 from 
>	above, and r=1.485e9)

        Ah ha, you spoted my deliberate mistake ... I got the  exponent
        wrong when converting from gees to m/s/s.  If G  is  2.94185e-5
        gees then this is  2.99985e-4  m/s/s.  Following  through  this
        means G/c = 1.00064e-12 or 1e-12 or 1 pS (p = \'pico\' = 1e-12).

        So the 1 pS (\'one pico ess\') limit is the \'100 diameter\'  limit
        for Vland.  And the 100 pS (\'one hundred pico ess\') limit is
        the \'10 diameter\' limit.  Thus ...

        Stress Factor      Difficulty     Comment
        ----   ----   ----
             < 1 pS        Routine        The \'100 diameter\' limit
           1pS -     3pS   Routine +1
           3pS -    10pS   Routine +2
          10pS -    32pS   Routine +3
          32pS -   100pS   Difficult      The \'10 diameter\' limit
         100pS -   316pS   Difficult +1
         316pS -  1000pS   Difficult +2
        1000pS -  3162pS   Difficult +3
        3162pS - 10000pS   Formidable     Real close!
        (and so on as required ...)

        You should be able to set this up in a spreadsheet  remembering
        that 1 pS = 2.93995e-5 gees and L (in miles) = 4000 * (M/G)^0.5


JSHiggin@aol.com wrote:
>>        Star/875     487
>
