    'body' => '
\'Memories of Traveller\' - now all we need is a President\'s Choice
product to go with it. (TNE would be line a certain margerine product
 - \'I can\'t believe it\'s not T:2000!\')

Anyways, I played Traveller on and off for a while after I got it,
but it wasn\'t until I was playing \'Expedition to Zhodane\' that I noticed
something odd. One guy kept saying how altruistic the plot structure of the 
adventure is - pcs, shanghied to an asteroid belt to mine, find a drifiting
ship and what do they do? Run with it? Nope, they help the helpless little
girl they find inside. Sniff, sniff. He wanted to take off with it to the
nearest pleasure planet. The adventure synopsis didn\'t cover that though.

Then I read a quote on this list (I think) from Marc Miller or someone
else instrumental to the development of Traveller. They said that Traveller
and Star Wars were always intertwined in their mind. I thought \'but 
Traveller is nothing like Star Wars\'. BUT - I was only looking at the
surface.

Although it is never stated outright, Traveller has a specific moral
tone to most of its adventures. (CT that is). Research Station Gamma,
Signal GK, Expedition to Zhodane, I could name more I\'m sure. They all
rely on the fact that the characters have to be curious, unfazed by
danger and bucking the system and altruistic. How odd. Although there
isn\'t an alignment system, characters are expected to have a certain 
moral outlook.

Anyways, Traveller rocks and shocks because it has a cool universe 
overflowing with possibilities and some very creative people put a lot
of work into it.

Ethan
