    'index' => 'aa835',
    'body' => 'Yo People,
 I\'ve always assumed that calculating jumpspace parameters is *fiendishly* 
difficult. That\'s why we haven\'t discovereed it yet :-). The Einstein who 
discovered this had no life and couldn\'t make her own tea. Jump theory allows

from jumps between almost any two points taking almost any amount of time. 
However if you go for extremes it requires extremes. E.g. if you want to jump

from Vland to Terra in 3 minutes you need a ship the size of a point, an 
infinate amount of tensile strength and half the lifetime of the universe to 
calculate it.
 So, instead, what is commonly used is a set of approximation equations 
(devised by some laid back Scout how was upset about flunking Jump Physics). 
They are easier to solve, more forgiving of errors but the payoff is in
certain 
restrictions (100 diameter limit) and randomness (6-8 days). Although
inexact, 
they seldom lead to mis-jumps and are good enough to support comerce.
 The 100 diameter is, so, a "rule of thumb". You can jump in less but the 
possibility of a "misjump" is greater. Note: a "misjump" is just a jump where

the factors from the n-millionth iteration of the real JumpSpace equations
take 
precedence. If you haven\'t calculated them it appears random.

 I find this interpretation conveinent as it allows the referee to
occasionally 
bend the rules. Once the players were shanghied by the military to run a
smoke 
cover mission. Once they got their scout-ship (of which the parameters were 
generally well known) the military linked the computers of three cruisers 
together for about 7 days (3 before they jumped in, 4 more to refine once the

*exact* parameters were known) to calc a course for them.
 This sent them on a hard-wired course through three systems. The first jump 
was from a normal distance, this brought them in at 47 diameters. A quick 
slingshot around a gas-giant and out again at *11* diameters, and finally
into 
the target system at 27 diameters heading, at high velocity, for the enemy
base 
(abandon ship!).
 What fun!
   Jo
