    'index' => 'aa839',
    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 176',
    'body' => 'Someone asked about missile sizes.  

First of all, in the MT Referee\'s Manual, there is a table for missile 
magazines which indicates that a volume of 0.1 kl is needed to store a 
missile.  

Secondly, in Special Supplement 3 "Missiles in Traveller" published in 
JTAS #21, "standard" missiles must be able to fit into a "standardised 
shipping/launching container".  The interior dimensions of this containor 
as given as 1 metre long and 15 cm in diameter, and the mass of the 
missile is given as 50 kg (which I think is born out by the MT magazine 
table).  The dimensions give a volume of 0.017 kl, and I suppose that the 
remaining space in the magazine is due to the exterior dimensions of the 
container, and compartmentalisation for safety.  SS3 also states that a 
standard missile turret include storage for 4 missiles per launcher.

There is an illustration of a missile which I take to be a "standard" 
type in an advert for a DGP "Behind the Claw" source book which never saw 
the light of day.  It had extendable attitude jets and an antenna.

In my game, I\'ve bumped up the volume of the missile a bit.  The 
container is 1 m long, and has a square cross-section with 30 cm sides.  
The missile itself fits inside this, and has a total volume of 0.05 kl (a 
cylinder 95 cm long and 26 cm in radius)  The missile mass is 50 kg, and 
the whole assembly masses 52 kg; nuclear missiles are a bit heavier.  
These volumes and masses come from attempting to reconcile SS3, MT 
magazine volumes, and the MT/COACC design sequences as adapted to a TL 13 
fusion rocket missile.

Of course, in t\'tne, I seem to remember missiles are "7 tons", either 
mass, or displacement (94.5 kl)!

