    'year' => 1995,
    'index' => 'aa862',
    'body' => '>>>>>	Ok, next big MT problem.

	It has been pointed out that the Traveller idea of defending gas 
	giants, of fleets refueling there before assaulting the main world,
	of SDBs hiding there to ambush fleets, of merchants refueling there,
	are all bogus ideas when confronted with a "reality" check.

	Fleets intent on pounding a mainworld would enter around the 200radius
	limit of that world, several tens of AU away from any gas giant.  SDBs
	stationed there would not be able to reach attack range of home for
	many hours, too long to prevent the reduction of their world.  
	Merchants waste too much valuable time moving to a GG first to refuel.
	Better to buy fuel and save on the man-days of salry/overhead, and
	move cargoes faster.

	So why station SDBs at GGs?  Why would an attacking fleet jump in
	system at a GG first?  Why would a merchant choose to go the a GG 
	first?

	The first thing that comes to mind is that a GG has a huge magnetic 
	and gravitic field that can mask the presence of ships upon emergence
	from jump.  SDBs would probably prowl around there to catch such 
	interlopers and provide early warning/defence if that happens to be
	a fleet.  Enemy scouts could use GGs to mask their presence in an
	enemy system, while aiming their sensors insystem to check for the
	presence of a fleet, ground defences, early warning picketts/bouys 
	ect.  They may be able to slip in, get target information, and get
	out undetected.  

	An invadeing fleet unsure of what awaits them at a target world could
	jump in near a GG to be partialy/fully masked.  It could then scan the
	system, refuel, and jump away if the system is too well defended.  If
	not it could refuel, dress their lines, and make a methodical attack.

	Because deadfall weaponry is so nasty, and any foreign ship has the
	potential to be an enemy/terrorist it may be that many worlds would
	forbid foreign shipping insystem.  A GG station would provide a way
	point for foreign traffic, with shuttles provideing passage to the
	main world.  It seems to make good military sense to me.  With the
	state of weaponry being as it is in MT I can\'t see any ship being 
	allowed anywhere near the 200radius limit of a mainworld without a
	thorough Mk1 EYEBALL search first.

	Smugglers make out on the deal as well.  They could easily hide 
	contriband at the GG, hire a local shuttle to pick it up, and thus
	circumvent local authority.

	(This all assumes that sensor ranges in MT are much greater than those 
	allowed in the combat rules.)

						Morgan Samuels

