    'topic' => ' Sensors and things',
    'body' => 'Hi,
 
> A passive sensor has effectivly an unlimited range, (and to some extent 
> so does an active one).
>>SNIP>> 
> The size of a sensor (at least say an optical one) limits the angular 
> resolution of the sensor.  A 30cm mirror gives enougth resolution to 
> image most stars (1arc-second). But the lvel of light is so faint you 
> need 8 or 10meter mirrors to collect enought light.

To first order the angular resolution is simply:

A.min = (1.22*wavelength)/diameter

Where A.min is in radians, wavelength is in meters, and diameter is the 
diameter of the detector (or in the case of synthetic aperture arrays, the 
distance between the far detectors (though sampling becomes an issue in this
case)).
 
Just some misc trivia :)

Merrick
