    'year' => 1995,
    'from' => 'liebx004@maroon.tc.umn.edu',
    'body' => 'Being that I have spent the last five (fruitless) years in the internatonal 
transportation business, the commerce systems in traveller have struck me 
as particularly shallow.  Basically, traveller (and mega-) commerce have 
been of the 18th century merchanteer variety: i buy cargo from a seller at 
point a, ship it to point b, and hope the selling price is > than cost of 
goods + transport costs.  really, that\'s it.  
here are some of the issues i bring to the table - i have solutions to 
them, but i am more interested in seeing if anyone except me REALLY cares 
enough to put them into practice (i am not currently in any running game)
1) shipping companies - using earth 1995 as an example - the merchanteer 
method of shipping just does NOT make sense economically.  just as the 
craftsman-style operations have gone by the wayside in favor of 
mass-production, economies of scale are also applicable to the shipping 
business.  because a large company, shipping a variety of products over a 
number of ports is relatively more insulated from the business price 
cycles , they can trim their profit margins to just above cost and still 
make a hefty profit - always undercutting the single-merchant who must take 
high margins to insure against the next shipment being a loser.  and 
shipping companies move to fill EVERY needed void.  sure, a major frieght 
line may not stop weekly at every world in the regina subsector, but 
certainly, if there is cargo to move for profit, they will have "feeder" 
service to those points, albeit with smaller vessels and irregularly or at 
long intervals.  simply, the merchanteer system cannot work.
2) standardization: in the 1960s, the steamship lines of the world realized 
the huge time savings involved in standardization.  rather than having 
every shipper send their cargo in boxes, pallets, etc to the pier where it 
would be loaded on the vessels, now 90% of the steamhsip lines use 
CONTAINERS.  8\' high and wide, and either 20 or 40\' long, they are 
optimized for road/rail/ocean transport.  sure, the management of empty 
container pools is complex, but the methods of making sure enough empty 
containers are available at any given point is now simply statistics: if 
there is a yearly surge in the need for containers in a given area, reduce 
rates for freight TO that area in the months preceeding - soon, the market 
will make sure you have enough containers.  why hasn\'t traveller figured 
this out?
3) Customs - the BIG bugaboo of traveller.  customs and import/export 
regulations - even in a relatively lassez-faire country as our own - are 
not a benign thing.  on the export side, the us government has a 10" thick 
manual listing controlled commodities (things you cannot export without a 
license, like nuclear switches), banned exporters (persons who are not 
allowed to export anything because of past violations) and export 
regulations.  the regulations manual for hazardous shipping - showing 
packaging, stowage, handling, and transport rules - are bigger, at about 
16-20" thick. on the import side it\'s even worse.  and this is one state, 
one one planet, all at roughly the same tech level. now image what regs 
would be like if you had to potentially deal with exports to 10,000 
worlds with different biospheres, religions, governments, languages, etc.
it\'s mind boggling.
4) and this is somewhat off-track: tech levels.  in a sector or subsector 
where there are tech 14 planets, why are there any that are tech 8 or9 or 
10? or any other number, for that matter?  i mean, i can understand that in 
some cases aboriginal populations would need protection (?) from high-tech 
infiltrating their development, but is it really logical to say that a 
planet would stay at tech 8 a one-week-jump from a tech 12 or higher?  not 
for years and years.  that\'s like saying that while europeans use 
telephones, we\'re still stuck with morse code in the usa.  i would say 
(conservatively) you would have a general diffusion of the average tech in 
less than 100 years.  i\'m sure someone will disagree, so i would like to 
hear it.
-Steve

