    'index' => 'aa871',
    'topic' => 'commerce and shipping',
    'body' => 'I\'m glad you brought this up, because this has also been a peeve of mine 
as well.  Along with religion, trade is one of the least developed areas 
of Traveller.  I suppose this is due to the orientation of most gamers 
and the wargamer heritage of Traveller itself - ever notice just how many 
pages are devoted to weapons and weapons systems in published Traveller 
materials?  Granted, most RPGs have the same orientation, but frankly I 
feel that too often Traveller is just "today with better guns."  

Anyway, here is how I have tried to deal with some of the issues Steve 
raised:

CONTAINERS: I have long assumed that essentially all trade travels in 
standard containers, and that all starship bays are designed to hold 
them.  In civilized areas, the ships in my campaign are nothing but 
drives, crew quarters, and fuel - all cargo is pre-placed in modules, 
delived to the 100D limit by tugs.  The model that Traveller presents is 
what I assume is in frontier areas like the Spinward Marches - trade is 
still developing, and networks are changing.  Since the rules make clear 
that starships hulls are in service for decades, even centuries, flexible 
designs that can handle a variety of tasks as the years roll by are a 
good investment.

SMALL TRADERS: Why do things like Free and Far Traders exist?  Why do 
mercantile styles of trading exist?  I model my universe on current world 
conditions yet again.  While large countries like the USA, France, or 
Japan have big container ships going back and forth between them, 
backwaters like the Ascension Islands or other isolated populations are 
serviced by small, antiquated ships that carry a wide variety of cargo.  
In the Spinward Marches, there are worlds only a few parsecs from Rhylanor 
that are essentially backwaters, tiny places with tiny needs.  That\'s 
where Free Trders go, not the highly populated systems.

CUSTOMS:  This is the most interesting point you raise.  I\'ve always used 
customs as a way to hassle players, driving the plot along.  Beyond that, 
I haven\'t given it much thought.  I always assumed that this was one of 
the few thing the Imperium did - regulating interstellar trade, that is 
(along with bopping the odd Zho or Solomani on the head).  I\'d be 
interested in what other folks have done along these lines.  


TECH LEVELS:  I alays treat tech levels as what the system is capable of 
"Manufacturing," not what is "For Sale."  When one buys a television in 
Haiti, it probably comes from Japan.  Of course, a television bought in 
the USA also probably comes from Japan.  However, if you really wanted 
one, an American company could build you a TV.  Thus, I\'ve always treated 
low tech worlds in Traveller as being those that have decided to import, 
rather than manufacture for themselves.  You can buy a Grav Belt on 
Knorbes, a tech two world in the Regina subsector - it\'s just 
manufactured somewhere else. 
	As to why some worlds have low tech levels, one might as well ask 
why some ares of our own world are still low tech, centuries after the 
industrial revolution.  Isolation, lack of natural resources, cultural 
barriers, all play a part.  I\'m not saying the Traveller univers is 
likely, but given the assumptions it\'s at least possible.  Remember, 
humans have lived in Africa longer than any other continent, and many 
parts of Africa are still poor and undeveloped, centuries after the 
cotton gin and the spinning jenny.

Mark Clark
