    'topic' => ' commerce and shipping',
    'body' => 'Taking your points one at a time...


1) The merchanteer model possibly can\'t be economically justified, but it
makes for a dandy game.  I\'ve run (and played in) a game where the players
set up a shipping line.  It ceased to be fun once it became a matter of
statistics.  (That\'s probably why my character engineered a resistance
movement to the Imperium during the FFW - boredom.)  Player interactions are
kept at the personal level, while bookkeeping is kept to a minimum.

2) Containerization exists in Traveller.  Check out the MegaTraveller Journal
(issue 3) for an equipment sheet for a standard container (one of mine). 
Other sizes exist.  My own detailed trade system assumes that freight is
usually in containers (except for lo-tech worlds), while cargo requires
players to have (or buy) their own (unless they\'re really lucky, or good
bargainers).

3) Customs exists, at least in my game.  Assume expert systems plus
Admin/Legal skill, unless you really like inventing regulations and red tape.
 Why else is exporting to hi-law worlds so exciting?  ("Captain Smith, under
the authority of the Refurbished Furniture Safety Act we are impounding this
cargo of grapple grommets until you file a T24/c with the requisite 24.2 and
65.3 attachments.")  

4) Tech level differences exist on Earth right now.  The key thing to do is
draw a distinction between knowledge-based technology and industry-based
technology.  For example, even a tech 1 world can have better medicine by
boiling water and keeping wounds clean.  Look at the UNICEF village in Kenya
(information available from UNICEF and many other NGOs) for examples of "high
science/low technology" devices.  
