Agreed, but big shipping companies don\'t provide the same room for
adventure as struggling independent merchanteers (all the
possibilities provided by a large shipping company can be included by
placing such companies alongside merchanteers in the same setting).
On a smaller scale, independent road hauliers still operate alongside
the major firms -- but they struggle.

>3) Customs - the BIG bugaboo of traveller.  customs and import/export 

I\'ve always assumed that freight has a consigner and a consignee, who
have already cleared their freight with customs at both ends, or are
responsible if anything goes wrong.  Of course, if things really go
wrong, the carriers are stuck with the problems -- but that is in the
realms of adventure!  As to speculative cargo, if something is
restricted, I always allow PCs a chance to discover this before they
buy, providing they think to check.  So many things are likely to be
banned or subject to customs tariffs on a given world that a random
roll involving the trade law level and some modifiers should be
sufficient.


