Not disagreeing, just putting an alternative :-).  Italy has a \'phone
system, but if you cross the Med. to N. African countries, the system
is considerably nore primitive, as are general levels of technology;
go even further south, and telecommunications are virtually
non-existent.  Italy to Tunis is considerably less than a week\'s
travel time, and virtually instantaneous communication.  Add to this
cultural and governmental resistance to technological change
(eg. Aramanx in the Aramis subsector), and you can justify the TLs of
most worlds (should you wish to).  I seem to remember this topic coming 
up on TML/XTML in the past, and there were two schools of thought:  TL 
uniformity, or wide variations over short distances.


