    'index' => 'aa877',
    'body' => 'Commerce and shipping

>here are some of the issues i bring to the table - i have solutions to 
>them, but i am more interested in seeing if anyone except me REALLY cares...
Any rules fixes are always more than appreciated on this (and the traveller,
i.e. TNE list). 

>1)...the merchanteer method of shipping just does NOT make sense
economically.

I quite agree. There seems little recognition among Traveller referees (or
even GDW themselves) of the huge multi-million ton bulk transports "bulkers"
that would perform most of the shipping in the year 5000-whatever A.D. when
Traveller is set.
However, there is always a market for the transport of small lots of
specialist goods, and this is (IMHO) where most Traveller trade comes from.
i.e. the trade tables given in the rules ONLY cover these sort of shipments
and don\'t (in my games) represent the bulk goods hauled (certainly not when
rolling up the few tons of your average cargo lot). Reasons for small lots
are:
(1) High value - too expensive to insure with a bulker.
(2) High value - insufficient security on a bulker.
(3) High risk - bulker won\'t or can\'t handle such cargo.
(4) Illegal - can\'t be smuggled through usual channels on a bulker.
(5) Special destination - bulkers just don\'t go there (low pop world, D-E
starport).
(6) Special destination - has to be landed in the middle of jungle, etc.
(7) Special timing - must be there by given date and time (bulker can\'t make
it quick enough).
(8) Personal value - owner wants to travel \'close\' to his possessions, not
have them stored at the bottom of a million-ton hold.
(9) Care - cargo requires constant care/maintenance/feeding that is too
troublesome/expensive for a bulker.
(10) Commercial secrecy - owner doesn\'t want competitors finding out where
or what he\'s transporting (bulker cargo lists would be fairly easy to come
by).

Major cases are those of destination and timing - yes, bulkers will go to
many worlds but (in the interests of economy) they may detour via higher pop
worlds before heading for lower pop ones (to ensure an otherwise loss-making
trip has some profit margin). Given these detours, the time factor for
loading and unloading a bulker, the inflexibility of bulker timetables, and
the fact that for a reasonable profit margin the bulkers are probably Jump 1
or 2 at most, any small trader able to pick up a small cargo at a moment\'s
notice and do Jump 2 at max speed for the given destination star system
might well seem like a better proposition for someone in a hurry to get his
cargo somewhere.

Naturally, some small traders might provide the \'feeder\' service you mention:
>certainly, if there is cargo to move for profit, they will have "feeder" 
>service to those points, albeit with smaller vessels and irregularly or at 
>long intervals.

PASSENGERS
In case (9) we\'re crossing an important boundary - that between bulkers and
passenger liners. My bulkers are pretty much like modern cargo ships, i.e
they are only equipped to carry a few passengers, and then not in any
comfort. Small traders can exist for passenger trade for the same reasons as
given for cargo, i.e. flexibility, speed, access, peculiar carriage
conditions, peculiar destination, etc. all the things that would make the
ticket office of a commercial line simply stare at you for asking. "Sorry? I
thought I just heard you ask PanStellar to fly you to the island of Banairos
in the middle of the Amarian jungle on Phlemos... Oh, you did... Sir, if I
might suggest that you try Honest Harry\'s Bucket-shop Tramp Traders...
Ticket desk? Ha ha - sorry, sorry. No, there\'s no ticket desk, just try the
crew bars on level 23. Harry\'s the one lying at the back, drunk, with
obvious signs of alcohol-induced incontinence... oh, and have a nice day."
(beaming smile from ticket clerk).

>2) standardization:

Traveller cargo does come in standard containers but because of the oddities
of ship sizes, some containers are pretty small. If I remember Traders and
Gunboats (CT Supp 7), the diagrams for the Subsidised Merchant (400 tons)
showed some containers - I think (total guess here) they were about 3x3x6
metres but it might have been smaller.

>3) Customs - the BIG bugaboo of traveller.

bugaboo. Referee heaven is what I call it! :-)

>...10" thick manual...16-20" thick...

Frank admission (or Peter, Tom, Harry, etc.): I don\'t know much about this
except what I\'ve read or watched on TV documentaries, but it seems that a
lot of freight (certainly EEC stuff) just flies by customs - in most cases
they just don\'t have the man-power to stop and check every shipment. As long
as the paperwork\'s okay, then you\'re through, no matter how many long pipes
you\'re carrying for someone\'s super gun.
Extrapolate using Steve\'s comments:

>...now image what regs 
>would be like if you had to potentially deal with exports to 10,000 
>worlds with different biospheres, religions, governments, languages, etc.
>it\'s mind boggling.

Yep. But what\'s interesting is whether it would slow down customs or speed
things up?

Customs post, checking vehicles coming off the inter-system drive on, drive
off ferry:

Officer 1: "Why\'d you just wave that truck through?"

Officer 2: "Driver\'s only bloody Vargr isn\'t he. You ever tried talking to
one? Try asking him what\'s in the back? I mean, this illegible scribble on
the documents means you can\'t tell what he\'s *supposed* to be carrying, let
alone what\'s actually in there. And there\'s no point holding him, cos he\'s a
contractor to some line or other so it\'s them you have to hassle, and the
boss spent four days last time trying to sort out the legalities with their
embassy and... well, basically I just don\'t want the hassle. Next time he
comes through I\'ll wave him into your queue and you can take his truck
apart, eh?"

Officer 1: "Are you kidding? The length of my queue\'s doubled in the time
it\'s taken for you to tell me that! All these bloody day-trippers coming
over from Regina just for the duty frees. Oh yes, officer, of course this
entire BUS full of beer is just for my own personal consumption - for the
next 50 years, eh?"

Officer 2: "Ah yes, I know the guy with the bus - comes through about once a
week, doesn\'t he?"

TECH LEVELS

Ah, Steve\'s brought up an old and much-discussed point here, about why
aren\'t all worlds about the same tech level.
To summarise:
Tech level means average world ability to manufacture.
Some worlds don\'t have the expertise/raw materials/base population/etc. (no
on-world metals -> no steel mill)
Some worlds just find it\'s cheaper to buy in high tech goods. (on-world
metals are only found 2 miles under surface - too expensive to mine)
Some worlds aren\'t allowed higher tech for political/technical/etc. reasons.
(here Mr. Iraq, please have our latest jamming suite and we\'ll throw in
these nice radar systems too).
Some worlds have been exploited (a starting low tech world can\'t pay for
high tech so the corporations don\'t regard it as much of a market and prefer
to exploit it instead).
Some worlds don\'t want their populace high tech (low tech peoples with less
ability to communicate with each other and the outside world are far easier
to control in a dictatorship, religious system, etc.)
etc.
etc.

>...that\'s like saying that while europeans use 
>telephones, we\'re still stuck with morse code in the usa...

I think comparing the US and Europe with any \'third world\' country (or is it
\'developing nation\' now?) would quickly show that in the latter, the rich
may well have mobile phones, but the poor often don\'t have wired telephones
and certainly couldn\'t make them, nor know how to repair them.

Given the wide-ranging politics and boom-bust nature of economics, etc. I
can well see how tech levels would (deliberately or otherwise) vary widely
from world to world. The Imperium doesn\'t (TNE: didn\'t) have the will or
power to try to even things out - average techs are much more likely to be
equal and stable in the "rediscovered" worlds of TNE.

Just some thoughts, remember none of this has passed through my brain on the
way to the keyboard so my body (excepting two or three fingers) disclaims
all responsibility for anything said herein.

Andy

