>Being that I have spent the last five (fruitless) years in the internatonal 
>transportation business, the commerce systems in traveller have struck me 
>as particularly shallow.  Basically, traveller (and mega-) commerce have 
>been of the 18th century merchanteer variety: i buy cargo from a seller at 
>point a, ship it to point b, and hope the selling price is > than cost of 
>goods + transport costs.  really, that\'s it.  
>here are some of the issues i bring to the table - i have solutions to 
>them, but i am more interested in seeing if anyone except me REALLY cares 
>enough to put them into practice (i am not currently in any running game)
>1) shipping companies - using earth 1995 as an example - the merchanteer 
>method of shipping just does NOT make sense economically.  

	Straight Off, you have to understand that over the immense inter-
stellar distances involved in traveller, trade and commerce start to once 
again resemble the kind of commerce that took place back in the 1700\'s.  
Primarily this is because of the large amount of time it can take to get 
from point A to point B.  To be totally honest todays shipping just does 
not take as long, most shippments are in less that a couple days and there 
are even some that happen over night.  In traveller it can take up to a 
bloody month to just jump four times(Depending on the ship.)  This in and 
of itself makes it so that  a merchant has to risk a lot on his jumps, he 
absolutely has to make a profit, not just hope he gets one.  Further this 
is a mater of Trader captains and Merchant princes, these people own thier 
entire business and some even take pride in thier ability to trade, a lot 
like a frontiersman of the 1700\'s.  So befor you completely rewrite the 
commerce issues in traveller think these things thru.  True I would agree 
if I could get  from Vland to Solomani space in a couple of days, but this 
jus will not happen in the traveller system.

Stay Frosty, 

