    'body' => '
Styopa wrote:
 
> here are some of the issues i bring to the table - i have solutions to 
> them, but i am more interested in seeing if anyone except me REALLY cares 
> enough to put them into practice (i am not currently in any running game)

If you have solutions, I\'m interested to hear them!

  First, about craftsman-style, economies of scale operations: 
  Right now, the ability to do one-time, unique "crafted" manufacturing 
at a sane price is growing quite rapidly.  I wouldn\'t be surprised if the 
ability to do one-time, single-merchantman operations at a high profit 
level ALL THE TIME (well, high enough to get his own niche) also expands. 
Ever heard of niche marketing?
  And the single merchantman can react to changes in the business climate 
far more quickly than any megacorp can.

  Second, on standardization: in both MT and TNE the Displacement ton is 
the basic unit of shipping.

  Third, on customs: the vast complexity of customs only helps to provide 
more marketing niches for the single merchantman, who can exploit new 
reg\'s and erratic law changes much more quickly than ye olde megacorp.  
Moreover, he is simply too small a target for most bureaucrats to waste 
time attacking.
  The only problem he may face is reading all the red tape: but by TL B, 
it\'s almost certain that you can buy programs which can interpret a 
particular form of legal language, thus saving on time.  Or he can simply 
hire a lawyer\'s services: consider this part of his operating costs.

  Fourth, on Tech Levels: While the Solomani (like you and me) like to 
get as much tech as possible, the Vilani (and possibly other cultures) 
have a much greater desire for stability than tech.  After all, the folks 
in China deliberately chose to stay at a lower tech level than was 
neccessary for centuries after the Mongol Hordes were vanquished.
  Moreover, remember that the Vilani have existed for 11,000 years, and 
have serious influence on the Imperium.  Such people may, quite 
rationally, decide to stay at a particular Tech Level to obtain certain 
cultural goals, to remain compatable with nature, etc.
  People _can_ live quite comfortable at low TL\'s, and if they can get 
their hand\'s on off-world medical technology, why shouldn\'t they?
  Finally, remember that the real NEED for Tech Level growth remains 
military.  And the Imperial Military in Traveller is uniformaly TL F.  
What Tech Level `the little people\' choose to live at is irrevelant.
  

