    'topic' => ' commerce and shipping',
    'body' => '"Styopa" <liebx004@maroon.tc.umn.edu> wrote:

[about the Traveller interstellar economic system, deleted]

Yeah, the handling of interstellar economics may be a bit off in the game,
but that\'s probably because some allowances were made to keep the players
involved -- paperwork adventures just don\'t seem to go over well.  Still....

Freight shipping companies do exist (like Tukera Lines) that dominate the
jump-3 and jump-4 long-range shipping along the xboat routes.  However, 
the Imperial Ministry of Transportation has fixed the rates that commercial
ships can charge for freight at kCr 1 per ton per jump, the same way that
passenger rates are fixed.  So the money you make depends on how efficient
your ship is and whether you can fit the freight in your hold, as long as 
you\'re operating as a shipping and not a trading concern, which works a
bit differently.

Containers have existed in Traveller for a long time, but are only referred
to in the type "R" Subsidized Merchant information.  They\'re three meters
by three meters by six meters, and displace 54 kL.  The "Fat Trader" could
carry fifty in its\' 200 displacement-ton hold (in Classic Traveller), but
a couple would probably be used to store the baggage of the passengers.  I
suppose the bulk traders that we haven\'t seen much of (like MT\'s "Common
Imperial Transport" of 20000 d-tons) would mainly be containerized, and 
many would operate on the trade routes that follow the xboat routes. 

Container pools could easily exist, and we wouldn\'t have to worry about 
them.  An article in _Traveller\'s Digest_ had pools of portable low berths
that would be mounted on the low berth racks in the ship so that long
distance travel, say from Mora to Vland, could be done by freezing the
passenger once and moving the berth from ship to ship.  You\'d probably
have to travel on a line like Tukera or make some sort of arrangements
with a travel agency on scheduled shipping for this to work real well, 
and you\'d probably have to stick to xboat routes, but it\'s safer than 
reviving at each stop every week.  The portable berth pool was managed by 
IMoT\'s Imperial Starport Authority (the body that runs almost all Imperial 
ports), and captains bought into the pool of portable low berths in 
proportion to the number of spaces they carried to support them; the
folks at DGP said that it would cost the same as permanent low berth
fixtures for simplicity.  A similar system to handle empty cargo
containers can easily be imagined, paid for by the freight owners.

As for customs troubles, it\'s probably best to assume that the players
understand and follow the regs unless there\'s some good reason not to.
If I remember right, expanded character generation for merchants requires
all characters to have Legal skill before they can take the test for
promotion to Captain.  No reason to sweat this stuff too much, it\'s
just a game.  

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>

