    'body' => 'Steve "Styopa" raises some important issues regarding the

commerce rules.  I think that many of us care about them, and

there are probably a number of "fixes" in use.  I\'d like to see

Steve\'s approaches, especially because he has experience in the

field.  Here are my comments about the issues raised in Steve\'s

post:



1) (these numbers don\'t necessarily correspond to Steve\'s)  Earth in

1995 may not be a good analogy to all of the Imperium in 5600. 

The designers express (in the three original black books) their

intention that the Imperium be somewhat analogous to Earth\'s
mercantile age.  One reason is probably their belief that players
would enjoy the flexibility of owning their own ships more than
the constraints of being employees of megacorporations (I myself
did so when I started playing some 14 or 15 years ago, but now I
don\'t mind having my players work for someone else, fit their
adventures into their schedules, and hide them from their bosses).



2) There are major shipping companies in Traveller.  See Book 7:
Merchant Prince for a discussion of megacorporations like Tukera
Lines and Makhidkarun, which cover the entire Imperium (Book 7
also discusses shipping companies in the other major polities).  See
The Spinward Marches Campaign for a discussion of Al Morai, a
shipping company that serves the Spinward Marches.  Al Morai
has standard ships, standard bases, and (if memory serves) uses
containers.  



3) Are there freighters, tankers, and passenger ships owned by
individuals or small companies on Earth in 1995?


