    'body' => ':) At least we got some discussion going!!  Yahoo!
Anyway, I thank you all for your comments.  I think I now have a much 
better feel for the tech differences in the Traveller universe.

Anyway, now that I have you all thinking a bit about commerce in Traveller, 
here\'s a couple (real-life) situations guaranteed to make players pull 
their hair out, without neccessarily turning your game into "Bankers & 
Bookkeepers" (pardon the earthly idiom; I leave it to you all to translate 
these into terms compatible with your needs):
1) many countries (mainly 3rd world) rely on a couple of different means to 
raise funds...first is called legalization.  BEFORE goods can be shipped, 
they have to be stamped at the local consulate.  Of course, this takes 
about 2 minutes, but costs $200 or sometimes a percentage (2-5%) of the 
invoice value.  Note, this MUST be done or the customs officials at 
destination will seize the goods, netting more $$ for the govt & 
themselves.  THe second way of making money is similar, but involves a 
thorough pre-shipment inspection of the goods by a certified examiner, who 
then seals the goods and clears them for shipment.  In this case, the docs 
must be stamped AND the seals unbroken...or else.
2) Customs officials carry grudges...a long time.  Piss one off, and 
curiously, your shipments seem always to hit that "random inspection".
3) How about certain far eastern countries where you can provide a service, 
but then are advised that you cannot legally accept money from a local 
resident.  You must have them pay a state agency, who then pays 
you...usually taking about 10-50% (yes, 50%) as "Handling Fee". Surprise.
4) The law of the sea states that a captain may jettison ANY cargo deemed 
unsafe for his vessel.  No questions asked. hehehe.
5) Finally, a neat insurance trick: if a vessel sinks or is severely 
damaged, a "General Average" is declared.  The trick is that the owners of 
the cargo carried ARE RESPONSIBLE FOR COMPENSATING THE STEAMSHIP LINE FOR 
ITS LOSS!  Hee hee.  Say the ship sunk is worth 10 million, and the total 
value of goods carried is 800,000.   If you have a cargo worth 40,000 on 
the vessel, you owe the steamship line 40/800 or 1/20 the value of the 
vessel, or $500,000!!! (plus you still have to legally pay the freight 
charges).

I have a zillion of \'em.  All true, too.
Again, thanks for all your comments.
PS: Not to start a wor that\'s probably already been heavily hashed, but 
does anyone else think GDW shot themselves in the head by effectively 
discarding the most complete and magnificent game universe in the biz? 
(TNE)  Just wondering.

