    'subj' => 'Small Traders Pt II',
    'month' => '02',
    'date' => 'Tue, 21 Feb 1995 09:24:29 +0000',
    'day' => '21',
    'year' => 1995,
    'from' => 'Andy Lilly',
    'topic' => 'Small Traders Pt II',
    'body' => 'What I really didn\'t accentuate sufficiently in my previous post (re why do
small traders still exist, particularly on the main trade routes) is the
speed factor.
Given a bulk trader (B) and a small trader (S) with equivalent jump and
manouevre drives, S will beat B to a given market 99 times out of 100.
For B: Wait at port 1 for given departure time - all cargo should be booked
in several days in advance and should be loaded many hours in advance (for
customs, containerisation, etc.), get clearance for shuttle, shuttle up to
B, docking with B or orbital port, transfer (in space or through a bustling
orbital port) from shuttle to B, sealing up and checking of B, e.g. are the
bow doors locked closed, etc. - subtle European jibe - check all passengers
on board, power up engines, move out to jump distance, and jump). At the
other end, reverse this process but include making sure cargo for the next
planet isn\'t blocking the unloading of cargo for the current destination,
add in safety factors for handling bulk containers in such a huge ship
(probably in vacuum), check the correct packages are being taken down, wait
for the next shuttle if there are insufficient to take the entire
consignment (possible hundreds of thousands of tons for a hi pop planet),
etc.
For S: Leave port as soon as the cargo is loaded and cleared (no need to
book or load in advance), get clearance once only - for leaving planet, head
straight for jump distance, and jump. At the other end, reverse this process
but DON\'T add any extras: assuming S can land on-planet again, there\'s no
shuttling; there\'s only a few crates in the back so keeping track of which
to unload and getting access to same is far easier than for B.

That might also explain why a lot of smaller traders are given mail runs -
they\'re almost certain to get there faster.

Just my Cr0.02

Andy

