    'topic' => ' commerce and shipping',
    'body' => 'Steve expresses his disapointment at MegaTraveller shipping:
>Being that I have spent the last five (fruitless) years
>in the internatonal transportation business, the commerce
>systems in traveller have struck me as particularly shallow.  
 Learning how to handle a real sword after many years
of Fantasy RPG experience taught me that you can *never* have
a realistic RPG system for any profession. It makes sense:
if it is professionally realistic then you need a professional
to be able to work it! The best you should aim for is a
model that feels right to a someone with a little knowledge.

>1) the merchanteer method of shipping just does NOT make sense
>economically.
 I\'ve always assumed there existed the large shipping
combines that accounted for 98% of shipping. This, however,
is boring to role-play. Thus the action usually centres on
the small feeder operators or contract haulers.

>2) standardization
 I agree 100%. I put an article on the TML a couple of
years ago detailing standardised 1, 2, 4, and 8 ton containers.
The rules don\'t explicitly mention this, but they don\'t
overrule it either (thanks for giving the actual measurements
for modern contains. I wanted those when I was doing my own
system.)

>3) Customs
 Heh. Try living in the European Community! I normally
roll -vs- the Law Level with a +/- depending on the type
of cargo. Ever think of wraping some rules around your
experience? This is XBOAT, not TRAVELLER. Mega/Traveller
don\'t belong to GDW here. We can do what we want.
 Of course there are plot ideas from this. Different
companies producing competing AI software to fill out
your custom\'s forms :-).

>4) and this is somewhat off-track: tech levels.
 You have made a common mistake. That is, to assume that
the Tech Level is the level of goods available on a planet. What
the Tech Level is is the level of goods that can be *produced*
on that planet.
 Take Ireland as a modern example. Breaking down to
WBH levels you might say we are up to tech 8 on Computers (the
Shannon Silicon Valley) but we can\'t be beyond 4 or 5 in
personal or military weapons systems!
 Similarly 3rd world planets or planets that primarily
produce Natural Resources don\'t need to be able to produce
things that are that high tech. They need them to work but
they don\'t need to produce them locally.
 This is what makes commerce work. Ireland would shrivel
up and die in a remarkably short time if it had to rely only
on what it could produce itself!
    Jo
