    'topic' => 'yet more shipping and commerce',
    'body' => '
I think there are plenty of reasons that shipping and commerce are very 
different in the Imperium then they are today...

Time lag in communications.

I think this alone describes why a lot of the Imperium is the way it is.

Picture a situation: A new product is developed on Planet X, 6 parsecs away
from Planet Y. 2 inhabitants of Y are on X the day the product is unveiled.
They both know people on Y will love it. But how to get it to Planet Y from
X???

One is a representitive of a big shipping company. If he was to follow
standard operating procedure like on modern Earth, he\'d have to contact his
bosses on Planet Y, get approval, arrange customs clearances, etc. This
would take a lot of time, at least 1, probably 2 weeks for each jump
back and forth. And he\'d have to stay on Planet X the entire time to 
make sure the supply of this miracle product doesn\'t dry up. Of course,
once purchased and shipping, the product would probably have a marketing
strategy all the way to the final consumer.

The other person is a free trader captain. She just digs into his pocket,
buys a cargo bay full of the stuff and takes off. Upon arrival at Planet X,
she finds someone who will retail the stuff and tries to geta good price for
it.
Oh, she might have to bribe a few customs officials too.

One is low risk, but very slow, the other is much higher risk, but much 
quicker. Oh, and the second one has much higher potential profit.

So, which do you think PCs would rather be involved in?

As for standardized containers, sure, the big lines probably use them, 
but what happens when you want to bring back a herd of elephants for
your personal zoo? What about that shipment of highly radioactive artifacts
that have to be kept in a pure oxygen atmosphere or they\'ll be ruined?
There are a lot of things that don\'t fit in 2-ton standard containers
or that big companies can\'t or won\'t touch. In a real Imperium, the kind
of trade the players deal in would probably constitute less than 1% of
total interplanetary trade. That\'s still a lot of money...

Ethan
',
