    'body' => 'pbertigl@io.com (Paolo Bertiglia) wrote:

>Why the container storage must ever be inside a ship?

The ship may need to re-enter atmosphere, and the freight containers,
while tough, might also find the extra micro-meteoroid protection useful.
Traveller ships can get to quite fast speeds.  Otherwise, yeah, it
doesn\'t need to be inside if the containers can withstand vaccuum
for a week.

Incidentally, this brings up another freight quirk in Traveller that
people might be interested in.  According to the rules, usually
freight taken on in orbit is delivered when it reaches orbit of the
destination world, and freight taken on on-planet is delivered when
it reaches the surface of the destination world.  For most shipping
to class A/B/C starports, this works great, since those ports have
high-ports and shuttle service.

But here\'s an old trader trick to get some extra cash.  Take on a
shipment bound for a class D/E/X starport in orbit.  Fly it to the
destination under the standard shipping contract, where the freight
is legally delivered when it reaches orbit, and charge the shipper
shuttle fees to land the freight.  If the ship is an unstreamlined
old sub liner shuttling the passengers and cargo down with its\'
small craft, doing this becomes understandable.

Another comment, on container scale -- the 54 cubic meter containers 
from the fat trader are roughly the size of a trailer for a twenty
foot trailer truck that you might see on the road.   
 
