    'body' => '>Do you think there would be the equivalent of cruise ships?
>Just big ol\' ships that people take trips on, not so much to get anywhere,
>but to just to hang out and relax for a while. I have these visions of
>Capt. Stuebing on the Tukera Princess... how exciting and new.

For an interesting take on this, read Norman Spinrad\'s _The Void
Captain\'s Tale_, which details some of the doings of the captain of
what in some respects is a "cruise ship", and of the "floating
kultura" of people who take the cruises. (One might also look at his
_Child of Fortune_ for a look at a particular type of "traveller".)

I too was wondering just what it is people _do_ on these one-week jump
periods. Maintenance? Keeping the books? Studying? Excercise?  There
has to be some way of keeping travellers from dying of boredom.
That\'s what stewards are for, I guess.

I think a lot of SF fans, when they think of "the romance of space"
and "the adventure of planetary colonization", are assuming it\'s like
the experience of people crossing the Atlantic on sailing ships and
starting colonies in the New World, where in all actuality it would be
like travelling in a submerged nuclear submarine to set up a camp in
Antarctica during the winter. In space, you can\'t go up on deck; on
many colony planets, you can\'t go outside without a pressure suit, and
going off into the wilderness is an invitation to a messy death.

-- 
Erich Schneider  erich@bush.cs.tamu.edu  http://bush.cs.tamu.edu/~erich
