Well, in the 18-19th centuries, most passengers passed the time on ship
with on board games: it seem\'s probable that a culture based on jump 
would have a mind-boggling amount and variety of activities to do on 
board, ranging from prayer sessions (you\'d be surprised how many people 
think that jump space is somehow supernatural) to Virutal Reality 
seminars.  I suspect that many people will just watch their favourate TV 
shows, or gather around a coffee table and just chat their way through 
the week in jspace.

All spacer are extremely wary of children onboard, while in jspace.  
Bored out of their skull\'s, they are certain to devise some form of 
`diversion\' that could spell TROUBLE... especially if the kids are 
from a space station, and know how to `hot wire\' the saftey\'s...

> Do PCs have to have certain physical characteristics
> that make them especially good space dwellers (eg. they don\'t vomit when
> ever they end up in zero-g)? 

Well, few spacers suffer from jump sickness.  They are likely to 
have a feel for their ship.  Anything else?

> Is living on a navy ship with a crew on the
> order of 30,000 people anywhere near the experience of living on 200-ton
> free trader?

It\'s very, very different in almost every way imaginable.  It\'s the 
difference between living in a small, steel city and a small, steel 
apartment.

Moreover, since so many Imperials are used to living in artifical 
enviroment\'s, I suspect that many would feel quite comfortable living on a 
Imperial capital ship.  Social character\'s, especially. 

> Basically, while the PCs aren\'t necessarily the Buzz Aldrins and Neil 
> Armstrongs of the Imperium, they aren\'t the average office workers either.
> Where do they fit in? What sort of attitudes do planet-bound people have
> about space and "travellers"?

Free Traders are likely to be viewed as "tailess/furless Vargr" by the 
general Imperial public, and "lowlife criminal scum" by the Navy.  These 
people are just too deeply involved in too many shady deals to have a good 
reputation.

The above is the viewpoint of officaldom and mainline Vilani and 
near-Vilani systems (mainly, systems within the borders of the First 
Imperium).  In Solomani-dominant areas (conquered regions of the Solomani 
Sphere, and the Domain of Deneb) the image tend\'s to be strongly 
romantizied... after all, Solomani Sphere folk have little love for the 
Imperium, and Domain people - the frontier folk of the Imperium - like to 
root for the `little guy\', and have a high tolerance for irregular 
activity.  They tend to view Free Traders as the Han Solo\'s of space, 
(usually) good people at heart but too free to follow megacorp routine.

> Do you think there would be the equivalent of cruise ships?
> Just big ol\' ships that people take trips on, not so much to get anywhere,
> but to just to hang out and relax for a while. I have these visions of
> Capt. Stuebing on the Tukera Princess... how exciting and new.

I suspect that there are two kind\'s of ship\'s are to be found.  One kind,
found largely in Core Sector (where shipping companies race each other
to put out the latest and the greatest), is simply the latest in luxury.  
Gold-plated hull\'s, marble computer terminals, ex-Admirals as Captains, 
these are the kind of ship an up-and-coming Noble just *has* to be seen on.

The other kind of cruise ship is found in the equally rich - but 
politically unstable - Solomani Rim Sector.  "Pure Power" is the 
watchword here, with nothing but cutting-edge technology and performance 
levels that wouldn\'t shame a warship.  Usually MUCH smaller than their 
massive Core brother\'s (about 10-20,000 Disp tons, compared to the 
100,000 - 500,000 Disp level\'s), these are the ship of choice for yachts 
for sector-level Dukes to the more important Count\'s.

Both ship\'s can be found on regular routes in Gushemege, Dagudashaag, 
Zarushagar and Massilia sectors.  Core-style ship\'s dominate Core and 
Vland sectors; Solomani-style ships dominate, well, the Solomani 
Rim.  True cruisers (in contrast to expensive liners, which isn\'t into
sightseeing) are rarely seen elsewhere in the Imperium, and are almost 
always Solomani-style.

> Just wondering, 
> Ethan

