    'body' => 'Yo,
 Ethan asked: Who lives in space?
 In my own campaign there are "races" of people
who primarily live in space. I put "race" in quotes
because it becomes hard to differentiate a race from
a culture. Some share a culture because they all do
common jobs in common conditions. Some share a gene
pool for similar reasons. Lets look at each.
 Traders. Known racially as "macarim". These are
the owners and operators of the various sall to middling
trade concerns and space ships. [Sort of a bastrardised
cross between Hobbits and Medieval Jews.] They tend to
be distinct both socailly and (consequently?) genetically.
The best merchant crew is one born and raised to it
so they perpetuate their place. They are quite clannish
as who you know is very important in their business.
They almost always have a "cousin" who can get what you
need.
 Many of them never set foot on a planet. Most
would never want to. Stations are stopovers and
sources of income. Compare them with the people who
run canal barges in the Low Countries of Europe.
 Belters. This just doesn\'t cover asertoid miners
but basically most of the space-based industrial
raw material culture. They are pretty much limited to
their own selves for socialisation and, again, thus
become self-perpetuating. Take modern oil-rig workers
and take it to the logical conclusion.
 Navy. This is a polyglot culture. Although Navy
brats tend to become Navy recruits their cultural values
tend to driver them more towards recruitment and adsorbtion
rather than self reproduction. Since a recruit may almost
never see their homeworld again (or, at best, infrequently)
they are embraced and absorbed within the Navy "culture"
as a point to focus on. Later it becomes their primary
cultural identity.
 Scouts. This is both like, and unlike, the Navy.
Although rather promiscuous and prolific, Scout children
don\'t often become Scouts. The Scouts rush to embrace and
support any cultural quirk that anyone has. This, in itself,
become their defining "culture". Their over-tolerance
of all cultures and their attempts to personally "get into"
each makes them what they are.

 In addition to their own "cultures" each of the
above also has their own language or dialect of standard.
This arises naturally from a need to adsorb people from
all different linguistic backgrounds and also from the
derivation of profession specific words, etc.

    Jo
