>the heat of public disapproval off the Emperor, as far as I know.  The 
>Solomani Autonomous Region had been established in 704, at the opposite 
>side of the Imperium from the most dangerous psi insts.  Were people 
>blaming the Emperor for "losing the Solomani Rim"?

(complete speculation) Two words: Hivers. Oh yes, you thought they were
cute little starfish who didn\'t know when you had bad B.O., but they\'re
actually quite smart.

The hivers created most of the evidence used by unwitting Imperial agents
in the supressions and dismantling of the psionic institutes in Imperial
space. While many institutes were partly funded by Zhodani agents, many
were run by independent Imperials. Evidence was fabricated and much of it
was distorted truth - one Zhodani visit becase heavy Zhodani funding, etc.

Why?

Increased acceptance of psionics by Imperial citizens would lead eventually
to a larger number of Zhodani/Imperial client states on the borders, leading
eventually to Imperial worlds voluntarily joining the Consulate and
embracing its philosophies.

Zhodani political and social culture has proved itself to be the most
successful model of human society ever and a large influx of willing
Imperials into it would mean increased human stability for centuries
to come.

On the other hand, if the Imperium were to remain intact, its social
structure would collapse under the pressure of its size, in the same
way that all previous Imperia (??) had already given way.

SO - if the Imperials could be made to reject the most basic tenent of
Zhodani culture, what would happen?

Warfare along the Zhodani/Imperial border, stressing the Imperium and
internal Imperial stresses exaggerated by increasing acceptance of Zhodani
culture, resulting in the eventual collapse of the Imperium.

Looks like they got it right.

Why would the Hivers want the Imperium to collapse?

Continued Imperial military activity along the Solmani border is dangerous
to the Hivers, as it comes very close to their border.

Continued Imperial expansion along all borders represents a danger to
the Hivers, as they cannot hope to prevent increased Imperial control
of worlds along their border, either through settlement, economic
means or warfare.

Not to mention the opportunities that would be created by a full-scale
interstellar war. The Hivers sell a lot of high-tech equipment which would
be hard to come by in those, pardon the expression, Hard Times.

That\'s my take on it. The Hivers were scared of the eventual Imperial/
Zhodani cultural merging, which would have signed the papers for human
domination of that part of the galaxy. I mean, can you blame them?

Ethan

PS Ever wonder what\'s on those other borders with the Aslan, Zhodani, Hivers,
K\'kree and Vargr? There must be _something_ out there...
