    'body' => '>Warfare along the Zhodani/Imperial border, stressing the Imperium and
>internal Imperial stresses exaggerated by increasing acceptance of Zhodani
>culture, resulting in the eventual collapse of the Imperium.

This didn\'t come out right. What I meant was:

a) Warfare along the Zho/Imp border, stressing the Imperium and
b) internal Imperial stresses that would have been soothed by gradual
    acceptance of Zhodani philosophies would now be exaggerated
c) resulting in the eventual collapse of the Imperium.

But I\'m sure you got my drift.

To elaborate my point let\'s look at Hiver border and Imperial borders
and where the Imperium and Hivers have a position for expansion - be it
by conqureing worlds, absorbing populated worlds or economic expansion
(increased trade).

Hivers:

Hiver/K\'kree - the Hivers dealt with this one a while ago. The K\'kree
now have a heavy dislike of any dealings with the Hivers. Neither side
wants to touch this border.

Hiver/Solomani - This is basically the same as the Imperium as far as
the Hivers are concerned. The solomani look at this border as a place for
expansion, as do the Hivers, to a lesser degree.
For the Hivers, this border needs to be dealt with somehow.
The best way is by being friendly and making the Solomani look elsewhere
for military targets and general expansion - preferably the Imperium.
The Hivers are content here to settle for economic expansion.

Imperials: (lots)

Imperial/Solomani - volatile border. Must keep patrolled with a heavy
military presence. Most planets in this region are already settled
and none would willingly join the Imperium. No chance for expansion
by either side without major war.

Imperial/Aslan - the main problem here is those damn Ihatei constantly
trucking across the voids and claiming land on Impy planets or claiming
whole planets. War would be unplesant for both sides. The void make it
difficult to expand in this region.

Imperial/Vargr - not a real border per se, but Vargr raiders are a 
pain in the ass along Corridor. A heavy military presence must be
kept to keep Corridor safe for Imperial traffic. The combination of the
void here and excessive Vargr corsairs make this region undesirable
for expansion.

Imperial/K\'kree - no real border here, as there is a large client state
buffer area. The K\'kree have good technology, but due to the massive size 
of their ships, pose a low military threat to the Imperium (by tonnage,
Imperial ships heavily outgun K\'kree ships.) Expansion in this area is 
difficult, due to mixed K\'kree and human influences.

Imperial/Zhodani - the Zhodani would just as well leave this alone, but
Imperial expansion along this border is a problem. The Imperials have a
dislike of Zhodani culture, as well as a general acceptance of killing other 
humans, so find this battle an easy one to justify.
If the psionic supressions had not happened, this border would be quite
the opposite - a place where the best parts of Zhodani and Imperial culture
might have mixed, creating a stable region of new Zhodani worlds, 
independent client states and Imperial worlds friendly to the Zhodani.
This would help relieve the military pressure in this area, allowing
more fleets to deal with the Vargr and Aslan borders.

Finally,

Imperial/Hiver - the Hivers have a history of disliking war. The Imperials
have a history of liking war and being damn good at it. The Imperials
also have a massive military that any minor technological advantage by
the Hivers can not offset. There are some client states in this area as
well, but absorbing them would give the Imperials even more border with
the Solomani, giving the Imperials a better tactical position. (This is
debatable I think, but, what the heck). Also, the Imperium would like to 
have many parts of Hiver technology without having to buy it.

SO:

If there was peace along the Imp/Zho border, making the Marches and Corridor
less of a headache, the Imperium would be looking long and hard at taking
control of a fair chunk of Hiver space.

If there was friction along the Imp/Zho border, intermittent wars would cause
enough trouble in the Imperium to eventually drag it down into the pits.
Ignoring the Hivers the entire time, of course, except for all the supplies
and technology the Hivers would sell to the them.

QED.

(I wasn\'t satisfied with having an entire xboat digest to myself - I had to
come
back for more. You may think this sounds like a wacky conspiracy theory,
but I have grainy 8mm film footage of Strephon being shot. Dulinor shot
everyone
EXCEPT Strephon and was going to force him to hand the throne over,
but on a grassy knoll just off to the side, the Hiver ambassador pulled out
a high powered rifle and shot Strephon, ruining Dulinor\'s plans. To quote
Dulinor - "I\'m just a patsy.")

Ethan
