    'topic' => 'Grav Skateboards, Design Alternatives, & Containers',
    'body' => 'Yo Folkes,
      A question came up last night during Paranoia:
"How much would a grav-skateboard be?" After thinking
for a moment I decided that the MegaTraveller "vehicle"
generation should be able to handle this...
      We decied not to let price be a question and
first used TL12 grav. The minimum size for a grav
drive yielded 200 kg of thrust. This is *more* than
adequate for a grav-skateboard. (Unless it is for
a K\'Kree or something :-) Batteries were the best
option for power and the "hull" could be "open topped"
and armour-1 (fibreglass?). In the end our "vehicle"
came out as:
      Vol: 4ltr, Wt: 3.1kg, Thrust: 200kg,
      Duration: 1 hour, Cost: 30854Cr.
This was nice, but expensive. So next I tried using
the cheapest grav (TL 9). The minimum size here
resulted in 1000kg of thrust, a bit high, but
allowed for (K\'Kree users and) possible conversion
by a hobbiest into a grav-go-cart. It was also
a bit heavy and rather large. The result was
a quarter the price, though.
      The mid-range grav (TL10) was a bit slimmer,
a bit trimmer, and in the middle cost-wize. Here
is a summary table:

Grav Skateboard:
TL  Vol   Wt   Thrust Duration Price
9   40ltr 68kg 1000kg 7.6min    8,532Cr
10  30ltr 26kg  400kg 1 hour   15,280Cr
12   4ltr  3kg  200kg 1 hour   30,854Cr

 The way the pricing doubles every increment
makes for a good upgrade path for the hobbiest.
If you take 1Cr=1$ it is still reservedn for the
rather well off but if you take 10Cr=1Pound, as
I do, it become achievable to many more. (Just look
at how much one of those more advanced radio
controled planes or cars is!)
 At the lower exchange rate grav-skateboard
parks are supportable as well as clubs and
league events.

 Another alternative: I allow another type
of "thrust suspension" that doesn\'t work off
a grav drive, but rather reacts to an artificial
gravity field. Basically it distorts the field
to provide "thrust" or whatever. I assume
cargo palettes work this way as well as mobile
cargo winches (which you can anchor in thin air :-).
Of course all these are useless on a ship without
artifical gravity or a planet. (The characters had
an "anchor" built into the hilt of one of her
swords, "just in case".)
 I\'ve never thought about stats for how to
construct "vehicles" with these gizmos but if I
do, I can post it. (Unless someone else beats me
to it.

 Another idea I\'ve never had time to play
around with is something out of MERP. At the
begining of <something> Law there are tables
given for producing items that are smaller,
lighter, or stronger than normal. So if you
wanted something, say, 20% lighter you could
pay twice the cost for it. I think 100-95%
smaller was 1000x the cost.
 What effect would this have on vehicles
if this were applied to the MegaTraveller
design system? (I can find and post the table.)
 Rob Dean, you\'ve designed a lot of vehicles.
What sort of components would be worth making
smaller/lighters dispite a possible increase
in cost?
 Steve Higginbotham, you\'ve worked with
TCS a lot. How might this apply there and
what sort of effect do you predict?

 Lastly, the skateboard nonsense lead me
thinking. If a modern container is 8x8x20/40
that\'s just a 36.25/72.5 kl hull. I might play
with the design system and design some modern
containers.
 Strikes me if there is a standard container
size there will be all sorts of "extra modules"
you can plug into your cargo hold. E.g. a
"passenger module" that allows you to take on
an extra passenger, ...

   Jo Grant
