    'body' => 'Jo:

>  Another idea I\'ve never had time to play
> around with is something out of MERP. At the
> begining of <something> Law there are tables
> given for producing items that are smaller,
> lighter, or stronger than normal. So if you
> wanted something, say, 20% lighter you could
> pay twice the cost for it. I think 100-95%
> smaller was 1000x the cost.

>  Steve Higginbotham, you\'ve worked with
> TCS a lot. How might this apply there and
> what sort of effect do you predict?

    I allowed this kind of thing as a research item in the Islands game.
There were only two items researched - M-drives and computers.  And
smaller computers aren\'t really relevant to MT.
    There are really only two starship components in MT that are worth
paying for to get smaller items: power plants and M-drives.  Both are
a large part of any warship (usually the largest two pieces other than
the fuel supply), and they collectively provide a large part of the 
limiting factors for weaponry on warships.
    It is also possible that a smaller spinal mount weapon would be
desirable.  I tend to think not - most ships carrying spinal mounts
are large enough to have room to spare.

    What I would really expect to see is more and better fighters at
lower TLs.  By TL15, you don\'t really need the extra room, but the
lower TL fighters (TL12-14) would become a lot more competitive if
extra money could go toward fitting more hardware into a fighter-sized
hull.
    These "better" ships from TL12-14 would apply for all ship sizes
that could be imagined, but it isn\'t too likely that it would be worth 
the loss of tonnage implied by raising individual prices significantly.
Note that TL12-14 ships already cost more than a similarly sized TL15
ship.  Quite a lot more.  So a TL13 world will already have a smaller
Fleet than a comparable TL15 world.  Making that worse would not be a
terribly bright idea, given the relatively small gains to be made by
the trade-off.
    Note, btw, that allowing smaller components (in exchange for more
credits) will encourage higher ships with about one higher jump number
than "normal" for a given TL...

    A more militarily significant change would be to allow the manufacture
of better computers at lower TLs in exchange for extra tonnage and LOTS
of extra money.  That would be significant enough that everyone who wanted
to be competitive in the Great Game would buy into it to the extent that
the budget would allow...

                ----Steve

PS.  Y\'all have a nice Mardi Gras, now...:-)


