    'body' => 'pete.burke@compudata.com (PETE BURKE) writes:

>2) Did DGP ever come out with The Black Duke? I don\'t remember seeing 
>ANY adventures produced by DGP except in the Traveller\'s Digest.

_The Black Duke_ never came out, but they did come out with _The
Flaming Eye_, an adventure in the Ziru Sirkaa.

>3) What is the structure of the Julian Protectorate? I can\'t seem to 
>find much info about them. How long have they been in existence? I 
>remember seeing something about a Julian War. I was wondering if there 
>was any official (or unofficial) source that has detailed the Julian 
>Protectorate. What kind of Government do they have? What is their 
>feeling toward the Imperium?

_Challenge_ #49 has an extensive article on the Protectorate,
including a map of Mendan sector. Humans and Vargr have lived in that
region since the Rule of Man, but the JP itself dates from the Julian
War (it\'s named after Julian Menderes, a charismatic head of the
Menderes megacorp, a powerful player in the region). The War was a
Pacification Campaign-style attempt to reincorporate the "coreward
Makhidkarun territories" that met very stiff resistance (eventually
leading to extensive penetration into Antares sector before peace was
declared - an embarassment the Imperium prefers to gloss over).

The government is somewhat like that of the Solomani Confederation,
but less centralized and without the odious totalitarian
aspects. Basically, the Protectorate provides a dispute resolution
structure, trade regulation mechanisms, and crisis military force for
a group of variously-sized member states (ranging from interstellar
polities to nations on balkanized worlds). Protectorate states are
characterized by generally close cooperation between humans and Vargr;
the headquarters world, Asimikigir, has a true dual-species culture.
This is in contrast to the second-rate organization of the region, the
Third Empire of Gashikan, which has a long history of Vargr-hatred
(originating with the Sack of Gashikan, when said world was looted by
Vargr and attacked with nuclear weapons). 

The JP has generally positive relations with the Imperium but
agressively maintains its own identity as a polity. With the
Rebellion, they tended to support Brzk; they have close ties with that
region of the Imperium, and the Antares region was briefly a JP member
state. 

>9) Terra is two parsecs from the nearest system (according to Library 
>Data N-Z).  How did they skip jump-1 and go right to jump-2?

They didn\'t - they just made two jump-1 jumps. The US Space Force
constructed (over an extended period) a refueling depot about one
parsec out from Terra, which was used as a stopping-off point for the
USSF mission to Barnard\'s Star (under UN Space Coordinating Agency
auspices). But as well all know, what was to be a triumphant
demonstration of American technology encountered something much
bigger...

-- 
Erich Schneider  erich@bush.cs.tamu.edu  http://bush.cs.tamu.edu/~erich
