    'body' => 'PETE BURKE asks, inter alia:

>4) Are there Imperial Courts to handle Imperial Law? Where are they (or 
>how often do they occur: 1 per sector?, 1 per subsector?).

I don\'t think that there is any canon on this point.  I\'m now writing an
article for submission to the Traveller Chronicle addressing law and
justice in the Imperium.  You can consider the following a work in
progress:

In my own games, there is a well developed and rather complex, but still
quite small, Imperial judiciary.  In general, the Imperial courts have
original jurisdiction over admiralty (any litigation involving spacecraft),
Imperial criminal law (like importing Hiver warbots), and other matters of
Imperial edict, as well as appellate jurisdiction over
regulatory adjudicative bodies (like the Ministry of Spacers\' Health and
Safety), the highest manorial courts (courts run by the landed nobility),
and any issues of violation of the rights of Imperial citizens.  

The sheer number of admiralty cases mandates a lot of Imperial courts. 
Usually, these are funded the local nobility, but the judges still owe fealty
directly to the Emperor, not the sector dukes.

I recently posted some other ideas to this list, in response to questions
posed by Alvin Plummer.  I don\'t remember in which digests, however.

>7) (text deleted) Who makes up the Imperial Army and what are it\'s [sic]
>duties? Is it the Army of Capital/Core?

I think that Steve Higginbotham described the Imperial Army as command
formations and cadre that were filled in by local reserves in wartime.  This
sounds reasonable to me.  In Fifth Frontier War, the Imperial Army starts
with a few brigades and regiments (the Marines are all regiments), but
after a while the Rimward Forces begin to arrive.  I think that the Rimward
Forces are local troops, perhaps up to army group level (like Porozlo\'s
XXXX unit), with regular Imperial army personnel in the higher
command and liaison functions.  Again, I refer you to earlier digests, but I
don\'t know exactly which ones.  Maybe Steve does.

>8) Am I asking too many questions?

I don\'t think it\'s possible to ask too many questions.

>9) Terra is two parsecs from the nearest system (according to Library 
>Data N-Z).  How did they skip jump-1 and go right to jump-2?

The first jumps were within the solar systems -- microjumps, in effect.

