Pete Burke aks:

>2) Did DGP ever come out with The Black Duke? I don\'t remember
>seeing
>ANY adventures produced by DGP except in the Traveller\'s Digest.

As already mentioned, the Black Duke was never published, but DGP\'s other
produ
ct, the Flaming Eye, was. Also, GDW\'s Knightfall was written by Joe D.
Fugate,

Sr., and so in essense could be considered a DGP product (the quality of this
p
roduct is far superior to normal GDW standards, and closely resembles the
quali
ty one would expect from DGP)

>4) Are there Imperial Courts to handle Imperial Law? Where are they (or
>how often do they occur: 1 per sector?, 1 per subsector?).

As this issue has never been discussed much in official Traveller or
MegaTravel
ler material, it has been necessary to make up a thing or two. One must keep
in
 mind, that imperial law mostly (if not only) applies to the space between
worl
ds. Thus, in most cases, local law will apply.

In my games, imperial law is the jurisdiction of the landed nobility. Putting
t
he judiciary responsibilities in the hands of a (mainly) hereditary group of
pe
ople may not seem to ensure fairness, but on the other hand, it\'s not a
perfect
 world.

In practise I would say that the noble person in question presides as a judge
o
ver a court consisting of civil servants and/or military personnel, depending
o
n the issue involved. You can consider this as an Imperial Court. The way I
han
dle them, they do not exist as permanent institutions, but only on an ad hoc
ba
sis. Thus, the question of how many there are, can\'t meaningfully be
answered.

Now these are just my idiosyncratic views, but I agree in general with
sudet@we
ll.sf.ca.us concerning jurisdiction.
