ahead.

There is sufficient evidence in MT to conclude that Solomani hostilities
towards the Imperium following Strephon\'s assasination was _NOT_ a planned
operation by the Solomani Confderation civillian government.

We have to assume that the Confederation\'s intelligence assets where
efficient enough to learn of the assasination, and escape the Imperial
capitol before that system was closed to traffic.  To do otherwise is to
assume complete incompetance on the part of their intelligence apparatus.

Now, consider the best possible transit time for the news of Strephon\'s
assination from the capital of the Imperium to the capital of the
Confederation.  Allow a reasonable (even if short) time for debate on the
proper response by the Confederation.  Now compute the transit time _back_
to the border systems of the Confederation from which the attack would have
to be launched, and you can arrive at the earliest possible date for the
attack to begin.

Compare your results against the published materials, and you will discover
that Solomani forces had _already_ attacked the Imperium, _before_ any
possible decision could have reached them from the central government!  

After having eliminated the impossible (a central, considered decision to go
to war), what remains must be the truth: Either the Solomani Confederation
had a general order of long standing that the war was to be resumed upon the
death of Emporer Strephon, OR one or more officers on the border recieved
the information concerning the Emporer\'s death and acted on his (or her) own
initiative to resume hostilities (!).

Either that, or it\'s all a hiver plot.  ;-)


