    'body' => 'The mail rules in Traveller are a bit vaque.  I don\'t know where I 
remember the following from, but I think it is correct.  To carry mail, 
you need a mail contract, which I take to mean a contract with the local 
Postal Union, an type ofinstitution vaguely mentioned in the Library Data 
(MT Imperial Encyclopedia).  To hold a contract, the vessel concerned 
must be armed (in order to protect the mail) and have sufficient gunners 
to operate the weaponry.  I also assume that ship captains & crews would 
be vetted for their reliability, so that for example ex-Navy crew would 
find it easier to get a contract.  Some reasonable ship-board security 
against hijacking would also be in order.  I seem to remember that 
Subsidised vessels were favoured, presumably because they could be relied 
upon to serve a given area regularly.

In my game, I restrict mail to 54 kilitre blocks, which is a standard 
transport crate.  I add the population of the source world to that of the 
destination world, and roll 2D10; DM -1 if travelling to or from an xboat 
route, but +2 if travelling between 2 worlds on an xboat route.  If the 
roll is less than the sum of the populations, then there is a mail crate 
waiting to go.  The mail is sealed in the crate, and may or may not 
actually be 54 klitres in volume; regardless, the payment is Cr. 20 000, 
and the volume is 54 klitres of hold space.

In Starship Operators Manual, one of the "Old Timer" anecdotes refers to 
a scam involving the mail.  As a crate did\'t get sent if there wasn\'t 
enough mail to fill it to a certain fraction.  Thus, a ship captain would 
find out how much mail was waiting, and if it was close but not quite 
close enough, he would post a load of bogus packages to his next 
destination.  As the postage on such a small fraction of the total mail 
load was small compared to the payment for shipping the entire crate, he 
could ensure a profit.  However, he was caught out when he realised that 
if he put dodgy addresses on, the packages would be returned, and he 
could get paid twice for only one set of postage.  As the return 
addresses were dodgy too, the post office ended up opening the parcels 
and realised what was happening.  An investigation ensued, and the gready 
ship captain was caught.  At least, that\'s how I remember it!

