    'index' => 'aa977',
    'body' => 'Ethan Henry:
>The Imperium isn\'t at _war_ with either the Vargr or Aslan, so, for the most
>part, the Imperial Navy is required to respect Imperial borders. Vargr
>raiders can\'t be chased back to their bases. Vargr corsairs jump out,
>slap a few merchants around and head home. A little cunning, a few drop
tanks
>and those big old battleships can\'t do much to stop them. The Imperial 
>Navy is designed to scare off major intruders and fight major battles,
>not to chase penny-ante Vargr around.

You\'re missing the point. By \'menace\' I\'m not talking about the 400 T
Corsairs that snap up a merchant once in a while (The small pirates are
another painful subject. I want them to be possible, but the dynamics of
jump travel and the spacing of inhabited worlds are against them... but
let that lie. Even if they had a realistic basis for existence they 
wouldn\'t be a menace). I\'m talking about those mythical raiders who attack 
actual Imperial planets and defeat Imperial starships. They just can\'t
exist. Anything big enough to be a threat needs the facilities of a base
world, and any such world can be treated like the US Navy treated the
Barbary States. The Imperial subsector fleets alone are strong enough
to deal with anything the Vargr can come up with. (OK, they may need to
borrow a regular fleet to retaliate).

>As for Aslan, they\'re annoying in a long-term way. They drop several tens
>of thousands of Aslan down in an uninhabitated part of an Imperial world,
>which isn\'t _that_ big a deal. Until they do it to every world along the
>Imperial/Aslan border. And they start taking more land. And pretty soon,
>you have a lot of Aslan under Imperial rule - for now.

Again you\'re missing the point. Leaving aside the fact that the Imperial
Navy is perfectly capable of intercepting those Aslans before they drop,
such settlers are not a threat. In fact, Aslans are in many way just the
kind of subjects that a ruler dreams about. Loyal. So what you do if you
have missed a drop is to go visit the _ihatei_ lord and demand he swears
fealthy to Norris in exchange for letting him stay on the land (Because
the Navy IS strong enough to boot out any single settlement). Then you
charge him with the responsibility of defending those lands against other
_ihatei_. And Presto Chango you\'ve got a border guard instead of an
invader.

>Vargr, maybe not. While they might not do a lot of damage in a military
>sense, they can play real havoc with trade and shipping in the area.

No they can\'t. The Imperial Navy is plenty big enough to make the life of
a pirate very hard. Place one 30.000 T Cruiser at the 100 diameter limit
of each world and the merchants have a safe spot to jump to and from. And
do you know how many cruisers the Imperial Navy budget runs to? (Btw. I 
don\'t mean to say that a single cruiser is the optimum way to protect a 
star system. I think some orbital forts with fighter bays would be more 
like it. But the cruisers will work.)

>The smaller the ship, the better. (Gee, don\'t _players_ usually have small
>ships?) 

Yep. That\'s the painful part of it. The PCs can\'t get away with piracy
either.

>Not to mention that mercenaries fighting Vargr units have to worry
>that the Vargr might not follow the Imperial rules of war. No more
>surrender and activate the repatreation bond - you\'re going to die.

What mercenaries? The Imperial Navy will make sure no Vargr ever reaches 
orbit, much less the surface.

>As for the Aslan, yeah, it probably is crisis mongering, at least before
>the Collapse. There are probably a lot of Aslan under Imperial rule and
>they don\'t have any problem with it. Aren\'t there a fair number of Aslan
>in the Darrian confederation that have served them in the past as
mercenaries?
>Promise them a little land and those Aslan will probably fight like hell...

How right you are.


