>From: Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
> 
>(major snippage)
> 
>*>Vargr, maybe not. While they might not do a lot of damage in a military
>*>sense, they can play real havoc with trade and shipping in the area.
> 
>*No they can\'t. The Imperial Navy is plenty big enough to make the life
>*of a pirate very hard. Place one 30.000 T Cruiser at the 100 diameter
>*limit of each world and the merchants have a safe spot to jump to and
>*from.
> 
>A couple of years ago, a freighter carrying illegal Chinese immigrants 
>sailed into San Francisco Bay.  It passed by TWO Coast Guard stations, the 
>Treasure Island Navy Base, NAS Alameda, the Golden Gate Maritime Radar 
>Station, and any number of commercial ferrys and container ships.
>The first person to realize that something was *wrong* was a military 
>policeman at The Presidio, who saw the freighter beach itself.  

Did it fire on anything on its way in? Did it fire on anything after it
got in? Did it capture any prizes? Most importantly, did it fight its way 
out (with its prize) past two Coast Guard stations and a Navy base? I think 
not.

What happened to the next ship that tried the same stunt? 

>To assume that every Vargr raider is going to announce itself from the 
>moment of breakout is silly. 

Certainly. But then, I don\'t assume so. And it is nowhere as silly as
believing that anyone can make a living (as in "surviving for any length 
of time") out of playing tag with a 30,000 T cruiser or the equivalent.
Remember, piracy is a career. You survive being a pirate by a) Capturing
valuable prizes more or less intact, b) Avoiding getting withing shooting 
range of a regular warship, and c) having a safe place to hide and dispose
of the loot. The Imperial Navy is big enough to make the first two 
incompatible and strong enough to treat any Vargr border nation like the
US treated the Barbary States if they try to provide the third (Though
I\'ll grant you that there are ways around that).

A smart Vargr leader will hijack an Imperial-design 
>ship, take it back to the Extents, and plug as many weapons as they can 
>into the hull.

Recipe for roast moose: First you catch a moose...

But, leaving aside the first step (catching the first ship), what then?
You jump into the system. You bluff the Planetary Guard into thinking you
a harmless merchant ship. You get assigned a flight path that dosen\'t take 
you near any other merchant. You get inspected by the Customs Service...

Now what?

>(snip)
>*What mercenaries? The Imperial Navy will make sure no Vargr ever
>*reaches orbit, much less the surface.
> 
>The most popular joke in the bomb shelters of Berlin in 1942 was "where is 
>Meyer?"  This referred to Goering\'s promise that: "if a single bomb falls 
>on Berlin, you can call me Meyer!"  At the time, the Nazis thought that 
>there was no way Allied bombers could reach the German heartland...
>unfortunately, they had never heard of the B-17....
>My point is simple, where there is a will, there is a way.

And my point is even simpler: Where do you find the will? Vargr may be more 
impetuous than humans, but they couldn\'t have survived 300,000 years if they 
were suicidal. Piracy is not a viable way of living except in rare conditions
where you find merchant ships in areas with few naval ships to protect them. 
In out of the way places. And thanks to the jump drive each stellar system 
is effectively ONE place. That means that the Domain worlds bordering on the 
Vargr Extents are, what?, 100, 200 places in all. And the Imperial Navy has 
a lot more than 200 ships. A LOT more. A humongous lot more. I mean, you may
think there\'s a lot of peanuts in a 50-kg sack, but that\'s just...

So you might have smart criminals capturing a merchant ship every once in
a while by relying on the kind of sloth you gave an example of above. A
once in a lifetime coup for each gang that sets them up for life, even. But
a whole corsair industry like the Carrebean Buccaneers or the Barbary
Pirates? I\'m afraid not.

Now, if the drive was a warp drive so that pirates could lurk between stars
and intercept merchants then things might be different.


