    'index' => 'aa993',
    'topic' => ' Legality - A reality-check',
    'body' => 'On Tue, 14 Mar 1995, Jo Grant wrote:

> like America (although unfortunately this attitude seems
> to prevail books, literature, and games) perhaps a more global
> view should be taken.
>  What\'s it like in Canada, Sweden, Germany, and Finland?
> I\'ve seen people post from these countries. Tell us what law
> levels outside of the US are like.

Well, in Canada at least, there are some pretty heavy restrictions on the 
ownership of private firearms, especially handguns. Shotguns and hunting 
rifles used to be exempt from registration, but no longer. Handguns are 
restricted and controlled heavily. There are no CCW laws that I am 
currently aware of. In terms of self defence, there is room for 
justifiable homicide...however, incidents such as the Japanese exchange 
student in the US getting blown away by a homeowner for trespassing would 
be met with one gargantuan piece of prosecution.

In terms of citizen safety?

Canada has a murder rate of appx 2.5/100,000 compared to the rate of 
about 10.0/100,000 in the United States. Violent crime (as measured in 
the US, which uses four categories, as opposed to the seven utilized by 
Canada) is higher in the US as well.

Property crime, however, is slightly higher in Canada than it is in the 
United States.

What does this mean for future societies? It depends upon what kind of 
model the future goverment is founded on. The United States was born in a 
Revolution, and is found on principles and ideals of individualism, and 
their culture and society reflects this. Depending on how a government 
and society came into being, the Law Level and how the people perceive it 
will be different- In Canada, the attitudes towards gun control are much 
different than they are in the United States, simply due to historical 
and social factors.


