Hans Rancke-Madsen writes:

>So you might have smart criminals capturing a merchant ship every once in
>a while by relying on the kind of sloth you gave an example of above. A
>once in a lifetime coup for each gang that sets them up for life, even. But
>a whole corsair industry like the Carrebean Buccaneers or the Barbary
>Pirates? I\'m afraid not.

Between this and your other post, I have a lot of issues to (try to) 
address, but it\'s going to take some time to make sure the assumptions
I make make sense (ie. I don\'t want to stick my foot in my mouth :).

But just in case anyone else has any input:

1) I don\'t think there will/can be one very secure jump-in point per system.
2) Many systems have a lot of intra-system travel, which could be easier
   to hit, although less lucrative.
3) I don\'t think the subsector/system navies have quite so many ships
   as you propose, although this varies over time.
4) Vargr raiding bases are secure, as Imperials won\'t chase them over the
   border.

While the Imperium is strong, I think it\'s not as overpowering as you
make it out to be - otherwise it would have conquered it\'s neighbours
a long time ago, wouldn\'t it have?
Also, both the Solomani and Zhodani who have overall/maximum tech levels
at least one lower than the Imperium have given them a run for their
money in the various border wars. While they\'d be less organized, who is
to say the Vargr couldn\'t do the same?

Anyways, I shall look further into it as time permits.

Ethan

(Not to mention that source material seems to imply that it does happen,
so it must be possible)
