    'from' => 'Mark Cook markc@PEAK.ORG',
    'topic' => 'RPGs: An *American* viewpoint...',
    'body' => 'In XBOAT Digest 210 Jo Grant <Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com> writes:

> Let some of the non-American readers of the list
> correct me if I am wrong, but I think America is one of
> the few countries on this world where this sort of attitude
> prevails. In Ireland the citizens don\'t have guns (other
> than farmers with hunting rifles and shotguns), the police
> don\'t have guns, and most (but not all) of the criminals
> don\'t have guns. The citizens don\'t want guns, the police
> don\'t want guns and the criminals can\'t get them.

That may be true for Ireland, but what about your neighbor
to the immediate north?  There\'s a country that bears a
striking resemblance to the infant USA about 220 years ago.

> Not every European country is quite up to this standard
> but I think the 2nd Amendment (?) "we have a right to blow
> away tresspassers" attidute is uniquely American.

Perhaps, but the Second Amendment, which, by the way, reads:

"A well-regulated militia being necessary to the security of
 a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear arms
 shall not be infringed."

was deemed to be as relevant in maintaining the nature of the
U.S.A. as it was in forming it.  They reasoned that if the people
needed to throw of the yoke of an oppressive government by force
once, they just might need to do it again.

> Rather than assume future society is all going to look
> like America (although unfortunately this attitude seems
> to prevail books, literature, and games) perhaps a more global
> view should be taken.

It\'s already been done.  FGU marketed a game call Bushido several
years ago, based on feudal Japan.  It was pretty good as I recall.

Perhaps there\'s a reason that so many of the role-playing games
harbor USA-centric mindsets:

1. The games are developed in the U.S. by people saturated with
   with U.S. attitudes and ideals (whether they\'re all U.S. citizens
   or not is immaterial).
2. The U.S. is currently (and has been for decades) the leading
   producer of visual media entertainment (movies, TV series, et.al.).
   A significantly high proportion of these are adventure-theme
   stories, and contain high levels of violence and/or firearms.
3. The U.S. entertainment industry would not consistantly produce
   this type of entertainment if it didn\'t have a *VERY* large
   audience.
4. The U.S. does not necessarily have a more violent history than
   other (European) countries, but it\'s history is certainly more
   well publicized than most other countries.  As a sort of \'thought\'
   experiment, I offer the following: stop a random Japanese citizen
   on the street in Tokyo and ask him about the 19th century U.S.A.
   (you know, cowboys & indians, wagon trains, the railroads\'a comin\'
   through and all that other Hollywood tripe). Then ask him about
   19th century Argentina and see if it illicits as many images.

Besides being the hotbed of RPG development, the U.S. is a *natural*
breeding ground for adventure concepts, by virtual of American fiction
themes and the general lifestyle.  It also offers one of the largest
markets for RPGs as well, and, like Hollywood, it pays to cater to
your biggest audience.  

While taking a global view might be more "enlightened", I doubt it
would last long in the marketplace.  I ask the rest of the readers
of the XBoat Maillist, how likely are you to buy a games with titles
like:

  "Russets & Sodbusters: Roleplaying on an 18th century rural Irish farm"

  - or -

  "Eat your Neighbor: Roleplaying an Ethiopian Famine Victim"

  - or -

  "Swim for Your Life!: Monsoons among the Urban Poor of Bangladesh"

Or did you have something else in mind?  Commodities brokering in
London?  Perhaps roleplaying the owner of a vineyard in the south
of France?  Truck driver in Siberia?  Postal clerk in Milano?  Or
how about a police officer in South Africa? All pulse-pounding
opportunities in roleplaying, I grant you. :^)

BTW, lest you think that I\'m completely married to the requirement
of firearms in an RPG, I feel I should mention that TSR\'s Dungeons
& Dragons is the most widely sold roleplaying game in the world,
and *THEY* hack each other up with swords. :^)

        - Mark C.

