worried about getting blown up by a terrorist bomb.

> but I think the 2nd Amendment (?) "we have a right to blow
> away tresspassers" attidute is uniquely American. 

Actually, the Second Amendment only mentions \'the security of a free State,\'
nothing about trespassers. The legality of shooting criminals in
self-defense is _not_ uniquely American, though--America got it from
England, where self defense was respected for centuries before America was
colonized. Things only changed in England in the 1920\'s when Parliament got
scared by the idea of a Communist takeover, and decided to disarm the people
as a preventive measure. 70 years later, most English subjects don\'t even
remember the way things used to be.

>  Rather than assume future society is all going to look
> like America ... perhaps a more global
> view should be taken. 

Agreed. On the subject of Traveller law level, though, America is
unfortunately _not_ that different from most other countries--our
"representatives" have been rushing ever faster to embrace just the sort of
oppresive laws found elsewhere. Laws do vary within the U.S., but within my
grandparents\' lifetime, the law level for the majority of Americans has gone
from 0 to around 4-5. Since most worlds in Traveller seem to have rather
high law levels, I\'d say this trend is already being reflected nicely.

And Spider writes:

> incidents such as the Japanese exchange 
> student in the US getting blown away by a homeowner for trespassing would 
> be met with one gargantuan piece of prosecution. 

Yoshi Hattori, the student in question, was shot for making threatening
moves _while_ trespassing. That aside, the man who shot him would have been
met with prosecution in any American city outside of Texas--where it\'s legal
to shoot someone just for trespassing at night.

> In terms of citizen safety?

Actually, no gun (or armour) control laws have ever reduced crime in any
place (inside the U.S. or outside) they have been tried. Indeed, there is
considerable reason to believe that they _increse_ crime. The crime rate in
any society will depend on the general passiveness of that society, and on
the lengths to which the government is willing (and able) to go. 

Of course, Traveller law levels aren\'t only about gun control--that\'s just
the part that is most immediately of interest to players. Higher law levels
are likely to have much more effective police and much less crime--as in
Japan, where the police are allowed to do anything they want, including
torturing suspects.

Of course, that doesn\'t mean that only high law level areas will have low
crime. Consider Switzerland, where crime is also negligible, but people are
armed to the teeth relative to most other countries (including much of the
U.S.).

> What does this mean for future societies? It depends upon what kind of 
> model the future goverment is founded on.

I would argue that _any_ government will inevitably become more oppresive
until its law level is high enough that the leaders feel secure in their
control of the populace--a point that will always be well above that where
it\'s legal to own guns and armour.

The length of time this will take should vary considerably, and is not
necessarily as dependent on the original nature of the government as you
might think. As I mentioned earlier, it took centuries for the British
government to stamp out the right to self-defense. Many areas of the U.S.
have accomplished as much in less than a lifetime--despite the American
belief in personal freedom being much greater than that of the English.

There are some things that can derail this trend, though. If the oppressive
government can be driven away, or is destroyed by some disaster, the law
level can rapidly decrease. This needn\'t be permanent, either. For instance,
during the LA Riots and in the aftermath of Hurricane Andrew, the
government\'s enforcers were unwilling or unable to act, so for the duration
of the crisis citizens effectively lowered the law level by several points.
When the government was able to resume control, things returned to the way
they had been.

Let\'s look at how this applies to a future society--that of Neubayern, about
which I have posted several articles before this.

For most of its history, Neubayern was a democratic society which combined
almost libertarian attitudes about victimless crimes and weapon ownership
(drugs, prostitution legal, no obscenity laws, no laws restricting
ownership of weapons) with socialist welfare and social service programs.
There had been no wars, and only rare instances of severe civil unrest.
Overall, a law level of 0.

About 150 years before the "present," Neubayern was attacked by another star
system. This traumatic experience resulted in a number of changes to
Neubayern\'s society. First, a new \'ruling class\' was created. Entry was
limited to military officers, law enforcement, and a variety of management
types--all of whom had combat training. Only this class was allowed to vote,
although the forms of the government remained as before (something like the
situation in the Zhodani Consulate).

The new leaders wanted to consolidate their power, so (among other things)
they needed to disarm the non-ruling class population--and since the rulers
wanted to maintain their status as a _charismatic_ oligarchy, they had to
make the people _want_ to be disarmed (and lose various other civil rights
at the same time). Searching the history books, they hit upon a scheme which
had worked very well on ancient Terra--they declared a \'War on Drugs.\'

Recreational drugs, which had previously been perfectly acceptable, where
suddenly found by government studies to be the root of all evil. Not only
were these certain drugs the ultimate evil, anyone even remotely associated
with them deserved to suffer any unpleasant fate the government cared to
inflict upon them. 

Over several decades the Neubayern government, with the cooperation of the
media, worked the populace into a state of hysteria over the evil drugs, so
that they were soon actually demanding that the government take away their
civil rights in order to \'make the streets safer.\' In addition, the vast
increase in drug profits caused by their illegality caused the rise of
criminal gangs that would cheerfully kill their rivals (and any bystanders
in the area) in order to expand their territory and profit. This dramatic
increase in crime, in turn, fed further hysteria, which led to tighter
government controls, and higher drug profits. The general public was soon
caught in an escalating upward spiral of hysteria, terror, and government
control.

Within 100 years, civil rights were only guaranteed to members of the ruling
class. The government still couldn\'t just arbitrarily oppress the other
citizens, though--Neubayern\'s long tradition of freedom was still
remembered, if no longer honored. Instead, the government would first
demonize citizens it wanted to oppress. The general public had been
conditioned to believe that the government was perfectly justified in any
action, even murder, as long as the victims were first villified in the
media as drug dealers, pedophiles, or whatever.

At this point, the state of affairs on Neubayern had become nearly identical
to that of certain major American cities today, notably New York and
Washington. The primary difference is in the status of the ruling class. In
those American cities, a very small number of people (U.S. Senators,
billionaires, etc.) can not have their rights ignored, and even they are
restricted--for instance, only the most powerful (such as Senator Kennedy)
were allowed to arm their private soldiers with automatic weapons, and
certainly nothing heavier.

On Neubayern, the ruling class was much larger--a full 10% of the
population. These people had kept their rights entirely intact (largely
because they represented a much wider variety of interests), and so it was
not uncommon for rich members of the ruling class to own military
equipment--some very large companies even owned small warships. At this
point, the law lever for most people was fairly high (9), but unchanged for
the rulers.

This state of affairs would have continued indefinitely, for it was
certainly to the ruling class\' liking, if not for the Imperial invasion. The
government had decided to surrender to the Imperial forces as part of a
strategem to eventually defeat them, but this angered the Neubayern Army,
which believed (with a good deal of justification) that it could have kept
the Imperial Army from conquering the planet for many years.

Following the Cluster Liberation War, the Army\'s high command (who were
around back when Neubayern was peaceful, isolated, and free), commisioned a
study on what whould have happened if the Imperium had invaded a Neubayern
in which the entire populace was still able to own weapons, and backed up by
the Neubayern Army. The study clearly showed that the Imperium could not
possibly have conquered Neubayern in ten years without resorting to nuclear
attacks (which was against Imperial doctrine at the time).

Although Neubayern had emerged from the Occupation in much better shape than
if it had fought, the reults of the study when released caused so much
outrage among the voters of the ruling class that they forgot their earlier
hysteria and desire for power, and restored civil rights to
everyone--lowering the law level to 0 for everyone.

As far as crime rates, Neubayern had very little crime for most of its
history. The War on Drugs caused crime to skyrocket to levels comparable
to modern citys in the American Southwest (the high number of armed
ruling-class kept things from getting as out of hand as they have in New
York and Washington.) --and the two nuclear attacks Neubayern sustained
sent crime totally out of control. During the Occupation, things settled
down to the pre-nuclear attack situation. Imperial forces restricted
ownership of heavy military hardware, but this never had an impact on street
crime anyway. Following the Occupation, when civil rights were restored,
the crime rate dropped away over the following decade to nearly its pre-War
on Drugs level.

