    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> has been making some points about the
unlikely survival rate of Vargr corsairs.

I would like to suggest a few ways they might survive a bit longer:
 
>>...Place one 30.000 T Cruiser at the 100 diameter
>>limit of each world and the merchants have a safe spot to jump to and
>>from.

Corsairs might take the chance to jump in closer than 100 diameters.
Dangerous, but then the rewards might be considerable.
Plus there is all the in-system traffic between the planets, moons, gas
giant refineries, in-system prisons, research stations, etc.
This might be spread over a considerable distance (in terms of starship
movement rates) and hence is difficult to police for exactly the same
reasons as have been quoted in the "I can jump in a big rock and blam your
planet before you know what\'s happening" and the "I can jump all my ships in
and not worry about going to any gas giants - stuff High Guard" debates.
In-system traffic would, IMHO provide a far greater chance for piracy,
especially since it won\'t tend to have a jump drive and hence the final
emergency option of jumping to safety.

>>A couple of years ago, a freighter carrying illegal Chinese immigrants 
>>sailed into San Francisco Bay.  It passed by TWO Coast Guard stations, the 
>>Treasure Island Navy Base, NAS Alameda, the Golden Gate Maritime Radar... 
>What happened to the next ship that tried the same stunt? 

Everyone gets lax. Corsairs can afford to take one-off risks like the
freighter above, because the rewards of capturing another ship are great
financially (especially in the rarer ship environment of TNE). Insider
knowledge (of valuable cargos, naval manouevres, etc.) would be especially
valuable to the corsairs and would help to minimise risks.

>>To assume that every Vargr raider is going to announce itself from the 
>>moment of breakout is silly. 

>Certainly. But then, I don\'t assume so. And it is nowhere as silly as
>believing that anyone can make a living (as in "surviving for any length 
>of time") out of playing tag with a 30,000 T cruiser or the equivalent.

So what can the Vargr corsair do to avoid the cruisers, assuming he hasn\'t
caught some in-system traffic several hours travel time from the nearest
navy ship? Might I suggest:
(a) The covert "I\'m an honest merchant" approach, or
(b) The "I\'m using my stealth techniques, your cr*ppy merchant sensors can\'t
see me!", followed by:
(c) Lasing the target\'s commo antennas, or turning on the corsair\'s jammers
(to prevent the target calling for help, confusing its sensors, etc.)
(d) If the cargo is particularly valuable (and resistant to damage) and the
ship is not, just blast the ship until you\'re sure the crew is pulped.
(e) If the navy heads in your direction, turn on the stealth, turn on the
decoys, turn on the jammers, and run for it.

Oh, I forgot to add before (a), Send another corsair somewhere else to
hassle a ship (but keeping its jump drives warm and ready to go) to attract
the attention of the navy in the wrong direction while (a)-(e) above occurs.

THE ANSWER TO LIFE, THE UNIVERSE, AND WHY SDBs HANG OUT IN GAS GIANTS :-)
Naturally, the navy might use equivalent stealth, etc. but it can ill afford
to cover the vastness of space (even given a few limited trade routes
between in-system worlds) by leaving lots of very quite stealthy ships just
sitting there. Ah! Maybe I\'ve finally found a use for those \'tiny\' 400 ton
Systems Defence Boats at last! Additionally, corsairs might well want to
refuel out of the way of normal traffic - i.e. in gas giants - ah ha! So
that\'s why the SDBs hang out there too!

LEGALITIES OF ARMS AND ARMOUR

Jo Grant then talks about why guns and combat armour aren\'t a legal right...

> In Ireland the citizens don\'t have guns (other
>than farmers with hunting rifles and shotguns), the police
>don\'t have guns, and most (but not all) of the criminals
>don\'t have guns. The citizens don\'t want guns, the police
>don\'t want guns and the criminals can\'t get them.

Perhaps true in Ireland - certainly not true in England. The Hungerford
massacre a few years ago indicated just how a \'civilian\' with an interest in
weaponry can get hold of automatic weapons and go on a killing spree.
Licenses for guns are easy to get ("I just need to kill some vermin on a
friend\'s farm") as are licenses for explosives ("We\'re just going to remove
some tree stumps to ease ploughing in this field"). A lot of people are
fascinated by guns. Guns are relatively easy to acquire if you are a weapons
collector, mercenary (yes, they exist in the UK and some of them have locked
basements full of GENUINE machine guns, mortars, etc.), sports shooter,
hunter (big game or ala "Let\'s blow away some innocent little grouse") or A
CRIMINAL. I live near Harlow, Essex, England. I used to rent a room in
Harlow. My landlord had a scar right down one side of his face from where
someone used a knife on him. He knew people who walked up and down the
streets outside carrying loaded pistols - not for burglary specifically,
just for \'protection\' or whatever. This street was one block from the town
centre shops and only two blocks from the local police station. The
increased use of weapons - real and replica - by criminals has led to an
increased number of armed officers being regularly deployed on the streets
(not as foot patrols but to deal with specific incidents).
I\'ll let you conclude just how difficult it is to get weapons, legally or
illegally. And I haven\'t even mentioned the IRA yet... but then they\'re good
boys now, aren\'t they?

Ironically, of course, the whole discussion started about battledress and
combat armour which are totally different to the above discussion because
normally people with illegal weapons at least have the decency to conceal
them. Wearing b\'dress, etc. is a definite no-no in my games because it\'s
just so bleeding obvious! :-)

> Not every European country is quite up to this standard
>but I think the 2nd Amendment (?) "we have a right to blow
>away tresspassers" attidute is uniquely American.

Over here (UK), if you harm a trespasser, he\'d better have been standing
over you with a machine gun up your nose and a machete at your throat
(preferably having raped your wife, beaten up your children, etc.).
IF NOT, he\'s the one who will be suing you in court because you kicked him
in the groin and now he\'s suffering mental stress because he can\'t be the
full male father figure he\'s always wanted.
Better still, if you kill him, you\'ll be the one in court on a murder
(manslaughter if you\'re lucky) charge.

I SHOULD KNOW - I\'m a black belt in karate and have spent a lot of time
resolving what I should do if I ever have to use my skills to defend myself
in a life or death situation. Let\'s just say that there\'s only one sure way
of ensuring my opponent doesn\'t turn up in court claiming that he was only
carrying the burglary tools for a friend, broke into my house because he
thought he heard someone calling for help, was grappling with my wife
because she seemed hysterical and that I then needlessly broke several of
his limbs without due cause. 

THIS SHOULD BE A SERIOUS CONSIDERATION FOR PLAYERS thinking about owning
armour or weapons, especially if they\'re going to use them. Several years in
jail really kills a character\'s playability.

More importantly, JUSTICE SUCKS, especially now the UK lawyers have seen
just how much cr*p the judicial system will accept on compensation claims,
etc. ala US courts, OJ "it\'s a joke trial really" Simpson, etc.

What happens when the players are attacked by someone but don\'t kill them?
If the person has a good lawyer, contacts in the judicial system, etc. it
could the players who are being tracked by the police... no matter that the
guy was a drugs smuggler, etc. Justice ala Columbia, etc.

"Stick these ideas in your fish tank and see if they blow bubbles".
Just throwing thoughts in your direction...
(and ducking the hand grenades likely to be thrown back)
[ANY FLAMES TO ME PERSONALLY - DON\'T WASTE LIST BANDWIDTH]

