    'from' => 'Andy Lilly',
    'body' => 'Oh, and while we\'re on the subject of limiting weapons, etc. I would like to
paraphrase (to save space) a certain Mr. Metlay\'s comments from 1990 (TML
Message #964, Thu, 8 Feb 90 19:41 EST, From: METLAY@vms.cis.pitt.edu):

When "Stref was still kicking and lawnorder prevailed Throughout Our Fair
Kingdom", the Imperial government had a vested interest in maintaining peace
and quiet and therefore prohibited people from GETTING any of the really
balance-wrecking weapons. Those who broke the rules were hunted down and
summary justice applied by the authorities, who enjoy the concept of
citizens with high energy weapons and rigid armor about as much as the DEA
enjoys the concept of drug smugglers having easy access to shoulder-launched
missiles and heavy machine guns. The advantage the Imperium has over the
current US in this case is that the Imperium has no legal, moral or ethical
obligation not to go in shooting, with heavier guns than the bad guys have.
Arms suppliers are usually a hunted breed for similar reasons, unless they
"follow the rules" and keep good records and check licenses.

This generally restricted the average Traveller to TL10 weapons and armour -
no Gauss, high energy weapons or combat armour or battle dress.

Metlay notes that "The improvement in game quality was amazing: if all you
have is an ACR and a combat environment suit, you tend to think harder and
plan more carefully before you start shooting, despite the fact that you
know the people you\'ll be fighting are no better off than you are, normally.
Firefights were significantly fewer and further between, and carried an
element of real risk in them: the armor/weapon balance at TL 10 is such that
(at least under the old rules) you could take a hit, or even two, and hold
body and soul together for a few more rounds before passing out, adding to
the drama and excitement of the game. Since I was fortunate enough to be
dealing with sensible and mature gamers in most instances, parties were
quick to recognize the element of risk and fun this added to the game, and
followed policy with thankfully little whining from people who felt
emasculated without a giant, plasma-shooting phallic symbol on hand."
(Just couldn\'t resist quoting that verbatim)

In the Shattered Imperium, these regulations are more difficult to enforce
so weapons and armour MAY be available, but obviously the bad guys also have
anything they want.

He suggests alternative ways to keep this stuff out of the players\' hands:

(1) Cost. High-tech guns cost a lot, are difficult to find and at low TL are
over-sized and poorly built.
(2) Maintenance. A revolver can lie in a drawer unused and untouched for
literally years and yet come up firing at a moment\'s notice. One TL up from
that, though, we have the autopistol, which is much more inclined to be
finicky if it\'s dropped, not kept clean, not handled and oiled often, or
even fed the wrong sort of supposedly-fine ammo. Machine guns are for the
most part even more
complex, and so on up the ladder. Modernisation (TLs above the minimum for
the weapon) will increase reliability, etc. but only to a point.
Clearly Gauss and Hi-E weapons involve high precision mechanics,
micro-electronics, electrical factors (high power), computers (assisted
sights, control of fusion reaction, etc.). The military designs (at high TL)
must be fairly rugged or the Imperial forces wouldn\'t use them. But these
weapons must be maintained and serviced on a regular basis. According to the
rules in
Mercenary (CT Book 4), a HiE weapon must be completely disassembled and
serviced once every 24 hours. Even given "modernisation", the service time
will still be days or a week. Given these are basically small nuclear
reactors you can\'t just open them up on the workbench in the engine room of
your ship! Armouries at TL12+ are among the best-equipped and specialist
shops in history! Gauss weapons are an easier proposition but still require
considerable maintenance.
Note that the same problems hold for Battle Dress, whereas one can get away
with Combat Armour in a pinch since it doesn\'t have powerpack problems.
(3) The "ice factor." In a given campaign... "it might be considered common
for starfarers to wear pistols of some kind in their day-to-day activities.
However, the carrying of rifles is frowned upon, since a longarm isn\'t
usually something you\'re keeping handy for self-defence in an emergency. If
a party is transporting precious cargo, bodyguarding, or doing other
high-risk work, then passersby who recognize this tend to treat such parties
with respect. However, the average guy who goes out with rigid armor, a
Gauss or HiE rifle, or both, for no good reason other than to "be ready for
trouble," is going to attract scorn and derision from those around him, if
in fact he isn\'t arrested or simply shot from behind as a risk to pedestrian
traffic. He\'s obviously either a criminal, a sociopath, or a stupid showoff,
all of which make him too dangerous to leave at large. These items, with
their connotations of Imperial force and heedless crushing of resistance,
will inspire nobody. You won\'t get hired as a starmerc if you walk into your
interview armed that way; you\'ll be considered too stupid to be a safe
employee!

Andy (with acknowledgements to Metlay)
