    'index' => 'ab007',
    'topic' => ' Law Levels and Consitutions',
    'body' => 'Spider has summed up Canadian law quite well.  

As to differing backgrounds, the US guaranteed every citizen "life, liberty,
and the pursuit of happiness"; the Canadian equivalent is "peace, order, and
good government".  Whether either of these guarantees has been kept is a
matter of opinion...


On the psychology of wearing protection, a personal opinion:  

 I teach high school in Metro Toronto (population 2.5 million, plus another
1-1.5 million in surrounding suburbs), the city in Canada that most closely
resembles an American city.  We are beginning to get the same types of
problems that are common on the American news programs (drive-by shootings,
gangs/guns in schools, etc.)  

I have contemplated wearing kevlar, but have decided not to.  Why?  Because
is it looks like I\'m ready for trouble, some hormone-hopped adolescent kid
will give it to me.  This goes double for carrying an offensive weapon.  I am
much safer when I look like I\'m outside the threat-counterthreat dominance
game.  


Asbestos warning: I\'m not claiming (or even trying to imply) that all
American schools (and cities) look like they do on CNN.  Hey, when LA rioted
CNN interspersed shots of a few vandalized Toronto blocks with shots of
burning LA buildings - and it looked like Toronto was in flames.  (Actual
damage was very slight, less than that caused by partiers after the World
Series.)  However, I\'m assuming that the CNN view of America will be the one
most familiar to those living outside the States.
