    'body' => 'Mark Cook <markc@PEAK.ORG> wrote:
> "A well-regulated militia being necessary to the security of
>  a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear arms
>  shall not be infringed."
> 
> was deemed to be as relevant in maintaining the nature of the
> U.S.A. as it was in forming it.

Some relevant, contemporaneous quotes.  The following are excerpts from
President George Washington\'s address to the Second Session of the First
Congress of the United States of America.

   "Firearms stand next in importance to the Constitution itself.
 
   "They are the American People\'s liberty teeth and keystone under
    independence.   The church, the plow, the prairie wagon and 
    citizen\'s firearms are indelibly related.
 
   "From the hour the Pilgrims landed, to the present day, events, 
    occurrences, and tendencies prove that to insure peace, security,
    and happiness, the rifle and pistol are equally indispensable.
 
   "Every corner of this land knows firearms, and more than 99 & 99/100
    percent of them, by their silence, indicate they are in safe and 
    sane hands.
 
   "The very atmosphere of firearms anywhere and everywhere restrains 
    evil interference--they deserve a place of honor with all that\'s good.
 
   "When firearms go, all goes--we need them every hour."

It is highly interesting to compare and contrast this with the rhetoric
being generated by our current President and Congressional leaders.

> 2. The U.S. is currently (and has been for decades) the leading
>    producer of visual media entertainment (movies, TV series, et.al.).
>    A significantly high proportion of these are adventure-theme
>    stories, and contain high levels of violence and/or firearms.

A highly interesting article in the Washington Post described an interesting
reason for this.  The Post\'s reporter was examining an increasing trend
toward violence, particularly in television.  Several sources in the
entertainment industry cited the increasing EXPORT (ie: non-US) market as
driving this trend. 

According to the story, non-US markets for US entertainment are now large
enough that the industry (and particularly the segments of it that produce
syndicated television shows) consider the overseas salability of a product
to be the key to profitability.  Assuming that US revenues cover production
costs and perhaps a bit more, overseas sales represent pure profit, for
little or no additional investment.

The keys to export-market salability are (you guessed it) sex and violence.
Unlike intricate plotting, witty dialog, or (usually topical or US-centric)
humor, these two concepts are fairly universally understood, and easy to
translate to differnt languages and even cultures.  Try an experiment
sometime - turn the sound way off (or way down) and see which shows you can
still follow without the dialog, and which you can\'t.

> While taking a global view might be more "enlightened", I doubt it
> would last long in the marketplace.  I ask the rest of the readers
> of the XBoat Maillist, how likely are you to buy a games with titles
> like:

On the other hand, wouldn\'t MegaTraveller\'s Rebellion have been a _lot_ more
interesting if it had been plotted along the lines of the English Civil War?

Wouldn\'t the Collapse have been more interesting had its writers actually
studied the Sack of Rome, and used that as a model for the Vargr raiders?

However, to get back to the topic at hand, I have refereed a number of
Traveller games, with different styles of campaigns.  In at least one
campaign I could think of, the player-characters owned Battle Dress  Of
course, as members of a mercenary company, they _needed_ it for their
primary business (of course, they were usually smart enough to leave the
armor at \'work\' when they went on R&R - the time that they didn\'t culminated
in several arrests).

On the other hand, there were plenty of characters in other campaigns where
the only time they saw battledress was on the tridee screen in the news
reports from Efate.


