    'topic' => 'Vargr Corsairs',
    'body' => 'Ethan Henry:
>Hans Rancke-Madsen writes:
> 
>>So you might have smart criminals capturing a merchant ship every once in
>>a while by relying on the kind of sloth you gave an example of above. A
>>once in a lifetime coup for each gang that sets them up for life, even. But
>>a whole corsair industry like the Carrebean Buccaneers or the Barbary
>>Pirates? I\'m afraid not.
> 
>Between this and your other post, I have a lot of issues to (try to) 
>address, but it\'s going to take some time to make sure the assumptions
>I make make sense (ie. I don\'t want to stick my foot in my mouth :).
> 
>But just in case anyone else has any input:
> 
>1) I don\'t think there will/can be one very secure jump-in point per system.

Actually, there need not be. I used the single 30,000 T Cruiser because we
have figures for how much they cost and how much the Imperial Naval budget
is, but I don\'t really think that would be the way a world was defended. As
I said in an earlier posting, orbital fortresses with fighter crafts is what
I would expect.

>2) Many systems have a lot of intra-system travel, which could be easier
>   to hit, although less lucrative.
>3) I don\'t think the subsector/system navies have quite so many ships
>   as you propose, although this varies over time.

Ah, but that\'s one of the things that are fixed. Well, not the exact number
of ships, but the total budget. Using CT figures (which are the ones I can
remember off-hand), a planet with ten million citizens has a military 
budget of 5,000,000,000 Credit (5000 MCr). Of this 15% goes to the subsector
forces and 15% goes to the regular navy. 70% (3500 MCr) goes to the local
planetary defense forces. That gives them a fleet bought for ten times the
yearly budget, or 35,000 MCr. That\'s 350 SDBs or a light cruiser or several
orbital fortresses with several fighter squadrons. You can scale that up
for worlds with populations 8, 9 amd 10 yourself.

But what about those worlds with less people I hear you ask. Well, they
will have to rely on the subsector forces (since we can\'t be sure that
the regular fleet isn\'t off somewhere fighting Zhodani). But the subsector
forces are based on the revenue derived from all the worlds, most especially
the High-population worlds. On the average each subsector will have one
Population A and two Population 9 planets. They may not be the ones with the
highest tech level, so their tax credit may not be worth a whole Imperial
credit each. But unless the worlds are really low-tech their money will be
worth, say, 25% to put it low. So the budget will easily reach 375,000 MCr
for a subsector fleet worth 3,750,000 MCr. That\'s an awful lot of ships.

>4) Vargr raiding bases are secure, as Imperials won\'t chase them over the
>   border.

What makes you think they won\'t? My impression of governments, based on my
historical knowledge, is that they hardly ever takes any crap from anyone
weaker than themselves. I cite the case of the way the US dealt with the
Barbary States as an example, because I think that\'s exactly the way the
Imperium would deal with the Vargr. In fact, it\'s the lynchpin of my
argument. If the Corsairs can rely on secure port facilities at friendly
nearby planets, then they are indeed viable. But it would take, not one,
but multible generations of singularily incompetent Admirals to have let 
them get away with it for so long.
 
>While the Imperium is strong, I think it\'s not as overpowering as you
>make it out to be - otherwise it would have conquered it\'s neighbours
>a long time ago, wouldn\'t it have?

Lot\'s of historical examples of large nations that left their weaker
neighbours alone (as long as the neighbours didn\'t make a nuisance of
themselves). After all, just because you can do something dosen\'t mean
you are prepared to pay the price. Conquering and occupying a Vargr
state would take a lot more ressources than blowing their spaceport
apart every time you got raided by a Vargr Corsair. Pretty soon the
Vargr government begins to hunt down the Corsairs themselves to avoid
that.

>Also, both the Solomani and Zhodani who have overall/maximum tech levels
>at least one lower than the Imperium have given them a run for their
>money in the various border wars. While they\'d be less organized, who is
>to say the Vargr couldn\'t do the same?

That\'s like pointing out that the runner-up of the heavy-weight boxing
championships gave the winner a run for his money, so why couldn\'t a
bantam do the same? Have a look at the map in "Cogs&Dogs" and you\'ll see
that the Vargr border states are quite a lot smaller than the Solomani
Confederation and the Zhodani Consulate. 

Andy Lilly writes:
>Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> has been making some points about the
>unlikely survival rate of Vargr corsairs.
> 
>I would like to suggest a few ways they might survive a bit longer:
>  
>>>...Place one 30.000 T Cruiser at the 100 diameter
>>>limit of each world and the merchants have a safe spot to jump to and
>>>from.
> 
>Corsairs might take the chance to jump in closer than 100 diameters.

Can\'t do that according to the rules.

>Plus there is all the in-system traffic between the planets, moons, gas
>giant refineries, in-system prisons, research stations, etc.

As I pointed out earlier I\'m not talking about the odd 400 T Corsair. They
have their own problems, notably the fact that while there may not be
enough 30,000 T cruisers to protect all the places where they can find
appropiate prey, they can be dealt with by much smaller ships. If you
think the Imperium can afford an awful lot of cruisers then you\'ll be
amazed at how many "Gazelle" Class Escorts they can afford. But what I\'ve
been tlking about is those 30,000 T Corsairs that appear in the
Megatraveller material. A pirate ship is a business. They need to make
a profit appropiate to the expenses incurred. 30,000 T ships are 
expensive to run. Furthermore, such a ship needs the support of a big 
shipyard. Such shipyards can be discouraged from supporting them. The 
Imperium has the wherewithal to do the discouraging.

>So what can the Vargr corsair do to avoid the cruisers, assuming he hasn\'t
>caught some in-system traffic several hours travel time from the nearest
>navy ship? Might I suggest:
>(a) The covert "I\'m an honest merchant" approach, or

"Please stick to your assigned travel orbit. If you deviate we\'ll blow you
apart."

>(b) The "I\'m using my stealth techniques, your cr*ppy merchant sensors can\'t
> see me!", followed by:

But it\'s the military grade sensors you need to avoid. Btw. what stealth
techniques? AFAIK there are no stealth techniques in the Traveller rules.
That\'s one of the would-be pirates\' big problems. If there are I will 
certainly revise my stance. Sufficiently effective stealth techniques will 
indeed lift the pirate survival rate into the realm of the possible. It 
will also affect straight naval battles profoundly.

Tim Salisbury writes:
>>From: Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
>>*The Imperial Navy is plenty big enough to make the life
>>*of a pirate very hard. Place one 30.000 T Cruiser at the 100 diameter
>>*limit of each world and the merchants have a safe spot to jump to and
>>*from.
>> 
>I hate to jump in (ha, ha), but I need to double check this.  Our solar =
>system as 9 planets, an asteroid belt, and quite a moons.  To keep =
>pirates out of the system, we would need one of those cruisers for each =
>planet, and a few spares so the ships and crews could rotate every six =
>months or so.

You can rule out Mercury and Venus. They are withing the Sun\'s 100 diameter
limit. The various moons are propably within their respective planets\' 100
diameter limits. Then you\'re assuming that there are people near every
planet. OK, if there are then we need 7 or 8 cruisers (or their equivalent
in orbital fortresses or whatever). That\'s still within the Imperial Navy 
budget.

>Assuming the 200 or so worlds near the Vargr boarder, each with 10 or so =
>planets, and some of these systems would have less people in them then =
>the cruisers protecting them.

To start with most of those planets wouldn\'t have anything worth protecting
(or robbing). 

>Now, examine the cost of maintaining this blockade against the cost of =
>loosing a some 200 to 400 ton displacement vessels every year.  I hate to =
>sound mercenary, but to a sector spaning government, loosing a few =
>citizens every year to pirates would be cost effective.

I grant you that. But loosing what you need to support running a 30,000 T
Corsair _will_ hurt.

>Next, add jump mechanics.  Just making certain you are close to the =
>planet is a challenge for a highly trained Navigator and a high tech =
>computer, now you will add the added challenge of getting as close as =
>possible to this cruiser.  

Just close enough to be inside its firing range.

>Unless there are fixed jump points instead of =
>a grey area just beyond the 100 diameter limit, this pinpoint accuracy is =
>probably not possible over interstellar distances.  

Propably? Where in the rules does it say that? 

>Even if these =
>cruisers could make safe passage to the main world in a system, maybe =
>in-system traffic would be vulnerable to the jump-capable pirates, =
>especially when you consider the value of spacecraft, capturing a launch =
>every few months would still be profitable, especially when you consider =
>a Vargr Pirate has no ship payments and a crew that works for shares and =
>the thrill.

I can see that I will have to work out exact figures for the cost of running 
a pirate ship. But remember that that cost is only one part of the whole 
