    'body' => '
Tobia is a tech-15 industrial world of twenty billion, with a 
first-class starport and naval base, ten field armies equipped to
Imperial standards, and is seemingly the last world which might fall
to the massive wave of Aslan immigrants that occurred in the first two
years of the Rebellion.  So how\'d the Aslan end up in control of it 
and all the Imperial territory "behind the claw" rimward of Gazulin?

To start with, I\'m going to take the view that the "As" allegiances in
the Imperial Encyclopedia are wrong.  Why?  I think they make more sense
as indicating worlds that picked up an Aslan population but that stayed
under Domain control.  DGP\'s maps and UWPs for 1120 seem more plausible,
and they\'re repeated more.  By this view, the Domain only lost control 
of Sindal and Tobia subsectors, and Duchess Sharikkamur is able to draw 
the line at Gazulin.  

Can the Aslan even get these two subsectors?  I think so.  The regular
navy is gone, sent to spinward by Duke Alexander under the old Frontier
War emergency mobilization plan.  That leaves the colonials, probably
a sorry collection of tech-14 or worse hulks over a century old, maybe
augmented by some tech-10 or so local builds.  The subsectors both seem
to hinge on only two worlds.  The tech-14 naval base at Albe/Sindal 
probably supports the tiny 1203rd Fleet; the sector capital at Tobia
the 1204th Fleet.  These worlds are key industrial worlds with high
populations and first-class ports; nothing else nearby quite compares
to them.  I get the impression that the local colonial fleet wasn\'t very 
good, because Tobia is far to the "rear" of the expected fighting in a 
Frontier War.  In any case, as the only big tech-15 ship-building world 
this side of Trin, Tobia will need to use it\'s resources to support the 
regular navy, not the colonials.  The Imperial fleets will have only one 
tech-level on the ihatei, maybe less.

It turns out that the table in Rebellion Sourcebook about "Expected
Force Strength on World" gives results identical to the figures for
static defense forces in the old Fifth Frontier War board game.  Then 
both Albe and Tobia have ten field armies equipped to Imperial standards 
(TL-14/15) for local defense.  This is *very* impressive by 5FW standards.  

The Imperium could easily miss the significance of the Aslan raids on
the Glorious Empire, since they\'d been expecting the Tlaukhu or some
Aslan clan with initiative to move on the anti-Tlaukhu Aslan splinter
state for a long time.  But Tobia is just six parsecs from the Imperial
border.  A military invasion could be on them before they have time to
realize that some of the Aslan are up to something.

The Imperium may also be slow to recognize a threat from the Aslan,
both because there\'s been peace with them since long before the First 
Frontier War, and because they\'ve been good trading partners and some
have been immigrating for a long time; their first thoughts when there\'s
trouble will be to talk with the offending clans to figure out what\'s
the problem, not prepare for an onslaught.  And since the region is a
frontier, Aslan colonists may actually be welcome in controlled doses. 

Let\'s say that the Aslan factions that claim the Peace of Ftahalr is 
void can assemble a fairly large fleet, including an "AssaultRon" or
two worth of colony ships.  It shouldn\'t be hard, since one of those 
colony ships from Rebellion Sourcebook could carry a lift infantry
brigade.  They can get to Tobia from outside Imperial space from the
rift side in three jumps, and without running into serious resistance
from the low tech worlds en route -- those are bypassed, and the fleet
refuels at subsidiary gas giants.

In the battle at Tobia, I think that if they throw in everything that
they have, a handful of Aslan clans could gain control of Tobian local
space.  If this happens, the Aslan "ScoutRons" and "CruRons" (actually
Aslan hryo are mixed units, but anyway...) and anything else can now 
start to bombard the surface.  The Aslan may take serious damage in
this phase, but it\'s reasonable that they prevail.

Gazulin can be notified by fleet courier in two weeks, but there isn\'t
anything there that can help.  To get notice to Trin by fleet courier
and have a fleet respond at jump-4 would take ten weeks; four to get 
news there, and six for the fleet to get to Tobia.  That\'s with zero
time refueling on the way.

By 5FW, if the Aslan have "24 bombardment factors", about two CruRons
and four ScoutRons equipped for bombardment, there won\'t be anything
*left* of the ground forces after ten weeks of orbital bombardment.  
Admittedly, the Aslan really don\'t want to mess up Tobia this much, 
since they want to colonize.  So they offer the Tobians a chance to
surrender, which Duke Alexander takes, and the Aslan land a handful 
of occupying divisions.  Trouble is, this frees up the rest of the
fleet to go reinforce the attack on Albe, and it\'s likely that some
high tech Tobian equipment falls into Aslan hands....  Meanwhile, the 
Imperials are so distracted defending Tobia and Albe that all sorts of 
assorted Aslan colonists, many completely uninvolved, sweep into the 
area with only token resistance at best. 

The lack of a decent Imperial naval force in the area is then directly
responsible for the failure of the defense.  Tobia\'s field armies make
much more of a difference if the Aslan are forced to rush the landing. 

I\'m not saying that Tobia necessarily fell this way in the game, they
may just have been overwhelmed by the flood of peaceful settlers.  But
the point is that a military attack on part of the Trojan Reach by the
Aslan could work.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
 
