    Ever priced this?  Imagine if you will, that someone GIVES you an
old 1000T Oberlindes liner (sans weaponry).  It\'s not much as warships
go, even fully armed, but it\'s better than most everything else out
there, right?
    So, anyway, imagine you are arming this ship.  30 beam lasers will
cost you MCr30.  30 Missile launchers will cost you MCr22.5.  Quite
a lot of cash to have on hand, eh?  And if you have the cash, you can 
arm the ship.
    Why you would want to, we\'re not sure.  If you have MCr30 laying 
around loose, RETIRE!  YOu\'re RICH ALREADY, you d@#$ fool mutt!  Hell,
SELL the Oberlindes liner to someone else for a quarter what it\'s worth.
That\'ll bring you another MCr100 or so.  Then you\'re REALLY RICH!
    But, let\'s assume you were stupid enough to really want to waste
MCr30 to "get rich quick" by being a pirate...
    So, you\'ve spent the money.  Now find some prey.  Note a few key
guidelines here:  Your typical merchant ship is worth maybe MCr50 or
so NEW.  After you put a hole or two in it, it is worth a lot less.
Most likely, it\'s cargo is not worth beans (less than a million, most
likely).  Note that an M-drive hit (the most likely severe hit in MT)
will cost you around MCr10 to repair.  A power plant or J-drive hit
(fairly likely in CT) will cost you three or four times as much.
    So, if you capture a ship, taking one good hit in the process, you
break even.  Assuming you don\'t damage the prize too much, anyway.;-)
    Keep in mind here that if you run into an Impy heavy fighter
(50T, 9fib computer, 3 missile launchers), it\'ll tear you to pieces.
Just one of them.

    So, you just traded MCr30 (in cash), and a ship worth MCr400+, for
the life of a pirate.  Where you MAY break even, if you are reasonably
lucky.  And where the very first time you find yourself within 300,000
Km of an Impy heavy fighter, you die...


