The main thing I\'ve noticed in the whole gun debate in the U.S. is that
the gun-ban folks frequently break the #1 rule in statistics:  Correlation
does not imply causation.  Even the Seattle-Vancouver study which was
widely touted as a very well done study was wildly misquoted in papers and
by advocates.  All it found was that there was a correlation between
homicides and the number of guns.  That means the homicides could be due to
the proliferation of guns (A causes B), that the proliferation of guns was
due to high homicides (B causes A), that there was a third agent causing
the homicides and the proliferation of guns (C causes A and B), or that the
correlation was just a coincidence (A and B are not related).  Yet most of
the quotes I saw focused only on the first possibility, and some headlines
even said things like "Study Finds Guns Cause Homicides."

This is also a problem in the widely claimed statistic that owning a gun at
home makes you more likely to get shot.  Until recently all that studies
found was a correlation between gun ownership and deaths.  The overwhelming
conclusion in the media was that this meant you were more likely to die if
you bought a gun.  The far more likely conclusion in my opinion was that
this just meant people who lived in more dangerous areas were more likely
to buy guns.  The most recent study I\'ve seen accounted for this and found
that independent of the crime rate in your area, owning a gun made you more
likely to get killed by your own gun than a criminal\'s.  Something like
twice as likely, not the 5 times widely quoted (the remaining 3x I presume
would be due to my conclusion mentioned above, meaning my conclusion is
"more" right :-).  Unfortunately, it didn\'t break up those killed into
those who bothered to train and practice with a gun, and those who just
bought a gun without ever learning anything about safety.  I think that\'s
as careless as lumping unlicensed and drunk driver fatality statistics in
with those for licensed drivers.  Would you want your car insurance rates
determined that way?

BTW, I don\'t like guns.  I don\'t own one, I don\'t plan to buy one.  I\'ve
never fired anything more than a BB gun.  And I think the NRA is doing gun
owners a great disservice in many of its extremist positions (opposing
licensing of gun stores!?).  I just hate it when people abuse statistics
for their political gain.  And I think if they want to change the 2nd
Amendment, they should do it the correct way -- with another Constitutional
Amendment.  It\'s sad the double standard many organizations have when it
comes to protecting the 1st Amendment vs. the 2nd Amendment.  "Times
change, what the country\'s forefathers were thinking when they made the
2nd Amendment doesn\'t apply anymore."  With the Internet, desktop
publishing, and the huge effect the media has on society, you could say the
same thing about the 1st Amendment.

How does all this relate to Traveller?  Well, most of it doesn\'t.  :-)
Just be careful when you start using statistics to figure out the effect of
law level.  For the most part stay away from newspaper and news magazine
articles except to find references to research.  If you bother to dig up
the original research papers, you\'ll find most of them know the #1 rule and
state in their conclusion that all they found was a correlation.

> And isn\'t it interesting how few terrorist acts have ever
> happened in either the USA or Switzerland?  As opposed to
> England, Northern Ireland, Germany, Italy, other European
> places with tight gun laws?

For the US, I think that has more to do with it being a bigger country
requiring you to run futher if you want to get out.  It\'s also halfway
around the world from most of the world\'s political hot spots.  If you
were going to blow up a building, would you rather be a half hour plane
trip or an 8 hour plane trip from a country offering political assylum?

For Switzerland, it\'s probably because they\'ve been neutral in just about
everything.  And everyone likes their chocolate.  :-)
