    'body' => 'CORSAIRS
In x212, Hans Rancke-Madsen made some points about Vargr corsairs.

>>Corsairs might take the chance to jump in closer than 100 diameters.
>Can\'t do that according to the rules.

Sorry, thinking about my campaign there, where you can jump in/out of
anywhere, it just affects the chances of a misjump or ending up with only
half the ship managing to drag itself into hyperspace, etc.!

>As I pointed out earlier I\'m not talking about the odd 400 T Corsair...

Sorry, I wasn\'t really following things too closely (the amount of mail I
get to read I don\'t take everything in). I would like to agree that any
large corsair (Vargr or whoever) ain\'t going to survive long and, as you
pointed out, becomes economically unviable very quickly.
However, smaller ships (scouts up to say, Broadsword 800-tonners) might be
easy enough to steal, cheap enough to maintain/repair, require a small
enough crew and be small enough to evade the usual patrol ships, that they
might make a living out of piracy. Frankly, I\'d expect them to have at least
smuggling as a side line (for when the going is tough) or maybe they hire
out as mercenaries.

JSHiggin then mentions the cost of arming a stolen merchant to make it a
worthwhile pirate, and concludes:
>    So, you just traded MCr30 (in cash), and a ship worth MCr400+, for
>the life of a pirate.  Where you MAY break even, if you are reasonably
>lucky...

Again, large corsairs don\'t make sense UNLESS they are supported by a
suitable sponsor (a local Vargr world government), have proper fighting
ships (old sold-off Imperial models or newer stolen ones or even
custom-built ones if it\'s a government job) and work with inside
intelligence or as a pack (appropriate for the Vargr, eh?)
I would like to draw a vague analogy with Water Raleigh and his merry
\'pirates\' who preyed upon the Spanish merchants with the unofficial
\'blessing\' of Elizabeth I. (cor, 3 lines of history, I bet there\'s an error
there somewhere!)

>> 2) Many systems have a lot of intra-system travel, which could be easier
>>    to hit, although less lucrative.
>
>    Why?  Why would they have a lot of insystem traffic, and why would
>it be easier to hit?

If you use WBH or Scouts to generate systems, you get a large number of
in-system worlds (other than the mainworld) with colonies, labs, military
bases, etc. Quite often I\'ve found they come out with better ratings for
temperature, agriculture, etc. than the mainworld. In almost all cases
(especially for asteroid habitats, etc.) there is (in my games) an awful lot
of in-system traffic, carrying foodstuffs from the Ag worlds, water from wet
to desert worlds, ores from mines to In planets, hydrocarbons from gas
giants, etc. etc. etc.). The in-system traffic certainly exceeds the
inter-system traffic levels in most systems I\'ve examined - if you can mine
an outer world and use cheap in-system transport to get the ore back, what\'s
the point of bringing in ore in expensive jump-capable ships from other
systems?
A lot of CT\'s original trade relied upon the single world generation system
which meant if a planet had scarce resources (non-Ag, non-In, etc.) it had
to import from other _systems_. The more realistic WBH and Scouts systems
show how much more likely in-system traffic is.

>> 4) Vargr raiding bases are secure, as Imperials won\'t chase them over the
>>    border.
>Why assume this?  There is only one case I know of...

See Q Eliz I analogy above. White Dwarf\'s infamous Sable Rose adventure is a
good example of searching out pirates who have the unofficial blessing of
their world government.

Steve continues about the problems of piracy and cost to repair ships:
>    We never looked back (except for a lot of jokes about the "blender
>murders", of course ;-) )...

A lot of players certainly don\'t seem too worried about putting their ship
in danger for other reasons - piracy is just a different risk to be taken.
Let\'s face it, RISK TAKING is a major way of gaining face among your equals,
which is presumably why some Vargr are so eager to be pirates?

WEAPONS AND ARMOUR

Poor old Jo Grant\'s getting a bit stomped on...
>    What about those lads shooting at the Brits in Northern
>Ireland?  Where are they getting them from?

Steve continues:
>...It seems
>to me that a civilized society should not fear to allow 
>ANYONE to be armed.

A nice idea, except you do have to be careful about people who are not
intentionally criminal, e.g. fruitcakes, nazis, etc.

>...In Switzerland, every adult male gets to (HAS to)
>keep an assault rifle...in his home.  The crime rate is as low as Ireland\'s,

Nice idea. If you limit the ammunition and, better still in Traveller, have
a unique identifier for every gun and its rounds (radioactive trace elements
in the bullet metal, etc.) then everyone can be defended while still being
able to catch those people who abuse the system. Anyone else got any clever
ideas for expanding on this? Except, "every adult male gets his own
battledress" is still out the window, as far as MY game\'s concerned ;-)

Oh, and congratulations to "John H. Kim" <jokim@mit.edu> on his marvellous
summary of how statistics can be used to prove anything, particularly if
you\'re a news reporter.

Ken Hagler then talks about guns and says:

>Michael Ryan writes:
>[quoting a character from a Heinlein book]
>>  he says that if you are
>> carrying a weapon, you will be more prone to put yourself into situations
>> where you\'ll need to use it.  The same would go for body armor. 
>
>Not at all. I carry a weapon fairly often, and I am not even remotely prone
>to put myself into such situations. Anyone who would unnecessarily do so is
>either crazy or stupid--an US media reports to the contrary, carrying a
>weapon doesn\'t make people crazy or stupid.

It\'s strange though, when I play Traveller, none of the players really
contemplate the dangers of guns to their characters. I (ironically, as the
referee) am the only one who, when faced with having to shoot someone,
always try to make sure I\'m behind good solid cover with an aimed shot, etc.
The rest of them just stand in the middle of the street blazing away with
their autopistol, not worrying about the fact that I\'ve quite clearly stated
they have two opponents, one with an Ingrams, the other with an autoshotgun.
It\'s not heroism - they just plain don\'t understand the threat. Now, this
might not really translate to real life, but I wouldn\'t mind betting that it
does match quite closely. Maybe that\'s because I\'m in the UK so no one here
really has much experience of the use of genuine firearms. I\'m considered a
coward in combat - and that goes for my Wizards in AD&D too - all the 10th
level 100+ Hit Point fighters keep asking why I hang around in the middle of
the party, keep invisible most of the time and don\'t charge up the front and
stab the dragon with my dagger... :-) The only way I find of waking players
up to the dangers of guns is to keep showing them the gunfights out of Total
Recall, as an example of a sci-fi film using projectile weapons. (sigh)

Andy

