    'body' => 'Someone remarked on my remarks about being obviously unarmed and unarmoured
were I work.  (Sorry, but that newletter was too big for my system to read
online, so I can\'t remember your name.)

Let me clarify that I am dealing with adolescents here, most of whom are on
the "hormone hop".  They have a certain amount of self-control, but still do
many things without thinking.  Sort of a stimulus-response kind of thing. 
One of the "games" that they play is dominance: they engage in a lot of
maneuvering to establish a pecking order.  (Hey, you remember high school.) 
With certain kids, violence and strength is part of this.  They swagger, pump
iron, do steroids, and carry weapons.  Give them a challenge and they
respond.  

If I looked liked Arnie then they could back down in front of their friends
without losing face, but I am 5\'8" and 130 pounds!  To back down in front of
me would be humiliating.  Even if I was armed, they would have to try
something.  Instead, I find other ways of controlling them when necessary
(and most of the time they need advice more than control).

My favourite example is of a student who was wandering the halls yipping
(rather like a small dog).  I politely asked him to stop (it was disturbing
my class) and he refused, profanely.  He was obviously seeking a
confrontation.  Instead of giving him one (which would have raised his peer
status by defying authority) I remarked to one of my female students that his
undershorts must be tight enough to hurt.  She dissolved into giggles and he
disappeared, fast.  

Relevance to Traveller?  This type of approach (non-confrontational,
psychological) will be necessary for the bulk of RCES missions (all the
non-SAG missions).  The trick is to find out what is going on while remaining
a neutral.  My personal bias is that this type of adventure is much more fun
than a combat-oriented one because it involved more role-playing and
interaction.  I\'ll admit it\'s a lot harder to run this type of adventure,
because you must role-play the NPCs to a greater depth than usual to allow
the players a chance to figure out the NPCs\' motivations and goals.  
