    'index' => 'ab047',
    'body' => 'I finally had the opportunity to use one of my most closely-held "dirty GM 
trick":

Here\'s the band of intrepid PCs, who, upon finding that the vessel in which 
they are travelling is actually being crewed my individuals whose 
intentions toward the party were completely and irrevocably malign, decide 
to storm the bridge and sieze the ship. 
Upon reaching the command level, they managed to bypass most of the 
security systems,and reach the final hallway.  They were a bit wary, as it 
was about a 70m long hallfrom where they entered to the door to the bridge 
(it basically ran the length of the ship).  No side doors.  Suspecting 
ambush or murderous fire from the bridge iris valve, they spent about 15 
mins trying to figure out how to get up the hall.  eventually, they rushed 
the bridge door, with 2 ready to provide covering fire from behind.
oddly, the rush party reached the bridge door with out taking any fire.
now they were REALLY suspicious.  of course, their suspicions ended when 
the anti-hijack program, which had noted them coming down the hall - no 
question were THEY hijackers! - simply flipped a circuit.  Ironically, the 
player with the character who had "Naval Architecture 1" actually had a 
suspicion - he realized that not ALL the grav plates in ships have to be 
installed in the floor....they can be placed, for example, at the end of a 
long, smooth hallway, which turns into a 70m vertical shaft with a sudden g 
change.  hahaha.  2 actually survived, landing on the bodies of their 
friends....  >:)

