    'index' => 'ab048',
    'topic' => 'test rules',
    'body' => 'i have a system that i would like some people to playtest - the players in 
my campaign are too gun-shy to get in enough combats to see if this works.

here\'s the basic premise: one roll gives you whether you hit, the location, 
and damage all at once.

i have some digitized outlines of people in various attitudes (positions, 
not mental states) prone, standing, running, standing in groups.  on each 
outline, i have marked out areas in grey (where wounds are serious) and 
black (where wounds would be critical).  there are five sets of pics, one 
each for point blank, short, med, long, vlong (each set is about 1/2 the 
size of the previous).
I also have a transparency on which i have printed 40 concentric circles, 
with 30 lines in a radial pattern from the center out.  each weapon class 
(CPR, laser, energy, gauss) has notations on the circles, showing where a 
given roll with that weapon would hit.  for this, you first lay the 
template on the appropriate target, aiming wherever you want. roll 3d6 -2x 
your skill (i wanted a steeper bell curve) and a 30-sider (i had one, and 
needed something to use it with...).  cross index your adjusted accuracy 
roll with the radial line indicated by the d30, and you have it!
(fyi, i use a 3-tier wound system...for any wound, roll 2d6 vs. END to stay 
up.  roll is at +4 for a med wound, +8 for a crit.  any previous wounds add 
+2 per light, +4 per med, +6 for crit.  roll double your END & you are 
dying.  roll 3x END and you are way dead.)
it seems to work really quick, and my players like the hitlocations & 
aiming part...anyone interested? i could output the graphics to an *.eps 
file set and upload \'em.
-Steve

