    'date' => 'Sat, 18 Mar 1995 17:12:04 +0100 (MET)',
    'day' => '18',
    'body' => 'Steven Bonneville wonders how Tobia ever fell. So do I. My conclusion is that
it is so bizzarly impropable that it ever did that it didn\'t.

>Tobia is a tech-15 industrial world of twenty billion, with a 
>first-class starport and naval base, ten field armies equipped to
>Imperial standards, 

It also has system defenses worth 70,000,000 MCr. That\'s meson guns and
System Defens Battleships equivalent to 70 trillion credit squadrons. 

(20 billion people @ Cr 500/year gives a yearly budget of MCr 10,000,000 or 
10 TCr gives a fleet worth 100 TCr, 70% of which goes to system defenses).

>To start with, I\'m going to take the view that the "As" allegiances in
>the Imperial Encyclopedia are wrong.

Good start. Otherwise you will have to explain how the Aslans conqured
Glisten, one of the four most important planets in the Spinward Marches,
with defenses four times as strong as Tobia and located 30 parsecs from
the Aslans\' supply bases.

>By this view, the Domain only lost control 
>of Sindal and Tobia subsectors, and Duchess Sharikkamur is able to draw 
>the line at Gazulin.  
> 
>Can the Aslan even get these two subsectors?  I think so.  The regular
>navy is gone, sent to spinward by Duke Alexander under the old Frontier
>War emergency mobilization plan.  

Agreed.

>That leaves the colonials, probably a sorry collection of tech-14 or worse 
>hulks over a century old, maybe augmented by some tech-10 or so local 
>builds.

Ahem. The local builds would be TL 15. Tobia is TL 15, remember. The _ihatei_
ships, now, will be obsolescent TL-13 ships (assuming for purposes of
argument that no _ihatei_ comes from Aslans worlds of less than TL 14).

>The subsectors both seem to hinge on only two worlds. The tech-14 naval 
>base at Albe/Sindal probably supports the tiny 1203rd Fleet; the sector 
>capital at Tobia the 1204th Fleet. These worlds are key industrial worlds 
>with high populations and first-class ports; nothing else nearby quite 
>compares to them.  

I agree 100% percent with you.

>I get the impression that the local colonial fleet wasn\'t very good, be-
>cause Tobia is far to the "rear" of the expected fighting in a Frontier War.


Impression, eh? Well, the _facts_ are that subsector fleets are supposed to
be maintained at subsector level. That means that in, say, Five Sisters,
they would only be TL 12, but in Tobia the would actually be TL 15. However,
the rules does say that Subsector Fleets are composed of obsolescent ships,
so let\'s keep them at TL 14.

>In any case, as the only big tech-15 ship-building world this side of Trin, 
>Tobia will need to use it\'s resources to support the regular navy, not the 
>colonials.  

Tobia has the yard capacity to maintain its defense forces, the whole Sector
Fleet AND the Subsector Fleet. Why not? For all practical purposes it pays 
for them all. (Well, there will be a significant contribution from Hradus,
but I don\'t have the conversion tables for credits here, so I can\'t figure
out how much).

>The Imperial fleets will have only one tech-level on the ihatei, maybe less.

Uh-uh! They will have AT LEAST one tech level on the ihatei, propably more.

At this point it will be helpful to mention that Steve Higginbotham once
estimated that ton for ton (or was it credit for credit?) a TL 14 ship is
50% more effective than a TL 13 ship, 10 times more effective than a TL 12
ship, 12 times more effective than a TL 11 ship, 1000 times more effective
than a TL 10 ship and able dto defeat any number of TL 9 ships.

Since Tobias system defenses at least will be TL 15 (even if the Subsector
Fleet isn\'t) it will also be helpful to know that a TL 15 ship is 3 times
better than a TL 14, 5 times better than a TL 13, 20 times better than a
TL 12, 500 times better than a TL 11, and infinitely better tha any TL 10 or
9 ship.

So let\'s see how many Aslans we need to achieve parity with this force.
Let\'s ignore the Subsector Fleet, since it is propably out somewhere else
in the subsector kicking ihatei off lesser worlds. We have the defensive
forces worth the taxes of 14 billion people (70% of the true population).
They are 5 times as effective as their opponents (TL 15 vs. TL 13). A
typical _ihatei_ fleet is evenly divided between 10,000 T warships and
50,000 T transports which conveniently enough costs almost the same. So
half the money used to equip an _ihatei_ fleet goes into transports and
only half into warships. An Aslan clan can\'t afford to use its whole
naval budget on _ihatei_ ships; if it did it would soon be invaded by a
neighbouring clan. I assume they use 10% of their budget. (If you don\'t
agree, what percentage would you think proper?). That means the Aslan
fleet would consist of the _ihatei_ fleets of 14*5*2*10 billion Aslans.
That\'s 1400 _billion_ Aslans! I know Aslan worlds tend to run into the
billions, but 1400 billion? Note that this gives the _ihatei_ no more
than an even chance of winning. Less than that, actually, because we
haven\'t considered the fact that the Tobia defenses are non-jump ships
and ground installations while the Aslans\' are jump ships. Once they\'ve
won they will have 25 billion relatives to settle on their newly acquired
real estate. And then they will have to defend Tobia against the Domain
fleet that will arrive in six months time.

>The Imperium could easily miss the significance of the Aslan raids on
>the Glorious Empire, since they\'d been expecting the Tlaukhu or some
>Aslan clan with initiative to move on the anti-Tlaukhu Aslan splinter
>state for a long time.  But Tobia is just six parsecs from the Imperial
>border.  A military invasion could be on them before they have time to
>realize that some of the Aslan are up to something.

I wouldn\'t fire my Chief of Intelligence if he missed such a build-up,
I would hang him for treason.

>And since the region is a frontier, Aslan colonists may actually be 
>welcome in controlled doses. 

Aslan colonists in controlled doses are not a problem, they are a
palliative (not that any is needed). "Do you swear allegiance to the
Arch-Duke of Deneb?" "Aye, verily!" "Right! Please patrol this system 
and defend it against any other _ihatei_." "Your word is our command,
Sire!"

>In the battle at Tobia, I think that if they throw in everything that
>they have, a handful of Aslan clans could gain control of Tobian local
>space.  

1400 billion Aslans. Some handful!

>If this happens, the Aslan "ScoutRons" and "CruRons" (actually
>Aslan hryo are mixed units, but anyway...) and anything else can now 
>start to bombard the surface.  The Aslan may take serious damage in
>this phase, but it\'s reasonable that they prevail.

Now the Aslans kills off the whole population of Tobia? Well, it makes
more room for them, I suppose. It also removes any restraints the
retaliatory fleet might have had on their actions. The Aslans would
propably just have time to decontaminate the planet and settle their
loved ones on it before the Imperial fleet arrived to wipe them out.
Good planning on the part of any insane Aslan admiral.

>To get notice to Trin by fleet courier and have a fleet respond at jump-4 
>would take ten weeks; four to get news there, and six for the fleet to get 
>to Tobia.  That\'s with zero time refueling on the way.

OK, 3 months instead of 6 for the retaliation to appear. Incidentally,
Lintl (Reft 0503) is a TL 15 world with 40 billion inhabitants. That 
gives, without looking at any other worlds in Reft, a subsector fleet of
30 trillion credit squadrons. Since Lintl strangely enough dosen\'t have
a naval base, most of the fleet is propably based on Peshtorno (Largest
population world of those with naval bases). That means Tobia can expect
help in 4 weeks. (Hey, 25 TL-14 TCr Squadrons is a little help, right?).  

And don\'t forget Tobia\'s own Subsector Fleet. That is propably only one
jump away, so they could be back to help in two weeks. That\'s another 15
TCr squadrons.

>The lack of a decent Imperial naval force in the area is then directly
>responsible for the failure of the defense.  Tobia\'s field armies make
>much more of a difference if the Aslan are forced to rush the landing. 

50 TCr squadrons seems a pretty decent naval force to me. Even if they
are non-regular TL-14 pukes. (Though why Tobia and Lintl would support
TL-14 ships when they can support TL-15... Well, it\'s undoubtedly something
politically determined). But give me the subsector fleets of Trojan Reach
and Reft and I will guarantee you to kick the Aslans off any place they
manage to establish themselves. Give me a half-decent spy network and I
will guarantee to intercept most of them in advance.

>I\'m not saying that Tobia necessarily fell this way in the game, they
>may just have been overwhelmed by the flood of peaceful settlers.  

Enough peaceful settlers to outvote 20 billion Tobians? Keeping in mind
that peaceful settlers would be oathbound to Duke Alexander? You\'ve just
doubled the strength of the Imperial forces in Tobia Subsector, laddie!

>But the point is that a military attack on part of the Trojan Reach by the
>Aslan could work.

I disagree.



