    'body' => 'Mark Seemann wrote: 
>Hans Rancke wrote:
>>But it\'s the military grade sensors you need to avoid. Btw. what stealth
>>techniques? AFAIK there are no stealth techniques in the Traveller
>>rules.
> 
>Equip a small ship - say, a Scout/Courier - with an EMM package and a far
>orbit Active EMS jammer. The EmLevel will go from faint to none (so, no
>electromagnetic emission ?at all?), and the ship can jam all active 
>sensors. Pretty hard to see, huh?

Mark, an active EMS jammer is a _beacon_. It\'s the equivalent of a defensive
wall: easy to spot, but hopefully impossible to penetrate. (To which an
Imperial warship will say "Oh, yeah?" and lob off a few salvoes of missiles
backed by it\'s factor 9 computer).

Tim Salisbury wrote:
>now, speaking as someone who works for the Army, out of that budget, you =
>still have to take out [a whole bunch of things]
>[...]
>I would be very suprised if even 10% the Navy\'s budget went to ship 
>building, and even then most ships get retired after about 40 or so years. 

There\'s no surprises in this matter. That\'s one of the fixed points in my
argument (I always like to have some basis in fact to lend versimilitude
to an otherwise bland and unconvincing argument). The only rules we have
on the subject states that you pay 10% of the purchase price of a ship in
yearly maintenance, and that this pays for all support. Since an annual
overhaul only costs 1% of the purchase price this dosen\'t seem unreasonable.

Note that in my own campaign I often come up against situations where the
rules state that this or that planet would have 70 TCr worth of defenses
where I only want them to have a lot less. One of the dodges I use is the
MISS Factor (Military Inefficiency Spending Syndrome  -  the widely held 
notion that military organisations tend to pay more for what they buy than
private businesses (note that for my purpose it is irrelevant wether this
is actually true or just an urban myth)). By varying the MISS factor of
different goverments I can make some interesting situations. But that is
in my campaign. The official rules have nothing like that (I also have
the high-population worlds spend less tax money on the navy, but that\'s
unofficial too). And when I argue on this list I use official rules unless
noted.

>>Propably? Where in the rules does it say that? 
> 
>When you roll dice to see just how far away from the planet, and just how =
>long the jump took you.  If I plan to be 100 diameters out from Earth in =
>exactly seven days, and I come out of jump 8 hours later then expected, =
>the Earth will have moved along it\'s orbit some distance from where you =
>expect it to be.  Remember, the rules have Jump lasting from 6 to 8 days.

Yep. The rules also state that you can jump to a tolerance of 3000 miles
(Actually, here I\'m relying on Steve; I\'ve never calculated it myself).

>I don\'t think those 30,000tn Vargr ships in the sourcebook are pirate =
>ships.  They seem more likely to be war ships, possibly 5th frontier war. =

Whatever they are they are in trouble if they ever venture into Imperial
space. I just noticed that they are TL 11. TL 15 ships are 500 times as
effective as TL 11 ships.

>We also have to consider one simple game mechanic thingie:  If there were =
>no pirates, there would be no excuse for Players ships to be armed, and =
>not much risk in space travel.  Pirates are around for plot element if =
>nothing else.

You\'re absolutely correct, but don\'t you think that it\'s a serious flaw
that you can\'t have pirates in the game without violating several of the
basic rules of said game? Not to mention historical facts based on the
same sort of violations?

Andy Lilly writes:
>Again, large corsairs don\'t make sense UNLESS they are supported by a
>suitable sponsor (a local Vargr world government), 

And, as I have argued, there is a very simple way of discouraging any
potential sponsor. QED Large pirates don\'t make sense.

>>> 4) Vargr raiding bases are secure, as Imperials won\'t chase them over the
>>>    border.
>>Why assume this?  There is only one case I know of...

And page 62 of _Rebellion Sourcebook_ states that the Imperium did use
punitive raids. The problem is that GDW assumes that it will take a huge
amount of ships to keep the Vargr in check whilst their rules show that
it wouldn\'t take nearly that much. The 16 regular fleets in Corridor is
a HUGE overkill.

>It\'s strange though, when I play Traveller, none of the players really
>contemplate the dangers of guns to their characters. I (ironically, as the
>referee) am the only one who, when faced with having to shoot someone,
>always try to make sure I\'m behind good solid cover with an aimed shot, etc.
>The rest of them just stand in the middle of the street blazing away with
>their autopistol, not worrying about the fact that I\'ve quite clearly stated
>they have two opponents, one with an Ingrams, the other with an autoshotgun.

But don\'t they learn? I\'ve had a healthy respect for guns in Traveller ever
since one of my characters got blown away by an NPC run by a Referee who
had forgotten the -8 DM snub pistols got at medium range... ;-(

Tim Salisbury again:

>Ouch!  Would someone with a copy of Fifth Frontier War please tell me if =
>there are 4000 cruisers IN the Spinward Marches?  

Yes there is. And you don\'t need cruisers, you can use a few score fighters.
And there are TENS of thousands of fighters in the Spinward Marches.

>If I were a pirate, I wouldn\'t jump my multi-million credit ship into a 
>system blind and start shooting at the first ship I found.  I would send my 
>agent ahead to snoop around the star port and look at shipping doccuments, 
>or hack into the starport computer and get some scheduals and cargo and 
>passengeer lists.  I would watch the local patrols, and even if they moved 
>in a random fasion, they would have to follow the laws of physics, so I 
>could make a good guess where they were. 

So far, so good. You\'ve made a better start than many.

>My ship then jumps in far from the 100 planetary diameter limit, and 
>maneuver using only 1 gee (so others wouldn\'t see my true performance),

Go ahead and use your full powers. You\'re far enough away from anyplace
to be out of detector range. In fact, you will HAVE to use it, because if
you try to match courses with a CT or Megatraveller ship using no more
than their performance you will have to start in the same place. CT and
MT interplanetary travel is constant-acceleration. If you\'re using TNE
rules this isn\'t so, but then the merchant is most propably using a jump
drive. It\'s a lot faster and thus a lot more economic. Besides, I\'m not 
arguing against the possibility of pirates in a post-Collapse environment.

>get into a vector that would take me near enough to a shipping lanes 
>and wait.  If a ship is going from planet A to planet B, it has to be 
along course C. 

Gee, I wonder if there is anything a merchant can do to foil this brilliant
plan? Nothing, except taking his ship a few percent outside his direct
route. It\'s cheap, costs him only a few hours extra travel time, and it
makes him pass you a a distance beyond your detector range.

>Now, some Traveller material 
>(TNE actually, when talking about the Virus blockade) implied you could 
>even tell what planet a ship has jumped from or is jumping to by it\'s 
>vector to or from a jump point.  If I know The Queens Gold will be heading 
>from Regina to Roup, then I can try to intercept it along that vector.  

No you can\'t, because The Queens Gold will certainly jump from a safe point
to another safe point.

>Now, assume you do have a battle station [...] this system then no longer 
>has a pirate problem.  And now you are spending mega-credits on something 
>you don\'t need.

No, I\'m spending mega-credits on something I would have to pay for anyway:
system defense.


