    'year' => 1995,
    'from' => 'Rob Prior',
    'topic' => 'Favourite Game (nostalgia)',
    'body' => 'While rummaging through my office looking for old material for this
afternoon\'s game, I came across some stuff from a campaign I ran years ago.

It was loosely based on Twilight\'s Peak: a merchant ship trying to stay
afloat and me trying to keep the players on track.  

The most interesting character was Albert the Commando Accountant ("have
notebook, will travel").  The player is one of the most devious and cunning
chaps I\'ve met (he runs a terrific game of Runequest, too) who delighted in
finding psychological and legal leverage on the baddies.  Plots 3-4 levels
deep!  It was amazing.  "Please don\'t force me to audit you.  It\'s such a ...
messy ... death."

The group did eventually solve the adventure, although I received some forced
science lessons on the way.  ("Of course there\'s something going on.  That
ecosystem/orbit/atmosphere/etc. is obviously artificially maintained.  Here,
I\'ll prove it to you.")  Never run an exploration adventure with scientists
unless you want to spend a lot of time building your worlds.
