    'index' => 'ab054',
    'body' => '    I\'ve been reading the revived discussion about the fall of Tobia with
some interest.  Cynthia and I even spent an evening trying to come up with
some combination of incompetence and treason that might do it.  Herein my
tuppence worth on the debate:

Steve Bonneville:
> Tobia is a tech-15 industrial world of twenty billion, with a 
> first-class starport and naval base, ten field armies equipped to
> Imperial standards, and is seemingly the last world which might fall
> to the massive wave of Aslan immigrants that occurred in the first two
> years of the Rebellion.  So how\'d the Aslan end up in control of it 
> and all the Imperial territory "behind the claw" rimward of Gazulin?

    Where are you and Hans getting that population for Tobia?  The only
info I have on it sets it at 6 gigapeople, not 20 gigapeople...
    Note that GDW assigns a combat value of 500 battalions to a "field
army", making it about 25 divisions equivalent.  That sets Tobian Army
strength at about two million men, which is rather large by modern
Terran standards (China might have one that big?  Russia did once upon
a time when it used the initials USSR), but in comparison to the pop-
ulation (6 Gp) is rather small, actually.  We can not too unreasonably
assume that a modern trend towards smaller professional armies may
continue into the distant future and allow that nothing unusual is
represented by an Army that size.
    Keep in mind, though, that TL15 "armies" have considerable "organic"
spacegoing capability.  After all, a TL15 grav-tank is different from
a fighter primarily in the way its crew are addressed ("driver", "gunner",
as opposed to "pilot", "gunner")...


> To start with, I\'m going to take the view that the "As" allegiances in
> the Imperial Encyclopedia are wrong.

    Good move.


> By this view, the Domain only lost control of Sindal and Tobia subsectors,
> and Duchess Sharikkamur is able to draw the line at Gazulin.  

    I think this view is indefensible.  A force sufficient to take Tobia
is sufficient to blast through all the way to Glisten and beyond.  Plus,
one must keep in mind that the guys who took Tobia are now arming them-
selves to Impy standards, and are at least ten times as effective as
they were _before_ they took Tobia.  So a force capable of taking Tobia
should be more than capable of pressing on as far as, say Rhylanor.
    Note, btw, that the Zhodani Consulate was incapable of capturing TL12
Jewell in spite of limited Naval assistance in the defense of Jewell, and
a three year siege.  It is being assumed that what the Zhodani Navy could
not do (take a high-pop, high-tech world) in three years was done by a
bunch of Aslan amateurs in archaic ships in only a few months (and a
higher tech target than the Zhos had, to boot.)...
    Spare me.


> That leaves the colonials, probably a sorry collection of tech-14 or
> worse hulks over a century old, maybe augmented by some tech-10 or so
> local builds.

    This is silly!  It is cheaper to build and maintain new TL15 ships
than it is to maintain TL14 ships.


> The subsectors both seem to hinge on only two worlds.

    And very stout hinges those two worlds are, too! ;-)


> The tech-14 naval base at Albe/Sindal probably supports the tiny 1203rd
> Fleet;

    Why is this fleet described as "tiny" here?  I wouldn\'t be terribly
surprised to learn that it was tiny, but I don\'t recall reading that 
anywhere....


> I get the impression that the local colonial fleet wasn\'t very good,
> because Tobia is far to the "rear" of the expected fighting in a 
> Frontier War.

    Well, not necessarily.  Going back as far as Leviathon, I recall
reading of Zho forays into the Trojan Reaches, closer to Tobia than the
actual main battles of the FFW were to Trin.


> In any case, as the only big tech-15 ship-building world this side of
> Trin, Tobia will need to use it\'s resources to support the regular navy,
> not the colonials.

    What?!?  Have you any idea how much shippping Tobia is capable of
supporting in its yards?  Try 150,000,000 displacement tons.  Perhaps
as much as 50% more than that...
    Unless the "regular Navy" routinely operating in the backwater
Trojan Reaches is at least that large, you can pretty much count on
the colonial squadrons being pretty much exclusively TL15.


> The Imperial fleets will have only one tech-level on the ihatei, maybe
> less.

    Even if I bought the arguments for TL14 Impies (I don\'t), I would
agree with Hans here - one TL AT LEAST.


> The Imperium could easily miss the significance of the Aslan raids on
> the Glorious Empire, since they\'d been expecting the Tlaukhu or some
> Aslan clan with initiative to move on the anti-Tlaukhu Aslan splinter
> state for a long time.

    Only if the Impies are stupid could they miss the significance of
this move.  After all, it involves a bigger war than the FFW, conquest
of more territory than has changed hands in the last 800 years along the
border with the Zhos, and LARGE naval/marine/army forces operating
literally years away from home.  It also implies a humongous effort for
the Tlaukhu in moving these guys over the J-5 route to get here, including
the securing of the near terminus of the J-5 route.  WIth ships that are
seldom more than J-3, remember?


> But Tobia is just six parsecs from the Imperial border.  A military
> invasion could be on them before they have time to realize that some of
> the Aslan are up to something.

    Well, no.  An Aslan warfleet will be J-3.  Which means at least three
weeks to reach Tobia.  Impy spy-ships in Aslan space (if there aren\'t any,
then there is prima facie evidence of treason and gross incompetence on 
the part of both INI and <whatever the local intelligence operation is> -
I\'d start on the hangings right as soon as I found out that the spy ships
weren\'t there, if I were the man on the hotseat in Tobia) can reach
Tobia in a week.
    And _that_ is assuming that INI and co. are so incompetent that the
first clue they can get of major Aslan fleet movements are when the ships
leave orbit.


> The Imperium may also be slow to recognize a threat from the Aslan,
> both because there\'s been peace with them since long before the First 
> Frontier War, and because they\'ve been good trading partners and some
> have been immigrating for a long time; their first thoughts when there\'s
> trouble will be to talk with the offending clans to figure out what\'s
> the problem, not prepare for an onslaught.  And since the region is a
> frontier, Aslan colonists may actually be welcome in controlled doses. 

    You are using the civilian definition of "threat" here.  The Impy Navy
had better (unless charges of treason and inpcompetence are appropo here,
too) have detailed plans for dealing with invasions under several
scenarios, ranging from "an Aslan clan on the move" up through "full-scale
war with the Tlaukhu".  That\'s what they get paid for.
    The notion that the "correct" response to Aslan Fleets across the
border would be to talk to them to find out why they are here is ludicrous.
Try a real-world example - France invades Germany with eight divisions, say.
Now I admit that the French idea of a division is not much, but the Bundes-
wehr isn\'t all that big an Army either.  Would you reasonably expect that
the first response in Berlin would be to call for the French Ambassador
to ask what\' wrong?  Or would they do what has historically been done in
similar situations throughout history?  Start Mobilization, start fighting
to expel the enemy, call in the Ambassador to give him his passport back 
and expel him, THEN, MAYBE, wonder what went wrong...

    Now, keep in mind that I do not disagree with the notion that Aslan
colonists might not be welcome on many of these worlds.  If *I* were
governing one of those backwaters down near the Florian League, a few
million Aslan militiamen might look like a wonderful opportunity!
    On the other hand, it\'s illegal as Hell for them to come in.  A clear
violation of the Treaty of Ft<whatever>.  So in spite of the fact that
I (the governor of Podunk III) might welcome them, the Navy (which out-
votes me big time) willl send them packing back home as soon as they are
found.


<your discussion of an Aslan attack>

    Nice.  But you have no _idea_ just how hard it is to get together the
requisite force.  For Aslan Ihatei, who are using archaic ships even by
Aslan standards.
    And 5FW is a really lousy analysis tool for this job.  5FW makes the
standard wargame simplification of reducing the number of units on a side
to a "representative" level similar in overall structure to the actual
units present in the war.  If the Spinward Marches could afford only the
Naval Units shown in the 5FW game, then how could an Aslan clan afford the
THOUSANDS of cruisers and transports supposedly sent across the Rift into
the new lands?  And if there were not thousands of transports, then not
much in the way of Aslan colonists would be present, and they\'d be incapable
of colonizing half the Trojan Reaches.  Not to mention that they would
have no NEED to colonize more than a world or two...


> So they offer the Tobians a chance to surrender, which Duke Alexander
> takes, and the Aslan land a handful of occupying divisions.

    Why should he do something so stupid?  More treason?  Or just
incompetence?  The Aslan aren\'t going to nuke Tobia.  Several reasons:

        1)  nuke it, and you have gained nothing.  If you want the land
intact, you have to take it the old-fashioned way.
        2)  Tobia has TL15 Nuke dampers.  No meaningful bombardment will
reach the surface.
        3)  Tobia has TL15 point defenses.  No meaningful bombardment will
reach the surface.
        4)  Tobia has TL15 deep meson sites.  No meaningful bombardment
force will survive trying to bombard the surface.

    So Alexander is not seriously at risk of orbital bombardment, and he
is still sitting on his deep-meson sites and his Army.  Surrendering at
that point (when your enemy is far from his base of supply, and you have
a bigger Army sitting right on top of YOUR base of supply) would be
insanely idiotic.  Or treasonous.  Or both.  Note, btw, when figuring out
Alexander\'s actions, that he is in a stronger position under the Impies
than he ever would be as an Aslan puppet, and the Aslan offensive is
completely untenable.
    Especially if he picks a clan at random, and concentrates his forces
exclusively on THEIR assets.  Then the next clan.  And so on.
    How long will the individual clans stick around?


> Trouble is, this frees up the rest of the fleet to go reinforce the 
> attack on Albe, and it\'s likely that some high tech Tobian equipment
> falls into Aslan hands....

    Quite so.  So why should he do it?
    Also, you now seem to have created a second fleet/army force to take on
ALbe?  Where did it come from?  Who is coordinating all these wonderful
fleet movements?


> Meanwhile, the Imperials are so distracted defending Tobia and Albe
> that all sorts of assorted Aslan colonists, many completely uninvolved,
> sweep into the area with only token resistance at best. 

    I frankly can\'t see this sort of attack distracting me long.  You send
a few BatRons to Tobia to send the rabble there home.  Ditto Albe.  Then 
send a few BatRons into the former Glorious Empire to remind them why
the Treaty of Ft<whatever> was signed.  (Hint: it wasn\'t signed because
the Imperium was so weak that the Tlaukhu felt sorry for them).


> The lack of a decent Imperial naval force in the area is then directly
> responsible for the failure of the defense.  Tobia\'s field armies make
> much more of a difference if the Aslan are forced to rush the landing. 

    If this were to happen, then I would expect wholesale trials/executions
for Treason, plus a myriad of similar trials for gross incompetence,
followed by myriads of Impy officers being cashiered.  Then look for the
Aslan to be kicked right back out.  because if taking a world like
TObia is easy enough for the ragtag Ihatei to do, then the Impy Navy could
do it back quite easily.
    Note, however, that I consider this scenario as ludicrous as any I have
come up with to explain the loss of Tobia.  And I have come up with some
doozies!
    The best so far required that the Impies be fighting both the Solomani
Confederation and the Zhodani Consulate when Tobia falls.  Even then the
Aslan had to have help from the Islands Federation (which is about as
tough as the Impy Trojan Reaches, having similar TL, and a similar high-tech
populace).  And even then I don\'t really BELIEVE that Tobia would fall.


    Unfortunately, they all fall apart on the twin altars of Money and
Power.  The Impies have both in droves.  The Ihatei don\'t.


Hans:

> At this point it will be helpful to mention that Steve Higginbotham once
> estimated that ton for ton (or was it credit for credit?)

    Ton for ton.  It\'s worse, credit for credit, since the higher TL ships
are generally cheaper than the lower TL ships, ton for ton.

    Your analysis of required Ihatei numbers to take on Tobia I agree with
mostly, but I think that any commander who attacks with less than three to
one superiority in measured strength is a fool.  He should have five to
one before he even seriously considers the problem, IMHO.


                                ----Steve

