    'body' => 'Alun Moon writes:
> Isn\'t this more due to the ease of controling entry/exit to the US rather 
> than "gun control"?

Huh? Controlling entry/exit to the US isn\'t \'easy,\' it\'s impossible! Now,
this doesn\'t prevent our idiot Congress from trying with stuff like
immigration limits and the War on Some Drugs, but all such attempts
accomplish is to cause crime and make our neighbors laugh at us...

Andy Lilly writes:

> Nice idea. If you limit the ammunition and, better still in Traveller, have
> a unique identifier for every gun and its rounds (radioactive trace
elements
> in the bullet metal, etc.) then everyone can be defended while still being
> able to catch those people who abuse the system. 

That\'s one of those ideas that sounds good at first, but doesn\'t work in
practice. US citizens go through _billions_ of round of ammunition each
year, many of which they manufacture themselves at home. For years, the US
government tried to keep track of ammunition purchases (without individual
identifiers, even), but all this ever accomplished was the generation of
mountains of worthless paperwork. That law was actually repealed--and the
repeal of a gun-control law is _very rare_ here...

Now imagine what that would be like if there was a unique identifier to keep
track of, and this was being done across many systems. You\'d need whole
planets full of bureaucrats just to run the system!

> The rest of them just stand in the middle of the street blazing away with
> their autopistol, ... they just plain don\'t understand the threat....
> Maybe that\'s because I\'m in the UK so no one here really has much
> experience of the use of genuine firearms.

Ah yes, this syndrome occurs in gamers with too much exposure to
television. It\'s not unique to the UK, either--it\'s pretty common here in
the US. The victims of this syndrome have seen so many gunfights on TV that
they gradually come to believe that the TV gunfights are representative of
reality--which they\'re not. Ever. This delusion overwhelms the common sense
of the victim--but happily, there is a cure. Just run the battle
realisically, and the players will behave rationally with their next
characters. :-)

Rob Prior writes:

> Someone remarked on my remarks about being obviously unarmed and unarmoured
> were I work. 

That would have been me.

[Stuff on kids deleted.]

Yes, I\'m familiar with that sort of behavior. Aside from being young enough
to remember high school (more clearly than I would like), my father is a
teacher in a junior high school here in California.

I didn\'t mean to suggest that you should go around threatening brain-dead
coke-head punks, or anything. I just meant that as long as trouble is likely
to come to you anyway, it\'s much safer to be prepared for it than to rely on
the (non-existent) mercy of sume gangbanger for your continued health. Of
course, if the rules up there are anything like the ones teachers here live
with, you\'re basically screwed no matter what...

>   The trick is to find out what is going on while remaining
> a neutral.  My personal bias is that this type of adventure is much more
fun
> than a combat-oriented one because it involved more role-playing and
> interaction. 

I agree. I prefer missions that stress investigation and/or diplomacy. I do
like to let players have massive firepower, but put them in situations where
actually using it inappropriately would have disasterous consequences.


