    'index' => 'ab063',
    'body' => 'Sorry, I\'ve lost track of who\'s said what, so some general comments below:

STEALTH TECHNIQUES
>> Equip a small ship - say, a Scout/Courier - with an EMM package and a far
>> orbit Active EMS jammer. The EmLevel will go from faint to none...
>    Uhhh...Are you aware that jammers emit EM?  So when you turn your
>jammers on, the EMM becomes worthless (they locate you by your jammer
>emissions), and if you leave it off, then the active sensors get you.

I allow most systems to have increased effectiveness for higher cost/mass,
etc. as long as this doesn\'t overbalance TL dependency. EMM shielding (from
my limited memory) isn\'t TL-based so high TL EMM ought to be able to fool
lower TL sensors pretty well. It would have to cost a damned lot to prevent
unbalancing the game, but for lower TL worlds which can only support say a
TL12 navy, a TL15 super-EMM-masked ship ought to be pretty near invisible.
Clearly the analogy is between 1940s radar and modern stealth bombers. Come
to think of it, stealth bombers are pretty good against modern radars,
dropping the radar cross section (technical blather, I think I know
something about this) by a factor of 1000 or more, so your TL15 intruder
ship looks smaller than even say a missile, to the TL12 SDB.

>    Note also that neutrinos are not covered by EMM....

Sensors not commonly available in the modern world are difficult to judge,
but I would presume that if nuclear dampers, etc. can moderate nuclear
reactions, and repulsors can affect gravity particles/waves, then there
ought to be Counter-Measures to reduce your \'signature\' for neutrinos,
densitometers, etc.

VARGR (AND OTHER) CORSAIRS
Steve mentions that in-system traffic carrying ores and food (my previous
posting) wouldn\'t make a great pirate target.

I agree, unless you have:
(a) Slightly larger corsairs which can engulf small (few hundred ton) ships
and carry them off whole.
(b) Sufficient time (once ship has been shot up) to extract the valuable
parts (computer, power plant or jump spares, etc.).
(c) You use intelligence (as elaborated upon by myself and ????????) to pick
the worthwhile targets (carrying gems, weapons, etc.)

ARMOUR AND WEAPONS
I mentioned you shouldn\'t let nazis and fruitcakes have guns, Steve replied:
>    So the governmnent should be allowed take MY guns because YOU are a
>Nazi?  What a novel theory of government!
Sorry, I should have specified that there should be some test to determine
if you are fit to hold a gun, not that the fear of \'nazis\' should prevent
_anyone_ from owning a gun.

Later he continues...
>    No, you missed the point!  This is the way it really is!  They don\'t 
>have neat tracers on the bullets, and the only identifier on the gun is
>the same one as on every gun (serial number and ballistics).  I am not
>suggesting that this might work.  I am saying it DOES work in the one
>country willing to try it.
Sorry, again I meant that in (say) Traveller, you\'d have to have the extra
security, because I know well that my players would immediately abuse the
system.

>    AS to "every adult male in BD", note that that is a sexist remark.  Why
>not give the babes BD too?
I was altering the previous quote about "every adult male" in Switzerland
being given an assault rifle. My quote was not intended to be sexist,
although it does indicate the sexism practiced in Switzerland - why aren\'t
the adult women given assault rifles as well? Perhaps they are?

ON THE PROBLEMS OF EDUCATING PLAYERS
Steve volunteers:
>    Another way to wake them up is to let a few of them get blown away for 
>their stupidity.

I do try not to kill PCs unless they really deserve it. I have found a good
way of running combat whereby good armour (CE suit or better) reduces damage
significantly, but quickly falls apart under sustained fire. So when the
player first takes a hit, they\'re knocked over with little damage. Then you
tell them how much less armour they\'ve got left and they start calculating
how much real damage will penetrate the next time... it\'s a bit like
ablative armour used to be played.

Oh, and a classic from Steve:

>    I don\'t actually consider "peaceful" to be synonoymous with "civilized",
>actually.  If I did, then any cemetary would be "civilized".

Rather ironic, eh? When trying to bring home the dangers of weapons.
Thug: "So wat yu gonna du wid dat gun then?"
Judge Dredd: "I\'m going to CIVILISE you, perp\'."

NASTY GRAV PLATES
Steve "Styopa" then mentions an anti-hijack trap:
>not ALL the grav plates in ships have to be 
>installed in the floor....they can be placed, for example, at the end of a 
>long, smooth hallway, which turns into a 70m vertical shaft with a sudden g 
>change.  hahaha.

Or fit grav plates which can be upped to 6g. Turn on plates, watch hijackers
crumple to the floor (unable to move or use weapons), flood area with tranq
gas (or have heavy ceiling plates with release catches - only a 2-3m drop,
but at 6gs... WHUUMPH splat).

Sorry, this was supposed to be a 10-line reply but I\'m waffling as usual...

Andy

