    'body' => 'Nrunner@ix.netcom.com (Archie Tindell) wrote:

>        Has anyone thought about vac suits with lanthanum grids?

You can\'t in CT; jump ships must have a displacement of at least 100 tons.

There\'s a loophole in MT, though.  Jump drives can be no smaller than 2
cubic meters, as I recall.  So a jump drive and it\'s fuel could fit in
twelve cubic meters.  If a jump-1 drive, it would move a 100 cubic meter
ship; if jump-6, a 28.5 cubic meter ship; about two displacement-tons.
It\'s not a vacc suit, though, and you\'d need to fit a computer, power
source, and life support into a displacement ton of volume.  Maybe 
something at tech-20 or so would be close to a "jump" suit in MT.  There\'s 
no rule that I know about in MT that would contradict this, which would
allow the construction of "jump-message torpedoes" that you could shove
out a cargo lock.  MT never mentiones a 100 ton limit, to my knowlege.

Looking at the numbers, my guess is that this "loophole" is actually an
error that was never caught in the ship design sequence, and that the
minimum size rule for jump drives should read:

  A jump drive may not be smaller than one + (jump number) displacement
  tons in volume; a jump-1 drive must be at least 2 tons in volume, a
  jump-6 drive at least seven tons in volume, and so on.

This brings back the old jump drive limits as seen in Classic Traveller.

This error may carry over to TNE, but I\'d have to check.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
 
