    'date' => 'Tue, 28 Mar 1995 08:17:51 +0000',
    'body' => 'In x224, Archie Tindell asks:
>	Has anyone thought about vac suits with lanthanum grids?

Wow! (Well for me anyway). What a thought! There are plenty of reasons why
not - in theory there are minimum sizes for jump drive, power plant, etc. in
CT, MT and (I think) FF&S, all of which would normally preclude such a small
jump-capability. However, you can get tiny powerpacks to provide energy for
laser and fusion weapons and to power battledress, etc. so maybe the rules
could be bent accordingly.

There are some other problems. The vacc suit would be an extremely confined
space for a week\'s jump (not so bad in my game where jumps only take about
24 hours). The person has to have food, water, heating and armour - the last
to protect against the strange effects of jump space which, due to the small
size of the vacc suit\'s grid is likely to be pretty much pressing against
the suit\'s visor (watch your astrojumper go nuts with jump sickness). Then
there\'s all the waste recycling (okay, standard vacc suits have it but this
is a week or two\'s worth), plus there\'s all the maneouvre drives (jet packs,
whatever) required to take you out to the 100 diameter jump distance, etc.
plus all the rigours of being such a tiny target in space with other traffic
around (fried by a passing fusion exhaust, etc.)

It sounds pretty damn dangerous, but it could be used in some hairy
adventures! Especially since I allow jumps to occur (at increased
probability of misjump) within 100 diameters - one could have stormtroopers
popping into existence in the sky only a few miles above the planet\'s
surface! Okay, so they wouldn\'t all pop out at once, and a fair few would
pop out around the wrong planet or in deep space (marines are expendable)...

Andy

