    'topic' => 'Jump uncertainty - a theory',
    'body' => 'I\'ve been musing on the vagaries of jump travel, especially the \'residual
velocity vector\' of a ship that emerges from jump space.  The following is
strictly \'pseudo-science\' that I\'m adapting for my campaign.

A ship \'conserves velocity\' when it emerges from jump space, that is, it
will have whatever velocity vector it had when it entered j-space.  My
question is:  velocity vector _relative_ to what?  After all, there is no
absolute frame of reference from which one can calculate a velocity vector.

My solution:  the velocity vector is the sum off all the ships force vectors
relative to _every_ body in the universe.  I\'m only really thinking about
gravitational force, which is proportional to the mass of the body _and_ is
inversely proportional to the distance seperating the body from the ship.

In a jump, the only vectors that really make a difference are those produced
by ship-planet, ship-planet\'s sattelites and ship_system primary.  Other
vectors have an effect, but it\'s negligible in proportion to the \'major\'
vectors.  No computer could possibly calculate more than a small proportion
of these vectors...

Now, I introduce some black magic.  When these vectors fall below an
arbitrary value (say, Planck\'s constant multiplied by c^2), quantum
uncertainty can have some unpredictable effects on the \'resultant\' vector. 
The \'resultant\' vector will always be off by a random amount and direction,
possibly no more than a few ms^-1 and a couple of seconds of arc, but it can
sometimes be more (some sort of random distribution).  So, you can never be
_sure_ of your exact velocity when you emerge from j-space, and (at the risk
of awakening a sleeping monster), it makes it impossible to simply attach a
jump drive to a planetoid and send it to cause havoc - without some form of
course correction on emergence it will miss it\'s target.

Well...my physics isn\'t real good, and it\'s only a game after all, but it\'s
a working theory.  I\'ll brace myself for the flames ;-)


