    'body' => '>A ship \'conserves velocity\' when it emerges from jump space, that is, it
>will have whatever velocity vector it had when it entered j-space.  My
>question is:  velocity vector _relative_ to what?  After all, there is no
>absolute frame of reference from which one can calculate a velocity vector.

I think you are little off here.  The fact that there is not one absolute
reference frames doesn\'t mean that there isn\'t a frame than can\'t be
applied to every point in the universe (in fact there are an infinite
number).

The conserves velocity rule is acutally very clear.  Take _any_ reference
frame, after the ship jumps it has to have the same velocity vector
with respect to that reference frame.  This has the additional meaning
that every trip you have to make up the differences in planetary and
stellar motions.  I don\'t know how big the velocity differences are
between stars, but if you ever found a way to jump accross the galaxy
I think it\'s going to be non-trivial.


