Mark Clark <markc@brahms.udel.edu> wrote:
> [good review of GDW\'s latest Traveller publication]

Thank you for the review, Mark.  While I\'ll reserve judgement \'till I\'ve
seen the book myself, it sounds like I\'ll be giving this one a miss.

> Those who have been following the Traveller News Service 
> in Challenge will be happy to know that the "Corn Dog" mystery is finally 
> solved - they\'re a copy of Terran corn dogs, made from sea slugs (yum!).

And here I thought they were fried Hiver grubs.  How dissapointing.

> The Ithklur stuff is essentially all original, and very unsatisfying.  
> The Ithklur seem like the Three Stooges doing Monty Python routines with 
> guns.

That\'s original?

Not only has it been done before, it\'s been done better.

> This from the company that brought us 2300AD, the game with the best damn 
> alien aliens ever in a roleplaying game.  Somebody should just slap these 
> guys for geting all caught up in post-modern literary theory and angst.  

Better yet, I encourage people to vote with their wallets.  Refrain from
buying the book sight unseen - peruse a copy at your local game store, and
decide for yourself if this is the sort of material you really want to see
in Traveller.  If, after looking for youself, you decide that this is what
Traveller is really about, by all means spend your money.

If, on the other hand, you think that a Science-Fiction game should pay more
attention to science and less to fantasy; that a good alien race should be
more than John Cleese in a rubber Godzilla suit, then tell GDW so in the
manner that\'s most likley to get their attention: Don\'t Buy the Product.

Repeat the procedure as necessary on future occasions until GDW\'s writers
get the message (or are eliminated from the genre by the magic of market
forces, for failing to get the message after frequent repetition by the
game-buying public).

> They\'re probably just made because they didn\'t think up Magic: the 
> Gathering of All Disposable Income.

Probably.  If GDW\'s past performance is any guide, they\'ll notice the
money to be made in the collectable card trading game business in another
year or so.   Just in time to spend their money developing a product
which reaches market the same month that the fad becomes passe.

> Oh, one last thing - there\'s a reference on page 57 of H&I to a Ithklur 
> prisoner who was tortured and then _EATEN_ by K\'Kree.  How did this get 
> past the editors?

What editors?

GDW\'s quality control has improved since the MegaTraveller days, but they\'re
still not up to what they should be.  Something about busy production
schedules and the need to ship a product on schedule, I\'m sure - reality
does interfere with getting a product up to best possible standard.

On the other hand, it might behoove GDW to take a careful look at their
competitors, such as Steve Jackson Games, who seems to be able to release
high-quality products regulary (and at least at the store where I shop,
garners considerably more shelf space than GDW).

On the other hand, perhaps the Ithklur ARE vegetables.

wildstar@qrc.com

