>1. In the initial phase os such an attack, the attacking troops would be 
>very close to the edge of the jump field.  (One note I have somewhere 
>says that you need at least one meter between you and the jump field in 
>order to survive)

One of the books (perhaps Starship Op\'s Manual?) does mention the
possibility of EVAing in jump space. I think it IS possible, you just can\'t
afford to \'stand up\' on the hull or your head \'disappears\'.

>2. Drilling in through the hull whilst in jump, means that you are 
>destroying part of the Hulls jump grid.  Doing this while the jump field 
>is active, and the ship in jump, will probably destroy the ship!

Ah non monsieur! The hull grid can take quite large amounts of damage
without necessarily destroying or throwing the ship out of jump - somewhere
(Starship Op\'s Manual?) is mentioned the fact that hull breaches might
sometimes cause the field to dip, perhaps even into the ship, but given that
the field is at least 1 metre from the hull, to get it dipping inside the
hull would require a hole at least 2 metres in diameter (to a first
approximation).

Jump-hijackers aren\'t impossible, just insane! I\'d do the old "I\'m an
innocent passenger, please ignore the huge bulge under my armpit" hijack
approach any day of the week... :-)

Andy

