    'topic' => '[X230] Jump reference frame',
    'body' => '
X::>>A ship \'conserves velocity\' when it emerges from jump space, that is, it
 ::>>will have whatever velocity vector it had when it entered j-space.  My
 ::>>question is:  velocity vector _relative_ to what?  After all, there is
no
 ::>>absolute frame of reference from which one can calculate a velocity
vector.

X::>I think you are little off here.  The fact that there is not one absolute
 ::>reference frames doesn\'t mean that there isn\'t a frame than can\'t be
 ::>applied to every point in the universe (in fact there are an infinite
 ::>number).

 Including the one that uses the jumping ship itself as a frame of 
 reference.  That makes my velocity vector zero, and I\'ll come out 
 of jump with a vector of zero.  Since my vector is zero, I\'m at 
 rest, and "compensation" is trivial - I point my ship the way I 
 want to go, and start going there.

 Hmmm...  There\'s obviously a flaw in the reasoning above...

X::>The conserves velocity rule is acutally very clear.  Take _any_ reference
 ::>frame, after the ship jumps it has to have the same velocity vector
 ::>with respect to that reference frame.  This has the additional meaning
 ::>that every trip you have to make up the differences in planetary and
 ::>stellar motions.  I don\'t know how big the velocity differences are
 ::>between stars, but if you ever found a way to jump accross the galaxy
 ::>I think it\'s going to be non-trivial.

 You\'re right, but that\'s because when you jump, _all_ vectors 
 relative to your chosen frame are preserved - including that of 
 the entire universe, if you choose yourself as the frame.

 The velocity differences can range from negligible (for a 
 microjump over a distance that would take more than a week to
 cover in realspace) to 600 m/s for a jump exactly 180 degrees
 across our galaxy to a point exactly as far from the center of 
 galactic rotation as Sol.  It can also go higher, as the orbital 
 velocity of any body is measured relative to its primary, and when 
 the body is in the portion of its orbit such that it is moving in 
 the same direction as the primary, relative to the galactic center 
 of rotation, the velocity vectors add.  For what it\'s worth, the 
 orbital velocity of Terra relative to Sol is 29.72 km/s.  For 
 Traveller (World Builder Handbook) purposes, that\'s a G3V primary 
 with a planet of size 8 and density 5.5 g/m^3 in orbit 3.  (Orbit 
 0 is vacant in the Sol system.)

 Now, the question that comes before the court is "What really 
 happens to a ship in jumpspace?"  If momentum is conserved (which
 is really what they\'re saying when they talk about conserving 
 vectors), then it must _always_ be conserved - which means that 
 either the matter and its associated momentum is somehow 
 "available" to realspace while a ship is in jump. or it is somehow 
 transferred to one or more bodies that remain in realspace, and 
 borrowed back from those same bodies, in exactly the same 
 quantities, when the ship exits realspace.  Of course, there\'s 
 also the problem of conservation of mass-energy as well; you can\'t 
 just have several hundred tonnes of matter just disappear for a
 week without some sort of compensation.

 I\'ve run up against this problem more than once, and never found a 
 satisfactory solution under CT or MT rules.  The TNE alternate
 rules from FF&S plus a little massaging of numbers _might_ (I 
 haven\'t yet sat down to work out the details) allow a solution 
 based on (but not identical to) 2300\'s stutterwarp - raise the
 cost, limit the "speed", and change the discharge requirement to a 
 time-in-operation based one rather than a distance-based one.  
 Stutterwarp never has the ship out of realspace; the change of 
 position is instantaneous (like electron tunnelling is) and 
 doesn\'t affect any vectors associated with the mass of the ship.  
 Where the Modified Stutterwarp (MSW) differs from the CT/MT/TNE
 Jump Drive (JD) is in the vector adjustment to compensate for 
 differing stellar/planetary orbital velocities relative to the 
 Arbitrary Frame of Reference (AFR).  Under the JD paradigm,
 compensation is made strictly at the ends of interstellar transits 
 - you match the target body\'s orbital velocity either before you 
 go into jump, or after you come out - not during that week in 
 transit.  With MSW (or even standard SW), you can spread that 
 modification over the entire week of transit, thus saving that 
 time at either end of the journey.  The other effect that 
 Stutterwarp has, which I can\'t reasonably "fix" (if it needs 
 fixing at all), is that a Factor-6 MSW drive (capable of 6 parsecs 
 per week) will be able to do a one-parsec transit in about one 
 day, whereas _any_ JD will take a full week to do the job.  This 
 will likely change the character of individual systems (in-system 
 travel will probably be faster) and local/regional interstellar 
 polities (over the short interstellar haul, travel and comm will 
 be faster), but the overall Imperium will probably not change too
 much (over the long haul, it still takes just as long).  I think.  
 I\'ll have to explore this...
