    'from' => 'Ethan Henry',
    'body' => 'So, on the weekend I caught (lord knows why) a documentary about
Vancouver (B.C.)\'s port, the biggest and busiest port in Canada.

They had crews go and follow the in-port happenings of a Greek
tramp freighter crew, getting their cargo loaded and unloaded,
a big, BIG wood pulp freighterwith their very modern dual-built-in
loading gantrys, some of the local port staff who pilot ships in,
a business that supplies food and supplies to ships and an 
interview with the Harbourmaster.

It occured to me (of course) that this is probably a lot like what a
starport would be like - lots of ships coming and going, cargo getting
loaded and unloaded, etc. There were a lot of interesting things that
I think would apply in campaigns...

Local Pilots. In order not to screw up the rather tricky job of 
moving these big ships into the rather tight port, a local pilot
comes aboard to bring the ship in from the harbour. At big starports,
this would probably be the norm to prevent pilots unfamiliar
with the starport procedures from messing up. Only at really big
starports though.

Land-based ports. Given the amount of cargo that needs to be loaded
and unloaded, unless you have a REALLY big orbital spaceport,
you\'re going to have to do it dirt-side. Given the high costs of 
orbital ports vs relatively cheap ground-based ones, you\'d better
have a darn good reason for having a huge orbital port. Also,
for reasons I\'ll mention in a bit, most ships would find it impossible
to use cargo shuttles.

Handling agents. A ship in port has to pay for a lot of things - 
the local pilot, berthing fees, taxes, excises, duties, food and
supply costs, etc. For a ship that spends a few days in any given
port, it\'s rather unlikely that the ship\'s captain will have the 
time and inclination to do all this himself. Thus, the handling
agent. Familiar with local customs, laws and business, he does all
that stuff and the captain pays him for all the ship\'s costs while
in port.

Cargo crews. Apparently in Vancouver, there are so many ships, sometimes
your cargo crew won\'t show up either \'cause the weather\'s bad and they all
stayed at home or there just aren\'t enough people to unload all the ships
in at a give time. Also, some types of cargo need special handling 
equipment, like grain or coal and if there\'s 8 grain ships in at once,
it might be tough sharing the grain loading equipment. Some starports
would have robots, of course, but this probably invites other problems
and worries, not to mention TNE virus effects.

Sailors\' taverns. I forget what it was called, but apparently in almost
every major port there\'s a bar/hotel called the Sailor\'s somethingorother.
It makes it a little easier for foreign crews to find their way around -
there\'s one stop where they can get a drink, meet other crews and find out
about local attractions. Most real ship crews phone home too, which
starship crews won\'t do, but there\'d presumably be an xboat drop for
sending letters home instead, if the spacers had a permanant home to send
anything to.

General Crowding. Any successful port soon outgrows itself. Vancouver 
apparently has ten or twenty ships anchored in the bay at any given time,
waiting for a berth. For most big starports (any type A, I\'d think)
there would be several ships waiting in orbit for a landing spot. 
Presumably, most planets would have a small orbital station where captains
could go to arrange an agent, etc while waiting, even if orbital cargo
loading
is impossible.

Big, BIG ships. PCs, in their 200-ton Free Traders, need to take very
profit-dense cargo to make money. This, however, probably isn\'t
the backbone of interstellar trade. If planets are like countries today,
some will produce lots of agricultural goods (like Canada, grain and 
wood pulp) and some will focus on manufactured goods (like Japan, where
there are literally no natural resources). For things like grain and
wood pulp, you ship them in the biggest ship possible that doesn\'t
break under it\'s own weight. Grain freighters would be in the thousands of
tonnes range, if not the tens of thousands. The same would go for
petroleum, wood products, even water to desert/arid worlds. PCs\' ships 
would be dwarfed beside these ships. In some cases, these big ships
might not even unload at the starport - why unload a crude oil tanker at
the starport when you can fly it right to the refinery? On some worlds,
this may be prohibited though, making it difficult to transport that amount
of cargo unless prior arrangements have been made.

Anyways, that\'s enough rambling, but it gave me quite a few ideas on how 
big starports might work.

Ethan
