    'topic' => ' Lagl Question',
    'body' => '>I\'m in the process of combining the various Traveller rules books into a three
>book set.  I\'m doing this by typing (and sometimes scanning) the rules into 
>Wordperfect.  I know this is legal because it\'s for my own personal use and I
>paid for the originals from which I\'m doing the copying.
>
>Is it legal for me to give my document to others?  By "give" I mean just that.
>I certainly am not charging for this.
>
>My document differs from the normal rules because 
>
>a) it consists of only three volumes:  the library, the player manual and the
>   referee manual
>b) I\'ve changed rules that aren\'t logical or that I just don\'t like
>c) where MT and CT conflict, I\'ve had to make choices
>
>Your opinions are eagerly anticipated.

In Canada, doing this for yourself is legal (even the backups, as long as you
only use one at once).  

Giving it to someone else is not, any more than you can \'give\' me a copy of a
new computer game that you\'ve bought.  Well, you could give the changes to
someone else, but not the original rules (no matter what format).  As for
deciding which version of a rule to use (CT or MT), you couldn\'t quote more
than the "fair use" amount without permission.  

Try asking GDW.  If the material is out-of-print, they _may_ give you
permission to distribute something free of charge.  For example, I have
permission to distribute large-format deckplans (for use with miniatures).  I
must include the GDW copyright notice and can only charge enough to cover
photocopying and postage.  Notice that this doesn\'t compete with any GDW
product, because I am only distributing the deckplans not the descriptions
and ship statistics.  
