    'topic' => ' Starport pilots',
    'body' => '>>Local Pilots. In order not to screw up the rather tricky job of 
>>moving these big ships into the rather tight port, a local pilot
>>comes aboard to bring the ship in from the harbour...
>I dunno.  The reason they do it with cargo ships is because compared
>to other means of transportation, they are incredibly unmaneuverable.
>... In Traveller, we\'re talking about ships with
>1G maneuverability minimum.

1) If we are talking about "supertankers" they may not necessarily have 1-G 
maneuverabilty (of course if they land on planets they *must*). Super-tanker 
toddles at .001G to the jump-point. Pop! It appears at its destination. It now 
has to toddle in to port. If you have to maneuver this behemoth into port while 
PCs in 200t zip about at an amazing 1-G you might well want a special pilot. 
Some ports may require that you have a lisenced pilot for their port. There is 
the possibility that if there *is* an accident and your ship is being flown by 
a pilot you might be able to shift the brunt of the leagal problems onto them. 
Imagine if Exxon could have blamed a hired pilot on their little problems...

2) Back in the 16th Century there was a well known Irish pilot by the name of
Granuail (Grace O\'Malley). She would sail out in her galley and meet merchant
ships passing through Clew Bay in Northwest Ireland and offer to pilot them 
through for a fee. She would explain that although the bay appeared calm and 
placid that they were, in fact, dangerous waters and many another merchant
ship 
passing through without a O\'Malley pilot met bad ends.
This might be appropriate for ports in difficult belts, or in systems with a 
large corsair presence, or just place with low law levels.

So there you go.

Jo
