    'body' => '>X::>I think you are little off here.  The fact that there is not one
absolute
> ::>reference frames doesn\'t mean that there isn\'t a frame than can\'t be
> ::>applied to every point in the universe (in fact there are an infinite
> ::>number).
>
> Including the one that uses the jumping ship itself as a frame of 
> reference.  That makes my velocity vector zero, and I\'ll come out 
> of jump with a vector of zero.  Since my vector is zero, I\'m at 
> rest, and "compensation" is trivial - I point my ship the way I 
> want to go, and start going there.
>
> Hmmm...  There\'s obviously a flaw in the reasoning above...

There is a measure a velocity relative to the distant masses of the universe 
(distant galaxies etc) which is relatively invariant with position [certainly
over the distances we are talking about: 1-6 parsecs vs 1-6 mega-parsecs+)]  
When you compensate for the relative movement of star systems, measurements of 
the remaining velocity are essentially consistent.  ***Provided none of you are 
moving at relativistic velocities -- in which case you have to apply some math 
to your velocity (and time ans space) measurements, but physics still explains 
your differing measurements as consistent within Relativity.**

This is the nearest thing to an "absolute" frame of reference, and is the one
astronomers attempt to use when measuring factors like the microwave background 
temperature from the big bang... 
you can still reasonably assert that if you measure your velocity before and 
after Jump, relative to distant galaxies, that you\'ll get the same numbers - and 
that the local star system you jump from will have quite a high velocity 
relative to the target star; hence, although you had a low intrinsic velocity

when you started, you\'re positively zipping when you come out of jump!  Full 
thrust to slow down into the local system....

[for a good description of problems like this, read the EE Doc Smith "Lensman" 
books, or (probably) GURPS Lensman.  The cause is different (inertialess travel 
retaining previous inertia when you drop the inertialess-ness drive) but the 
effect is similar.


The velocity differences can range from negligible to quite high: try a 
micro-jump across the solar system!

>For what it\'s worth, the 
> orbital velocity of Terra relative to Sol is 29.72 km/s.

So if you were in solar orbit beforehand, but diametrically opposite Terra, and 
jump to near Terra, you have a velocity relative to Sol which is the same as 
before, but Terra is moving in the opposite direction at a further 29.72 km/s: 
59.44 km/s relative to you... Oops!

> Now, the question that comes before the court is "What really 
> happens to a ship in jumpspace?"  If momentum is conserved (which
> is really what they\'re saying when they talk about conserving 
> vectors), then it must _always_ be conserved - which means that 
> either the matter and its associated momentum is somehow 
> "available" to realspace while a ship is in jump. or it is somehow 
> transferred to one or more bodies that remain in realspace, and 
> borrowed back from those same bodies, in exactly the same 
> quantities, when the ship exits realspace.  Of course, there\'s 
> also the problem of conservation of mass-energy as well; you can\'t 
> just have several hundred tonnes of matter just disappear for a
> week without some sort of compensation.

existing C20 theories of wormholes permit you to "step outside" spacetime, 
without breaking the conservation rules:  you haven\'t destroyed anything, you

took it with you!  The Trav jump scheme is really like a week-long wormhole, 
created to order, arrvining hopefully where you wanted but not properly under

control, so similar considerations probably hold.


