    'body' => '
peterb@cnct.com (Peter L. Berghold) writes:

>>Presumably, most planets would have a small orbital station where captains
>>could go to arrange an agent, etc while waiting, even if orbital cargo loading
>>is impossible.
>>
>And when shipping slows down for whatever reason the surrounding towns start
>to dry up REAL fast.

This is kind of a chicken and egg problem (sort of) - which was first,
the city or the port? In the case of Vancouver, if all shipping stopped
tomorrow, things wouldn\'t be pretty, but the city wouldn\'t disappear.
The port area would, sure, but a lot of Vancouverites wouldn\'t notice for 
a while. While startown\'s fortunes would be directly related to
the volume of traffic, there\'s probably still a real city not too far away
which would keep startown from disappearing completely.

Oh, and Peter\'s comments about container shipping is a good one, but
their usefulness in orbital unloading depends if ships are allowed
to land anywhere, or just at the starport. If small shuttles could take 
the cargo right to the receipents, fine, but if the shuttles just go to 
the starport to drop it off, no big win. Well, except for unstreamlined
cargo ships. I think a whole sourcebook could be written on starports.
Hm. Maybe I should go buy a copy of TNE and write a challenge article...

Now, one other idea is: what about secondary planets in the system?
What if, for instance, the primary spaceport in the Sol system was Luna,
or Mars, instead of good ol\' Terra? There\'d be big, BIG bulk freighters
making the run between the port and the main world, but the main world would
be spared the effects of having anything really nasty unloaded right on their
doorstep.

But enough.
Ethan
