    'from' => 'Michael Llaneza mllaneza@mercury.sfsu.ed',
    'body' => 'In the discussions of interstellar supertakers I would like to point out 
one thing:

with a properly calculated jump route, such a ship doesn\'t need maneuver 
drives, and never comes inside the (a) 100-diameter limit.

this is dependent on
1) being able to place the ship in the destination system with a 
reasonable degree of accuracy
2) maintaining its original vector so that it coasts to where the tugs 
are waiting.
3) tugs, shuttles, and fuel tankers waiting in every system on the ships 
route.

In operation these supertankers-in-space would jump into a system near a 
starport, coast on residual velocity, and rendevous with freight handlers 
and fuel tankers before jumping to another system. Each jump would have 
to be calculated to make the most efficient use of the ships vector with 
respect to your frame of reference, and with respect to the vectors of 
the planets being visited.

In my opinion, such ships would exist in the Imperium, making slow 
leisurely trips. However, they would only appear in areas with large 
amounts of bulk cargo to be moved and a sufficient starport network to 
supply the huge ships.

Warning: this is an _early_ beta release of an idea, be gentle

