Actually, what I envision here is somewhat similar to Intermodal Shipping as
it is done today.  Railroads move LOTS of trailers and containers between
intermodal yards.  The trailers and containers are then offloaded (swapped
actually) and tractors pull them to the end customer(s). 

I could envision intermodal terminals in orbit offloading containers and
both company and private handlers using non-starships ferrying one or more
of the containers to the end customer.  

Your right in that there may be planets that forbid ships of any description
just landing anywhere.  However, there is present day precident for that as
well. Aircraft are not allowed by the FAA to just land anywhere (except in
emergencies).  However, some private parties have heliports that range from
a circle on the front lawn to prepared sites, to landing pads on the roof. 

Container ships these days ply the oceans and the containers are
(interestingly enough) the same that is used by the intermodal trucking
system.  It is very conceivable (and I don\'t doubt for a minute it happens)
that a single container could be pulled by all three modes of
transportation...

