    'body' => '
(Continued from previous message)

 catering to _all_ tastes, translators, wexlers, and so on
 (Whoops, sorry.  A "wexler", from the German "Wechsel", is a
 money changer.  He\'ll take your Darrian credits and convert them
 to Domains, or vice-versa, at a bit of a premium.).  Usually 
 inside the extraterritoriality zone, so that you don\'t have to deal with the
 problems associated with the strange mores of the planet.

X::>General Crowding. Any successful port soon outgrows itself. Vancouver
 ::>apparently has ten or twenty ships anchored in the bay at any given time,
 ::>waiting for a berth. For most big starports (any type A, I\'d think)
 ::>there would be several ships waiting in orbit for a landing spot.
 ::>Presumably, most planets would have a small orbital station where captains
 ::>could go to arrange an agent, etc while waiting, even if orbital cargo loading
 ::>is impossible.

 Possibly.  But, I figure that there will be multiple downports in
 an area to handle overflow, with Starport Authority-provided
 transport and communication between them.  So that if your agent 
 is based at Kennedy Down, and they route you into Newark Down to
 relieve a traffic buildup at Kennedy, you\'ll be able to let your
 agent know, and he\'ll switch the necessary personnel and material 
 over to Newark.

X::>Big, BIG ships. PCs, in their 200-ton Free Traders, need to take very
 ::>profit-dense cargo to make money. This, however, probably isn\'t
 ::>the backbone of interstellar trade. If planets are like countries today,
 ::>some will produce lots of agricultural goods (like Canada, grain and
 ::>wood pulp) and some will focus on manufactured goods (like Japan, where
 ::>there are literally no natural resources). For things like grain and
 ::>wood pulp, you ship them in the biggest ship possible that doesn\'t
 ::>break under it\'s own weight. Grain freighters would be in the thousands of
 ::>tonnes range, if not the tens of thousands. The same would go for
 ::>petroleum, wood products, even water to desert/arid worlds. PCs\' ships
 ::>would be dwarfed beside these ships. In some cases, these big ships
 ::>might not even unload at the starport - why unload a crude oil tanker at
 ::>the starport when you can fly it right to the refinery? On some worlds,
 ::>this may be prohibited though, making it difficult to transport that amount
 ::>of cargo unless prior arrangements have been made.

 Check the economics.  You\'ll probably find that most worlds will 
 be minimally self-sufficient under normal circumstances, which 
 means that most trade will be technically in the "luxury" class.  
 Is it cheaper to build a high-efficiency waste reclamation 
 facility on a desert planet, and import Lake Erie once every few 
 years, or to import Upper New York Bay at frequent intervals?

X::>Anyways, that\'s enough rambling, but it gave me quite a few ideas on how
 ::>big starports might work.

 Sure.  If it works for you, go for it.  I\'m just giving you my 
 perspective.
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com
