X::>It occured to me (of course) that this is probably a lot like what a
 ::>starport would be like - lots of ships coming and going, cargo getting
 ::>loaded and unloaded, etc. There were a lot of interesting things that
 ::>I think would apply in campaigns...

 Reasonable hypothesis...

X::>Local Pilots. In order not to screw up the rather tricky job of
 ::>moving these big ships into the rather tight port, a local pilot
 ::>comes aboard to bring the ship in from the harbour. At big starports,
 ::>this would probably be the norm to prevent pilots unfamiliar
 ::>with the starport procedures from messing up. Only at really big
 ::>starports though.

 Well, probably not.  I\'d envision something more like a current 
 airport - lots of markers, beacons, vector indicators, a traffic 
 control center, landing areas, loading/unloading zones, 
 "taxiways", and so on.  All marked in variously appropriate ways.

X::>Land-based ports. Given the amount of cargo that needs to be loaded
 ::>and unloaded, unless you have a REALLY big orbital spaceport,
 ::>you\'re going to have to do it dirt-side. Given the high costs of
 ::>orbital ports vs relatively cheap ground-based ones, you\'d better
 ::>have a darn good reason for having a huge orbital port. Also,
 ::>for reasons I\'ll mention in a bit, most ships would find it impossible
 ::>to use cargo shuttles.

 Presupposes that your cargo ships are at least streamlined.  Which 
 adds to the cost of the ship.  Cargo shuttles from an orbital port 
 are the only solution for unstreamlined ships.  There will be a
 mix, with the downport handling ships up to the size where
 streamlining isn\'t economically ruinous, and an orbital port for 
 the really large ones - not to mention that even streamlined ships 
 above a certain size might not be able to manage their own weight
 without deforming if set down.  As I recall, a large ocean-going 
 vessel is built "dry" until it\'s at the point where it\'s large 
 enough to keep the work area safely above the water line.  Then 
 the hull is floated, and the work continues.  Otherwise, it 
 couldn\'t support its own weight without deforming.  That\'s not to 
 say that it\'s taken out of the drydock - only that enough water is
 let in to support the vessel\'s weight.  I\'d expect a streamlined 
 starship to be built to the point where the cost of shipping the
 unassembled materials breaks even with the cost of lofting the
 partial hull, and then lofting the hull and finishing the job in 
 orbit.  With the largest ships, and with unstreamlined ships, it\'s 
 likely that the entire job will be done in space.  So, while your 
 downport may be larger, I\'d expect a significant skyside as well.
 Probably (in traffic terms) about a Buffalo to the downport\'s 
 La Guardia.

X::>Handling agents. A ship in port has to pay for a lot of things -
 ::>the local pilot, berthing fees, taxes, excises, duties, food and
 ::>supply costs, etc. For a ship that spends a few days in any given
 ::>port, it\'s rather unlikely that the ship\'s captain will have the
 ::>time and inclination to do all this himself. Thus, the handling
 ::>agent. Familiar with local customs, laws and business, he does all
 ::>that stuff and the captain pays him for all the ship\'s costs while
 ::>in port.

 Yup.  Except for the local pilot, as above.  Multiworld corps that
 are involved in shipping will probably have a full time HA on at 
 least the largest (population) planets that they serve - and 
 probably a contract with an "authorized" HA on the others.

X::>Cargo crews. Apparently in Vancouver, there are so many ships, sometimes
 ::>your cargo crew won\'t show up either \'cause the weather\'s bad and they all
 ::>stayed at home or there just aren\'t enough people to unload all the ships
 ::>in at a give time. Also, some types of cargo need special handling
 ::>equipment, like grain or coal and if there\'s 8 grain ships in at once,
 ::>it might be tough sharing the grain loading equipment. Some starports
 ::>would have robots, of course, but this probably invites other problems
 ::>and worries, not to mention TNE virus effects.

 Well, as I understand it, most interstellar cargo would be 
 containerized in standard sizes, even "bulk" like grain or "fluid" 
 like oil.  That would allow for automated handling to a very great 
 degree, and probably wouldn\'t require an AI intelligent enough to 
 act as an active host for Virus (though egg-carriers are 
 possible).  Cargo crews would probably only be needed for those 
 cargos that can\'t be containerized in the standard manner - live 
 plants/animals, for the most part.

X::>Sailors\' taverns. I forget what it was called, but apparently in almost
 ::>every major port there\'s a bar/hotel called the Sailor\'s somethingorother.
 ::>It makes it a little easier for foreign crews to find their way around -
 ::>there\'s one stop where they can get a drink, meet other crews and find out
 ::>about local attractions. Most real ship crews phone home too, which
 ::>starship crews won\'t do, but there\'d presumably be an xboat drop for
 ::>sending letters home instead, if the spacers had a permanant home to send
 ::>anything to.

 Yes.  In fact, there\'d be a whole town or city there - "Startown".
 A generally less-than-savory place.  Taverns, flophouses, gambling 
 dens, information centers, post offices, a red-light district 
