    'body' => 'Wow, what a lot to comment on!!!

 which was first,
>the city or the port? In the case of Vancouver, if all shipping stopped
>tomorrow, things wouldn\'t be pretty, but the city wouldn\'t disappear.
>The port area would, sure, but a lot of Vancouverites wouldn\'t notice for 
>a while. While startown\'s fortunes would be directly related to
>the volume of traffic, there\'s probably still a real city not too far away
>which would keep startown from disappearing completely.

This is currently a significant fear in the shipping world - due to 
intermodal usage, international freight is becoming more & more centralized 
and squeezing out the mid to small ports entirely.  {SCENARIO HOOK} The 
competition for usage (between ports) -because of the tremendous effects on 
the local economy - might prove lethal...


>with a properly calculated jump route, such a ship doesn\'t need maneuver 
>drives, and never comes inside the (a) 100-diameter limit.

For ships like this, I like his idea...They coast on residual velocity, and
keep it from one system to the next - why would they ever need to stop?
(Coasting is the same as stopped to starships...)



>Container ships these days ply the oceans and the containers are
>(interestingly enough) the same that is used by the intermodal trucking
>system.  It is very conceivable (and I don\'t doubt for a minute it happens)
>that a single container could be pulled by all three modes of
transportation...

Conceivable?  hehehehe.  Sorry (no snideness intended), its my business, 
and for me the above is tantamount to saying "A spacebar an interesting 
device, and I suspect it\'s used very frequently."  Every day, a thousand 
times a day.  This is the norm for ANY freight that\'s more than 300-400 
miles from a pier.  The commonality isn\'t coincidental - it\'s the result of 
a worldwide standards agreement in 1964 (i think).  International standards 
are simple - 20 and 40 foot containers, with some oddball equipment (tall 
ctrs, 45\' containers, reefers).  US has additional \'standards\' accepting 
48\' and 54\' trailers and containers.  I suspect the Imperium would be sort 
of the same, with the Imperial standards, Aslan Standards, Solomani 
standards, with some common points between them.
I think the commerce system in an interstellar-aware system would be 
similar, just on a larger scale.  You would have the \'satellite economies\' 
of colonies etc on outsystem sites, which would feed raw materials and some 
mfg goods into the primary economy of the system, which would feed into a 
transit hub - a central site a good deal out from the system which would be 
the nexus of transit to/from the system.  Just as modern ports are strictly 
quarantined from their surroundings for various reasons, why would a future 
society be any different?  They would want to keep outside traffic very 
much at arms\' length until cleared for system entry/transit.  Placing the 
main upstation in orbit of the mainworld (as is 99%of the traveller 
universe) really doesn\'t make sense...talk about an invitation to 
smuggling, illegal entry, bilogical contamination, terrorism, etc etc.




> Check the economics.  You\'ll probably find that most worlds will 
> be minimally self-sufficient under normal circumstances, which 
> means that most trade will be technically in the "luxury" class.  

I respectfully beg to differ - the whole trend in technological advancement 
has been for greater transport capacity to allow greater population 
concentrations for greater efficiencies in other respects.  I doubt very 
much that population A worlds are self sufficient, ever.  If their 
interstellar support lines are cut, it would be DEVASTATING.  Imagine that 
the US suddenly was cut off.  We would suffer the aftershocks for decades.  
And the US is inarguably in the top five countries in the world when it 
comes to self-sufficiency in the important areas, i.e. food, energy, and 
raw materials.

> Well, as I understand it, most interstellar cargo would be 
> containerized in standard sizes, even "bulk" like grain or "fluid" 
> like oil.  That would allow for automated handling to a very great 
> degree, and probably wouldn\'t require an AI intelligent enough to 
> act as an active host for Virus (though egg-carriers are 
> possible).  Cargo crews would probably only be needed for those 
> cargos that can\'t be containerized in the standard manner - live 
> plants/animals, for the most part.

Petrochemicals and grains and lumber (raw or processed) already are subject 
to a great level of mechanization.  Containerization just clutters the 
efficiencies - which is more economical, to stuff grain into bags, onto 
pallets, into containers, and onto the carefully arranged racks on a ship, 
or to hose the grain like water into the empty hull bottom, and suck it out 
like a vacuum cleaner at the destination?

