    'body' => 'Yo Folkes,
 When I did my "cost of cargo" analysis one of the surprises
I got was that cargo becomes really cheap when shipped in bulk.
Here is an abbreviated table showing the cost in credits per
2-week jump (assuming a ship carrying 10000 tons):

                Jump 1 Jump 2 Jump 3 Jump 4 Jump 5 Jump 6
Tech Level 12   5.27   7.57   9.94   23.39  14.97  17.35
Tech Level 13   4.95   7.05   9.10   11.20  25.84  15.71
Tech Level 14   4.86  13.15   9.01   11.11  13.51  15.61
Tech Level 15   4.57   6.45   8.34   10.22  23.57  14.27

Yes! That *includes* cost of ship, life support, crew salaries,
and jump fuel. And this is for a streamlined 1-G maneuver drive
ship.
 So, contrary to my intuition, this would pretty much make
bulk carriers something that definately exists in a standard
traveller universe.
 Perviously I would have argued that most worlds would be
independantly supportable because of the cost of trade. However
if it gets this cheap then it makes sense to follow the modern
model of very interdependant nations.
 Anyone have any idea of how much volume is in a modern
super/tanker? How many containers on a modern container ship?
 This data supports the view that the bulk of shipping
is done by large shipping combines and that PC shipping only
realy comes into play picking up the tail ends and special
cases.
 Of course, you *must* have full holds to realise the
actual cost. However at that low a cost even low profit cargos
(like grain) still are worth shipping.

  Cheers,
    Jo
