    'from' => 'Eric Nolan ericno@microsoft.com',
    'body' => 'Ethan Henry said:

>Local Pilots. In order not to screw up the rather tricky job of
>moving these big ships into the rather tight port, a local pilot
>comes aboard to bring the ship in from the harbour. At big starports,
>this would probably be the norm to prevent pilots unfamiliar
>with the starport procedures from messing up. Only at really big
>starports though.

John Kim replied:

>I dunno.  The reason they do it with cargo ships is because compared
>to other means of transportation, they are incredibly unmaneuverable.
>An oil tanker moving at 5 knots (5.5 mph) needs over a mile to come
>to a complete stop.  Steering becomes impossible at slower speeds,
>hence the need for tugs.  In Traveller, we\'re talking about ships with
>1G maneuverability minimum.

Large Starports would almost certainly have local pilots.  Note that 
the fact that starships have a large maneurerability does not 
necessarily mean they can get into a narrow dock more easily - it does 
mean they can go from a safe vector to a collision vector more quickly 
(and hit harder when they do).
Even indicating where a ship should go is a far bigger job than in the 
2D floating port.
Local pilots never need to physically board ships however, remote 
control of ships systems by either a living being or an AI/Computer 
would seem more likely.  (They\'ll have to change that in TNE though, 
won\'t they. ;>)

Back to Ethan\'s comments:

>Land-based ports. Given the amount of cargo that needs to be loaded
>and unloaded, unless you have a REALLY big orbital spaceport,
>you\'re going to have to do it dirt-side. Given the high costs of
>orbital ports vs relatively cheap ground-based ones, you\'d better
>have a darn good reason for having a huge orbital port. Also,
>for reasons I\'ll mention in a bit, most ships would find it impossible
>to use cargo shuttles.

Except of course for the fact that large freighters may not have 
atmosphere capability.

>Handling agents. A ship in port has to pay for a lot of things -
>the local pilot, berthing fees, taxes, excises, duties, food and
>supply costs, etc. For a ship that spends a few days in any given
>port, it\'s rather unlikely that the ship\'s captain will have the
>time and inclination to do all this himself. Thus, the handling
>agent. Familiar with local customs, laws and business, he does all
>that stuff and the captain pays him for all the ship\'s costs while
>in port.

The Big ships you mention later will be mostly operated by Mega Corps.  
They will have personell in all ports of consequence to handle all 
these matters.  Including the booking of unloading equipment and 
manpower.  (Does make it more difficult for the Free traders out there)

>General Crowding. Any successful port soon outgrows itself. Vancouver
>apparently has ten or twenty ships anchored in the bay at any given time,
>waiting for a berth. For most big starports (any type A, I\'d think)
>there would be several ships waiting in orbit for a landing spot.
>Presumably, most planets would have a small orbital station where captains
>could go to arrange an agent, etc while waiting, even if orbital cargo
loading
>is impossible.

Bummer for the big ships all right.  Plenty of scope for palm greasing 
and other nefarious activities there (depending on the law level of 
course).  Small traders have the advantage in this situation - being 
able to put down almost anywhere.
There\'s no reason that Agents etc. couldn\'t be organised on an 
electronic bulletin board system.  Captains should never need to leave 
the ship for communications like this.


Starports are an inherent part of a CT/MT style game.  Plenty of scenes 
can and will take place in them.  They are often the first part (and 
frequently the only part) of a planet to be seen by the PCs.  Anything 
that makes them seem more real is a good thing.
