    'year' => 1995,
    'index' => 'ab157',
    'body' => 'Something that no one\'s mentioned yet is longshoremen.  One of the reasons
for
containerization (in addition to faster loading) was to reduce \'shrinkage\',
which (if memory serves) approached 20 percent at some ports!  Longshoremen
had the legal right (enforced by force and years of tradition) to scavenge
anything spilled from a broken crate (and guess who could drop the crate to
break it?).  Containers helped stop that.  

Nowadays they still have the right to steal, although the percentage has gone
way down.  I remember when the west coast was shut down for a while: the
longshoremen had a wildcat strike to demand the reinstatement of a \'brother\'
dismissed for theft.  They didn\'t contest that theft (he admitted it) but
claimed it was legal under their contract.  He was reinstated and charges
dropped.

Try throwing that on some of your players when they have a high-value cargo
to unload!
