    'from' => 'STEVEN M BONNEVILLE',
    'body' => 'Jo Grant <Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com> wrote:

> Anyone have any idea of how much volume is in a modern
>super/tanker? How many containers on a modern container ship?

I checked the encyclopedia.  I don\'t know about *volume*, but a
modern supertanker can carry five hundred thousand tons of oil,
and ships with million metric ton oil tanks are apparently in
the works.   

A figure of 1000 containers of freight was given for an "average"
container ship, but I don\'t know if this is for the common 20\'
containers, or the 40\' containers, which according to the article
are a newer design.  If they\'re standard Traveller "20\'" containers,
you could probably carry 1000 on a 8000 disp-ton jump-1 ship, or
on a 10000 disp-ton jump-4 ship.  For MT, the jump-3 and 20,000
disp-ton "Common Imperial Transport" could carry about 2500 of the
six-meter containers, or 1250 twelve-meter containers, so these
size guesses could go down a bit.  (Why is jump-4 important?  The
x-boat trade and communications lines, that\'s why, although you
could probably get by with jump-3 in many places.) 

Some more possible container sizes I\'ve calculated:
  All are three meters wide by three meters high. 
  Tonnage is calculated at MT\'s 13.5 kL/disp-ton.  Reduce the
    rated tonnage by 3.7% to get TNE\'s 14 kL/disp-ton, which
    might be more accurate -- I\'d have to check on the mass 
    per volume of liquid hydrogen. 

TYPE        LENGTH                        VOLUME
Standard.    6 meters; "20 feet"           54 kL;  4 d-tons
Double.     12 meters; "40 feet"          108 kL;  8 d-tons
Triple.     18 meters; "59 feet"          162 kL; 12 d-tons
Mail.      7.5 meters; "25 feet"         67.5 kL;  5 d-tons
Ten-ton.    15 meters; "49 feet"          135 kL; 10 d-tons

A 150 kL container of 11 and 1/9 d-tons and 16 and 2/3 meters
(about 55 feet) would also be possible, but fitting it or the
ten-ton containers would probably be a pain.  The ten-tonners 
would probably be easier to deal with, since they\'re a simple
multiple of the standard container size.

You could build specialized containers, too.  Built-in fusion
reactors powering a refrigeration system, or internal gravitic
compensators, perhaps.  Or use a modified triple-sized container 
to carry some *very* alien passengers, like Jgdi.

Traveller has tiny "Ro/Ro" ships too -- the Subsidized Merchant
can "kneel" and let ground vehicles drive right into the six
meter high cargo bay.  This probably isn\'t a real big deal on
advanced worlds with gravitic transporters, but it might be a
useful capability on the low-tech circuit.  

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>

