    'index' => 'ab173',
    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 239',
    'body' => 'An awful lot of designs I\'ve seen have the fuel lumped as a bland box
somewhere, usually as an afterthought. Since fuel is a major component of
jump-capable ships (and in the old CT rules you needed x % (was it 10?)
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Yep. A J-6 ship has to have a whopping 60% set aside for jump fuel, assuming
it isn\'t using drop tanks. This brings up something I\'ve never seen mention-
ed here & that is that some of the BB designs in the old CT Supplement 9 -
Fighting Ships, don\'t have enough internal tankage to be able to power a
J-4 jump. Some examples are the Kokirrak (p42) & the Tigress (p38). On
the other hand the Plankwell *does* have enough internal tankage for J4
but it\'s wimpy factor-3 meson screen, compared to 8 & 7 for the
others, makes it *alot* more vulnerable to meson fire. (Which also makes
me wonder why *any* imperial BB has less than a factor-9 screen esp. a
ship as individually important as the 500,000t Tigresses.) As it turns out,
from what I remember, if you only allocate enough fuel for J3 (30%) than
you have ample room on the big BB\'s to load it up with *everything*. If
you want J4 internal tanks (40%) then you have to sacrifice something,
even with a million ton design. (btw, the CT stats for the J5 Azhanti\'s
sets aside 33,000t, out of 60,000t total, for fuel. This provides for
a single J5 plus 3,000 energy points to power all the other ships functions,
including the 2G maneuver drive with zero agility. Any way you look at it
a ship like this is basically an armored fuel tank. Although the tanks would
rarely be completely full, a fuel hit, esp. from meson fire would
be pretty common. No wonder battle riders became such a big hit.

Phil
Pugliese

ppugliese@pimacc.pima.edu

allocated to bridge and control systems, etc. as well) I tend to allocate it
fairly early and, like yourself, it tends to surround most areas of the
ship. I do not use this as a deliberate protective measure, it merely
reflects the way cabling, hydraulics, landing gear, sensor antennae, hull
grid, fuel and all the other components would be likely to be spread out
over a ship\'s hull. Of this general \'waste space\', the fuel areas do tend to
be concentrated toward the rear (i.e. where the drives are). But then I map
fairly accurately using a strict 2 1.5m squares per displacement ton of each
component, so everything from drives to computers to staterooms to fuel is
accurate.

Cmdr Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)

