    'body' => 'Hmmm...this seems to be ship design week....

A.S.Lilly@bnr.co.uk (Andy Lilly) wrote:

>IN RESPONSE TO HIS VEHICLE ARCHIVE COMMENTS IN XBOAT 248:
>Are these vehicles archived somewhere? Do you have pictures of them? Are the

Yes!  If you have access to ftp (or can get it through gopher, the World
Wide Web, or a ftp-mail-server) I think most of the Traveller ftp archives
have a large number of the MegaTraveller designs developed by members of
the TML.  They\'re usually stored in UNIX compress format (.Z) since there\'s
so many, as digested text files.  Format quality varies.  Design quality
also varies, so it can\'t hurt to review a design that you plan to use a
lot.  Some great ideas, though, and everything from buses to starships to
the "meson-gun submarine".

One site that I\'m sure has them is "ftp.engrg.uwo.ca", formerly known as
"sunbane", the central ftp site of the TML before the MPGN days.  It\'s
still running, and the designs are in the directory:
  /pub/traveller/vehicles

"ftp.engrg.uwo.ca" is a standard anonymous ftp site; to be brief, UNIX
Internet folks type "ftp ftp.engrg.uwo.ca" then log into the ftp site
as user anonymous, password guest.  You use "cd" to change directory,
"ls" to list directory, and "get" to get an individual file.  Oh yes,
before you get any compressed files, type "bin" so you\'re in binary
mode.  

Two files are indices for the digests, so that you can find out what 
designs are in which files.

After you get the files you will either have to run the UNIX program
"uncompress" on them (i.e., "uncompress TL07.Z" to uncompress file
TL07.Z) or use a program that can understand the format for a Mac or
PC (or Amiga, or whatever).  You end up with a text file.

For the most part, they\'re unique designs done as text only, so pictures
aren\'t available.  There are some conversions of old designs and some
attempts to recreate actual historical or modern vehicles, and many of 
the invented designs have descriptions written by the designer.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>

