    You are making a silly assumption.  Specifically, you assume that
an attacker must attack all gas giants in a system.  Not true.  The
attacker may attack at any point in the system of his choice.  The 
defender, not knowing where the attacker will choose to attack, must
defend _every_ place the attacker is likely to attack.  So in our
solar system, four gas giants plus Pluto plus Terra must be defended.
Which divides your strength into six mutually unsuuported groups.  An
attacker of equal strength just has to pick one of your groups, jump in,
and attack it.  He has a six to one strength advantage, so he wins.  This
can be repeated almost endlessly, since when the attacker "jumps out",
he may "jump out" to another planet in the same system, appearing 
there one week later, and attacking THAT planet\'s defender.  It\'s called
"defeat in detail", and it\'s the worst nightmare of any commander in
charge of forces scattered widely from each other...
    There are other detail sorts of problems with your basic outline of
the course of a battle, but I won\'t bother going into them now, since
my comments have all been made before...

    As to the charge that SDB\'s don\'t have spinal meson guns, why not?
The SDB\'s *I* design all have spinal meson guns.  The only SDBs
around that I have ever seen that DIDN\'T have meson weaponry were
the "standard Trav" SDB, plus all the variations and derivatives designs
posted here over the years.  _Good_ SDB\'s are the size of a light
cruiser, not a 400T nothing...

                                ----Steve

