    'index' => 'ab237',
    'topic' => ' Naval ranks',
    'body' => 'Hans:

>> Crew for High Orbital System Defence Organisation 

>> BRIDGE
>> Num    Position                               Rank          
>>      UPP/Trm
>>    1  Pilot                                   Ensign        
>>    2  Navigator                               Ensign        
>>    3  Co-pilot                                Ensign        

> As I understand it ensigns are officers-in-training. You\'d have a few in
> each department, but they would be superfluous to the running of the ship.
> They\'re _learning_ how to do their job, not qualified yet.

    This is not quite the way they do things in the USN, but pretty close.
Note that, among other things, the Navigator on a US warship is usually
the same rank as the Chief Engineer, one rank below the XO.
    Naval vessels in the real world don\'t have pilots or co-pilots, of
course,
they have watch officers, instead.  The senior watch officer should be
somewhere between LTjg and Cmdr...

    Note also that in USN usage, a seaman/fireman/airman is "in training".
Skilled crewcritters are petty officers, so the PO ranks tend to predominate
on our warships.

> Shouldn\'t you have enough pilots, navigators, etc. for three shifts? Or
> at least two?

    In US usage, the "Navigator" is the department head of the Navigation
Department, and so should not be duplicated.  Of course, the Nav Dept.
will have quite a few guys...


>> GUNNERY
>> Missile Bays:
>>    1   Bay Petty Officer                      Master C.P.O. 
>>    2   Junior Bay Officer                     C.P.O.        
>>    3   Bay Weapon Rating x2                   Able Spacehand

> A Master CPO is an awfully high rank for someone in charge of a 4-man
> team. I\'d suggest four spacehands, one of them able and the rest 
> ordinary or less. 

     There are very few MCPOs in the US organization for a ship\'s crew (a
submarine usually has only two, if it even has that many).  With a four-man
crew, we would have probably one spacehand, two junior petty officers,
and a first class PO to run things.


>> FLIGHT
>> Each SDB crewed by:
>>    1   SDB Commander                          Ensign        
>>    3   SDB 1st/2nd Officer x2                 Master C.P.O. 
>>    4   SDB Battery Officer x4                 C.P.O.        
>>    7   SDB Rating x5                          Able Spacehand

> I\'d suggest one sub-lieutenant, one ensign, one CPO and 9 spacehands.

    Either an LT or a LTjg, a CPO, six POs, plus three spacehands.


>> COMMAND
>> Num    Position                               Rank          
>>      UPP/Trm
>>    1  Commanding Officer                      Captain       
>>    2  First Officer                           Commander     

> In a napoleonic Era a full captain for a ship with a crew this size would 
> be quite reasonable (Indeed, it would be a job for a quite senior captain),

> but then, that would have been a 2nd rate Ship-of-the-Line. This is a navy 
> whose capital ships runs into thousands of crew. If \'captain\' still is the
> highest rank for the commander of a single ship then there would\'ve been
> a shifting of the ranks that would make a HOSDOC a commander\'s ship (OTOH
> \'Commodore\' may have become a "senior" captain in which case captain would
> be right. An XO one rank lower than the captain is standard.

   Frankly, comparing the HOSDOC to Impy warships in general, it should be
commanded by a CMDR AT MOST.  Which would leave the XO, the Chief Engineer,
and the Navigator at LCMDR.


>>    3  Chief Engineer                          Commander     

> But your Chief Engineer is in charge of 6 people. That\'s a sub-lieutenant\'s
> billing IMO.

     The Chief Engineer is in charge of all the engineering/maintenance
crewcritters.
They are nominally the equal of the Navigator, and only slightly junior to
the XO.


>>    4  Chief Gunner                            Commander     

> With 51 people I wouldn\'t rate him higher than Lt. Commander.

    The Gunner is not the equal of the Navigator and Engineer.  I 
agree with Hans here.


>>    5  Flight Tactician, A Wing                Commander     
>>    6  Flight Tactician, B Wing                Commander     
>>    7  Flight Tactician, C Wing                Commander     
>>    8  Flight Tactician, D Wing                Commander     
>>    9  Flight Tactician, E Wing                Commander     
>>   10  Flight Tactician, F Wing                Commander     
>>   11  Flight Tactician, G Wing                Commander     

> Six identical departments rate a seperate OIC. Have a Flight Chief as
> department head. He\'d be a Lt. Commander and the individual FTs would
> be lieutenants.

    What is a Flight Tactician?  The individual pilots are the tacticians out
there.  However, there should be a Wing Commander in charge of all
the fighters who stays at home, plus a squadron commander for each
squadron who flys with his squadron...


>>   12  Chief Medical Officer                   Commander     

> The medicos are special, all right (I believe they are always officers),
> but a full commander for a departmwent of four? OTOH I think you\'d need
> more medical staff than 4 for 700+ men.

   How did you manage a medical department of only four with a crew of 700?

    Note, finally, that any _real_ warship carries enough crew for three
watches
at all the important stations.  Real warships also have minimal automation,
since
they have to carry around enough guys to have installed spares for battle
casualties.

                                        ----Steve

