    'topic' => 'Ancient dogs',
    'body' => 'David P. Summers writes:
>[Someone else]:
>>I was just thinking. If the Vargr are really derived from dogs ala
>>Grandfather and all that, what genetic characteristics would they have
>>retained?
> 
>Actually, it my understanding that this isn\'t strictly true.  They are
>genetically engineered (and then evolved) from the same canine stock
>that later gave rise to wolves and dogs (and other canine species) on
>earth.  I similar to how humans evolved from the same primate stock
>that also gave rise to baboons, chimps, etc.

No. Consider the timescale. The men that the Ancients grabbed from Earth
(for whom I\'ve just recently coined the term "Homo Antiquitus") were all
Homo Sapiens. Most of his present day descendants (Solomani, Vilani,
Zhodani, and Darrians to name some) are fully interfertile. Possibly
some of them are not; I wouldn\'t like to bet on the Genoee or the Floriani;
but if the descendant brances of Homo Antiquitus, evolving on different
worlds for 300,000 years, are still compatible, then their common ancestor
must be too. Similarily the doggy ancestors must already have been dogs 
300,000 years ago, not proto-dogs. 300,000 years aren\'t much evolutionarily 
speaking (I\'m more interested in how the Vargr can look like a variety of 
canine races that hadn\'t even been bred till a few hundred years ago ;-).



