    'index' => 'ab255',
    'body' => 'Yo Folkes,
      In going over Rob\'s designs I noted his use of
"asymetrical computer arrays" in some designs. For those
who skipped them over, the basic ideas is to install,
say, two computer-1\'s and one computer-7. The ship can
gain all the considerable benefits of computer-7 but
loses its redundancy for damage. As on small combat ships,
particularly fighters, the computer is responsible for
a large percentage of the cost, this seems a simple
and beneficial trade off.
      However, it does call into question some of the
assumptions I had made about the triple redundancy
requirement for starship computers. This question came
up recently in my own campaign. I used, as an example,
the real-world example of the Space Shuttle. (What I
can remember of it, anyway.) It also has three computers.
They each perform the necessary calculations of space
flight all in parallel. One is used as the primary source
of results. However, these results are cross-checked
against the #2 computer. If they are the same, they
are accepted. If they differ the #3 computer is
consulted and the best two out of three is chosen.
      This is the model I had assumed the traveller
triple computers also ran under. Thus, for all normal
operations, all three computers run the same calculations
in parallel. Only when at dock (and for doing jump
calculations, which are fiendishly difficult in my
world) can the computers be run either separately or
dynamically linked for higher productivity (sum the
squares of the computers and take the square root,
eg. Computer-3x3 = sqrt(3*3 + 3*3 + 3*3) = computer-5).
      By this logic a computer array would operate at the
ability of the smallest computer (the only way to keep
them in sync). Thus a asymmetrical computer array would
be of no use except for independent operations.
      What have other people assumed? If you do allow
asymmetrical computer arrays I think that could have
a wide reaching influence. I know my players, for certain,
would have upgraded their computer a few jumps back
to gain the benefits. They could have afforded one,
but not three.
   Cheers,
     Jo
