    'topic' => 'Amphibious senses',
    'body' => 'Hi there

I\'m working up a description of an amphibious race, and I was wondering 
how well senses transfer from water to air and back; if your ears are 
adapted to water sonic properties, would you be deaf in air, or 
sensistive to frequencies not normally encountered in air-borne sounds, 
or just reduced in hearing abilities, or what?  I\'m looking to have an 
idea of the senses, and my first idea is that eyes are adjusted to air, 
to look out of the water at threats, etc., and the ears are adjusted to 
the water.  This leads to a language which has a verbal form, augmented 
by body posture in air, and taste signals in water.  However, how 
feasable a verbal language is if your hearing is adapted to one 
environment I don\'t know.  I\'ll stop now, and wait for any answers.

