    'id' => '<199505031714.NAA27183@Mithril.MPGN.COM>',
    'body' => 'I think Steve made some interesting points in xboat 261:

>    Actually, about 95% of the stuff that comes over this list...

I do try to skip through the content, but I know what you mean sometimes.

>    BUT, note that the tendencies to play "kiddy games" (your
>phrase) is not exclusive to CT.  Or MT.  Or any other game.

Again, quite true. Ever tried AD&D? With youngsters? I play it and I\'m proud
of it, but then that\'s because I run an adult group and the games are
realistic, gruesome and detailed. I\'ve rarely seen children able to run good
games because they don\'t have the experience nor, ironically, imagination
required. This is particularly true in the past 5-10 years (certainly in the
UK) where most children seem to have been brain-washed by computer games - a
major cause of the destruction of their imagination, because everything is
provided for them on the screen.

>    But the CT people seem to spend a lot of time trying to
>_justify_ their "kiddy games", more so than most other people
>do....

I am probably guilty of this in my own _Traveller_ games. My group consists
of:

Myself (degree in electronics, mostly a computer programmer, doing a PhD in
radar),
My wife (PhD chemist),
Chaz (degree in electronics - background in radar, GPS, etc.),
Neil (degree in physics, background in computing),
Laura (doing a PhD in historical literature research),
Nick (degree in electronics),

and an assortment of others at various times,

BUT:
the players don\'t have a background in sci-fi (from childhood reading,
etc.), nor do they have their own Traveller rulebooks. They seem to have
quite a lot of difficulty handling some Traveller concepts, so the last
thing I try to do is confuse them with technicalities (unless Chaz starts
disputing something to do with radar!). Technicalities scared off one player
totally (come back Barry, all is forgiven) - perhaps because he did not have
the technical background of the other players, for he is quite happy to
continue to play in my AD&D group.

Having witnessed some of the acts they have got up to, I would in no way
class my Traveller as a \'childish\' game (for the same reasons I classed ,
but I think it is necessary to recognise that some gamers have to sacrifice
a small degree of reality in their games in order to maintain a smooth game
flow.

That is not to say that xboat & TML should not discuss matters of reality!
It is up to individual referees to decide what they include in their games.
Similarly, when quoting data, referees should remember to say if it is canon
or from their own games.

Andy

