    'topic' => 'RE: CT Computers (Asymetrical Computer Arrays)',
    'body' => '>For example the I (& Ibis) machines, are 1ton.  Thats 14 m^3, a lot of 
>volume.  I have in there... CPUs, memorys, storage (on-line, off-line, 
>magnetic/optical whatever), cooling & ventilation, printers, and a 
>supply of stores (paper, floppy disks etc).
>
>I am though trying to rewrite the CT rules on computer program size and 
>computer capacity, the CT computers seem a little small.

You\'ve read too much MT, and believe the re-interpretative post hoc 
explanations: CT computers as the authors first knew them were something 
different...

CT was written as "1950\'s SF with 1960\'s technology" - those computers use 
VALVES!  Transistors were brand new (and "would never catch on \'cos they were

too unreliable"), and ICs had not been dreamt up yet.  It was the computer 
itself that took up the whole mammoth 13.5m^3, and took umpteen kilowatts to 
cook the valves; and the computer staff probably spent most of their time 
continuously replacing blown valves (hence the manning levels!)

When DGP and GDW came up with MT, they tried to use 1980\'s and early 90\'s SF
and 
technology, and with that described an entirely new type of ships computer,
but 
with the same displacement etc as the original books.  They just filled the 
extra (implausible) space with workstations, displays and access spaces
instead 
of valves.

----

If you can get hold of a copy, yopu might like to look up FGU\'s SPACE Opera 
computer rules.  They had massively parallel computing way ahead of reality
(all 
of a decade...) - their memory units *are* the processors, so the large 
computers are *very* powerful.


