    'from' => 'Jo Grant Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com',
    'topic' => 'SDBs in Gas Giants',
    'body' => 'Greetings!
    I only skimmed when the SDB discussion flew past before.
But, judging by Andy\'s summary, I think I have a different
interpretation that might be new (I trust Andy to tell me
immediately if I\'m covering old ground and I\'ll desist
further verbiage...).
    The operation of going into a low, atmosphere grazing
orbit around a massive Gas Giant was less than simple. You
can only scoop across the equator. And only when the winds
are in your favour (cross winds and turbulence in a Gas
Giant\'s atmosphere are *bad news* to a scooping ship). Your
course is set well beforehand and fixed. The gravity grows
high enough that later course correction is not really
possible. Any deviation, anyway, is likely to move you out
of the "safe zone". The slingshot in and out again accelerates
you to speeds you can\'t really handle other than by prediction.
Add to this the fact that your sensors are going to be
almost useless for seeing ahead or below for EMS and Neutrinos.
Can\'t think why densiometers can\'t warn your about air
density ("It is vitally important for a <starship> to have
a fully functioning barometer". Who recognises that quote? :-).
    Did you see the atmospheric braking manoeuvre in 2010?
Ever think what sort of static charge you build up on
such a manoeuvre? Even with a static discharge probe you are
going to be followed by a continual lightning bolt from it
miles long (don\'t stroke your ship\'s cat while skimming :-).
One wrong move and you can face the prospect of being deep
enough in the well, without enough manoeuvre to never get out.
    I wrote a story a few years back about a ship whose
static discharge probe had been unknowingly damaged (someone
ran a forklift into it in a previous starport). As they
begin to skim the read the static building and work out
what is wrong. There is nothing they can do, though. Their
course is locked. Eventually the lightning strikes crippling
several systems. They can level their flight but they are
too deep to climb out again and into the really nasty
atmosphere. Imagine a leaf in a turbulent stream. Needless
to say, it doesn\'t have a happy ending.
    [I have this and other "traveller" stories. I usually find
such stuff on lists irritation so I haven\'t posted it. If there
is interest, I will. Be vocal.]

    So, having set what I see as the scene, lets look at what
this might mean in a game. Firstly, most of my Gas Giants have
a series of weather satellites but in place by the Scout service
to (monitor for science and) predict and advise ships of local
weather conditions. Frequently, if the system is in any way
civilised, there will be a cracking station with skimmer ships.
A cracking station takes low level hydrocarbons (methane, or
ammonia, or else just hydrogen and a carbonaceous chrondite
planetoid) and cracks it into higher multi-chain hydrocarbons
(like gasoline, kerosene, etc). Oil and petroleum are not going
to be common in the universe at large (being a by-product of
long-term life of particular sorts). All plastics (except rayon)
are petroleum derivatives. Thus petroleum cracking and plastic
synthesis will generally be important industries.
    Skimmers are not your meagre ships boats or cow-like tankers.
As they have to regularly deal with skimming, several times a
day, what is a low level risk for a tanker becomes statistically
higher. They are usually needle configuration, streamlined with
an airframe. Topped out as much as possible on manoeuvre drive.
Their pilots are usually at least pilot-3 and have a reputation
for being "wild and crazy beings". They also act as unofficial
rescue boats for spacers who have accidents around Giants.
[You could even theorise an Imperial Drama program about a station
and its skimmers. Sort of "Baywatch" in space. Gas Giant
surfing dudes. :-]
    Now, imagine a hostile naval force in a refuelling situation.
They will not have the co-operation of the weather satellite. They
will have to take their own scans and use historic data to
predict optimal conditions. They may storm a cracking station,
if it exists, and suborn the skimmer pilots, and take use of their
local knowledge. Or else use the cracking stations skimmers
themselves. Odds are if the system is in any way defended the
defenders have already blown the station and skimmers.
    So the naval fuel shuttles must start the operation of
skimming the giant. These tend not to be highly manoeuvrable
ships and are going to be transversing generally fixed
courses.
    Take a skimmer, as described above. Cut down its fuel tank
and replace it with some moderate armament. Call it a SBD.
Let it lurk in an equatorial orbit at or around skimming level.
It is damn difficult to see into a Gas Giant but not quite so
bad trying to see out. They Navy is likely to be passing around
its own telemetry (although probably encoded). If it can\'t get
enough info it can alter orbit till it is just above the line
where it can (periscope up!). Once it can see them incoming on
a particular course it can assume they won\'t deviate. It can lurk,
like a shark, until within range of a shuttle and then fire.
Almost any surface explosion is likely disrupt it. The static
discharge probe (presumably retracted for normal flight) and
surface sensor arrays seem particularly likely targets. They can
only undergo limited evasive actions. Any less-than-trivial
adjustment would doom them (by the above reasoning). Sort of
like trout-farm fishing. Then they just descend again and surface
elsewhere.
    Thus, the target of the SBD attack is the fuel shuttles,
not the naval ships themselves. Anyone ever design an armoured
fuel shuttle?

    Is there an astrophysicist on the list? I would be interested
in comparing my assumptions to reality. For the four gas giants
in the Solar System, what depth would have to be penetrated before
a air-pressure equivalent, say, to earth sea level, was achieved?
What would be the gravity at that point? Assuming we are starting
at a 1-diameter orbit and flying a course to that depth and
out again in an hour (standard skimming time) what is the maximum
speed achieved and what manoeuvre is necessary?

    I will go off and design a skimmer. I\'d like to digest others
reactions to my assumptions and then I\'ll propose a SDB design based
on the skimmer. Other proffers welcome...

  Jo
