Sound Travels well underwater.  Hearing organs adapted in air work
"OK" in water.  I don\'t know about the other way.

Water scatters light so vision is restricted in range.  As you go
to any real depth, you run out of light.  Eyes can work well for
both water and air, but some (not all) species will have trouble
focusing in the other medium.

As far as lanuage goes.  If we are talking about a developed race,
body form are probably going to be less popular as they progress
because a) they are harder to record, b) they don\'t transmit well
over "voice only" media, c) they make you stop tasks you are working
on when you want to communicate (this is probably the most important,
unless the species has "extra" limbs to spare for this purpose, in
which case it would lower the barriers to such communication).  I
am assuming moving and positioning of limbs.  If you have to move
and position the whole body, it would be even more inconvenient
and would probably drop in popularity more quickly.

Taste has the problem that, even under the best circumstance, it
is going to be slower than other forms.

