    'topic' => ' SDBs (again?)',
    'body' => '
I sent off something a few days ago about gas giants, bit it never seemed
to hit the list. Odd. So, here goes again.

Somebody wrote that they thought that SDBs were underpowered and
usually too spread out to be effective. That is, If you had 100 SDBs
against 100 invaders, even though the SDBs may have some advantage by 
having no jump drives (CT&MT), they\'d be spread out over an entire system,
thus reducing their effectivness to defend any one spot. I don\'t think
that that\'s necessarily how it is...

First of all, what would a SDB look like? It wouldn\'t really be the 400t
Patrol Cruiser detailed in the old black book. More likely, it would be a 
cruiser-sized vessel, in the 1kt-10kt range. There would be no jump drive,
no fuel purification plants and probably less sophisticated life support
systems because they wouldn\'t spend so long in deep space. This translates
into a ship that could easily outgun a jump capable ship of equal tonnage.
The vessel would be built somewhat higher than local tech level, but
maintained at planetary tech level, meaning that extremely old SDBs would
either be in bad shape or have to be overhauled every few decades.
(Ships build higher than local tech level would have been built out of
system or built by bringing in off-world contractors and high-tech parts.
It would cost more, but presumably, it would be worth the money, especially
if you\'re a tl 11 or 12 world, expecting tl 14 or 15 ships to be your
eventual concern).

SDB distributions wouldn\'t be uniform across the system - you defend
places where there\'s people or resources you want defended. As Jo Grant
describes in the last xboat, gas giant skimming is probably less than
trivial.
A small number of high-g, specially designed SDB lurking just under the
surface of the gas giant can cause enough trouble to severely hamper
fuel scooping.

SDBs surrounding a world would be backed up by close orbit forces
(atmospheric jet fighters) and deep meson gun sites on larger/high tech 
worlds. (I think these alone would severely hassle any hostiles trying
to land on a world, but using SDBs gives you a chance to stop them from
even trying to land). Most orbital landing craft have low accelerations
and probably handle like pigs in an atmosphere, making them easy targets
for fighters. So, anyone trying to put down a big force onto the ground
is going to have to somehow endure a fight between them, in space 
shuttles, and ground defenders, in F-15s or what have you.

In short, although SDBs probably aren\'t quite as powerful as a naval
cruiser or battleship, they can probably hold their own quite well.
Also, I think that most SDBs wouldn\'t have been designed to hold
off Imperial forces - after all, why would the Emperor invade his own
worlds? (Ha!) They\'d be built to repulse excursions from border states
and be used for internal security which would be either lower tech
or small (< 1000t) vessels.

Fights in which the hostiles are trying to capture an asteroid belt or 
orbital station are left as an exercise for someone with more time and/or
imagination than myself.

Ethan
