    'body' => 'Mark Clark <markc@brahms.udel.edu> writes:

> HOW LONG CAN A HUMAN LIVE UNPROTECTED IN SPACE
> 
>     If you *don\'t* try to hold your breath, exposure to space for half a
>     minute or so is unlikely to produce permanent injury. Holding your
>     breath is likely to damage your lungs, [ ... ]

This is something I\'ve wondered about.  In SCUBA class, you\'re taught that
the problem is relative volume.  Air breathed at 33 ft depth will expand to
twice its volume at sea level.  But air breathed at any pressure will expand
to fill a vacuum (near-infinite volume?).  Lungs must be able to retain SOME
air though, even in a vacuum.  The question is, how much?  If possible, it
would make sense for spacecraft to keep their atmospheric pressure low enough
that you CAN hold your breath, which would give you the best chance of
surviving.  I agree "the bends" are probably the least of your concern at
that time (I think you only need repressurize to 1 atmosphere for treatment,
which is probably at the top of your agenda anyway, although there might be
some immediate stroke danger from nitrogen bubbles, especially if you\'re out
there for a while).

