I didn\'t mean to impugn you... 

I was illustrating some gaming history, and the way that games derive from
the 
books the game authors read, and the subsequent revisionism as the present 
overtalkes the future.  Recent books, and hence new-from-scratch games (eg
not 
TNE) emphasise the compactness and portability of computers (to the extrem of

cyber-stuff), \'cos the authors have met ICs and powerful microcomputers.

Trav is one of an older genre of games derived from still older books, in
which 
heavy power-plant, fuel and drives dominate the ship, and massive computing 
engines figure highly.  [For a good laugh, re-read EE Doc Smith\'s Lensman
books, 
in which the older dictionary definition of "computer" is used ("one who 
computes") - they navigated by slide-rule!

There never was a ship with so much volume, mass or power comsumption
dedicated 
to computation as Trav envisaged in its "future"!  It is one of the "quaint 
charms" of Trav to recognise the \'50s and 60\'s SF stories in it;  and I
derive 
some amusement from reading the efforts of later authors to make it all sound

plausible while struggling not to remove the foundations of the rules...

>Does it matter what the details of the technology are, what\'s important 
>is the performance and abilities.  Leavened by a little bit of "science" 
>by checking the "does it feel right" factor.

It *was* "science" and "feel right" when CT first came out!  In MT they tried
a 
revised "science" and "feel right", but since then the present has overtaken 
them again... (But no-one foreshadowed the Pentium divide-bug!)

I felt in MT that the boware was OK - the number of workstations and
holo-tanks 
you could add fleshed out the required volume until it sounded plausible,
like 
the 3m separation between deck-levels (1.5x1.5x3m "ton") allows a sensible 
ceiling and inter-deck trunking.

MT tried to glide over the CT "programs" and concentrate more on the effects.

(In CT, with a Model 1, you had to swap out programs to run even simple
tasks, 
like swap Maneuver for Fire Control!)
MT tried to make it feel like the programs were intricate and extensive
(giga- 
or tera-bytes of holographic storage), unlinke the reels of mag.tape for CT.
(or 
was it paper tape???)


