    'from' => 'Jo Grant Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com',
    'body' => 'Andy Lilly writes:

>Ever tried AD&D? With youngsters? I play it and I\'m proud
>of it, but then that\'s because I run an adult group and the games are
>realistic, gruesome and detailed. [...]
>My group consists of:
>Myself (degree in electronics, mostly a computer programmer, doing a >PhD in

radar),
>My wife (PhD chemist),
>Chaz (degree in electronics - background in radar, GPS, etc.),
>Neil (degree in physics, background in computing),
>Laura (doing a PhD in historical literature research),
>Nick (degree in electronics),
>and an assortment of others at various times,

As a long term, ancient gamer, I sympathise with many of your
points. I do a lot of fantasy gaming as well. I used to check
out new systems looking for one that had a more realistic model
of fighting, etc, etc. Then I started doing some SCA (historical
recreation) where you actually put on armour and bash people
with sword size and weighted objects. The conclusion I came to was
that no system I had seen came close to reality and it was
unlike that one ever would.

The wider lesson I learned was that *any* element of *any* RPG
system will always fall down and fail to satisfy a professional
of that element. This makes a degree of sense. If the system is
truly realistic then you need to be a professional to operate
the game mechanics. E.g. if you had a professional (expert? :-)
system for fisticuffs, say, then it would mimic all the decision
making processes necessary for doing such professionally. For
you to succeed you would have to make the correct expert decisions
and thus might as well be a professional boxer.

So where does that leave us? If you accept that any system is
only going to be an approximation then what you have to do is
to pick/tailor that approximation to meet the level of expectation
that your players require.

Andy broke down his group as an example, I\'ll break down my
current group for my example:

Me      Degree in Mathematics, employed as a computer professional
Wife    Doctorate in Biblical Studies, in academia
Derek1  Basic Leaving Cert education, works in a print shop
Derek2  Basic Leaving Cert education, sells plastic barrels
Colin   Studying for Leaving Cert

All are around their late 20s (except Colin who is 17). With
this sort of varied, non-technical, background this influences
what gets singled out as important in the campaign. They run
a merchant ship. When I work to produce CARP software it is
more along the lines of shipboard account management, and
course plotting. They don\'t care about ship design, they just
want to know what ships are on the market (and actually used on
ship for 3 years, real time before I realised that it was
underdesigned by 16 tons! But then that turned into an interesting
plot device...)

The summary of what I am trying to say, is that different groups
will require different support in various areas. In an open forum
like this you have to expect that 95% of what is here is [largely]
irrelevant for each particular campaign. Aside from being inevitable,
there is a certain benefit. Areas where heated debate takes place
on the list that is of no direct interest on your campaign can
exist as coloured backdrop. The raging debate over human attitudes
towards Vargr could surface as anything from what _else_ is on
the news to NPC motivations. Balkanised systems could be all het
up with accusations and counter accusations of member states
developing or researching high-V planetary bombardment weapons
provide tension leading to a plot device. Recent independent studies
calling into question the relevance of SDBs might prompt actions
from industrial action to a crackdown on government expenditure.

None of these may be directly relevant to the main plot/theme of
a campaign, but, they can all add richness and texture to
almost any campaign.

Jo

