    'topic' => 'Lessons of Modern War  ',
    'body' => 'TOWERS/ARAMIS 1108

Darius Jedburgh lent on the wrecked remnants of the shattered striker grav
tank 
his unit had lost earlier to a tac missile hit, "There\'s nothing worse than a

battle won - except a battle lost."
	Captain harrelson, Jedburghs aide de camp and executive officer of the 
Red Hawks mercenary unit grunted in agreement.  His main worry was being put
on 
another damn starship for a weeks jump - if god intended man to travel in
jump 
space, he would have fitted him with a jump drive !

harrelson activated the map box precariously positioned on the remains of the

grav tanks shattered hull, amidst a bottle of half drunk reginan brandy (1102

vintage), and a wad of papers and after action reports.  after connecting the

battle computer link, they went over the tactics of their previous three day 
engagement to see what tactical lessons they could employ next time.

The first key to their success was in using their air/rafts effectively.  
Previous experience (raid on camp V) showed the potential of the extra
mobility 
for creating mobile fortresses in which the commando company could deploy, 
strike, or hold terrain, and then scatter.

The second key lay in their communications network.  by hooking up mapboxes
and 
"squirting" data concerning their positions to prearranged nodes, the company

could keep in touch and adjust tactics as the situation demanded.

The third lay in re-arranging pallets of logistical supplies.  each platoon
had 
supply pallets containing sufficient medical supplies, food, water,
ammunition, 
power packs etc. to keep operating.  The system also minimised the number of 
troops diverted to making up supplies as necessary for porting to the 
battlefield.

The fourth lay in the choice of weapons.  though a little controversial the
red 
hawks stead-fastly refused to upgrade to gauss rifles, in spite of the higher

tech tickets they could compete for.  The key problem lay in resupply - in a 
longer campaign gauss may be difficult to obtain, and if operating in a
hostile 
environment ie. a planet whose government is both lower tech, AND not happy
to 
see us, they may embargo gauss rounds, making life rather difficult.  besides

Jedburghs ACR had jammed a total of three times - he relied on it, and would
not 
change it for a squad of PGMP equipped marines, besides as he often joked "If
I 
need PGMPs - what the hell does the enemy over the hill use...."

