    'body' => '==SKIMMER CHARACTERS==
Rob - If not to xboat, at least send \'em to me, please!

==CLOSE-DEFENCE OF STARPORTS, ETC.==
Bart, here are my views, i.e. what happens in my game (NB: starport refers
to any docking situation, including small ships into large ships):

(1) All starships are required (by Imperial/local law) to have their weapon
systems (including weapons sensors) powered down when within weapons range
of the starport. The device (typically a computer program) responsible for
this is called the \'weapons interlock\' program. This also explains why
anti-hijack systems may not use any external ship\'s weaponry for ground
defence.
(2) Possession of a starship with a faulty or tampered interlock system is a
SERIOUS offence.
(3) Starport sensors can detect the following:
 (a) Close range - if an individual weapon is powered up.
 (b) Medium range - if shields or multiple weapons are powered up. 
 (c) Long range - if spinal weapons or active (weapons) sensors are powered
up.
(4) Doing any of the above without bloody good reason you tend then to
discover:
 (a) Starports have better sensors than you.
 (b) Starports have better weapons than you.
 (c) Starports tend to have patrolling ships which can come and get you.
 (These follow naturally for any large starport when you consider the total
value of the landed ships, cargo, buildings and people within the port -
people expect their investments to be protected, even at a civilian port).

Operation of the interlock may be automatic (receiving a beacon from the
starport or when passing within a given zone known by the navigation
program), or manual (requiring the pilot to activate it). It may be possible
for some military ships to remotely activate the interlocks on some civilian
ships (by mimicking a starport beacon, etc.). Yearly (or whenever)
inspections are required for ship safety certification and checking of the
interlock system would be included in the inspection.

The hidden explosive cargo is a different type of risk. However, the sensors
available to a starport (as per a starship) should allow it to detect
reasonable quantities of unstable/radioactive elements and hence detect
nukes. Random customs boarding (while the vessel is still some distance from
the port) can prevent such a situation as well as their more common use for
detecting smuggled goods, illegal immigrants, etc.

But that\'s just what goes on in my campaign... no one\'s gonna blow up my
orbital starport after I\'ve spent weeks designing the floorplans :-)

Andy

