    'body' => '1.Rob - Post the skimmer character information -


2. I wish to respond to the points made by JSHiggin in xboat digest 271.  In his
comments of digest 270 he lists the ages of the technologies I mentioned, and
lists them in 
terms of Terran years.  With the star spanning universe having planets of 
variable tech-levels is it not the case that to a tech level 0 caveman, a map
box which may have first been built 10,000 years is still a novety ?
	Secondly when discussing the air/raft, my point was mainly concerning 
the employment of 3d mobility, and making use of it, as oppossed to treating
the air/raft as a car without wheels.
	Third, from my own experience as a player in campaigns and a referee, it 
was always a little more difficult to obtain PGMP and FGMP technology (imagine 
the USA with this kind of hardware available `off-the-shelf`), and so my article 
discussed abeit briefly, the pros and cons of the best of the unexotic weapons - 
namely the ACR versus the Gauss rifle, and it was my assertion that nine times 
out of ten, it would probably be easier to use ACR\'s rather than Gauss Rifles.

An interesting example of the age of these weapons could possibly have been 
witnessed in comments by a US general in a UK documentary (Horizon: The i Bomb)
about technology and warfare.  He showed the example of the Somalis who had a
culture thousands of years old which has barely changed to adapt to the 
Twentieth century, yet were using modern Russian assault weapons, and rocket 
launchers, the Afghans are another good example.  What I am saying is that the 
difference between the age in which a weapon was invented and the culture which 
operate it (and vica versa) is irrelevant, particularly in a traveller setting.  
I hoped to provide ideas for players to use their tools in possibly a more 
imaginative manner, unless the referee hands out striker grav tanks, battle 
dress and fgmps regularly (and I would hate to envisage the opposition...)

In summary, if you had already considered the ideas I put forward in the original 
article, then I apologise sincerely for wasting the news groups time.

regards
Jeff
