"We All Died at Breakaway Station," a pulp science fiction novel from 
theh late 1960s, has a scene in which two characters in a small ship 
(a courier or something) have gotten separated from the fleet, and 
their computer is damaged by enemy fire, so they have to navigate 
back to wherever they belong by using a slide rule.  I\'ve forgotten the
author\'s name.

"Starman Jones," by Robert Heinlein, also from that era, has the 
navigation staff all calculate their jump numbers (or whatever they 
were called) individually, then program the numbers into the ship\'s 
drives only when everyone agrees.  Starman Jones comes up with a 
number different from the captain\'s, but is either shouted down or 
cold-shouldered into suppressing it, and everyone agrees with the 
captain\'s figures.  Of course they end up lost in space. I\'ve 
forgotten how they navigate their way back, but I\'m sure they used 
plenty of pencils.
