    'index' => 'ab312',
    'topic' => 'Mercenaries',
    'body' => 'Jeff, Steve...

I can well see Steve\'s points about the relative age of the mercenary
equipment mentioned in Jeff\'s post. However, I would like to point out that
a lot of people playing such characters (and to a degree their referees) are
rather ignorant of military tactics. Now, some groups are lucky - I get the
impression a lot of subscribers to the old TML (and possible current ones)
have or had military backgrounds anyway. But to the others, a bit of a hint
on why particular mercenary groups are so equipped is helpful. I don\'t have
the post to hand, but one might assume that Jeff\'s mercenary group is
planetbound and not the interstellar \'for hire\' group that most people think
of. After all, there are plenty of opportunities on a single planet for such
a group. Their limited experience and home world tech level (and the age of
settlement of the planet) would all determine how \'modern\' weapons and their
use were viewed.

>From my own viewpoint, I would think that at higher tech levels, mercenaries
tend (as Steve said) to be fairly equally equipped with similar weapons
(e.g. PGMPs, FGMPs) and then I think it is usually the (1) other equipment
and (2) tactics which matter more, i.e. 
(1) Chameleon armour, uncrackable communications links, computer-controlled
HUDs, etc. - very much electronic warfare.
(2) Getting more firepower to a position than the enemy - better protecting
your troops, supplies, etc. Careful use of grav AFVs, etc.

Remember the logistics: low tech war, lose one soldier with perhaps CR50k
training, CR2k of kit. Medium tech (say today\'s crack SAS, etc.) lose one
soldier - that\'s c. CR1M of training [semi-official figure] and perhaps
CR20k of kit. Lose a high tech infantry man (battledress and FGMP) - that\'s
perhaps CR100k training and perhaps CR1M kit? FOR A MERCENARY UNIT, which is
effectively a profit-based organisation (okay, so some people do it for
kicks!), you just can\'t afford to lose soldiers (or worse, vehicles) like
you can at low tech.

So, here\'s my version of higher tech!

============
Tyger, Tyger
============
