        Corporal Frank "Zappa" O\'Leary froze instinctively. His chameleon
armour - a lightweight, high maneouvrability battledress - continued to
\'flow\' for a fraction of a second before matching to the surroundings. Tiny
areas of the armour modulated its colour to match waving foliage around him.
        The jungle was dense, shadowy, heavy-leaved and oppressive. The
latter was helped slightly by the wide angle visor of the battledress
helmet. Helmet cameras compressed the view behind him into thin bands at the
edges of his vision; coloured blips played across the Head-Up Display,
displaying known troop dispositions as green dots. It was the orange dot
which was dangerous.
        Without moving his helmet, Frank\'s eyes flickered upwards. He could
not see the tiny hovering globes around him - each about fifty metres away
and ranging from ground to tree canopy in height. These camouflaged \'eyes\'
ranged across the electromagnetic spectrum over a far wider range than
Frank\'s puny human sight. Mostly remaining passive to hide their location,
occasionally a random drone would \'chirp\', sending a burst of active sensor
pulses into the surrounds, both it and its colleagues picking up and
processing the reflected signals.
        And one drone had chirped, located a target, and had failed to match
it against the constantly updated position data of Frank\'s unit. Not that
the drones would be expected to pick up any of his unit - the battledress
was designed to fool visual and IR sensors while absorbing radar,
ultrasonics and other detection systems. The orange blip was not visible on
passives, so Frank knew it must be well concealed - perhaps even in a bunker
or covered trench.
        Frank waited a further moment; his whole unit would have been warned
of the potential hostile and he knew better than to advance without orders -
the battle computer, or perhaps even his commanding officer, might decide to
send in a combat droid, or fuz-bomb or allocate an alternative trooper to
the job. Confirmation arrived. His eyes flickered across the holographic
displays on the visor, eye movement activating \'switches\' and automatically
relaying the message that he was on the job, assuming command of a drone,
instructing it to approach the hostile. Visual camera pickup flashed up in
one corner as Frank began to advance. He kept on foot - activating the
integral grav belt would be nice but the radiated fields from the damn thing
more than quadrupled his signature, even with the high tech ECM of the
battledress.
        The remote view of the drone flicked between visual and IR. Frank
noted the slight round coolness of a camouflaged pit trap on the ground
ahead of him. The drone sniffed no explosives, could identify no unusual
linearities within its vision (to indicate trip wires, etc.), nor could it
detect life forms within or around. Given the local tech, the \'natives\' were
obviously resorting to archaic trapping techniques! The drone continued a
further hundred metres then rose and skewed around to approach the hostile
from behind and above. Visual showed an area of thick growth but the
thermal-imaging showed multiple shapes - a gun pit of some sort. The drone\'s
sensors indicated a well-shielded power source - probably an energy weapon. 
        Frank had reached the trap pit but gave it a wide berth. After all,
the rebels might have obtained a \'Slinky\' or \'Weasel\' or some other
low-signature mine. He selected the ammo type for the multi-gun, confirmed
target programming with a single wink of the eye and pulled the trigger. The
IntelArm 97b \'Drifter\' puffed gently into the air and through a hole in the
canopy before igniting its weak rocket. As it powered in a short arc toward
the target, Frank decided it was time to move and clicked in grav, rising a
few feet and zipping away to one side. The rocket dropped through the canopy
approximately above the target - simple sensors pinpointed the target centre
- it showered pellets then an instant later fired its penetrating charge.
The charge bored a hole through the plasteel canopy on which foliage had
been laid for camouflage. The resulting explosion of molten steel was
augmented by the fire-cracker effect of the anti-personnel pellets, ensuring
no one survived.
        The drone showed Frank the results. He almost smiled but then his
HUD went hay-wire. His previous location near the pit, now a hundred metres
to his right, ignited as the enemy brought down retaliatory fire. Orange
hostiles began winking into existence as they opened fire at other members
of his unit. One was very bright - perhaps only ten metres away - his own
suit sensors suddenly blaring warnings of a head-shape emerging from the
ground with a linearity computer-resolved to be (93% likelihood) a heavy
automatic weapon - probably a light assault gun. The multi-gun came to bear
but interlocks were already warning him that using the fusion gun option was
dangerous - it\'s blast would tear through the jungle in the direction of a
member of his own unit perhaps only thirty metres beyond the target. The
computer had already selected fully-automatic AP Gauss. Frank pulled the
trigger and the target grew bright red. Visual showed - well, the head had
gone. The computer was already arming a grenade in the launcher and Frank
simply rose a few metres (to give a better angle into the hole) before
pulling the trigger and flying back and away. The earth erupted, enemies
dead or buried.
        Fire broke out around. Drones updated information. Orange dots
disappeared quickly from the HUD. Then all was silent.
        Frank allowed himself a smile now. The computer had decided the
rebels had insufficient reconnaissance kit to allow real troops in rather
than automated combat droids. And the local government had specified minimal
damage to the environment (it _was_ a nature reserve, after all), hence the
lack of heavy grav tanks. Frank was glad. The computer was always right.

