    'body' => 'Bart Van Brabant writes from Belgium:
 
>My question is, can this thing happen. Let\'s say I maneuver
>my little cruiser into the docking station and fire all my
>weapons with the result of destroying the spacestation or
>at least do loads of damage.
    You would probably blow out the bay and maybe one
or two neighbouring ones. That is assuming you were
docking in an internal bay, such as is used for repairs.
By design logic, it is much cheaper to build a stations
of irregular configuration where most of the docking
is intersersed over the hull or long gantries. This ploy
would be even less successful there.
    If you reference the previous "rock throwing" thread
you can see many strategies for one high-V ship (or rock)
that will take out an entire planet. Needless to say this
works much the same for a space station.
    There are more interesting, perhaps, ways you might
take out a space station.
    A normal starship missile comfortably fits inside a
grocery cart (I think). This wouldn\'t be that difficult
to smuggle into the StarSation\'s power plant. The power
plant will be a restricted area, but unless they are
expecting an attack the bribe value you need to get
it will be much less than the cost of the ship you would
smash above. I was reading the other day that if a
vehicle (fusino) power plant receives destroyed damage
it must roll 3D < Tech Level or dramatically explode.
A well placed missile (and a generous DM) might lower this
to D2.
    Another bizzare idea might be to load up your suicide
ship, not with explosive, but with propellant. It would
then (gently) impact into the side of the station and
ignite it. Assuming it was a reasonably small station
the delta-v from the resulting thrust and burn could
destabalise its orbit beyond recovery. Sure, it might take
a year or two before it finally falls into whatever it is
orbiting but that is a couple of years of publicity and
a lot of unwilling investors.


Jo
