    'from' => 'M. Stiavelli',
    'body' => 'I have followed with interest part of the discussions on the "Lessons of
modern war" or "the ancient art of war", depending on viewpoints..
(I subscribed only recently, I may have missed something)

I thought that I could also drop a few comments, drawing from my past
service in the Italian Army which is currently following rather standard
NATO concepts and schemes.

1- As it has been suggested already, strategic and perhaps high level tactics

ideas can be drawn from the past, but these old lessons are, in my opionion, 
often only little more than commonsense. 
The low level tactical implementation of operations relies very much on the 
detailed characteristics of the tools at hand. If one looks at the Falkland\'s

war, which is probably more relevant to mercenary tickets than the Gulf war, 
there have been occasions where a single SBS forward observer would
effectively
neutralize a battery or a company simply by directing shipboard gunfire. 
Neither Sun Tzu nor von Clausewitz could have expected that. 
It is very challenging to try and understand what the various Traveller 
technologies would do to ground combat.

2- NATO officers were trained in the dangerous art of "fighting by the book".

NATO doctrine was prepared on how to use in battle the standard NATO unit 
types. If applied without judgement such a conduct could cause defeat even 
against a lower TL opponent, provided he is smarter (which in the Gulf War 
wasn\'t the case). Actually the NATO pursuit of efficient C^3, is probably
based on the idea that only through high tech one could open up new 
strategic and tactical possibilities.

3- Logistics will get more and more difficult. I am sure that in many 
situations one will be better off with some weapons that do not require bulky
ordnance. Sometimes it will be easier to maintain FGMPs than find new 
cartridges. The F117s during the Gulf War, just to make one example, 
dropped bombs for several times their weight...I would expect that in the 
average interstellar campaign supply will be at least as important as in the 
North Africa during WWII.

If there is really a serious intention to work on a manual of military
tactics I would be happy to join! (btw I do not have Striker, is there a
way to get hold of one copy?)

       Best wishes,

            Max

