    'index' => 'ab321',
    'topic' => 'Interstellar Warfare',
    'body' => '     On May 16, Mr. Stiavelli wrote:
     
     "If one looks at the Falkland\'s war, which is probably more relevant 
     to mercenary tickets than the Gulf war, there have been occasions 
     where a single SBS forward observer would effectively neutralize a 
     battery or a company simply by directing shipboard gunfire. Neither 
     Sun Tzu nor von Clausewitz could have expected that. It is very 
     challenging to try and understand what the various Traveller 
     technologies would do to ground combat."
     
     I found this very interesting in light of events that occurred in my 
     current Traveller campaign.  I just completed refereeing a mercenary 
     adventure in which a Broadsword Merc Cruiser-equipped team of 
     mercenaries were sent to a backwater system to liberate it from a 
     squadron of vargr corsairs.  One of the issues that came up was 
     gaining control of close orbit.
     
     I was surprised at the strategy my players took.  They got the 
     corsairs\' attention by attacking several of the strategic points on 
     the main world and drew two corsairs into orbit.  Once they did, the 
     merc cruiser managed to disable one of them before either corsair 
     could even detect the presence of the Broadsword.
     
     The mercs quickly took control of close orbit airspace and the vargr 
     had to sue for peace.  Though I really wanted more "big gun" action in 
     my adventure, I had to realize the vargr had no recourse but to 
     negotiate for peace once they had lost dominance of close orbit and in 
     fact, their very method of getting back home was threatened.  
     Otherwise, the mercs could have placed a forward observer in the hills 
     and just started calling in a hail of shots from space to blast the 
     corsairs to pieces.
     
     Thanks for the interesting observations, Mr. Stiavelli.  If you\'ve got 
     more ideas, please share them.  As a person without military 
     experience trying to conduct a military campaign, any such advice is 
     welcome.
     
     --Chris
