    'body' => 'jfb94@aber.ac.uk (Jeff) writes:

>However, the problem was this - Striker appears to me to be more wargame 
>than role-playing game, whereas mercenary though sadly-lacking in vehicle 
>generation rules is great in its provision of an abstract mass-combat 
>system, which in our campaign we proved time and again works....

Well, if you absolutely don\'t get any fun out of tabletop wargaming, then
an abstract system is best. Otherwise it is quite possible to combine war-
gaming and roleplaying and to let one enhance the enjoyment of the other. 
I fondly remember an old fantasy campaign where the Ref ran both roleplaying 
sessions and tabletop wargaming. Our RP characters were adventurers who had 
bought captaincies in defunct regiments  -  regiments without men. We spent 
our time on quests to enhance our reputation (to attract men), we did 
favours for high noblemen to get them to persuade the king to reactivate the 
regiments, we scrambled to hire the 120 men it took to avoid deactivation 
next muster day, we worked harder to get more men so that we could provide 
our henchmen with suitable commissions and still harder to get the money
to buy colonelcies in our own regiments once they had grown big enough to
warrant a colonel and to avoid some rich twits buying them and taking over 
the fruit of all our hard work.
And then one day we were invited to a tabletop session and were informed
that _those_ 20 figures over there represented my regiment and _those_
over there represented my friend\'s. Believe me, it adds a whole new
dimension to a wargame when you know and care for those small lead figures! 


