    'from' => 'Aaron DaMommio aarond@pencom.com',
    'body' => '
Some comments regarding the discussion of high-tech mercenary units in the
future.

Given that reliability, support, and logistics seem to be major issues with  
current battle technology, might not some of the advantages of future  
technologies be that these issues could be addressed?

With hundreds of years to refine the concept of a mercenary unit, someone
might  
come up with battle armor, weaponry, and vehicles that are high-tech, but  
self-repairing and self-supplying -- ideal for a low-tech environment.

Suppose that at some point it gets harder and harder to squeeze real  
performance gains out of certain technologies. After that, the gains should
be  
in lower energy costs, greater reliability, lower expense, and greater  
versatility.

Some ideas:

- I once read a book with short stories about high-tech armor. It included an

essay purporting to chart the development of armor over centuries. The final

result was "smart-matter" whose shape was programmable; the "armor" was the  
weapon (and sometimes a complete vehicle) as well, and could form projectiles

or beam weapons from its own mass. This idea led to some odd, comic-bookish  
images, but provided food for thought.

- "Living Armor" that regrows damage, and can glean energy from solar or  
thermal sources.  Such armor might be biological in nature or might operate  
using nanomachines, the size of microorganisms, that are constantly repairing

and rebuilding it just as our own cells work on our bodies. The armor can  
adjust itself, tailoring itself to fit any occupant over a day or two. It
might  
be made out of ceramics and metal, and could "eat" lower tech items,
processing  
them to get building materials for repairs.

- John Varley in one of his stories posited a symbiotic partner for a person

that served as a sort of living vac suit. It provided protection as well as  
companionship. It was amorphous.

- Weapons based on any of the above principles

Such equipment would help a mercenary to concentrate on strategy rather than

supply. Of course, they might also tend to change the feel and flavor of your

Traveller campaign, as these kinds of technologies would be very popular and

easy to maintain, and thus potentially widespread. However, all technologies

have their own problems -- some ideas:

- An uninhabited planet where mutated nanotech lifeforms have gone wild
- Someone reprograms your armor so that it attacks you
- A virus attacks your armor or your weapons

While from what I read, powerful and interesting nanotech isn\'t that far off,
I  
think there are some problems with these ideas in terms of play. I think many

people choose Traveller because of its hard sf feel and because of its  
militaristic bent. While the militarism isn\'t directly endangered, ideas like

this begin to change the feel of technology. It\'s not so much solid stuff
that  
sometimes breaks down; it\'s more malleable, and is more likely to mutate than

to break. I think this is more accurate, because given the current rate of  
change of technology, our world 10 or 20 years from now will be very strange
to  
us; how much more strange, then, will the universe be hundreds and hundreds
of  
years from now?  In order to adopt more powerful technologies like these and

retain some of the same feel, I\'d suggest stressing the new problems brought
up  
by the new tech, to give a sense of gritty realism.

These ideas are of course just starting points. I\'d be interested in any  
comments.  Some game books with interesting biotech are GDW\'s DarkTek  
sourcebook for the Dark Conspiracy game, and West End Games\' Space Gods  
supplement for the TORG role playing game.  I haven\'t seen any good
discussions  
of nanotech for games, and any suggestions would be much appreciated.

--Aaron DaMommio
