    'index' => 'ab330',
    'body' => 'Chris (I am assuming we drop the Mr etc) writes:

>If you\'ve got more ideas, please share them.

Well, I have ideas, but are they right?

Jeff writes:

>..in the field of personal arms I am still not completely convinced. Gauss
>weapons may have higher magazine loads, but what about your second key - 
>logistics.

What\'s the best solution is unclear. There might even be no best solution,
namely depending on the campaign the order of preference might change.
In my campaigns the Imperial Marines get the best money can buy (although I
am not sure of what that is..), while the Imperial Army is more a 
sector/subsector level organization, with each planet contributing to his own
TL
(or in any case with what THEY can buy). As a result the logistic problems
for
the Marines and the Army are rather different. The Marines rely a lot on
energy weapons since they require maintenance but no ammo. The opposite is
true for the Army. The idea is that one could always repair a broken FGMP
may be getting spare parts from the friends up in the sky. As a result the
Marines are more easily deployable without preparation but more expensive
to maintain. I am not sure how realistic this is.

>The coalition relied upon ...

Yes, indeed a long campaign could have been a problem as far as I can guess
(I was not any more in the Army during the Gulf war). Part of the problem
lies in the size and diversity of the coalition forces. In the Sharp Guard
operation in the Adriatic Sea NATO has set up a Forward Logistic Site (FLS).
All the various NATO navies concentrate their logistic flow to the FLS that
in
turns distributes supply, spare parts and even mail to the various ships.
The big advantage of this setup is that none of the Navies (possibly except
the USN) has enough ships in the area to justify a completely autonomous
logistic chain. In the Gulf probably a similar setup would have not been
convenient. Since I assume the Imperial Army to be far from homogeneous,
logistics can be a lot of fun...I would think that mobile FLS would
be required.
In some operations where various mercenary groups and planetary armies
cooperate, an FLS would probably be an important asset.

Steve writes:

>Still? I\'m sure glad that we have never wuite fallen into that trap.

During my officer training in 1987 the Airland Battle doctrine so successful
in the Gulf was not yet really adopted by all the NATO Armies...I think
Airland Battle has been a great achievement, a book saying that you shouldn\'t
fight by the book...Also there is BIG difference in training concepts (not
only quality) between elite forces (Marines, airborne, etc) and the main 
front mechanized and armoured units.
The Gulf war was for the US, the French and, perhaps, the Brits the first 
war in years fought not only by elite troops. I was sure that any NATO army
had elite troops with the required degree of training and initiative for
that sort of actions, but I wouldn\'t have bet my money on the remaining 
forces.. And who would bet on the degree of preparation of the 
Vincennes or the Mora Imperial Army troops??

Before finishing this huge mail (sorry...) a proposal and a question:
1-perhaps we could start defining how a squad/platoon should be
equipped and then if we end up with different ideas..fight it out. Each
of us could set up a mini-wargame and test the various options. I would
see it as an Imperials against Imperials exercise. A Marines squad could
be carried on board an Empress APC (vehicle 36 in 101V) and a TL 14/15 
Imperial Army squad on an Astrin APC (33 in 101V). 

2- has anybody noticed/seen/heard about the US Army SIPE (Soldier Integrated 
Protective Ensemble Project) and AWE (Advanced Warfighting Experiment)
or the French ECAD (Equipment du combattant debarque\')? it looks like there 
will be combat environment suits with integral power supply, HUD, and IR 
chamaleon options pretty soon..


       Massimo

