    'topic' => 'Genetic Manipulation',
    'body' => 'Jo Grant <Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com> wrote:
>    There are many and varied laws throughout the Imperial member 
> states regarding what can and cannot be done through genetic 
> manipulation. Surprisingly there is correspondingly little Imperial 
> law covering the subject. Aside from the usual guarantees of planets 
> rights to control the import and export of new or altered beings the 
> one overriding restriction is that "No human DNA or DNA sequence may 
> be used as a basis for genetic experimentation or production." (The 
> legal interpretation extends to other sophont races as well.)

>From a gaming point of view, this has the nice result that it gives 
smugglers something to do.  The results of research done with human DNA 
outside the Imperium could be smuggled in, in ways that involve players. 
The research could be by the extra-Imperial worlds themselves, or extra-
Imperial states, or by Imperial megacorps with holding on those worlds 
(e.g. the SuSAG activities on Tarsus in District 268).

There is one official piece of library data that clashes with this 
Imperial Law, however, being the Spinward Marches world of Nexine, which 
"is an underpopulated water world where the Imperial Ministry of 
Conservation currently operates a reseeding program using _biologically_ 
_altered_ humans.  Candidates are provided with gill implants, synthetic 
skin insulation and webbed extremities.  They participate in sea farming 
operations under the world\'s shallow seas". (The underlining is mine)

The Imperium might be faced with a military problem in avoiding genetic 
research, in that the Solomani or Sword Worlds or whoever could threaten 
the Imperium with a biological agent against which it has no defense. 
Given that the Solomani are so proficient at things biological, the 
Imperium may well have trouble keeping up even if it did try. Solomani 
and Aslan mentions whole geneered human sub-races, some of which sound 
quite repugnant... Such an individual would probably have to contact 
smugglers to enter the Imperium, under the suggested Imperial Law.

The present problem with the Ebola (sp?) virus is an example of a 
threat. If it were more contagious, the human race would be in big 
trouble at the moment (if they let it spread any further, big trouble 
may yet happen).  There are other examples too, such as the growing 
incidence of cerebral malaria in South East Asia at the moment (spread 
by mosquitoes rather than contact with infected people, as with Ebola).

It is possible that there are secret Imperial military biological 
research stations (from which, naturally, things occasionally escape or 
are accidentally released), to attempt to defend against such threats.

I heard part of a story on a recent Australian radio science program 
that digestion weakens the effect of some pharmaceuticals (these enter 
the body via the gut, so they have to get through the stomach first). 
Some scientists are trying to get pharmaceuticals into plants which pass 
through the stomach (maize/corn being an example, I suppose), so that 
smaller amounts are needed to produce the same effect in the body. Such 
plants could be the object of a Safari Ship style adventure or an 
interesting cargo that not all worlds would accept.

Finally, here is the draft of a genetically engineered lifeform, 
designed for the Yiklerzdanzh sector, but can be transplanted.

Player Information

Gibbers are artificial lifeforms produced by the Carillon Harmonies, for 
sale to the mass market as living translators (cost Cr 4000). They 
appear to be based on omnivore gatherer stock, probably based on a marsh 
dwelling creature. They are short, squat creatures, with a large head 
mounted directly on the shoulders, bearing large multi-faceted eyes that 
are further apart than normal, large bat-like ears and a broad nose. 
Gibbers have sexual organs, but all gibbers sold to the mass market 
appear to be infertile.

Although Gibbers can fend for themselves in the wild after a fashion, 
they prefer to be fed. If one is fed by only one person for about a 
week, an emotional bond forms and the gibber will translate for that 
person, whenever held by the hand. They can eat virtually any type of 
food, and will be quite happy as long as the owner feeds them regularly, 
pays them attention from time to time and combs its fur. When left to 
their own devices, they scamper about and gibber to themselves, 
