    'day' => '19',
    'body' => 'Again on logistics..(hopefully with correct arithmetics)

To quantify the logistic needs of a medium-high TL campaign I have started 
considering a Sword World TL11 unit (safely below the TL of PGMP,FGMP).

BEGIN handwaving:

Each squad is on a TL11 Masala APC. 2400 ACR rounds are fired each
day, 10 MRL10 and 10 vanilla SAM (5 l, 10 kg each). The 3cm autocannon
fires 1000 rounds per day (5 turns at ROF 200). Personnel requires 5 l/5kg
per day (generous, but we italians like good food..).

3 squads plus 1 8 cm mortar firing 210 rounds per day (5 turns at ROF 42).

3 platoons plus 2 12cm mortars firing 270 rouds (5 turns at ROF 27) and
2 VRF (5 turns at ROF 1000) make a mechanized company.

3 mechanized companies plus a tank company (similar to the above but
with Gram tanks) plus 1 support battery on 4 20cm MD (5 turns at ROF 121,
max at TL 11) make a mechanized reinforced battalion (a combat group).

Each of these at the rates of fire described above would need
407 kl and 369 tons of supply per day. It is not unconceivable that the
peak ammo use could exceed those given above by a factor 10.
After all everything is assumed to fire only for 5 turns a day..

A division fielding 9 such groups (a mechanized NATO division would probably
field only 6 such groups but..) ends up needing 3663 kl and 3318 tons per
day.

Fuel requirements would be an additional 5.6 kl per btn (50 per division).

As a comparison the btn is equipped with 55 APC and 15 tanks ie
945 kl of vehicles and 6185 tons. In terms of volume, two "typical" days of
combat operations require as much cargo capacity as the initial deployment.

Actually, I have neglected other equipment, support units, and vehicles for
the 
MDs and heavy stuff that increase the deployment volume requirement, on the 
other hand I have also neglected spare parts which may end up requiring
between 
1 and 5 per cent per day of the volume of deployed equipment.

By assuming that each "elementary" component has a medium time between
failures of 5000 hrs. The chance of it breaking in a day is 0.16 per cent
(assuming it is in use only 8 hrs). I count 32 components in the Gram and
15 in the Masala. The chance of something breaking in a single day is 5
and 2.4 per cent respectively. Translating into spare parts volumes of
about 0.1 kl per vehicle. This is roughly 0.15 per cent of the vehicle 
volume per day.
HOWEVER, the opponent often tries his best to increase the damage..thus I
think that the 1 to 5 per cent given above is reasonable.

END handwaving....

Summarizing ammo supply is likely the worst problem for Armies equipped with
high ROF weapons (e.g. TL8 MRLS..), spare parts and fuel follow. Depending
on conflict intensity, daily  supply requirements may range from few percent
to
several times (!) the deployed volume.

Before something like this can be tried at TL14/15 we should try to
agree on a few rules..It is not unlikely that the use of energy weapons
at TL14/15 combined with the self-repairing technologies mentioned by Aaron 
on xboat digest 277 would reduce significantly any logistic problem. What
I do not know is whether this is realistic and desirable for the RPG
viewpoint.

                 Max
