David Jaques-Watson says:

>1.      Starship weapons use neutral particles (which hold together in
vacuum 
>but break up in atmosphere);

Reasonable assumption, still as it has been noted already, what you really 
need is a neutral beam not a beam of neutral particles. In a magnetic field 
the neutral beam becomes polarized and develops an electric field balancing 
the Lorenz force. A neutral beam is easier to produce than a beam of
neutrals.

>2. 	Surface PAWS are charged (generally following a laser-cut "hole" in the 
>atmosphere but which break up in vacuum).

It seems to me that plasma instabilities (e.g. Kelvin-Helmotz) will destroy 
such a beam rather quickly. Point defence usage would be possible but
probably 
nothing long range. I guess this is still matter of debate among physicists.

>..the main problem was not the range of the weapon, but the range of the 
> sensors..

Agreed, and it is also realistic. Once you see them, they are dead. 

>I do. We used it (home ruling??) with a danger space of 10 m

I do not have at hand now my ironmongery manual. By using the 50 ton bay 
meson in the MT rules and the blackglobe rules for energy transfer, I find 
that the MG transfers energy at 20,000 MW rate. This means 1.2E11 Joules per 
6 seconds turn = 0.03 kiloton.  By rescaling such an energy (crudely) one 
finds a 200 m danger space. Sounds a lot but is probably what one wants when 
dealing with strongly armoured, agile Grav Tanks.
In 6 seconds a supersonic tank can move 10 times that distance.

Peter H. Brenton said:
>I still think missiles (purpose built) would be the primary orbital support 
>weapon.

Might be, but a missile has to physically reach the neighbourhood of the
target
intact, avoiding anti-missile fire and  E^(any odd number)CMs. Also it has to

be quite a good missile to approach  a fast vehicle like e.g. the Invader 
Tank (vehicle 24, of 101 V).

High ROF Mass Drivers (from the ground) using the same smart rounds with 
terminal guidance could end up being more convenient since you reuse the 
propulsion system.

>The problem is one of intelligence, not targetting.

Yup, especially to get the sensors of those heavy MGs underground..

For the Xboat Ground Cbt Manual we should really agree on a set of concepts
and rules. If indirect fire is powerful, tanks will operate like cockroaches,
if it is not, then  the only enemy of a grav tank is another grav tank and 
one might end up with some kind of dogfight.

                                  Max

