    'topic' => 'More indirect fire and fleet maneuvers',
    'body' => 'Dear Jeff,

I feel that our opinions do not differ as much as it would initially
appear...

>Artillery today utilises smart technology ..

Indeed, I have in mind smart rounds like the IMC (Improved Conventional
Munitions), FASCAM (Field Artillery Scatterable Mines, GRAV!!),
SADARM (Search and Destroy ARMour), various ammo for the Phase II and III
of MRLS and ATACMS like the BAT (Brilliant Anti-Armor Submunition) and a 
few more things developed at higher TL. I haven\'t had time (yet) to make my
mind on whether mass drivers with smart rounds are better than meson guns.
In any case, I define as indirect all weapons that do not require direct
line of sight to the target, therefore including launch and forget missiles,
and most smart rounds.

>What say you Max in defence ????

You may be right indeed. Even forgetting about the real world and
concentrating on MT, I do not know which way it goes. A fast moving
Grav Tank has a very high signature...(at least acoustic..). The
issue is: how much firepower would be required to .. silence it?
if the firepower required is more expensive than another tank then..
I hope to find the time (and players) to equip different
forces at the same TL but very different operational concepts and
see what happens (I suspect that the outcome will depend a lot on the
terrain features, e.g. desert vs jungle). I guess that\'s what the Imperial 
Army and Marines would do anyway..As I suggested some time ago, if a few of
us
agree on the exact rules and each suggests an order of battle we could run
a few wargames in parallel... 

> AWACS ships are a little tricker - do you have designs for any for CT ?

I have designed some picket ships in MT (I could do it with HG if there is 
interest, although it is a long time that I do not use it). The main problem 
with MT is that the way sensors work is not very smart..

My house rule is that each sensor can perform ONE task per turn free
Each extra task reduces the UCP of every offensive weapon by one. In
addition if a ship signature is above faint I increase the difficulty
level by one unless sensors are on a boom.  
With these rules it is very convenient to have lots of small ships full
of sensors deployed around your fleet directing the battleships fire.
With such an arrangment the battleships would stay out of sensor
range of enemy battleships, and both parties would try to locate the
opponent\'s picket ships. If space fighters are used to locate the
opponent\'s picket ships and protect your own then the picket would
probably turn into an AWACS.

On another fleet combat issue, reading various discussions on the list I 
have the impression that it is generally assumed that fleets jump in a system
as a whole. Actually, since the time for jump is randomly determined
and may vary by up to one day, I\'ve always assumed that a fleet
will reach a system scattered in space and time. This makes fleet
operations even more difficult. 

              Cheers,

                Max
