    'index' => 'ab372',
    'topic' => 'Perspective.... ',
    'body' => 'Just a brief comment on Tim Salisbury\'s post in Xboat Digest 285

"One thing to note:  In Tom Clancy\'s novels, the complaint i\'ve heard is he
has 
the high tech stuff TOO realiable.  Alot of the toys we actually deploy
sometime 
have a 60% failure rate reported, so the real rate is probably much higher."

This is a statement well worth bearing in mind.  Here are a couple of Tech
Level 
7 - 8 examples from recent history.

1. The US army sought to develop a point defence anti-air system called the 
PIVAD or Sargeant York.  It had a radar which could track low flying rotary 
objects i.e. helicopters.  In its debut to esteemed members of the services,
the 
executive etc.  it was put through its paces, whereby it tracked a rotary 
object, and engaged - successfully destroying the fan on a US army field 
toilet...

2. The US Navy advanced AEGIS system enabled phenomenal response times as,
with 
minimal human inolvement, a radar would identify, track and prioritise
targets 
for the automatic missile system to engage.  On occassion this system has - 
recognised an A310 Airbus as an F-14 tomcat, and killed 300 people, and
nearly 
destroyed a quantas jumbo jet flying over the Pacific.

3. The gulf war of 1991 was characterised by pictures of highly accurate 
missiles hitting targets flawlessly.  remember many did not, and these were
not 
shown !  much work is being performed fitting GPS to paveway bombs and just 
about everything including the kitchen sink to improve accuracy - why if the 
weapons were so accurate in the first place ???

4. Also, the patriot missile system whose radar was confused by the poor
quality 
of Iraqi scuds that broke up on re-entry creating many targets....

In short, the state-of-the-art can be extremely tempremental, and players
scream 
"unfair, its not in the rules" when their gizmos break down.....

Regards
Jeff
