    'ts-index' => '1995-05-30.ab386',
    'ts' => '1995May30',
    'file' => 'XBOAT95/XBT95288.TXT',
    'id' => '<9505300804.AA12543@internet1.lotus.com>',
    'index' => 'ab386',
    'body' => 'To my disappointment, the article entitled "Ships and
cockroaches" had very little to do with the latter
and mainly concentrated on grav-tank aerobatics, which,
while I\'m sure is a jolly good topic in and of itself
was not what I was expecting. I am dealing with this
by considering for a moment...

    Consider for a moment: just how clean are traveller
spaceships? Are they the just-painted shiny bright of
StarTrek\'s Enterprise or the mangy and decrepit of
Alien\'s Nostromono? They answer, of course, is probably
yes to both, and all of the spectrum in between. So
consider for a moment all of the creepy crawlys, vermin,
and other garbage eaters that have plagued the earth
since before humanity evolved. Is it likely that we
could have left them behind when we went for the stars?
Would we even have had the choice?
    Consider the cockroach. Older than man, it is one of
the most successful species, evolutionary speaking.
I\'m willing to bet it could survive being trod upon by
a triceratops, I\'m willing to bet that zero-G wouldn\'t
phase it. Ships have wiring, air ducts, panelling and
sink fittings like any modern place. There are still
likely to be as many architecturally useless places 
for them to hole up. Food preparation and cleanup is
unlikely to be 100% efficient. Not worth the cost. If
a cockroach can live by eating the glue in corrugated
cardboard boxes today, I\'m sure it can live equivalently
by licking the lubricant from a starship\'s laser couplings.
    Consider the Norwegian rat. A bane to seafarers since
that first dugout log floated down a river. Starship holds
are big. Canisters may be tough but there are always
weaknesses. How much food does a battleship crewed by
thousands go through? Where do they store it? If mice can
learn to walk on tiptoe and survive in meat freezers,
I\'m sure rats could become very aware of "take hold" sirens
and "vacuum imminent" warnings.
    Consider mildew. A ship or station in normal orbit
transverses from light to dark much more frequently then
we terrestrial subjects experience. One of the complains
from Skylab was how the ship popped and pinged as the
hull expanded and contracted going in and out of the
light. No matter how advanced your life support, condensation
is going to be a problem. Where there is condensation and
head, you\'ve got mildew. Even with the best production
system, I\'m willing to bet that nature is still cheaper
a lot of the time. Spaceships will still have natural
fibre seat coverings, wall coverings, etc, etc. Plenty
of scope for scum eaters.
    So consider finally, as you run your games, what is the
potential for vermin. Not only will the tramp freighter\'s
they hire on leak oil, but also crawl cockroaches. Raw
recruits on a Navy ship get sent on rat patrol. The
sleepover room they hire at the starport D was cheap because
it has a mildew problem.



