    'year' => 1995,
    'from' => 'Orlando',
    'body' => '>Apart from starship indirect fire or support fire which is obviously
important,
>and has already been discussed in the list, one thing that I have always
found
>hard to accept is the lack of modern indirect fire weapons at TL 12-15.

I think there are a lot of improvements to be made, but the basic means of
delivery will remain unchanged: Throwing an object up so that it lands on
your enemy. Whether this is done with compressed air, chemical propellants,
or electromagnetic mass drivers is irrelevant - there are only so many ways
to throw a ball.

I think one reason artillery development pales in comparison to small arms
development is that the technology for small arms changes - lasers, PAWs,
and so on - while artillery delivery doesn\'t. The improvements in artillery
are going to be faster response time, coordination of multiple spotters,
and greater accuracy. I imagine that by the Imperial age, personal
navigation transponders will relay the exact position of each friendly
trooper, and sensor suites mounted on each trooper will provide information
on enemy locations in relation to their positions. Right now it takes a few
minutes at least, even with the aid of computers, to relay the position of
an enemy, calculate the attack, and traverse to fire. THat process gets
speeded up tremendously by computer and sensor improvements that allow for
such automated integration of information.

>operations, however the minimum meson gun size is crucial. I have
>tried to design TL 13 support vehicle in MT (the TL13 equivalent of the
M109)

Do you need a meson gun? Don\'t munitions improve at all at upper TLs?

>My feeling is that Army generals would either ask for lighter meson gun
>designs or for some new more powerful and smarter kind of ammo for the
>mass drivers.. The idea of hiding your artillery where the opponent cannot

Drones and missiles maybe become more effective and cheaper alternatives to
traditional artillery. A contragrav drone with masking a high velocity
could run anyone\'s day more than single round, and are especially more
effective when you consider advanced artillery rounds would be like small
drones anyway.

>see it, looks too good to be abandoned. Faster vehicles (especially with
>high signature) would just call for deadlier weapons.

The improved targeting I mentioned above might let artillery finally target
vehicles on the fly - right now it\'s just too difficult to hit a fast
moving vehicle with artillery.

>On a separate issue, how do people on the list see sensors and naval cbt?
>obviously it all depends on the precise rules, but I do like to have
>AWACS ships doing the sensor work for battleships. Is this common?

Not for battleships, no. They typically have pretty good sensors for
themselves. Aircraft Carriers seem to have the Command and Control ability
in US Naval doctrine. Of course this is based only on limited experience
with Harpoon. . . I"m sure some real naval times could tell more
accurately. Still, IMHO most starships will be capable of detecting objects
for themselves, and if fleet actions occur with ships several light-seconds
apart, independence will be even more important.

J Roberson      est. 1973
