    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

I.	BATTLEFIELD MESON ACCELERATORS

Excerpt from Striker [Mk 1]:

"Battlefield meson accelerators are introduced at tech level 15." (page 5)

"The firing sheaf is a circle centred on the MPI (after deviation), with a
radius equal to the weapon=92s burst size...A meson accelerator may fire=
 with
less than its stated burst size; if so, the fire mission order must state
the new burst size." (page 5)

The MPI is the Mean Point of Impact; ie. the centre of the fired shot.

The stats for the TL 15 battlefield meson accelerator are:

Power:	250 MW input
Volume:	15 m3
Weight:	15 tons
Price:	MCr 10
Burst Size:	10 cm
Crew Req=92d:	6
(Striker Book 3, page 39)

Note that Striker scale is 1 cm =3D 10 m. Therefore, 10 cm =3D 100 m radius;=
 200
m diameter. Max Stiavelli was exactly accurate in terms of danger space.
Next time, I=92ll look up the stats instead of going by memory!

----
Striker Book 2: Advanced Rules
=A9 Game Designer=92s Workshop, Inc
USA 1981.
Striker Book 3: Advanced Rules
=A9 Game Designer\'s Workshop, Inc
USA 1981.
Striker and Traveller are trademarks of Game Designers Workshop, Inc. Their
usage should not be considered as a challenge to these trademarks.
----

II.	MT BATTLEFLEET ARRIVAL IN-SYSTEM

Max Stiavelli writes:
>	I\'ve always assumed that a fleet will reach a system scattered in space
and time. This makes fleet operations even more difficult.

DGP recognised this problem, and came up with a revision that said (roughly)
that one ship would work out the jump calculations for the fleet, all would
jump together, and this would result in ships arriving within minutes of
each other. If you want me to, I will fish through my magazines and give you
the exact ruling.

III.	RE-WORKING TRAVELLER

Steve Lieb writes:
>	Is it just me, or is Traveller in need of a serious reworking=
 scientifically?

I thought that this IS what TNE was all about: that the game did not
correspond to reality, so change the game.

(As an aside) My beef with this is what I want to use the rules _for_. TNE
is more of a _simulation_ than a game. For an example of what I mean:
Harpoon is a _simulation_. It uses real-life stats and converts them to game
terms (and uses them so well that the US Navy uses the game for basic
wargames). However, this causes problems when you play:

a.	"Low-tech" troops and equipment do not stand a chance (as in reality);
b.	It is difficult to balance opposing forces in order to have a good "game"
(as opposed to a walk-over by one side).

Now, I don=92t (necessarily) dislike "reality" in a game - I want enough to
make it believable, but not enough to overpower it - I mean, this is a GAME,
not REALITY - that is the point, surely? If you played out "Die Hard 2"
using TNE, what you would get is "Die Frequently" (as an aside, my wife -
who is not overly fond of the DH movies - wants the 4th one to be called
"Just Die, Would You?!").

We can suspend disbelief and allow transporters in Star Trek - or allow
magic and fantastic monsters in AD&D - without worrying about the Heisenberg
Uncertainty Principle, or the conservation of energy, or the inverse square
law! Why can=92t this extend to SF? No, I do not advocate going as far as
Space Opera or Buck Rogers, although those type of games can be fun. I want
_harder_ SF than that.

However, the TNE rules seem to be over-complicated for a GAME. I believe
that GDW has made a marketing decision to allow themselves to be pushed into
a niche market. They now have the most realistic game system on the market
today (even if you include the errata - or perhaps BECAUSE of the errata!) -
but it appeals to a very small market because of its realism (and therefore
complexity). Look at what people are buying: apart from the Magic cardgame,
they are buying ROLEplaying games. These usually favour characterisation and
scenarios over rules - often, a GM can dispense with dice for entire=
 sessions.

At this point I will note what Derek Wildstar (wildstar@qrc.com) said in
digest 289:
>	If you want to play Star-Trek-like or Star-Wars-like games, Traveller: The
New Era isn\'t the right tool for the job.

And what Andrew Richard Doull (adou01@cs.auckland.ac.nz) said in Digest 292:
>	I feel GDW are closest to the gaming community when it comes to explaining
why they made their design decisions, and recognising a mistake when they
make one.

OK, so GDW are good guys in that they take notice of what people say, and
maybe I should just use the background (which I love) with another set of
rules. I have created a system based on (don\'t laugh) AD&D (cut in with a
bit of Buck Rogers), for one of my Traveller groups who prefer heroics to
realism...so, back to POW! WHAP! BASH!

IV. FREIGHT VS CARGO

In xboat 289, Robert Brennan wrote:
>       ...in MT there is mention of both freight and cargos but the two
seem confused...
I believe that that "freight" is other people\'s cargo! That is, "cargo" is
what you can buy, with all the requisite modifiers. Freight is what you
transport for other people, at a fixed price (Cr 1000/ton, isn\'t it?).

V. TRAVELLER FAQ - COPYRIGHT LAW IN THE USA

In xboat 290, Andy Lilly suggested that:
>       ...discussion of copyright law...should be on the list\'s FAQ...
Could you or someone else send a summary of the discussion to James Dempsey
for inclusion on the WWW FAQ? His address is jamesd@spirit.com.au - thanks.

- Hyphen
  (David Jaques-Watson)



