    'body' => '
  My players like the little touches which give a game a feel of
  realism - things like printing mission orders on standard forms, 
  and sticking those forms into a standard folder.  Things like 
  NPCs having noticeable quirks.  Things like foreign languages
  being written in non-Latin characters.

  It\'s feeding that last one that can really make a difference - 
  especially if the foreign orthography you choose to use is 
  consistent with the "feel" of the information you have on the 
  language you\'re using it to represent.

  For example, _Rats_and_Cats_ has Aslan male script as a flowing,
  ornate script with lots of curlicues.  Tamil and Malayalam both
  work well for that.  The female script is more angular - but in 
  keeping with the general feel of Aslan society, I\'ve chosen to
  use Arabic/Farsi to represent it - it\'s more angular than Tamil
  or Malayalam, but it still has the same kind of feel that I
  associate with Aslan society.  Another alternative for either
  might be to use a "Tengwar" font from JRR Tolkien\'s elvish
  languages.

  Vargr languages probably vary as much as Vargr polities do.  But
  because of the basic shape of the face and the structure of the 
  vocal apparatus, all of them are likely to have many harsh sounds,
  and lack softer sounds, especially the sibilants.  Almost any 
  "angular" charactery will work for that, from Japanese Kata-kana
  through Old Norse runic to "Klingon" representations.

  Vilani is a very formalized language, even in its current demotic
  koine form, in keeping with their social attitudes.  Devanagari
  works well to convey the kind of feel I get from it, with 
  Traditional Chinese or Korean hangul the best second choices.
  (N.B. The same can be said of the Newt/Bwap tongue, if you play
  with Newts.  Don\'t select similar-looking alphabets for Newts and 
  Vilani.)

  Zhodani was a tough one.  It "feels" more like Polish than
  anything else, for some reason, which makes it a slavic language.  
  OK, let\'s use the Cyrillic alphabet - but don\'t use any letters 
  that bear a strong resemblance to Latin alphabet letters, and use 
  similarly non-latin characters from the Greek alphabet to fill in.

  For Galanglic, naturally, I use the standard latin alphabet, in a
  font suitable for the purpose.  Representation of older dialects 
  of Galanglic (Anglic, English, etc.) I generally try to render in
  a font that looks "old fashioned" - perhaps Goudy Old Style for
  something dating back to the Rule of Man, Fraktur or blackletter
  for something dating back before Terran Confederation days, or
  pre-starflight.  The further back you go, the more you should vary
  spelling - mutate consonants (d to/from t, f to/from v, etc.), 
  add or remove aspirants (h, w), and so on.  With a little work, 
  including contextual analysis, your characters should be able to 
  dope it out, just like you or I can manage Middle English, or 
  someone with both Modern English and Modern German can figure out 
  a good amount of modern Dutch or Afrikaans. 

  Minor race tongues I look at on a case-by-case basis. only as 
  needed.

  Just tossing out some ideas.  Comments?
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com
