    'body' => '>For several years now a thought has been niggling at me. Traveller 
>seemed to lack something - and that something was a 3rd dimension to 
>the universe.
    This has been discussed before. I\'ll give a brief summary
of what I remember and then state my own views:
    1) Rationalisation: Space really is 3D but the physics
of jump-space are 2D. Thus the 2D maps are really of where systems
appear in jump-space rather than real space.
    2) Rationalisation: Space really is 3D but it is a bugger
to map so for the game\'s sake we use 2D.
    3) Rationalisation: Jump drive technology only works well
in planes parallel to the galactic plane. Several "parallel planes"
exist, the Imperium occupies only one. The others are only reachable
by STL drive.
    4) Refusal to rationalise: run it 3D.

    I run my game 3D. I have for a number of years and have
not found it a problem for my players. Mind you I use the
Sysgen software for my campaign background so I don\'t have to
worry about the massive amount of generation you need.
    As jump drives increase the number of stars you can reach
increased by the cube rather than the square. This generally
makes borders rather untenable. At the moment my characters are
moving from my equivalent of The Imperium to my equivalent of
the Solomani Confederacy. The two are currently at war but
there is no firm battle line. Rather just a increasing probability
as one moves in a general direction that each individual system will
be one or other.
    Another effect is that even if you are low-jump, the number
of worlds you can get to in 4 jumps is vast. Say you are looking
for a TechLevel-G world with a hydrographics greater than 4.
The odds are it will be within 4 to 6 jump-2s. No problem.
As I said above, you really need some form of automatic generation
to keep up with where the players can go.

>My campaign is *very* much a Merchant Prince one in a
>home-grown universe based on Anderson, Cherryh, Norton,
>et al. Any other Merchant Princes out there?
    My campaign has also been largely trade based. Again,
I use more software to manage this. When I ran it on
Tuesday they actually did get involved in a fire-fight
and is was more a question of "Use the lasers, those
bloody missiles cost 10,000 a shot!".
    [I\'m a big Cherryh-fan too and my campaign bears
much from her influence. Love to chat about it off-line
if you like. BTW: The Internet Cherryh Mailing list is
run from jaymin@maths.tcd.ie. Send a message saying you
would like to subscribe to it to that address. Plug plug.]

>Since Traveller was published, computers have progressed
>way beyond the simple models represented
    So? In our own era we have seen computers get
significanly more powerfull. My desktop machine at work
is about 40 times more powerful than the mini that my
whole college department ran off of. However, back then
I could write a simple "input three parameters and do a
basic calc" program and it would be about 4K. Now to
do the same with my tools at work results in something of
about 60-90K.
    Sure, hardware has improved, but in general software
has expanded to fill the gaps. I have absolutely no
problem with computers in traveller, and I\'m a computer
professional! If you want to search a database, the
algorithyms may be better, and the software faster, but
you can damn well bet the database will also be several
orders of magnitude larger. Just look at the net today,
compared to 10 years ago. There is a lot more out there,
but not that much more of interest (for me, anyway :-).


Jo
