  ^^^^^^^^
> writing system will mainly consist of one of these methods.
>
> Alphabetic grouping:
>    Generally symbols will be grouped at one level higher than
> their representation. I.e. if individual sounds are represented
> then spaces are more likely to occur between words. If words
> are represented then spaces are more likely to occur between
> sentences, etc. But not always.

Minor correction which might be of interest to the orthographers on
this list.  Korean uses a phonetic alphabet, making it more like
English than Chinese.  Groups of these characters are arranged to make
syllables, and groups of syllables make words.  Because of this
arrangement, written Korean looks like each syllable is a separate
character, but it just looks that way because you\'re used to words
being composed of characters.  Each syllable is further broken down
into its own characters, so Korean words are composed of syllables
which are composed of characters.

Because it\'s phonetic, there\'s no question about how a written word is
pronounced, and very little uncertainty about how a spoken word is
written, which accounts for the 99% literacy rate in both South and
North Korea.  Once you learn the alphabet, you can pretty much read
and write in Korean.

