    'from' => 'mstiavel@astro.sns.it',
    'body' => 'Thanks to Steve Bonneville for his extensive analysis of the power
balance in Imperium. I think it all makes a lot of sense in the
Imperium during peace time. During wartime, however, I still remain
sceptical. In my universe the Deneb Domain manages to successfully
fight off Aslan and Vargr during the Rebellion thanks to coordination
between the various Sector Forces, a similar coordination requires
homogenuous unit types and similar combat training. They all turn
out easier to obtain if there is a unique command. 

I have understood that e.g. the Duke of Lanth cannot stop the Imperial
fleet based there from being repositioned somewhere else, but can he 
interfere on what battleship types are built? or can the Duke/Granduke
of the Spinward Marches interfere on moving a fleet from Trin to Guzulin?
or on battleship design issues? or on budgetary issues?

I believe that in order to achieve something one needs a political 
decision at the start and no political interference from then on..
otherwise one ends up with things like the United Nations mission in
former Yugoslavia or a nice empty tunnel in  the middle of Texas, several
million dollars down the drain and formerly SSC employees looking for 
another job..
Regardless of what one may think of NASA achievements for instance,
the fact that NASA has to fight for money every year makes it very hard
for ESA to collaborate with it, since most space projects last for 
several years.
 
These issues would be similar for organizations spanning several months
of travel time. If one sector decides to change power plants bolting
techniques without the rest of Imperium doing it, this will cause
problems when ships from other sectors will operate there...
The same if they all start introducing a new model and somebody changes
his mind half way through..

Is it really possible to combine efficiency and local political control?

                            MAx


----
