II.=09MT BATTLEFLEET ARRIVAL IN-SYSTEM

Max Stiavelli writes:
>=09I\'ve always assumed that a fleet will reach a system scattered in space
and time. This makes fleet operations even more difficult.

DGP recognised this problem, and came up with a revision that said
(roughly) that one ship would work out the jump calculations for the fleet,
all would jump together, and this would result in ships arriving within
minutes of each other. If you want me to, I will fish through my magazines
and give you the exact ruling.

III.=09RE-WORKING TRAVELLER

Steve Lieb writes:
>=09Is it just me, or is Traveller in need of a serious reworking scientifi=
cally?

I thought that this IS what TNE was all about: that the game did not
correspond to reality, so change the game.

(As an aside) My beef with this is what I want to use the rules _for_. TNE
is more of a _simulation_ than a game. For an example of what I mean:
Harpoon is a _simulation_. It uses real-life stats and converts them to gam=
e
terms (and uses them so well that the US Navy uses the game for basic
wargames). However, this causes problems when you play:

a.=09"Low-tech" troops and equipment do not stand a chance (as in reality);
b.=09It is difficult to balance opposing forces in order to have a good
"game" (as opposed to a walk-over by one side).

Now, I don\'=92t (necessarily) dislike "reality" in a game - I want enough t=
o
make it believable, but not enough to overpower it - I mean, this is a GAME=
,
not REALITY - that is the point, surely? If you played out "Die Hard 2"
using TNE, what you would get is "Die Frequently" (as an aside, my wife -
who is not overly fond of the DH movies - wants the 4th one to be called
"Just Die, Would You?!").

We can suspend disbelief and allow transporters in Star Trek - or allow
magic and fantastic monsters in AD&D - without worrying about the Heisenber=
g
Uncertainty Principle, or the conservation of energy, or the inverse square
law! Why can=92t this extend to SF? No, I do not advocate going as far as
Space Opera or Buck Rogers, although those type of games can be fun. I want
_harder_ SF than that.

However, the TNE rules seem to be over-complicated for a GAME. I believe
that GDW has made a marketing decision to allow themselves to be pushed int=
o
a niche market. They now have the most realistic game system on the market
today (even if you include the errata - or perhaps BECAUSE of the errata!) =
-
but it appeals to a very small market because of its realism (and therefore
complexity). Look at what people are buying: apart from the Magic cardgame,
they are buying ROLEplaying games. These usually favour characterisation an=
d
scenarios over rules - often, a GM can dispense with dice for entire sessio=
ns.

At this point I will note what Derek Wildstar (wildstar@qrc.com) said in
digest 289:
>=09If you want to play Star-Trek-like or Star-Wars-like games, Traveller:
The New Era isn\'t the right tool for the job.

And what Andrew Richard Doull (adou01@cs.auckland.ac.nz) said in Digest 292=
:
>=09I feel GDW are closest to the gaming community when it comes to
explaining why they made their design decisions, and recognising a mistake
when they make one.

OK, so GDW are good guys in that they take notice of what people say, and
maybe I should just use the background (which I love) with another set of
rules. I have created a system based on (don\'t laugh) AD&D (cut in with a
bit of Buck Rogers), for one of my Traveller groups who prefer heroics to
realism...so, back to POW! WHAP! BASH!

IV. FREIGHT VS CARGO

In xboat 289, Robert Brennan wrote:
>       ...in MT there is mention of both freight and cargos but the two
seem confused...
I believe that that "freight" is other people\'s cargo! That is, "cargo" is
what you can buy, with all the requisite modifiers. Freight is what you
transport for other people, at a fixed price (Cr 1000/ton, isn\'t it?).

V. TRAVELLER FAQ - COPYRIGHT LAW IN THE USA

In xboat 290, Andy Lilly suggested that:
>       ...discussion of copyright law...should be on the list\'s FAQ...
Could you or someone else send a summary of the discussion to James Dempsey
for inclusion on the WWW FAQ? His address is jamesd@spirit.com.au - thanks.

- Hyphen
  (David Jaques-Watson)

