    'year' => 1995,
    'from' => 'Christopher Griffen',
    'body' => '     On June 14, Massimo Stiavelli wrote:
     
     >>One serious problem of the Traveller world is that the technological
     advancement has not been followed by a similar cultural and political
     development. Despite everything the world has evolved a lot in the
     last two thousand years. What we seen in Bosnia now, was rather normal
     two centuries ago...On average, countries that develop some technology
     develop also the cultural background to use it properly. Obviously
     there are exceptions, but I think that the trend is rather clear.
     Enslaving the population of a defeated city was normal two thousand
     years ago. Armies in the middle ages instead were satisfied by sacking 
     the 
     city and raping the women. Nowadays, these things are not normal 
     thanks God.<<
     
     I don\'t think that\'s necessarily true.  Technological advancement does 
     not necessarily guarantee any sort of cultural advancement, especially 
     in a universe in which the only mode of interstellar communication is 
     xboats, traders and other ships physically carrying in the news.
     
     In our own world, the same atrocities that have been committed for 
     time immemorial, lavished upon unsuspecting victims on a perpetual 
     basis.  With communication technology as it is (tv, radio, etc.) those 
     who want to be savage need to be a little more clandestine about it, 
     but given the right circumstances even the most technologically 
     advanced army and the civilization that supports it have been known to 
     take part in pillage, homicide and rape.
     
     As sentient beings, I think one consistent aspect of humanity has been 
     our aggression and violence.  Occurences of some of the aforementioned 
     atrocities might be anomalies in the future, but across a civilization 
     spanning hundreds of light years and consisting of trillions of 
     people, that\'s a lot of anomalies!
     
     The key is the dependency worlds have upon one another for trade and 
     life support (in some cases) and the "pony express" style 
     communications system.
     
     --Chris
