God.

Happened a lot during World War II.  Also Yugoslavia, Indonesia, Korea,
Vietnam, Burma, many wars in Africa and South/Central America, all during
this century.  

Routine targeting of civilian populations, indiscriminate use of landmines
(not to mention manufacture and sale of the same), poison gas, biowar...

I, personally, am not convinced that warfare is becoming more "civilized".  


> The Rebellion, the succession by right of assassination, etc.. are very
> hard to believe in the 56th century. 

Think of it as realpolitik: a willingness to admit to practices that today we
prefer to pretend don\'t exist, but engage in anyway.  After all, what is the
"right of assassination" but recognizing that a coup d\'etat can transfer the
control of the government?  Canada, Britain, the United States and many other
countries maintain diplomatic relations, give money and military support to,
etc. many countries where the governments came to power by coup.  
