    'topic' => 'The Imperium, culture, technology etc. ',
    'body' => 'There are times in a man\'s life when chocolate becomes a necessity, and when
its 
01:00 a.m. in a small Welsh coastal town, the only place is a dispenser
beneath 
the computer lab on campus.
	Therefore I thought a posting was in order to discuss, and hopefully 
contribute to the discussion regarding fuedalism, civilisation etc. by
comparing 
now, the future, and back again.  Some may claim that comparison is
impossible, 
but one thing is certain to me - human nature is eternal (and if someone else

said that I apologise...)

Firstly, lets consider What is our social system today - the International 
system is an anarchic collection of sovereign units (all states have equal 
sovereignty i.e. control over their borders, legal control within them over 
their citizens etc.) generally speaking these entities called states
represent 
distinct cultures with different social values etc. institutionalised in an 
administrative form by government.  In considering our world today I think it
is 
 necessary to remember that our values can colour our judgement without
careful 
consideration.  Democracy is not the system which governs the majority in the

world, and it is just another system - only better because it appears to keep

the \'wolf from the door\' effectively, it does have negative facets and
arguably 
a distinct lack of social justice - I only have to say to the American
audience 
here "O.J.simpson" for them to understand my point.
	I have been lucky enough to spend 5 - 6 years living in South and West 
Africa, the more low tech of todays societies, and hopefully feel I can add 
something distinct to this problem.  Today there are still fuedal societies
in 
existance, think of the Zulus in South Africa represented by their leader 
Mangesutu Butelezi - a fuedal system of leadership.  By and large the Zulu 
homelands (historical term now) are predominantly Incatha, politically.  The
ANC 
is largely made up of members of Nelson Mandela\'s tribe and outlook - lets
hope 
the right of assassination does not become South Africa\'s future...
Elsewhere 
in Iraq, Saddam Husseins precarious rule relies upon the posting of family 
members, from his native town of Tikriti, within a minority population in
Iraq 
(30% Sunni Muslim, 70% Shia(fundamentalist)).

Turning to the Third Imperium, what\'s changed in a few thousand (Terran)
years 
of evolution ? well, the anarchic environment is far less so.  The Imperial 
government is a federal type - super United Nations, with its armed forces 
raised from worlds by taxes, with control for the space between worlds.
Worlds 
are still individually sovereign, with extra-territorial starports akin to
those 
airports today.  As someone pointed out, the slow communication times (quick
for 
then), place restrictions on this \'utopia\'.  The logical way out is to
designate 
a caste-type system of people reliable \'to do the right thing\' in given 
circumstances.  The megacorporations appear to follow similar practise, as
does 
the armed forces.  In one of the Frontier Wars, The Spinward Marches went to 
war, the Imperial Government declared War formally as soon as word reached - 
this shows similar thinking - if not standard practise, after all the
frontier 
is such a long way from here.....
	If Fuedalism is dead, why is there so much emphasis placed in my state 
on knighthood\'s, with yearly lists of people invested for their services ?
and 
what do these people share ?  Also note the "Vons" in Europe, and existence
for 
better or worse of a noble class - its influence is diluted due to other 
structures i.e. mass communications, participation in the political system, 
economy etc.  but imagine the states of Europe hundreds of years ago - slow 
communication times, political awareness, participation restricted to higher 
echelons etc.   Think also of diplomats a couple of hundred years ago - today
by 
and large they are \'rubber stamps\' for a governments policies at the end of a

telephone or satellite link.  Then they were persons of enormous influence.

Consider the levels of order prevalent in todays world - not the past.  We
have 
high law levels (A+) such as in Singapore, "spray someones car and its the
cane 
for you son !", or zero - Liberia, where heads are placed on sticks today in
the 
1990s.  I must admit, whether or not its the fact that my work is
international 
politics, or not, I have a dark Hobbesian/machiavellian view of human nature,

and I think the wider public forget what a nasty place the world is, except
for 
15  minute blurring images presented by a friendly newscaster daily....

So has Traveller got it right ?  well from a role-playing view it would
arguably 
be a lot boring if the universe was uniform - imagine the world being
America, 
Britain or worse Bosnia (Twilight 2000 comes close I suppose).  Different Law

Levels work nicely, as do the types of government ranging from Democracy
(USA), 
to Monarchy (UK), to Anarchy (Former Republics of Yugoslavia), and Theocracy 
(Iran). The basis in Feudalism holds up well I believe, as perhaps it is
better 
to consider the alternatives - if the Imperium was just a government, 
states/planets would feel little empathy with it (bad news), and feel 
marginalised, but a system of nobles and trusted persons in contact with the
bg 
picture would be effective - I mean Bill Clinton or John Major contend with 
domestic problems and relations with say 30 important states and the odd
crisis 
or three - imagine your state, countries, and x worlds as well ? no way, 
something would give.  Perhaps Nobles are kind of ambassadors for the
Imperium, 
wielding influence (at best) in a benign way, reminding the worlds that they 
belong to something larger and better.  I mean if nobles are like royalty
today, 
what do they do mostly - maintain a high public profile for their followers,
and 
project a good image of their home world/subsector/sector wide....

I wish to turn now to the issues of Right of Assassination and the violence
in 
society today.  Someone has talked of the Imperial right of assassination as 
\'unrealistic\', others consider it a formal transfer of power, a process.
Does 
it happen in the real world today ?  not quite.  I mean noone will go to
Saddam 
Hussein pull a gun, say "by right of xyz....", shoot him, sit in his chair
and 
dictate policy - no in democracies we have what P.J. O\'Rourke calls
"character 
assasinations" or elections (sorry joke).
	In International Law we have De Jurre Governments and De Facto 
Governments, a neat play on words when either a civil war is raging, or a
coup 
de etat has occured, and the home governent is unsure which horse to back.
The 
key point it that it is very rare, by the rules of our game in the real
world, 
that a coup leader is not recognised as the legitimate power once he has his 
hands on the levers of power i.e. military, political etc. and what are these

levers ?  In a third world state typically they are - The media (or
broadcasting 
stations), the Mint, the parliament/assembly building, the military
headquarters 
etc.  note: in a third world country, or modern state they are often
clustered 
closely together for security, yet paradoxically make coups easier.  Think of

Washington D.C. and The Gambia.  The latter is 40 km wide, and 360 km long,
the 
capital is grouped on an island with all of the above there. A coup took
place 
there last year - easy, yes.  Washington D.C. - the Pentagon, political 
buildings, judiciary etc. all grouped together.  The difference is the
dspersed 
media - but then the Imperium negates that advantage.  In sum, the ability to

mount a coup in virtually any society is not impossible, just because the 
Imperium is so large, we think naaahh, but wait, if I was going to cause a 
revolution, a small fleet sufficient for the local depot, if not just Core 
system would be enough (Small means relatively !).  So what of the right of 
assassination - if you just killed your head of state routinely you would
create 
mass panic, and lack of faith in the system as a whole (key)  In Roman times 
there was a year in which several (36 ?) Emperors were elected and killed
off, 
yet always there was a ritual to go through of some kind.  The key here is
that 
humaniti I believe is a beast which along with a darker side to its nature is
a 
creature of habit.  The Right of Assassination is not the regal equivalent of

"you have the right to remain - dead !", but rather is the cumulation of the 
system by which persons outside of the royal blood lines ascend to power,
after 
all if Lucan were any other Emperor, he would have probably been tolerated,
and 
a family member take over, yet with no family, how would Lucan have been 
replaced - assassination most likely, as when he grew old, pressure would
have 
mounted (and Lucan does not strike me as someone to give up "Saddam of the 
spaceways").  In summary I think the Right of Assassination is not
indefensible 
in a future RPG, it is ekegant, but should not be interpreted literally.
	Finally, Finally, violence as becoming more civilised.  I think the 
writer mayhave spoken in the heat of the moment, and like the press and 
politicians, is being hounded remorselesly.  Violence, has never been a 
civilised affair, and what is there to suggest that new technologies will
ensure 
social checks on its existence (short of psionics).  Conrad Lorenz had a
theory 
of aggression concerning humans and animals (remember we are just a more
complex 
animal), and he spoke of animals having inhibitors due to their natural 
weaponry.  For example combat for animals is a largely ritualised affair,
rarely 
resulting in a fight to the death.  Lorenz suggested that humaniti\'s lack of 
natural weaponry led to combat being brutal and Hobbesian in the extreme.  
Combat as a civilised affair arguably existed for a time, during the Italian 
city-state wars of the Middle Ages when battles were decided by manoevre, the

losing side, like in a chess game, running off rather than fighting, but this

was a brief period.  The Gulf War of 1991 was hailed as a precision conflict
and 
shape of things to come.  But now as the data comes in, the results appear to

suggest that it showed the way of the future of warfare, but was not the 
watershed itself.  Pictures of bobs hitting taregts were propaganda for the 
public opinion at home - not every tomahawk hit its target, and pictures of 
gunship crews straffing troops in APC\'s "up close and personnal" were
suppressed 
for as long as practical.
	I have met Colonel Bob Stewart twice in the last six months (first 
commander of the UKs UNPROFOR contingent) and believe me he would not agree
with 
any statements concerning warfare as becoming more civilised.  His
description 
of entering a house one day to find the village inhabitants having been 
incinerated while bound up i.e. still alive is enough to put you off your 
dinner, and ensure when you turn the television off, you do not get to sleep.

As long as humaniti can find justification, its nature will be to do dark 
things.
	In closing ratehr soberly I hope I have contributed something to the 
discussion, I doubtless believe this posting is long enough to get myself
into 
hot water over some inconsistency.  I apologise for not mentioning previous 
posts by name, but you all had input into this one.  Finally, I considered
Max\'s 
statement in yesterday\'s posting regarding Political Correctness, and I want 
everyone to think of this;

What is political correctness ?  Is it a way of gaining recognition of other 
peoples prejudices expressed by language, or is it becoming a form of
linguistic 
fascism ?  for example if I wished to write a project comparing race or
gender, 
I would meet a hailstorm of protest at University - a bastion of intellectual

freedom (?)  If the University invited say a prominent member of a extreme
right 
wing political group to express its views so that we could gauge their
concepts, 
like any other party, would the university be treated as a institution acting
in 
a streetwise, conscious manner, or would it be demonised and face withdrawal
of 
support from funding sources ???
	I think PC is a frightening challenge in the incarnation it has reached. 
 It is not fashionable in my department to consider warfare and issues of 
military strategy "with 1989 there\'s little need for you people" - precisely
the 
attitude of before 1914 "there can be no war between civilised states". hmmm

Regards
Jeff

  

