    'body' => 'In XBOAT Digest 305, Steve Bonneville writes:

>We have one example of the procurement process from "classic" Traveller...

>...This was a fairly unique offer, since the Marches covered the additional
>cruiser by mounting a fund drive in the schools, collecting quarter-credits
>from kids\' lunch money for it, _Children of the March_.  But this sort
>of deal might be more common, without the patriotic bells and whistles
>and creative fund-raising.  (If I remember the library data version of
>this right, it added a comment about a minor scandal involving the way
>some local planetary governments handled the money....)

>From memory (I\'m sending from work), what actually occurred was that the
sector government didn\'t bother to try to collect the kid\'s lunch money (too
much effort to co-ordinate). They just calculated how much this amount would
have come to, and deducted it from the funds going to education. I do
remember that the Lib Data concluded with something like this:
"To this day, on some backwater worlds, there is still a fund-raising drive
for \'the ship fund\'".

Also in xboat 305, Aaron DaMommio said:
>While overall we seem to be doing pretty well as a planet, Bosnia proves
what  
>we are still capable of. Hitler and Mussolini aren\'t that far in the past,
and  
>atrocities occur all the time..... I just  
>don\'t believe that we as a race are inevitably getting "better" all the
time. I  
>think progress in the area of societal values is something hard-fought that

>could easily be lost.

I know quite a few people who would agree with Aaron, and disagree with the
"Gene Roddenberry" view of mankind. The best that humanity seems to be able
to achieve are those "brief, shining moments" [quote from Camelot]. Or as
the Terminator says, "Your race is bent on self-destruction". "Bummer, isn\'t
it?" replies the kid.

- Hyphen



