The relevant Traveller News Service dispatches are reprinted in the FFW
rulebook, actually.  :-)  There\'s a number of them - it\'s probably not
practical to summarize them here.

Other relvant material is the Classic Traveller adventure _Twilight\'s Peak_.

> The only bit I know is that Admiral Santanocheev was sacked (for some
> reason) by Norris via the (forged) Imperial Warrant. (Though from looking
> at FFW the game, there are far better people to put in overall command,
> like the genius planning 0 / tactics +3 admiral, rather than Norris, a
0/0.)

Because he (Stantocheev) was an idiot.  In the game, I believe his plotting
factor is 4, though there are worse in the game.  Replacing a high-plotting
value admiral with one that\'s plotting 0 is _very_ valuable.  Admittedly, the
plotting 0 tactics +3 admiral would be better, but Norris is the one
that the Warrant was for.  Also, check the rank number on that genius - if
I recall correctly, he\'s pretty junior - which means that he\'ll wind up
commanding one of your smaller fleets.

The plotting factor is the number of turns in advance that you must write
the fleet\'s movement orders - in other words, for Stantocheev, you\'ve got
to decide where his fleet is going on turn 12 when you\'re in turn 8!  Unless
you\'re good (or lucky), getting fleets to where they need to be while
plotting this far in advance is tough (even moreso if your opponent has a
smaller plotting requirement that you do).

The other important factor about how the rules work, is thate higher-ranking
admirals eventually wind up controlling your most valuable fleets - no
matter how good (or importantly, how bad) the admiral is!  There are a
number of really _bad_ high-ranking admirals in the Imperial mix, and the
Warrant is needed so that Norris (who is at least flexable, if not a great
tactician) can relieve these high-ranking idiots.

One more thing - the Warrant isn\'t forged (Norris didn\'t do that - he saw
the war coming, and predicted that some high-ranking idiot would gum the
Imperial works up).  So he went to Strephon, and requested the Warrant (see
Travellers\' Digest #9, page 9) so that he would be named Supreme Commander
of the Imperial defense of the Marches.  UNfortunately, the ship with the
Warrant (or rather, the ship Norris believed was carrying the Warrant) was
hit by Zhos on the way in, and went down in a Red-zone system.

Norris\'s "illness" was faked, so that he could personally retrieve the
warrant.  Norris felt that he couldn\'t order someone to go get it for him
because if it wasn\'t there, he would have ordered someone to peform an
Imperial crime.  So later in the war, Norris has the Warrant, and is
suddenly feeling fine.

