    'from' => 'ggoffin@igc.apc.org',
    'body' => 'The July 1995 World Press Review reports an article by Kieran Cooke 
in London\'s Financial Times (6 Apr 95), about new forms of piracy in 
Southeast Asia.  Here is an excerpt:

"In a typical case, a Southeast Asia-based crime syndicate will buy 
an old cargo vessel for about $1 million.  Syndicate members register 
the vessel under a new name with a flag-of-convenience country for 
about $5,000.  No inspection of the vessel is required."

The syndicate then sets up dummy offices as if it were a legitimate 
shipping company, forges ship\'s documents, and hires a crew (giving 
them false passports).  The syndicate learns when shipments are 
likely to be made, and their destinations.  When it gets a cargo 
loaded, it sails out of port, ostensibly toward the cargo\'s 
destination.  En route, the crew changes the ship\'s name, and takes 
the cargo somewhere else -- usually China.  

When the cargo\'s owner learns that the cargo hasn\'t arrived at its 
intended destination, an investigation begins.  Lloyd\'s shipping 
index reveals that the ship doesn\'t exist -- it is a phantom ship.

The International Maritime Bureau, a United Nations sponsored 
organization that investigates shipping crime, has at least four 
phantom ship cases under investigation in Southeast Asia.

I think that the phantom ship idea could be easily translated to the 
Spinward Main, especially in the areas along the Imperial border.  
I\'m surprised that I didn\'t think of it myself.

--Glenn
