    'body' => 'Hi there

>The relevant Traveller News Service dispatches are reprinted in the FFW
>rulebook, actually.  :-)  There\'s a number of them - it\'s probably not
>practical to summarize them here.

Not quite true.  As I remember, the news in FFW was pre-war.  The TNS for 
during the war was printed in several JTAS, and reprinted in JTAS 19 
"Traveller News Service (Revisited)".  This takes-up where the FFW TNS 
leaves off, with the call up of IISS reserves.  A synopsis of the FFW was 
printed in The Spinward Marches Campaign, along with maps.  
Unfortunately, the maps, the synopsis, and the TNS don\'t tally on details 
like which fleet was where when, although the dates etc. of major events 
seem to be correct.

With regard to Duke Norris\' illness.  TNS reported him ill with a 
"pneumonic virus" on 212-1107.  Santanocheev was first mentioned on 
268-1107, forbidding landing on interdicted worlds unless enemy forces 
have already done so; perhaps an attempt to pre-empt Norris\' visit toone 
of these worlds in pursuit of the Imperial Warrant.  On 302-1107, the 
office of the Duke denied reports of his death.  Admiral Santanocheev is 
mentioned in reports on 035-1108, 362-1108, 021-1109, and 029-1109, all 
showing how badly the war was going.  Finally, on 132-1109, Norris 
relieved Santanocheev of his command, taking personal control of the 1st 
Provisional Fleet, and going on to plan the fight-back.  650 days to find 
the warrant and then use it!

In SMC, it is indicated that while Norris was a veteran of Imperial Naval 
Intelligence, Santanocheev had set up a seperate agency, the Office of 
Naval Information, which he used in preference to INI.  Unfortunately, 
ONI were inept, and INI were to loyal to the Imperium to attempt to usurp 
the legitimate (if incompetent) Naval authorities.  Only a high noble 
with plenipotentiary powers (ie. Norris with a warrant) could do this.

Next week, we\'ll have a brief history of the Julian War, and the 
political intrigues leading up to it (not!)

