    'body' => 'I am trying to design an antimissile missile to be used in turrets
and bay weapons, so I have tried to patchup various information to
be able 1st to redesign the MT standard missile. However, I have found
some misleading information on various MT books.
In the Referee\'s manual, there is not hint that bay missiles are 
larger than turret missiles. However, in COACC it is stated that
starship missiles count as 16 cm howitzer rounds if they are turret
missiles, 24cm howitzer rounds if bay missiles....

COACC also states that the warhead of the standard 15cm missiles (the 50 kg
ones) is 30 kg and that the missile is capable of 6G for 6 turns..(that\'s
how I read 6G6..) are these 6 seconds turns or 1200 seconds turns??
If they are 6 seconds turns it is easy to design them, but they would be 
totally ineffective in starship combat. If they are 1200 second turns
it is not trivial to design them, since rockets or high perf. rockets
could not provide the required thrust and duration in the 20 kg that are 
left.. Also COACC states that starships missiles have solid fuel, which 
is not described in COACC..

Is there an "official" MT solution to these problems? if not I will try
to make my own hose rules on this...

       Thanks in advance

                  Max


