    'body' => 'Okay, here I am again with more questions about the MT combat rules.  
This time I\'m confused about interrupts, especially as they relate to
hand-to-hand combat, direct fire combat and the tactical points pool.

Here goes:

1. The group with the highest tactical points skill level decides who
   goes first in a combat scenario.  Fine.  Now, if both sides have an
   equal amount of Tactics skill, who wins?  I\'ve been having each side
   roll 1d6, with the highest value having the initiative.  Am I doing 
   this right?

2. Let\'s say I have Tactics-1 and you have no Tactics.  We engage in 
   HTH combat.  Because of my Tactics skill, I should go first.  Does it
   make sense, then, to have you able to interrupt me?  According to the 
   rules, "the defender may attempt to preempt the attack by interrupting 
   the attacker" in HTH combat.  That means that, if the interrupt roll
   is successful, my Tactics did me no good at all.  What\'s up with that?

3. There doesn\'t appear to be anything in the rules preventing a character
   from interrupting his direct-fire opponent.  For example, A is shooting
   at B.  B sees this and interrupts A, which means B is firing first.
   Now, does this make sense?  I understand if a character (say, C) sees
   A shooting at B and decides to interrupt A and shoot at A.  However, if
   B can interrupt B\'s own attacker, then what\'s the point of determining
   who goes first?  Am I missing something here?

I\'m wondering if interrupts are a waste of time and introduce unneeded
complexity into the game.  How do other people feel?

-- 
Erwin Fritz  (erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca)
Technical Analyst
DMR Group, Inc.

