13/7-95 Erwin Fritz wrote:

>Okay, here I am again with more questions about the MT
>combat rules. This time I\'m confused about interrupts,
>especially as they relate to hand-to-hand combat, direct
>fire combat and the tactical points pool.
>
>Here goes:
>
>1. The group with the highest tactical points skill level
>decides who goes first in a combat scenario.  Fine.
>Now, if both sides have an equal amount of Tactics skill,
>who wins?  I\'ve been having each side roll 1d6, with the
>highest value having the initiative.  Am I doing this right?

Well, there are several ways of deciding which side goes
first. The official rule is the side with the largest tactical
points pool, but, as you mention, this is not always decisive
(my players\' PCs often don\'t have tactics skill at all).
There\'s no official rule concerning what to do in this
situation, but DGP did mention this: As always in MT, don\'t
let rigid rules bog you down. Use common sense. This
was the way the rules were made in the first place.
DGP also makes some *suggestions* on the subject: Let
the person with the highest leader skill decide which side
goes first or flip a coin (or, as you do, 1D6).
Common sense could go something like this: The always
jumpy and paranoid PCs have been ready for combat for
hours, whereas the guards they have to battle are in a
slightly disadvantageous situation. Not enough to justify a
surprise, mind you. Then I would have my players go first.

>2. Let\'s say I have Tactics-1 and you have no Tactics.  We
>engage in HTH combat.  Because of my Tactics skill, I
>should go first.  Does it make sense, then, to have you
>able to interrupt me?  According to the rules, "the
>defender may attempt to preempt the attack by >interrupting the attacker" in
H
TH combat.  That means
>that, if the interrupt roll is successful, my Tactics did me
>no good at all.  What\'s up with that?

Well, you could always try to interrupt back. It is quite
possible to interrupt the interrupt. But remember the rule
which says only one interrupt per side per turn is allowed.
But as an interrupt is somewhat of a "charging towards the
enemy with your guns ablazing", it wouldn\'t be too
appropiate in a HTH situation. Remember that the only DM
you get on the task roll is your movement speed.
So your opponent would have to roll 7+ on 2D6 to interrupt
you (not that hard), but then you could try the same.

>3. There doesn\'t appear to be anything in the rules
>preventing a character from interrupting his direct-fire
>opponent.  For example, A is shooting at B.  B sees this
