    'body' => '>Date: Thu, 13 Jul 95 16:57:43 EDT
>From: "M. Harelick"  <msh9848@hertz.njit.edu>

>First off, I have a problem with this whole tactical point pool rule. 
>
>The problems I see with this are: 
>
>1. Why is tactics more important than dexterity? 

Imagine an Imperial Marine gets in a gunfight with a gold medal gymnast at 
the Imperial Olympics. My money\'s on the Marine to get the first (and last) 
shot off, even if the gymnast outpoints him/her heavily in the dex
department.

Traveller seems to assume that training is more important than natural 
ability in this sort of situation; for the most part, I agree with them. 
Tactics skill was probably chosen as a pretty good indication of this sort 
of training.

Which is not to say that this should be a hard and fast rule - there are 
many times that I want to run a combat round without any actual combat 
happening (during a chase scene, or whatever). In those cases, I\'d 
substitute something else for Tactics (appropriate vehicle skill, for
example).

>I think that alot of the Traveller combat system believes that two sides
>of a combat are going to act as two whle groups rather than as 
>individuals. 

This is true, and seems generally true for the Traveller rules. All the ship 
combat and construction rules beyond the original 3 booklets, for example, 
seem to be written for big warships battling fleet actions, rather than the 
small ship-to-ship actions that a scruffy group of adventuring 
"entrepreneurs" are likely to be involved in. While I appreciate the realism 
in rules that say the crew of the Centennial Eagle will be vaporized if they 
try and buzz an Imperial Destroyer (Star or otherwise), there are times when 
I want a group of PCs to be more heroically than the rules normally
encourage.

